d>6.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Highest - Chhattisgarh</td>\n<td>8.0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lowest - Delhi</td>\n<td>3.3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Infant Mortality Rate (per 1000 live births)</strong></td>\n<td rowspan=\4\>&nbsp;SRS - 2022&nbsp; &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>India</td>\n<td>28</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Highest - Chattisgarh and&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Uttar Pradesh&nbsp;</td>\n<td>38</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lowest - Mizoram</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Natural Growth Rate&nbsp;(per 1000 mid-year population)&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td rowspan=\4\>&nbsp;SRS - 2022</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>India&nbsp;</td>\n<td>13.5&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Highest -&nbsp;Bihar&nbsp;</td>\n<td>20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lowest - Goa and Kerala</td>\n<td>6.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 1 lac live births)&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td rowspan=\4\>&nbsp;SRS - 2022</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;India</td>\n<td>97</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Highest - Assam</td>\n<td>195</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lowest - Kerala</td>\n<td>19</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Neonatal Mortality Rate (per 1000 live births)</strong></td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>&nbsp;SRS - 2022</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>India</td>\n<td>20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Total Fertility rate (children per woman of reproductive age)</strong></td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>&nbsp;NFHS -5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>India&nbsp;</td>\n<td>2.0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Life expectancy at birth</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Male</td>\n<td>69.7 years</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>&nbsp;2022</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Female</td>\n<td>72.2 years</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(973, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2044. Crude death rate', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Crude death rate:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The crude death rate is the <strong>simplest measure</strong> of mortality.</li>\n<li>It is the number of deaths (from all causes) per 1000 estimated mid-year population in one year, in a given place.</li>\n<li><strong>Crude death rate</strong> = &nbsp;(Number of deaths per year)/(Mid-year population) x 1000</li>\n<li>Disadvantage: lacks <strong>comparability</strong> for communities with populations that differ in age, sex, race, etc.</li>\n<li>Currently, the crude death rate in India is <strong>6.0.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(974, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1700. Neonatal Mortality Rate', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Neonatal deaths</strong> are those that occur during the neonatal period, commencing at birth and ending at 28 completed days after birth.</li>\n<li><strong>NMR = Number of deaths of children under 28 days of age in a year x 1000/Total live births in the same year</strong></li>\n<li>Main causes of neonatal death are <strong>prematurity&nbsp;</strong>(leading cause), birth asphyxia, intrapartum-related complications, sepsis, pneumonia, congenital anomalies, tetanus, diarrhea, etc.</li>\n<li>India’s NMR&nbsp; is<strong>&nbsp;20 per 1000 live births&nbsp;</strong>(SRS 2020)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(975, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1699. Perinatal Mortality Rate', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>The term ‘perinatal mortality’ includes both<strong> late fetal death</strong> (stillbirths) and<strong> early neonatal deaths</strong>.</li>\n<li>Babies chosen for inclusion in perinatal statistics should be <strong>above a minimum birth weight</strong> (1000g at birth). If the birth weight is not available, a <strong>gestation period of at least 28 weeks</strong> should be used (as the weight at 28 weeks corresponds to 1000g). If both are not available, then <strong>crown to heel length of at least 35cm</strong> should be used.</li>\n<li>Generally, the <strong>PMR</strong> = Late fetal deaths and early neonatal deaths weighing over 1000g at birth x 1000/Total births(live+dead) weighing over 1000g at birth.</li>\n<li>The PMR is the yard-stick of obstetric and pediatric care before and around the time of birth.</li>\n<li>The PMR of India (2016) is 24 per 1000 births.</li>\n<li>The main causes of perinatal mortality are intrauterine and birth asphyxia, low birth weight, birth trauma, and intrauterine/neonatal infections.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Please note that the <strong>actual perinatal period commences from the 22nd week of life, but at that time the fetus weighs only about 500g.</strong></p>\n<p>Therefore, <strong>only for statistical calculations and international comparisons, to calculate the perinatal mortality rate, the period from the 28th week</strong> of life is taken, as then the baby weighs about <strong>1000g</strong>. As mentioned, babies included in the perinatal <strong>statistics</strong> must weigh above <strong>1000g</strong>.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(976, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1698. Maternal Mortality Ratio', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Maternal death</strong> is defined as the death of a woman <strong>while pregnant or within 42 days of termination of pregnancy</strong>, irrespective of the duration and site of pregnancy, from <strong>any cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy</strong> or its management but not from accidental or incidental causes.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/19493f9439a24b529b7a098cbbce594cx1280x644.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The main global causes of maternal deaths are <strong>severe bleeding, indirect causes</strong> (anemia, malaria, heart diseases), <strong>infections, unsafe abortions, eclampsia, obstructed labor,</strong> and other direct causes like ectopic pregnancy, anesthesia-related complications, etc.</p>\n<p>In India, the most common causes of maternal deaths are hemorrhage (leading cause), sepsis, obstructed labor, hypertensive disorders, etc.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(977, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0138. Socio-Economic Indicators of Health', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;Mnemonic: <strong>H – FLAGGED<br> <br> </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>H</strong>ousing [number of persons per room]</li>\n<li><strong>F</strong>amily size</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>iteracy rate [especially female literacy rate]</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>vailability of per capita ‘calorie’</li>\n<li><strong>G</strong>NP per capita</li>\n<li><strong>G</strong>rowth rate of population</li>\n<li>Un<strong>E</strong>mployment level</li>\n<li><strong>D</strong>ependency ratio</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(978, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0137. Disability Adjusted Life Year (DALY)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/68a5647564a1454282a4026c51022dd2x1200x394.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(979, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0136. QALY vs. DALY', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>QALY and DALY are disability indicators used as measures of health in a population.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p><strong>QALY </strong>(Quality Adjusted Life Years)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p><strong>DALY&nbsp;</strong>(Disability Adjusted Life Years)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Measures <strong>quality of life</strong> in health gain</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Measures <strong>health loss</strong> in quality of life</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Indicator of <strong>cost-effectiveness</strong> of intervention</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Indicator of overall <strong>burden of disease</strong> in a population</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Expressed as 1 or 0 where,</p>\n<p>1 = Perfect health</p>\n<p>0 = Death</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\308\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Expressed as 0 or 1 where,</p>\n<p>0 = Perfect health</p>\n<p>1 = Death</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(980, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0134. HDI vs. PQLI', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Human Development Index&nbsp;</strong><strong>(HDI)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Physical Quality of Life Index (PQLI)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Components</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Longevity (Life expectancy at birth)</p>\n<p>A decent standard of living (Real GNI per capita in PPP US$)</p>\n<p>Knowledge (mean years of schooling and expected years of schooling)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Life expectancy at 1 year of age&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Infant Mortality rate</p>\n<p>Literacy rate</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Range</strong></td>\n<td>0 to +1</td>\n<td>0 to 100</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(981, 'Community Medicine,', 'PM1691. National Immunization Schedule (India)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Vaccine</strong></td>\n<td><strong>When to give</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Dose</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Route</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Site</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\5\><strong>For Pregnant Women</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Td-1</td>\n<td>\n<p>Early in pregnancy</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Td-2</td>\n<td>\n<p>4 weeks after Td-1*</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Td-&nbsp;Booster</td>\n<td>\n<p>If received 2 Td doses in a pregnancy&nbsp;<br>within the last 3 yrs*</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\5\><strong>For Infants</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>BCG</td>\n<td>\n<p>At birth or as early as possible until one&nbsp;year of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.1 mL (0.05 mL until<br>1 month<br>age)</td>\n<td>Intra-dermal</td>\n<td>Left upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hepatitis B - Birth&nbsp;Dose</td>\n<td>\n<p>At birth or as early as possible within 24 hrs</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Antero-lateral&nbsp;side of mid-thigh</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>OPV - 0</td>\n<td>\n<p>At birth or as early as possible within&nbsp;the first 15 days</p>\n</td>\n<td>2 drops</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>OPV-1, 2 &amp; 3</td>\n<td>\n<p>At 6 weeks, 10 weeks, &amp; 14 weeks (can be given until 5 years of age)</p>\n</td>\n<td>2 drops</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pentavalent&nbsp;1, 2 &amp; 3</td>\n<td>\n<p>At 6 weeks, 10 weeks, &amp; 14 weeks (can be given until one year of age)</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>lntra·muscular</td>\n<td>Antero-lateral&nbsp;side of mid-thigh</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rotavirus</td>\n<td>\n<p>At 6 weeks, 10 weeks, &amp; 14 weeks (can be given until one year of age)</p>\n</td>\n<td>5&nbsp;drops</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IPV</td>\n<td>\n<p>Three fractional doses at 6, 14 weeks and 9 months of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.1 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-dermal 3 fractional dose</td>\n<td>Intra-dermal: right&nbsp;Upper arm (at 6, 14 weeks);<br>left upper arm (at 9 months)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>PCV</p>\n<p>(wherever applicable)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>At 6 weeks and 14 weeks; Booster at 9 completed months</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra·muscular</td>\n<td>Antero-lateral&nbsp;side of mid-thigh, right</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Measles/MR 1<sup>st</sup> Dose</td>\n<td>\n<p>9 completed months to 12 months<br>(Can be given till 5 years of age)</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5ml</td>\n<td>Sub-cutaneous</td>\n<td>Right upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>JE- 1**</td>\n<td>\n<p>9 completed months to 12 months</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>\n<p>Intramuscular(killed)/Subcutaneous (live attenuated)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Anterolateral aspect of mid-thigh/Left upper arm&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Vitamin A<br>(1st dose)</td>\n<td>\n<p>At&nbsp;9 completed months with measles Rubella</p>\n</td>\n<td>1 mL (1 lakh IU)</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\5\><strong>For Children&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DPT booster-1</td>\n<td>\n<p>16–24 months</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Antero-lateral&nbsp;side of mid-thigh &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Measles / MR 2<sup>nd </sup>dose</td>\n<td>\n<p>16–24 months</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Sub-cutaneous</td>\n<td>Right upper arm &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>OPV booster</td>\n<td>\n<p>16–24 months</p>\n</td>\n<td>2 drops</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>JE-2</td>\n<td>\n<p>16–24 months</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>\n<p>Intramuscular (killed)/Subcutaneous (live attenuated)</p>\n</td>\n<td>Anterolateral aspect of mid-thigh/Left upper arm&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Vitamin A***<br>(2nd to 9<sup>th</sup> dose)</td>\n<td>\n<p>16–18 months, followed by&nbsp;one dose every 6 months up to the age of 5 years</p>\n</td>\n<td>2&nbsp;mL (2 lakh IU)</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n<td>Oral</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DPT booster 2</td>\n<td>\n<p>5–6 years</p>\n</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>Upper arm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Td</td>\n<td>10 years &amp; 16 years</td>\n<td>0.5 mL</td>\n<td>Intra-muscular</td>\n<td>\n<p>Upper arm</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>*Give Td-2 or booster doses before 36 weeks of pregnancy. However, give these even if more than 36 weeks have passed. Give Td to a woman in labor, if she has not previously received Td.</p>\n<p>**JE vaccine is introduced in select endemic districts after the campaigns. Intramuscular (killed inactivated) vaccine is gradually replacing the live attenuated vaccine. This change is because the killed vaccines are more effective and require fewer doses.</p>\n<p>***The 2nd to 9th doses of vitamin A can be administered to children 1–5 years old during biannual rounds, in collaboration with ICDS.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(982, 'Paediatrics,', 'PM0701. Contraindications to Vaccines', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Vaccine</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Contraindications</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>All</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Anaphylactic reaction to previous dose</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Live vaccines (MMR, BCG, yellow fever,Varicella)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Pregnancy</p>\n<p>Radiation therapy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Yellow fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Egg allergy</p>\n<p>Immunodeficiency</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>BCG</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Symptomatic HIV infection</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Influenza, yellow fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Egg allergy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Pertussis-containing vaccines</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Evolving neurological disorders</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(983, 'Paediatrics,', 'PM0700. Adverse Events following Immunization', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p><strong>Vaccine</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p><strong>Common, Minor Reactions</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p><strong>Rare, Serious Reactions</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>BCG</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local pain and swelling</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Suppurative lymphadenitis</p>\n<p>BCG osteitis</p>\n<p>Disseminated BCG infection</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>Hepatitis B</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local reaction, fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Anaphylaxis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>Inactivated influenza</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local reaction</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS)</p>\n<p>Oculo-respiratory syndrome</p>\n<p>Anaphylaxis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>JE vaccine</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local reaction, low-grade fever, myalgia</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Neurologic events like encephalitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>Measles/MMR</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local reactions, fever, malaise, irritability</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Febrile seizures, arthralgia, thrombocytopenia</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>Yellow fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Headache, flu like symptoms, local reactions</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Vaccine-associated viscerotropic disease</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>Oral Polio</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>None</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Vaccine associated paralytic poliomyelitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\151\>\n<p>DPT</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\204\>\n<p>Local reaction, fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\235\>\n<p>Neurologic events like encephalitis, seizures, HHE (hypotonic hyporesponsive episode), anaphylaxis, persistent inconsolable screaming</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(984, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0698. Vaccine Vial Monitors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Vaccine vial monitors</strong> are used to monitor heat exposure of vaccines.</li>\n<li>It is a chemical indicator that records the cumulative heat exposure through a gradual change in color.</li>\n<li>If the color of the <strong>inner square</strong> is the <strong>same color or darker</strong> than the <strong>outer circle</strong>, it indicates that the vaccine has been exposed to too much heat and it must be <strong>discarded</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/3914a3eb19cf43ec9273112090e7b3f6x600x1199.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Currently, there are <strong>four types</strong> of VVMs (VVM2, VVM7, VVM14, and VVM30). They are chosen to match the heat sensitivity of the vaccine.</li>\n<li>The VVM can be located on the label of the vaccine or on the neck or cap of the ampule/vial.</li>\n<li>VVMs also help in <strong>reduction of vaccine wastage</strong> by indicating which batch of vaccines can be used first.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(985, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0697. Open Vial Policy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Open vial policy allows for reuse of partially used <strong>multidose vials</strong> of applicable vaccines under the Universal Immunization Programme in subsequent sessions up to&nbsp;<strong>4&nbsp;weeks</strong> subject to certain conditions and thereby reducing vaccine wastage.</p>\n<p>It is applicable only for <strong>DPT, TT, hepatitis B vaccine, OPV, liquid pentavalent vaccine, rotavirus vaccine(new version with the VVM on the side), and JE vaccines (inactivated). </strong>It is not applicable to <strong>BCG and measles vaccines.&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>Vaccine vials opened in session-site can be used in more than one session up to four weeks if <strong>expiry date has not passed, if storage and transport was appropriate, no contamination has occurred in vial septum, asepsis in withdrawing was practiced and if vaccine vial monitor has not reached discard point.</strong></p>\n<p>Open vials should <strong>not</strong> be submerged in water. All open vials should have a record of&nbsp;<strong>date and time of opening</strong>. At the end of a session, all vaccines should be returned to the cold chain point and segregated as re-usable and non-reusable. All open vials of BCG, measles must be destroyed after 48 hours or before next session, whichever is earlier.</p>\n<p>In case of any <strong>adverse events following immunization</strong>, all open vials should not be discarded until investigation is complete. All vials must be transported in zipper bags in the vaccine carrier and recorded in stock register. Ice packs used should be well sealed.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(986, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0696. Cold Chain Equipment', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Cold chain equipment :&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Storage :&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Walk in cooler (WIC)</li>\n<li>Walk in freezer (WIF)</li>\n<li>Ice lined refrigerator (ILR)</li>\n<li>Deep freezer&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Domestic refrigerator&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Solar :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Solar Refrigerator Battery drive</li>\n<li>Solar Refrigerator Direct drive</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Non electrical :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cold box</li>\n<li>Vaccine carrier</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Transportation :&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Refrigerator vaccine van</li>\n<li>Insulated vaccine van</li>\n<li>Cold box&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Vaccine carrier</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/549c3f139636430fa5c659529a31d432x1280x1489.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Electrical Cold Chain Equipment:&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Component</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Temperature (degree Celsius)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Level</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Other Comments</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Walk in Freezers (WIF)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>-15 to -25&nbsp; </strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>National, State and Regional vaccine stores</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Used for bulk storage of <strong>OPV </strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Walk in Coolers (WIC)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>+2 to +8</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Government Medical Store Depot (GMSD), State and Regional vaccines stores</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Used for bulk storage of most vaccines in UIP</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Deep Freezer (DF)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>-15 to -25&nbsp; </strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>District and Sub-district vaccines stores</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Used for bulk storage of <strong>OPV</strong> and ice packs</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Ice Line Refrigerator (ILR)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>+2 to +8</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>District and Sub-district vaccines stores, <strong>PHCs</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Has different <strong>temperature zones </strong>for different vaccines</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Front Load Refrigerator (Domestic)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>+2 to +8</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Sub-district levels, hospitals. dispensaries and nursing homes</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Used for all vaccines</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(987, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0693. Temperature Sensitivity of Vaccines', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Heat sensitivity</strong> in order of <strong>decreasing</strong> sensitivity:&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\791\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Group</td>\n<td>Vaccines</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A</td>\n<td>OPV</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>B</td>\n<td>Influenza</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>C</td>\n<td>\n<p>IPV</p>\n<p>Japanese encephalitis(live)</p>\n<p>Measles, mumps, rubella</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>D</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cholera</p>\n<p>DTaP</p>\n<p>Pentavalent</p>\n<p>Rotavirus</p>\n<p>Hib(liquid)</p>\n<p>Yellow fever</p>\n<p>Measles</p>\n<p>Rubella</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>E</td>\n<td>\n<p>BCG</p>\n<p>HPV</p>\n<p>Japanese encephalitis(inactivated)</p>\n<p>Tetanus, TD, Td</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>F</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hepatitis B</p>\n<p>Hib(freeze-dried)</p>\n<p>Meningococcal A</p>\n<p>Pneumococcal</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Vaccine <strong>sensitivity to freezing</strong>:</p>\n<p><strong>Rotavirus(liquid)</strong>&lt; T,DT,dT&lt; IPV &lt; Hib(liquid)&lt; HepB &lt; Pentavalent &lt;<strong>DTaP</strong></p>\n<p>Vaccines not damaged by freezing:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Yellow fever</li>\n<li>BCG</li>\n<li>Hib</li>\n<li>Japanese encephalitis(live and inactivated)</li>\n<li>Measles, mumps, rubella</li>\n<li>OPV</li>\n<li>Rabies</li>\n<li>Rotavirus(Freeze-dried)</li>\n<li>Varicella zoster</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/c7bd80ca927b42bcb0956bc12ae146b7x956x717.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(988, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0688. Herd Immunity', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Herd immunity is the <strong>level of protection of a community</strong> against a particular disease brought about by vaccination or immunization.</li>\n<li>It refers to group protection beyond what is afforded by the protection of immunized individuals.</li>\n<li>It is difficult to maintain the chain of infection if a large portion of the population is immune to a certain disease.</li>\n<li>Elements which contribute to herd immunity are:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Occurrence</strong> of clinical and sub-clinical infection in the herd</li>\n<li><strong>Immunization</strong> of the herd</li>\n<li>Herd <strong>structure</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The <strong>herd structure</strong> not only includes the primary species but also the presence and distribution of alternative animal hosts, vectors and other environmental/social factors that are related to disease spread.</li>\n<li>It is <strong>not possible or necessary</strong> to achieve 100% herd immunity in a population.</li>\n<li>The proportion of immune individuals above which a disease may no longer spread is called <strong>herd immunity threshold</strong>.</li>\n<li>This threshold depends upon the virulence of the disease, efficacy of the vaccine and contact parameter for the population.</li>\n<li>Herd immunity is determined by <strong>serological surveys.</strong></li>\n<li>Herd immunity doesn’t offer protection against diseases like tetanus.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(989, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0507. Investigation of an Epidemic', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>A) <strong>Steps</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Verification</strong> of diagnosis</li>\n<li>Confirmation of <strong>existence</strong> of epidemic</li>\n<li>Defining the <strong>population at risk</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Obtaining a map of the area</li>\n<li>Counting the population</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Rapid <strong>search</strong> for all the cases\n<ul>\n<li>Medical survey</li>\n<li>Epidemiological case sheets</li>\n<li>Searching for more cases</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Data analysis</strong> on the basis of time, place and person</li>\n<li>Formulation of <strong>hypothesis</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Testing </strong>of hypothesis</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluation </strong>of ecological factors</li>\n<li>Further investigation of population at risk</li>\n<li>Writing the <strong>report</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>B) <strong>Final Epidemic Report</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Background</strong> including geography, climate, demography, socio-economic groups, health service organization, surveillance data and normal disease prevalence</li>\n<li><strong>Historical data</strong> including previous occurrences of the epidemic, occurrence of any related diseases and discovery of the primary case in present outbreak</li>\n<li><strong>Methodology of investigations</strong> including case definition, epidemiological questionnaires, collection and laboratory techniques</li>\n<li><strong>Analysis of data</strong> including clinical and epidemiological data, modes of transmission, laboratory data and all their interpretations</li>\n<li><strong>Control measures</strong> including strategy definitions, methodology of implementation, evaluation methods and preventive measures</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(990, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0357. Uses of Epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>To study the <strong>rise and fall</strong> of disease in populations</li>\n<li><strong>Community diagnosis</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Planning</strong> and <strong>evaluation</strong></li>\n<li>Evaluation of individual’s <strong>risks and chances</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Syndrome</strong> identification</li>\n<li>Completing the <strong>natural history</strong> of disease</li>\n<li>Searching for <strong>causes and risk factors</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(991, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0350. Meta-analysis in Research', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Meta-analysis</strong> is a set of <strong>statistical techniques</strong> for combining <strong>quantitative results</strong> from multiple studies to produce a summary <strong>of empirical knowledge</strong> on a given topic.</li>\n<li>It refers to a method of systematic review.</li>\n<li>It is one of the most relevant methods in evidence-based medicine and ranks high on the evidence pyramid.</li>\n<li>Limitations\n<ul>\n<li>When testing is done before hypothesis generation, spurious results are found.</li>\n<li>Sample size may be misrepresentative.</li>\n<li>Publication bias due to suppression of some important information leading to <strong>file drawer effect</strong>.</li>\n<li>Heterogeneity of studies may force mashing together of disparate effects and lead to selection bias. This is also called <strong>apples and oranges effect.</strong></li>\n<li>Dissimilarities in control groups.</li>\n<li>Its <strong>validity</strong> is dependent on the <strong>quality of the systematic review</strong> and the original data used.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(992, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0349. Systematic Review in Research', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>A <strong>systematic review</strong> is the process of <strong>locating and synthesizing</strong> the research on a <strong>particular question</strong> using organized, transparent, and replicable procedures.</li>\n<li>It ranks <strong>high</strong> in the hierarchy of <strong>evidence</strong> in medicine.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Steps of a Systematic Review</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/8250c0995fa04120bc2944ae1b5d75fax1280x781.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>The research <strong>question</strong> formulated is always <strong>focussed</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>literature on studies</strong> is always found and appraised after criteria of eligibility are established.</li>\n<li>Meta-analysis is usually done in a systematic review but <strong>not always</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(993, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0348. Evidence Pyramid in Research', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The <strong>evidence pyramid</strong> gives the hierarchy or ranking of evidence from different types of methods used in research.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/0b73c37494284c61abab265d4c8b9acax1280x1603.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Animal research ranks the lowest, while <strong>meta-analysis</strong> ranks the highest and gives the best evidence.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(994, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0301. Randomized Controlled Trials', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Randomized controlled trials</strong> are a type of <strong>experimental studies</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Types</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Clinical trials</li>\n<li>Preventive trials</li>\n<li>Risk factor trials</li>\n<li>Cessation experiments</li>\n<li>Trial of etiological agents</li>\n<li>Evaluation of health services</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>General Design of an RCT</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b18b067a5846405b95d6bb11b2e1546fx1280x1482.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Steps of an RCT</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drawing up a <strong>protocol</strong></li>\n<li>Selecting <strong>reference and experimental</strong> population</li>\n<li><strong>Randomization</strong></li>\n<li>Manipulation or <strong>intervention</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Follow-up</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Assessment</strong> of outcome.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(995, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0300. Blinding in Epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Blinding</strong> is done in epidemiology to <strong>reduce</strong> the possibility of <strong>bias</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Types:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>In <strong>single blind trials</strong>, only the <strong>participants or group members</strong> are not aware of the group allocation.</li>\n<li>In <strong>double blind trials</strong>, both the <strong>group members </strong>and the<strong> observers</strong> are not aware of the group allocation.</li>\n<li>In <strong>triple blind trials</strong>, the <strong>group members, the observers </strong>and the <strong>analyzers</strong> are unaware of the group allocation.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The <strong>most commonly</strong> used type of blinding is <strong>double blinding.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(996, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0269. Relative and Attributable Risk', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Relative Risk:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ratio of incidence of disease or death among exposed to that among the non-exposed is called <strong>relative risk (RR).</strong></li>\n<li>It is also called <strong>risk ratio</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f8f2d7bcf01a465699a42d1a750c87b8x1280x704.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>It is the direct measure of the&nbsp;<strong>strength of association</strong> between suspected cause and effect in <strong>cohort studies</strong>.</li>\n<li>RR &lt; 1 indicates inverse association(protective effect)</li>\n<li>RR = 1 indicates no association.</li>\n<li>RR &gt; 1 indicates positive association.</li>\n<li>RR of 2 indicates a 100% increase in risk.</li>\n<li>Relative risk calculation (RR) = [ a/(a+b) ]/ [ c/(c+d) ] where,&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<table width=\237\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td colspan=\3\>Cancer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\3\>Exposure</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>yes</td>\n<td>no</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>yes</td>\n<td>a</td>\n<td>b</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>no</td>\n<td>c</td>\n<td>d</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Attributable Risk:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Attributable risk (AR)</strong> is the <strong>difference</strong> in incidence rates or proportions of disease or death between an exposed and non-exposed group.</li>\n<li>It is expressed in <strong>percentage</strong> and gives the extent to which the disease can be attributed to the exposure in a <strong>cohort study.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e22f0ba149fb4a2786d73446fd23c180x902x260.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(997, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0268. Cohort Study', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>A <strong>cohort study</strong> progresses from <strong>cause</strong> (exposure) <strong>to effect</strong> (disease).</li>\n<li>It is also known as <strong>forward-looking </strong>study, <strong>incidence </strong>study,<strong> prospective </strong>study, and<strong> longitudinal </strong>study.</li>\n<li><strong>Design of a cohort study:</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/2ea236bdd083460eaa50179f47f0948dx1280x1373.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Types of cohort study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Prospective (concurrent) cohort studies</li>\n<li>Retrospective (historical) cohort studies</li>\n<li>Combination cohort studies</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Steps of cohort study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Selection of study subjects</li>\n<li>Obtaining data on exposure</li>\n<li>Selection of comparison groups</li>\n<li>Follow-up</li>\n<li>Analysis in terms of incidence rates and estimation of risk</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Advantages of cohort study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Incidence can be calculated</li>\n<li>Several possible outcomes related to exposure can be studied at the same time</li>\n<li>Provides direct estimate of relative risk</li>\n<li>Calculation of dose-response ratio</li>\n<li>Minimization of certain biases</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Disadvantages of cohort study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Cannot use for uncommon diseases</li>\n<li>Expensive, requires a large population and&nbsp;longer time</li>\n<li>Many common administrative and ethical problems</li>\n<li>High attrition and selection of subjects is difficult</li>\n<li>Dynamism of diagnostics is difficult to incorporate</li>\n<li>Tends to alter the behaviour of subjects known as&nbsp;<strong>Hawthorne effect</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(998, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0267. Odds Ratio', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Odds ratio is a measure of the <strong>strength of association</strong> between<strong> risk factor</strong> and <strong>outcome</strong> in case control studies.</li>\n<li>Odds ratio can be arrived at from <strong>case control studies</strong>.</li>\n<li>It is also known as <strong>cross product ratio</strong>.</li>\n<li>A representation of the odds ratio <strong>(OR) </strong>is given in the picture below:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Calculation of odds ratio (OR) = (a/b)/(c/d) = ad/bc where,&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td colspan=\3\>Cancer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\3\>Exposure</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>a</td>\n<td>b</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>No</td>\n<td>c</td>\n<td>d</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>OR &lt; 1</strong> indicates <strong>possible protection</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>negative</strong> association) as the frequency of exposure is lower among cases than controls.</li>\n<li><strong>OR = 1&nbsp;</strong>indicates <strong>no association</strong> of risk with exposure, or that the event is equally likely in both groups.</li>\n<li><strong>OR &gt; 1</strong> indicates <strong>increased risk</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>positive</strong> association) as the frequency of exposure is greater among cases than controls.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(999, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0266. Bias in Epidemiological Studies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type of Bias</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Definition</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Methods to reduce it</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Observer bias</td>\n<td>Differential ability to observe. A <strong>subjective</strong> bias.</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Interviewers bias</td>\n<td>Interviewer asking <strong>leading questions</strong> to the subjects. Or interviewing cases thoroughly than the controls.</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Double blinding</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Memory/ <strong>Recall</strong> bias</td>\n<td>Differential ability of cases and controls <strong>to recall</strong> a certain detail. An <strong>objective</strong> bias.</td>\n<td>Decrease time from exposure to follow-up</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Surveillance bias</td>\n<td>Active surveillance leads to an <strong>increased chance</strong> of <strong>identifying</strong> the event.</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Reporting/ notification bias</td>\n<td>Diseases associated with <strong>stigma</strong> are <strong>reported less.</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Berkesonian</strong> bias</td>\n<td><strong>Hospital-based case-control studies.</strong> Occurs due to differential hospital admission rates.</td>\n<td>\n<p>Randomization or Matching&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Selection bias</td>\n<td>A <strong>sampling bias.</strong> Non-random allocation of subjects that do not represent the population</td>\n<td>Randomization or Matching</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hawthorne</strong> bias</td>\n<td><strong>Change</strong> in <strong>attitude/</strong> actions of the subjects under <strong>observation</strong></td>\n<td>Use placebo group</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Confounding</strong> bias</td>\n<td><strong>Factors related</strong> to <strong>both exposure</strong> and <strong>outcome</strong> distort the effect of exposure on outcome</td>\n<td>Matching, cross-over studies, randomization, or stratification</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Attrition bias</td>\n<td>Participants <strong>lost to follow-up</strong> have a different prognosis than those who complete the study.</td>\n<td>Randomization</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pygmalion bias</td>\n<td><strong>Researchers</strong> high <strong>expectations</strong> in the efficacy of the treatment <strong>change</strong> the <strong>outcome</strong> of that treatment.</td>\n<td>Blinding</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Neymans/</strong> Prevalence-Incidence bias&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Occurs due to the <strong>selective survival</strong> in <strong>prevalent cases</strong> usually seen in <strong>fatal diseases.</strong> Very sick patients are automatically excluded because of their early death.</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Neyman’s</strong> bias or prevalence-incidence bias example: a case-control study is carried out to study the relationship between tobacco smoking and acute myocardial infarction (AMI). The cases are interviewed one week after the coronary attack. If smoker patients with AMI die more frequently, the living cases will show a lower frequency of smoking, undervaluing the association between smoking and AMI. It has been shown that the bias occurs only if the risk factor influences mortality from the disease being studied.</p>\n<p><strong>Ecological fallacy</strong> results when characteristics of the group are assigned inappropriately to individuals.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1000, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0265. Case Control Study', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>In a <strong>case-control</strong> study, progression is from <strong>effect </strong>(disease) to<strong> cause</strong>&nbsp;(exposure) as the outcome or disease has already occurred. It is also called a&nbsp;<strong>retrospective</strong> study.</p>\n<p><strong>Design </strong>of case-control study:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/54361314f5e0423d9bef0e4acae144a0x1280x1242.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Steps of case control study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Selection of cases and controls</li>\n<li>Matching</li>\n<li>Measurement of exposure</li>\n<li>Analysis in the form of exposure rates, risk ratio, and odds ratio</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Advantages of case control study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Easy to carry out, rapid and inexpensive</li>\n<li>Requires few subjects, no risk to subjects</li>\n<li>Used to investigate rare diseases</li>\n<li>Different etiological factors can be studied and risk factors can be identified</li>\n<li>No attrition problems, minimal ethical problems</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Disadvantages&nbsp;of case control study:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Relies on memory or past records giving rise to bias</li>\n<li>Selection of appropriate control groups is difficult</li>\n<li>Incidence cannot be measured</li>\n<li>Does not distinguish between causes and associated factors</li>\n<li>Not suited for evaluation of therapy or prophylaxis</li>\n<li>Representativeness of the cases and controls is often inadequate</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1001, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0254. Levels of Prevention', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Level</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Primordial</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Primary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Secondary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Tertiary</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Phase of disease</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Underlying socio-economic &amp; environmental conditions leading to causation</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Specific causal or risk factors</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Early stage of disease</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Late stage of disease</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Aim</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Establish and maintain conditions that minimize hazards to health</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Reduce the incidence of disease</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Reduce prevalence by shortening duration</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Reduce number and impact of complications</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Actions</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Inhibition of emergence of socio-economic, environmental and behavioural conditions</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Protection of personal and community health by eliminating risks</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Early detection and intervention to minimize disability</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Soften the impact of long-term disease and disability, minimize suffering</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Modes of Intervention</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Health education</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Health promotion and specific protection</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Diagnosis and treatment</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Disability limitation and rehabilitation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Targets</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Total population or select groups</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Total population or high risk individuals/groups</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Individuals/ Patients</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Patients</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1002, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0253. Sentinel  Surveillance', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Sentinel surveillance</strong> is used to augment the notification systems used in surveillance of diseases.</li>\n<li>It detects the total case load and is used to identify the missing cases that are not notified among the old and new cases.</li>\n<li><strong>Sentinel data</strong> from the same is extrapolated to the entire population and the prevalence can be commented on.</li>\n<li>Advantages: <strong>Bias </strong>in reporting is <strong>minimized</strong> and the <strong>feedback</strong> is simplified.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1003, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0252. Monitoring vs. Surveillance in Disease Control', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>Monitoring</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>Surveillance</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Performance and analysis of routine measurements aimed at detecting changes in environment or health status of a population.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Continuous scrutiny of the factors that determine the occurrence and distribution of disease and other conditions of ill-health.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>One-time <strong>linear activity</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>Continuous cycle</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>No feedback</strong> present</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Feedback present</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>No inbuilt action component present</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>Inbuilt action</strong> component present</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Stops once disease is eliminated or eradicated</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p><strong>Continuous</strong> even after disease is eliminated or eradicated</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Smaller concept</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>Broader concept</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>It is a&nbsp;<strong>part of surveillance</strong>.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\301\>\n<p>It is not a part of monitoring.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1004, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0234. Epidemics and its Types', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>An epidemic is an occurrence in a community or region of cases of an illness that is clearly in <strong>excess of normal expectancy</strong>. Its types include:</p>\n<p><strong>Common source epidemics</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Single exposure or point source epidemics</li>\n<li>Multiple or continuous exposure epidemics</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Propagated or progressive epidemics</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Person to person</li>\n<li>Arthropod vector</li>\n<li>Animal reservoir</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Slow or modern epidemics</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Non-communicable diseases</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1005, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0233. Descriptive Epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Descriptive Epidemiology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Descriptive studies are used to describe a disease of <strong>unknown etiology</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Steps</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Defining the <strong>population</strong> to be studied</li>\n<li>Defining the <strong>disease</strong> to be studied</li>\n<li>Describing the disease by <strong>time, place, and person</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Measurement</strong> of the disease by <strong>cross sectional or longitudinal study</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Comparing</strong> with known <strong>indices</strong></li>\n<li>Formulation of an <strong>etiological</strong> <strong>hypothesis</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Uses</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Provides data of <strong>magnitude</strong> of disease load in community</li>\n<li>Provides <strong>clues to disease etiology</strong></li>\n<li>Provides background data for <strong>health planning</strong></li>\n<li>Contributes to <strong>research</strong> by describing the disease</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1006, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0231. Types of Epidemiological Study Designs', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Types of Epidemiological Study Designs</strong></p>\n<p>The flow chart below gives a glance into the types of epidemiological study designs and where they are generally used.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Descripitve study</strong> is used to <strong>formulate</strong> aetiological hypothesis of a disease. Whereas <strong>analytical study</strong> is used to <strong>test</strong> the hypothesis (i.e to accept or reject the hypothesis).</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/8bf47c838ad64276ab706c700cc1758cx1280x2995.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1007, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0230. Morbidity Measurements in Epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/5e17c2ec999e4412beacae58dadc5ea4x1280x1933.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1008, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0228. Incidence and Prevalence', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Incidence</strong>&nbsp;<strong>in Epidemiology:</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Incidence</strong> is the number of <strong>new</strong> <strong>cases</strong> occurring in a defined population during a period of time. The incidence rate is expressed in <strong>person-time</strong> units, usually per 1000 per year.&nbsp;It is given by the following formula:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/95992ed7fcdb46f682474bb07d7e3dcfx501x77.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>It is generally used for <strong>acute illnesses.&nbsp;</strong>It provides insight into the <strong>effectiveness of health services and programs.&nbsp;</strong>Incidence can be determined from <strong>cohort studies and longitudinal studies.</strong></p>\n<p>The incidence rate of <strong>spells of sickness</strong> = &nbsp;(Number of spells of sickness starting in the specified period/Mean number of people exposed to that risk in the specified time) x <strong>1000.</strong></p>\n<p>Special types of incidence rates:</p>\n<p>1.<strong> Attack rate: </strong>It is used when there is a risk for a limited period of time.</p>\n<p>2.<strong> Secondary attack rate: </strong>It is the number of exposed persons developing the disease within the range of incubation period following exposure to a primary case.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevalence in Epidemiology:</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Prevalence is the proportion of all cases, <strong>old and new</strong>, of a particular disease at a given point in time or over a period of time in a given population. It is a <strong>proportion,</strong> not a rate or ratio.&nbsp;Prevalence is always expressed in <strong>percentage.</strong></p>\n<p>It is given by the formula:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/6746ce2989d64d339e4454605f41cde0x520x80.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>It is useful to determine the <strong>magnitude </strong>of health problems.&nbsp;It can be determined from <strong>cross-sectional studies.</strong></p>\n<p>Types:</p>\n<p>1. <strong>Point </strong>prevalence is the prevalence at a point in time. Usually, prevalence is point prevalence unless <strong>otherwise specified</strong>.</p>\n<p>2. <strong>Period</strong> prevalence is the prevalence over a period of time.</p>\n<p><strong>Relationship</strong> between<strong> Incidence</strong> and<strong> Prevalence:</strong></p>\n<p>Prevalence depends upon <strong>incidence and duration</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Prevalence</strong> = <strong>Incidence x Mean Duration</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Longer the duration</strong> of the disease, the greater the prevalence.</p>\n<p>Few examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>In acute diseases, because of rapid recovery/death prevalence will be relatively&nbsp;<strong>lower</strong> than incidence. This is because, in some diseases (eg. food poisoning), the disease is so short-lived, there are no \old cases\.</li>\n<li>In chronic diseases like TB, prevalence will be <strong>higher</strong> than incidence.</li>\n<li>If a new treatment for a disease is effective, incidence does not change but <strong>prevalence decreases</strong> as the duration of disease decreases.</li>\n<li>If the treatment only prevents death but doesn’t cure the disease, it may cause a <strong>paradoxical increase</strong> in prevalence.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1009, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0225. Standardization of Rates in Epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p class=\heading\>Standardization of rates is done to allow for comparison of health statuses of two populations after adjustments for age, sex, etc. using a <strong>standard population.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>A) Direct Standardization:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Direct method uses <strong>actual age-specific</strong> death rates on <strong>standard population</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Concept</strong> is summarized by the given diagram:</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/70dcfc8c37c74afdb6759c7cb7ee6f17x1280x1097.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>It is feasible only if actual specific rates in subgroups of the observed population are available, along with number of people in each subgroup.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>B) <strong>Indirect Standardization</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Indirect method uses <strong>standard age-specific</strong> death rates on <strong>actual population.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Concept </strong>is summarized by the given diagram:</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/8f7182d47ddc46d99cd8bed41f711368x1280x1373.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>One form of this is called the&nbsp;<strong>Standardized Mortality Ratio</strong>.\n<ul>\n<li>It is a ratio of the total number of deaths that occur in the study group to the number of deaths that would have been expected to occur if that study group had experienced the death rates of a standard population.</li>\n<li>It is given as&nbsp;<strong>x 100</strong>.</li>\n<li>If the value is <strong>&gt;100</strong>, then greater mortality risk and if the value is <strong>&lt;100</strong>, lesser risk.</li>\n<li>It does not need known specific rates for adjustment, unlike the direct method.</li>\n<li>It can be used if the event of interest is the occurrence of disease rather than death.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Other indirect methods are <strong>life table analysis, regression techniques and multivariate analysis.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1010, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0216. Case Fatality Rate', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Case fatality rate </strong>=&nbsp;&nbsp;(Total number of deaths due to a particular disease)/(Total number of cases due to the same disease)x 100</li>\n<li>It is a good indicator of <strong>severity or killing power</strong> of a disease.</li>\n<li>It is used mostly in <strong>acute and infectious diseases.</strong></li>\n<li>No time interval is used.</li>\n<li>Case fatality rate is closely related to <strong>virulence</strong>.</li>\n<li>Limitation of CFR is that its usefulness for chronic diseases is limited because the period from onset to death is variable.</li>\n<li>It is expressed in <strong>percentage</strong>.</li>\n<li>CFR is an <strong>incidence proportion</strong> and not a true rate.</li>\n<li>CFR may vary for the same disease in different epidemics.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Case fatality of a few diseases:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rabies - 100% especially after symptoms manifest</li>\n<li>Ebola - 25 to 90%, average - 50%&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Yellow fever - 15 to 50%</li>\n<li>Chicken pox - 0.001%</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Diseases with a high case fatality rate: Tetanus, Rabies, Botulism, Ebola.</li>\n<li>Diseases with a low case fatality rate: Leprosy, Trachoma, Lymphatic filariasis.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1011, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0213. Mortality and morbidity indicators in epidemiology', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Mortality Indicators</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Morbidity Indicators</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Universal indicators:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Crude death rate</li>\n<li>Life expectancy</li>\n<li>Age-specific death rates</li>\n<li>Disease-specific mortality rate</li>\n<li>Proportional mortality rate</li>\n<li>Case fatality rate</li>\n<li>Years of potential life lost</li>\n<li>Adult mortality rate</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Maternal and child-related indicators:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Infant mortality rate</li>\n<li>Child death rate</li>\n<li>Under-5 proportionate mortality rate</li>\n<li>Maternal mortality rate</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Incidence and Prevalence</li>\n<li>Notification rates</li>\n<li>Attendance rates at OPD</li>\n<li>Admission, discharge &amp; re-admission rates</li>\n<li>Duration of stay in hospital</li>\n<li>Spells of sickness or absence from work or school</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/be7a147091124fdc8afea68390904d96x1280x2327.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1012, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0212. WHO Format for International Death Certificate', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/fb295bd091194819a13f5d892b2e51a3x1280x1444.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1013, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0211. Rate, Ratio and Proportion', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Rate</strong>:\n<ul>\n<li>It measures the occurrence of a particular event in a population in a given time.</li>\n<li>It consists of a <strong>numerator, denominator, time specification</strong> and <strong>multiplier</strong>.</li>\n<li>Numerator is often part of the denominator.</li>\n<li>Examples: Crude death rate, incidence rate.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ratio:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>It expresses a relation in size between two random quantities.</li>\n<li>It consists of only <strong>numerator and denominator </strong>and no time specification.</li>\n<li>The numerator is <strong>not</strong> part of the denominator.</li>\n<li>Examples: sex ratio, doctor-population ratio.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Proportion:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>It is a ratio that indicates the relation in magnitude of a part of a whole.</li>\n<li>The numerator is <strong>always</strong> part of the denominator.</li>\n<li>Proportions are usually expressed as <strong>percentage</strong> and it is often measured at a <strong>point in time.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e92a84967e2547a5bd4cc7edb66c6097x1258x1128.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1014, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2387. Cut-off points in diagnostic tests', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/77956c061f8a417f980dc92fa3b56592x1199x1136.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Highly <strong>sensitive</strong> test, when <strong>negative</strong>, <strong>rules out</strong> a disease. <strong>(Screening test)</strong></li>\n<li>Highly <strong>specific</strong> test, when <strong>positive</strong>, <strong>rules in</strong> a disease. <strong>(Confirmatory test)</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/fd3edf675b3f4e30a140e2ff769dc087x1200x1109.JPEG\><img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/94e48ae863c74fbea0b8bfed13733accx1280x1199.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Sensitivity</strong> (True-positive rate): High sensitivity indicates low false-negative rate.</p>\n<p><strong>Specificity</strong>&nbsp;(True-negative rate): High specificity indicates low false-positive rate.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1015, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0362. Repeatability of a Screening Test', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Repeatability</strong> is an attribute of an ideal screening test. It is also called <strong>reliability, precision, or reproducibility.&nbsp;</strong>It implies that the test must give consistent results when repeated on the same individual or material, under the same conditions.</p>\n<p>It depends upon three factors:</p>\n<p><strong>A</strong>. <strong>Observer variation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>All observations are subjected to variations.</li>\n<li><strong>Intra-observer </strong>variations or within-observer variations are when a single observer takes <strong>two measurements</strong> in the <strong>same subject,</strong> at the same time and obtained <strong>two different results</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Inter-observer </strong>variations or between-observer variations are when <strong>two different observers</strong> obtain <strong>different results</strong> on the <strong>same subject</strong> or material.</li>\n<li>They are minimized by <strong>standardization</strong> of procedures, intensive <strong>training</strong> of observers, and making use of <strong>more observers</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>B. Biological variation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is also called <strong>subject</strong> variation.</li>\n<li>They are due to <strong>changes&nbsp;in the parameters</strong> observed, variations in the <strong>perceptions of symptoms</strong> by patients, and <strong>regression to the mean </strong>where there is a tendency of values to be at either extreme of the distribution.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>C</strong>. Errors relating to <strong>technical methods </strong>is&nbsp;due to the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Defective instruments</li>\n<li>Erroneous calibration</li>\n<li>Faulty reagents</li>\n<li>Incorrect methods</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1016, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0361. Lead Time in Screening', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Lead time is the period between the <strong>first possible</strong> <strong>time</strong> of detection and the <strong>usual time</strong> of diagnosis.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b6e8bf826a364c7abb0006bc098eef63x1280x1020.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Lead time is the advantage gained by screening. It helps in the early diagnosis and treatment of disease. Early treatment reduces the severity by reversing the disease process.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1017, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0358. Validity of a Screening Test', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Validity/ accuracy </strong>of a screening test depends upon the <strong>sensitivity, specificity,</strong> and<strong> predictive accuracy</strong> of the test.</li>\n<li>It represents the closeness to a true value/ actual value.</li>\n<li>These are the <strong>inherent properties</strong> of a screening test.</li>\n<li>P<strong>P</strong>V and N<strong>P</strong>V are <strong>dependent</strong> on the <strong>P</strong>revalence of disease.</li>\n<li>Sensitivity &amp; Specificity are independent of prevalence of disease.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/62275b1d441443bc92db11bb3add523ex1280x959.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Formulae</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Sensitivity</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>TP</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span><br><span><strong>TP</strong> + FN</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Specificity</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>TN&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></span><sub><br></sub>FP + <strong>TN</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Predictive value of a positive test (<strong>P</strong>PV)</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;T<strong>P&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></span><sub><br></sub>T<strong>P</strong> + F<strong>P</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Predictive value of a negative test (<strong>N</strong>PV)</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;T<strong>N&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;</span><sub><br></sub>T<strong>N</strong> + F<strong>N</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Percentage of false positives</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;FP&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span><sub><br></sub>FP + TN</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Percentage of false negatives</span></td>\n<td><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;FN&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span><sub><br></sub>TP + FN</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>PPV</strong> varies <strong>directly</strong> with prevalence</li>\n<li><strong>NPV</strong> varies <strong>inversely</strong> with prevalence</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1018, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0356. Hills Criteria for Causal Association', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>It is also called <strong>Bradford Hill criteria.</strong></li>\n<li>It was established in 1965 by English epidemiologist, <strong>Sir Austin Bradford Hill.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Criteria</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p><strong>Brief Description</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Temporality</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>Suspected cause precedes observed effect.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Strength</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>Larger the relative risk, the more likely it is causal.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Consistency</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>If the association is observed repeatedly under the same or various conditions, then more likely it is causation.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Specificity</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>When exposure is associated with a specific outcome only, then it is more likely to be causal.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Plausibility</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>A biologically plausible mechanism between cause and effect can be support for causation.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Coherence</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>A causal conclusion should not seriously conflict with the present substantive knowledge of the outcome.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Analogy</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>Other established cause-effect relationships may be used in analogies to support this causal relationship.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Gradient</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>It is called dose-response or response curve. It refers to the existence of an exposure-response relationship.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\163\>\n<p><strong>Experiment</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\357\>\n<p>To check if the condition can be or has been changed, weakened or prevented by experimental approach.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1019, 'Medicine,', 'PM2303. NACO ART Guidelines- 2021', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table class=\t1\ cellspacing=\0\ cellpadding=\0\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<p class=\p1\>ART regimen</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<p class=\p1\>First-line for:</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<p class=\p1\>Tenofovir + Lamivudine + Dolutegravir</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<ul>\n<li>All PLHIV who are<strong> age &gt;10 years and body weight &gt;30 kg&nbsp;</strong>with <strong>HIV-1, HIV-2, HIV 1&amp;2 co-infection</strong>&nbsp;who have not received any ART&nbsp;</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Those with <strong>HIV-TB and HIV hepatitis co-infections</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\><strong>Pregnant women</strong>, pregnant women presenting in <strong>active labour</strong> and <strong>breastfeeding women</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<p class=\p1\>Abacavir + Lamivudine + Efavirenz</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>All PLHIV with <strong>abnormal serum creatinine</strong> values&nbsp;</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>All PLHIV with <strong>bodyweight less &lt;30 kg</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<p class=\p1\>Tenofovir + Lamivudine + Efavirenz /Lopinavir /Ritonavir</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\td1\ valign=\top\>\n<ul>\n<li>Women of childbearing age group who do not wish to take Dolutegravir</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p1\>All PLHIV who were on the previous recommended regime&nbsp;(Tenofovir+Lamivudine+Efavirenz) to be counselled to switch to new regime. Continue older regime if response is good</li>\n<li class=\p1\>Women in child-bearing age group to be counselled about Dolutegravir with opt-out option before switching to new regime</li>\n</ul>\n<p>*PLHIV: People living with HIV</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1020, 'Medicine,', 'PM2302. Opportunistic Infections/HIV related conditions and ART initiation', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Clinical scenario</td>\n<td>Action&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Any undiagnosed active infection with fever</td>\n<td>Diagnose and treat first; start Anti-Retroviral Therapy (ART) when stable</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tuberculosis (TB)</td>\n<td>Start TB treatment first; start ART as soon as possible after 2 weeks and before 2 months. For those with CD4 less than 50/cmm, start ART within 2 weeks Caution is needed for PLHIV with TB meningitis, since immediate ART is associated with more severe adverse events than initiating ART 2 months after the start of TB treatment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Pneumocystis pneumonia (PCP)</p>\n</td>\n<td>Treat PCP first; start ART when PCP treatment is completed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Invasive fungal diseases: Oesophageal candidiasis, penicilliosis, histoplasmosis</td>\n<td>Start treatment for oesophageal candidiasis first; start ART as soon as the patient can swallow comfortably. Treat penicilliosis, and histoplasmosis first; start ART when the patient is stabilized or opportunistic infection treatment is completed.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cryptococcal meningitis</td>\n<td>Treat cryptococcal meningitis. ART initiation should be deferred until there is evidence of sustained clinical response to anti-fungal therapy and after 4 weeks of induction and consolidation treatment with amphotericin B containing regimen.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bacterial pneumonia</td>\n<td>Treat pneumonia first; start ART when treatment is completed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Malaria</td>\n<td>Treat malaria first; start ART when treatment is completed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acute diarrhoea which may reduce absorption of ART</td>\n<td>Diagnose the cause and treat diarrhoea first; start ART when diarrhoea is stabilized or controlled</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Non-severe anaemia (Hb&lt; 9 g/dl)</td>\n<td>Start ART if no other causes for anaemia are found (HIV is often the cause of anaemia)&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Skin conditions such as PPE and seborrhoeic dermatitis, psoriasis, HIV-related exfoliative dermatitis</td>\n<td>Start ART (ART may resolve these problems)&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Suspected Mycobacterium Avium Complex (MAC), Cryptosporidiosis and Microsporidiosis</td>\n<td>Start ART (ART may resolve these problems)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cytomegalovirus retinitis</td>\n<td>Start treatment for CMV urgently and start ART after 2 weeks of CMV treatment&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Toxoplasmosis</td>\n<td>Treat toxoplasmosis; start ART after 6 weeks of treatment and when the patient is stabilized</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1021, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2192. Measles vaccine', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Measles vaccine:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Type: Live attenuenated, lyophilized (freeze dried), vaccine (Tissue culture vaccine- chick embryo or Human diploid cell line).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Strains used: 1. Edmonston Zagreb strain (most common).&nbsp;</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2. Schwartz strain.</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 3. Moraten strain.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Dose: 0.5ml.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Route: Subcutaneous.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Site: Right arm (usually).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Age of administration in National immunization schedule (India): 9 months (can be lowered to 6-9 months in epidemics and malnutrition) and 16-24 months.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Diluent for reconstitution: Distilled water or sterile water. (To be used within 4 hours after reconstitutuion).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Measles (and MMR) vaccine can lead to Toxic shock syndrome.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Measles vaccine is contraindicated in pregnancy.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Cold chain temperature for storage: +2 to +8 degree Celcius.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Protective efficacy: &gt;90% with one dose; &gt;99% with two doses.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Duration of protection: Life long.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>IP of vaccine induced measles: 7 days.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Ideal gap between two successive doses: 6 months.</p>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1022, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2084. Malarial parameters', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Malarial parameters:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Parameter</td>\n<td>Formula</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Annual Parasite Incidence</td>\n<td>\n<p>Confirmed cases in one year</p>\n<p>-----------------------------------×1000<br>Population under surveillance</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Annual Blood Examination Rate</td>\n<td>\n<p>Number of slides examined</p>\n<p>-----------------------------------×100 <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Population</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Slide positivity Rate</td>\n<td>Percentage of slides found positive irrespective of species</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Slide Falciparum Rate</td>\n<td>Percentage of slides positive for <em>P. falciparum</em></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1023, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2045. Periods of Isolation for Selected Diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong class=\ng-binding\> Periods of Isolation for Selected Diseases</strong></p>\n<div class=\panel-body ng-scope\>\n<p class=\ng-binding ng-scope\>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p><strong>Disease</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p><strong>Duration of Isolation</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Chickenpox</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until all lesions are crusted – usually about 6 days after onset of rash.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Measles</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>From the onset of symptoms (catarrhal stage) to 4 days after the appearance of the rash</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Cholera</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until 3 days of tetracycline therapy.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Diphtheria&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until 48 hours of antibiotics.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Shigellosis and salmonellosis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until 3 consecutive negative stool cultures.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Hepatitis A</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>3 weeks.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Influenza</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>3 days after onset.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Polio</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>2 weeks in adult; 6 weeks in children.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Tuberculosis (sputum +)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until 3 weeks of effective chemotherapy.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Herpes zoster</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>6 days after onset of rash.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Mumps</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until the swelling subsides.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Pertussis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>4 weeks or until paroxysms cease.&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Meningococcal meningitis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until the first 24 hours of effective antibiotic therapy.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\211\>\n<p>Streptococcal pharyngitis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\379\>\n<p>Until the first 6 hours of effective antibiotic therapy.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1024, 'Ophthalmology,', 'PM1899. WHO classification of trachoma (FISTO)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>WHO grading of trachoma</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>TF = trachomatous inflammation (<strong>follicular</strong>): <strong>five or more follicles</strong> (&gt;0.5 mm) on the superior tarsal conjunctiva.</li>\n<li>TI = trachomatous inflammation (<strong>intense</strong>): <strong>diffuse involvement</strong> of the tarsal conjunctiva,<strong> obscuring 50% or more</strong> of the normal deep tarsal vessels; <strong>papillae</strong> are present</li>\n<li>TS = trachomatous conjunctival <strong>scarring</strong>: easily visible fibrous <strong>white tarsal bands</strong></li>\n<li>TT = trachomatous<strong> trichiasis</strong>: at least <strong>one lash</strong> touching the globe</li>\n<li>CO = <strong>corneal opacity</strong> sufficient to blur details of at least part of the pupillary margin</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1025, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1779. Ending Cholera—A Global Roadmap to 2030', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>In October 2017, the <strong>WHO</strong> - <strong>Global Task Force on Cholera Control (GTFCC)</strong> has released, <strong>Ending Cholera—A Global Roadmap to 2030.</strong></p>\n<p>By implementing the strategy between 2017 and 2030, the GTFCC partners will support countries to <strong>reduce cholera deaths by 90 percent</strong>.</p>\n<p>The key points of the strategy include:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Early detection and quick response</strong> to contain outbreaks</li>\n<li>A targeted <strong>multi-sectoral approach</strong> to prevent cholera recurrence which includes:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Water, Sanitation &amp; Hygiene: </strong>Implementation of adapted long-term sustainable WASH solutions for populations most at risk of cholera.</li>\n<li><strong>Leadership and Coordination:</strong> &nbsp;Inter-sectoral collaboration and building of a strong preparedness and response strategy.</li>\n<li><strong>Health Care System Strengthening: </strong>Enhanced readiness for cholera outbreaks through capacity building for staff, and prepositioning of resources for diagnostics, patient care, and emergency WASH intervention.</li>\n<li><strong>Surveillance &amp; Reporting: </strong>Implementation of effective routine surveillance and laboratory capacity at the peripheral level to confirm suspected cases, inform the response, and track progress towards control and elimination.</li>\n<li><strong>Use of Oral Cholera Vaccine (OCV): </strong>Large-scale use of OCV is recommended to immediately reduce disease burden while longer-term cholera control strategies are put in place.</li>\n<li><strong>Community Engagement: </strong>By enhancing the communication on cholera control strategies, hygiene promotion, and cholera risk, by mobilizing community leaders as agents of change.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>An effective mechanism of <strong>coordination for technical support</strong>, advocacy, <strong>resource mobilization</strong>, and <strong>partnership</strong> at local and global levels.</li>\n</ol></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1026, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1775. Recommendations - WHO Guidelines for preventive chemotherapy to control soil-transmitted helminth infections in at-risk population groups', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>WHO </strong>has recently in September 2017 has proposed guidelines for preventive chemotherapy (<strong>deworming</strong>) to control soil-transmitted helminth infections in at-risk population groups.</p>\n<p>The main soil-transmitted helminths includes the roundworm (<strong>Ascaris</strong> <strong>lumbricoides</strong>), the whipworm (<strong>Trichuris</strong> <strong>trichiura</strong>) and the hookworms (<strong>Ancylostoma</strong> <strong>duodenale</strong> and <strong>Necator</strong> <strong>americanus</strong>).</p>\n<p>The following table shows various <strong>recommendations:</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Risk group</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Prevalence</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Frequency</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Drugs and Dosage</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Young children, preschool and school-age children</td>\n<td>Any soil-transmitted infection ≥ 20%</td>\n<td>Annual</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>\n<p>Single-dose albendazole (400&nbsp;mg)</p>\n<p>Or</p>\n<p>mebendazole (500&nbsp;mg).&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: A half-dose of albendazole (i.e. 200 mg) is recommended for children 12–23 months of age.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Any soil-transmitted infection &gt; 50%l</td>\n<td>Biannual</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Non-pregnant adolescent girls and non-pregnant women of reproductive age</td>\n<td>Any soil-transmitted infection ≥ 20%</td>\n<td>Annual</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>\n<p>Single-dose albendazole (400&nbsp;mg)</p>\n<p>Or</p>\n<p>mebendazole (500&nbsp;mg).&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Any soil-transmitted infection &gt; 50%</td>\n<td>Biannual</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pregnant women</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hookworm and/or T. trichiura infection ≥20%&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>And</strong></p>\n<p>Anemia ≥ 40%&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Single-dose albendazole (400 mg)</p>\n<p>or</p>\n<p>mebendazole(500 mg)</p>\n<p>in second or third trimester</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1027, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1726. Flea Indices', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>They are useful in measurements of density of fleas.</p>\n<p>They include:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Total flea index</strong> – it is the average number of fleas of all species per rat</li>\n<li><strong>Cheopis index</strong> - it is the average number of <em>Xenopsylla cheopis</em> species per rat,hence it is a <strong>specific flea index</strong>. It indicates the <strong>maximum explosiveness</strong> of the situation</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Specific percentage of fleas</strong> – it is a precentage of different species of fleas that are found on rats.</li>\n<li><strong>Burrow index</strong> – It is the average&nbsp; number of free living flea per species per rodent burrow.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1028, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1725. Rabies vaccines and immunoglobulins schedules', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>According to the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, Government of India:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f49dfa01d9bd424db725e4ebf600cb98x1280x3397.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>WHO category <strong>II</strong> or <strong>III</strong> exposures should receive&nbsp;<strong>post-exposure prophylaxis&nbsp;</strong>(PEP)<strong>&nbsp;immediately.</strong></p>\n<p>One <strong>intradermal&nbsp;</strong>(ID)&nbsp;dose is <strong>0.1 mL</strong> of vaccine and one <strong>intramuscular</strong> (IM) dose is an <strong>entire vial</strong> of vaccine, irrespective of the vial size.</p>\n<p>Should a vaccine dose be delayed for any reason, the PEP schedule should be resumed (not restarted).</p>\n<p><strong>Rabies Immunoglobulin(RIG):&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Passive immunization</li>\n<li><strong>Single-dose</strong>; after initiation of PEP and not beyond 7 days after the first dose of vaccine</li>\n<li>Max dose: <strong>hRIG - 20IU/kg ,&nbsp;</strong><strong>eRIG</strong><strong>&nbsp;- 40IU/kg </strong>body weight</li>\n<li>Vaccines should never be withheld regardless of the availability of RIG.</li>\n<li><strong>Alternatives</strong> for RIG- WHO recommends&nbsp;<strong>m</strong><strong>onoclonal antibodies&nbsp;</strong>(mAb)&nbsp;as a cocktail containing at least <strong>two antibodies</strong> against the rabies virus.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Administration of RIG:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>RIG should be administered&nbsp;<strong>into</strong> or <strong>around</strong> the <strong>wound site</strong> or sites.</li>\n<li>The&nbsp;<strong>remaining</strong> RIG, if any, should be injected <strong>IM</strong> at a site <strong>distant</strong> from the <strong>site</strong> of vaccine administration.</li>\n<li>RIG may be diluted to a volume sufficient for all wounds to be effectively and safely infiltrated.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Prioritization&nbsp;of RIG allocation (numbered according to priority order):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Multiple bites</li>\n<li>Deep wounds</li>\n<li>Bites to head, neck, and hands</li>\n<li>Patients with severe immunodeficiency</li>\n<li>Confirmed/probable rabies in biting animal</li>\n<li>Bites, scratches, and exposure of mucous membranes caused by a bat</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Pre-exposure prophylaxis&nbsp;(PrEP)</strong></p>\n<p>PrEP is considered in the following conditions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>High-risk groups- laboratory staff, wildlife wardens, veterinarians, animal handlers, and travelers to endemic regions.</li>\n<li>Remote, rabies-endemic areas where access to PEP is difficult</li>\n<li>Areas where&nbsp;dog bite incidence is &gt;5% per year</li>\n<li>Areas where vampire bat rabies is known to be present.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Pre-exposure rabies vaccination consists of <strong>3&nbsp;intramuscular (IM) or 3 intradermal (ID)</strong>&nbsp;doses. These are given on <strong>days 0, 7 and 21 or 28.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adults - the vaccine should always be administered in the deltoid area of the arm</li>\n<li>Young children (under 1 year of age)- Administration into the anterolateral area of the thigh is recommended.</li>\n<li><strong>Rabies vaccine </strong>should<strong> never</strong> be administered in the<strong> gluteal area.</strong>&nbsp;Administration in this manner will result in <strong>lower neutralizing antibody titers.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>For exposed or re-exposed patients who can document previous completion of PEP or PrEP the following guidelines would be applicable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Proper wound management should be done.</li>\n<li>There is no need for the administration of RIG.</li>\n<li>One site ID or IM vaccine administration on days 0 and 3.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Only adequate wound washing would be required in case of re-exposure where the animal bite victim has documented proof of complete PEP&nbsp;<strong>within the last three months.</strong></p>\n<p>The following cases are treated as fresh cases and given full PEP:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Those who have previously received full post-exposure treatment with neural tissue vaccines (NTV) or vaccines of unproven potency</li>\n<li>Those who cannot document complete PEP or PrEP treatment&nbsp;</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1029, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1724. Classification of Zoonoses', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Classification <strong>based on their reservoir hosts</strong> into:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Anthropozoonoses</li>\n<li>Zoo-anthroponoses</li>\n<li>Amphixenoses</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Classification based on life cycle if infecting agent is:</strong></p>\n<table width=\726\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Category</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\348\>\n<p><strong>Mode</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p><strong>Example</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Direct zoonoses</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\348\>\n<p><strong>Direct contact/fomite/mechanical vector</strong></p>\n<p>No essential developmental/ propagative changes during transmission.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p>Rabies , Trichinosis, Brucellosis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Cyclo-zoonoses</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\348\>\n<p>More than one <strong>vertebrate</strong> host is needed to complete the developmental cycle. Invertebrate hosts will not suffice.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p>&nbsp;Human taeniasis, Echinococcosis, Pentastomid infections</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Meta-zoonoses</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\348\>\n<p><strong>Transmitted by invertebrate vectors. </strong>Inside the invertebrate, the infective agent <strong>develops / multiplies. </strong>After an extrinsic period of incubation, the infective agent is transmitted to another vertebrate host.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p><strong>Arboviral infections, Plague and Schistosomiasis</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Sapro-zoonoses</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\348\>\n<p>Has <strong>both</strong> a vertebrate host and a non-animal (food, soil/ plants)developmental site/reservoir.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p>Various forms of larva migrants and mycoses</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1030, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1719. Classification of TB Patients Based on History of Treatment', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>New case</strong> is defined as a TB patient who had</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Never taken</strong> ATT previously or</li>\n<li>Taken ATT for <strong>&lt; 1 month</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Previously treated Case :&nbsp;</strong>Patients who have <strong>received 1 month or more</strong> of Anti TB drugs in the past. These include:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Recurrent TB:&nbsp;</strong>A TB patient who <strong>had completed course of treatment</strong> <strong>/ declared cured</strong> and now presenting as microbiologically confirmed case</li>\n<li><strong>Treatment after failure:&nbsp;</strong>Patients who had been treated for TB and <strong>their treatment failed</strong> at the end of most recent course of treatment</li>\n<li><strong>Treatment after loss to follow up:&nbsp;</strong>A TB patient who had <strong>been treated &gt; 1 month on ATT</strong> and registered as l<strong>ost to follow up</strong> and now presenting as microbiologically confirmed case of TB</li>\n<li><strong>Other previously treated patients:&nbsp;</strong>Patients who had been previously treated but whose <strong>outcome is now unknown/undocumented</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Transferred in:&nbsp;</strong>A TB patient who has been received in a TB unit after having registered in another TB unit for treatment.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1031, 'Community Medicine,', 'PM1718. Diagnostic algorithm for Pulmonary TB – National Tuberculosis Elimination Programme (NTEP) 2020 Guidelines', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Any case of&nbsp;<strong>presumptive pulmonary TB</strong>&nbsp;should undergo <strong>sputum examination + chest X-ray + CB-NAAT</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If sputum and chest X-ray normal:<strong> rule out TB and refer</strong></li>\n<li>If sputum is positive and CB NAAT is positive:<strong>&nbsp;microbiologically confirmed case of TB</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The following protocol is used for <strong>CB-NAAT testing:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e8d17e5087654b588b4b519b350acb71x1280x2558.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1032, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1713. Ridleys logarithmic scale in determining Bacterial Index', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Bacterial Index(BI) indicates the density of the leprosy bacilli in smears and includes both living and dead bacilli.</p>\n<p>According to Ridleys logarithmic scale, the range is from 0 to 6+ and is based on the number of bacilli seen in an average microscopic field of the smear using an oil-immersion objective.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>0</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No bacilli in any of the 100 oil-immersion field</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>1+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1-10 bacilli, on average, in 100 oil-immersion field</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>2+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1-10 bacilli, on average, in 10 oil-immersion field</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>3+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1-10 bacilli, on average, in each oil-immersion field</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>4+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>10-100 bacilli, on average, in each oil-immersion field</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>5+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>100-1000 bacilli, on average, in each oil-immersion field&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>6+</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>More than 1000 bacilli, on average, in each oil-immersion field&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>BI is calculated by adding up the index from each site examined and dividing the total by the number of sites examined.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1033, 'Dermatology,', 'PM1710. Important sexually transmitted pathogens and the diseases caused by them', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Pathogen </strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Disease or syndrome </strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Neisseria gonorrhoeae</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gonorrhea, urethritis, cervicitis, epididymitis, salpingitis, PID, neonatal conjunctivitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Treponema pallidum</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Syphillis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Haemophilus ducreyi</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Chancroid</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Chlamydia trachomatis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>LGV, urethritis, cervicitis, proctitis, epididymis, infant pneumonia, Reiters syndrome, PID, neonatal conjunctivitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Klebsiella granulomatis (prev called Calymmatobacterium)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Donovanosis (granuloma inguinale)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Herpes simplex virus</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Genital herpes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Hepatitis B virus</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Acute and chronic hepatitis&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Human papillomaviruses&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Genital and anal warts</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>HIV</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>AIDS</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Molluscum contagiosum</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Genital molluscum contagiosum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Candida albicans</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Vaginitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Trichomonas vaginalis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Vaginitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1034, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0495. Biological Transmission in Vector-Borne Diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>1. Propagative</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The disease agent only multiplies in the vector and there is no change in form.</li>\n<li>E.g., Plague bacilli in rat fleas.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>2. Cyclo-propagative</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The agent changes in form and in number.</li>\n<li>E.g., Malarial parasites in mosquitoes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>3. Cyclo-developmental</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The agent undergoes only developmental changes and not multiplication.</li>\n<li>E.g., Microfilaria in mosquitoes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>4. Transovarial</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Infectious agent is transmitted vertically in the vector, from parent to progeny.</li>\n<li>E.g., Rickettsia rickettsii in ticks.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>5. Transstadial</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The infectious agent stays with the vector from one stage of its life cycle to the next.</li>\n<li>E.g., Borrelia burgdorferi in ticks.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1035, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0491. Modes of Transmission of Communicable Diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\222\>\n<p><strong>Direct</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\282\>\n<p><strong>Indirect</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\222\>\n<p>Direct contact</p>\n<p>Droplet infection</p>\n<p>Contact with soil</p>\n<p>Inoculation into skin or mucosa</p>\n<p>Vertical (transplacental)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\282\>\n<p>Vehicle-borne</p>\n<p>Vector borne – mechanical or biological</p>\n<p>Air borne – droplet nuclei or dust</p>\n<p>Fomite borne</p>\n<p>Unclean hands and finger</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1036, 'Medicine,', 'PM0039. Period of communicability of important diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\498\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Disease</td>\n<td>Period of communicability</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chicken pox</td>\n<td>&nbsp;1-2 days before to 4-5 days after appearance of rash</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hepatitis B</td>\n<td>One month before the appearance of Jaundice till the disappearance of HbsAg</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Measles</td>\n<td>4 days before to 4 days after appearance of rash</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rubella</td>\n<td>7 days before to 7 days after the rash</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mumps</td>\n<td>4-6 days before to 7 days after symptoms onset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pertussis</td>\n<td>7 days before to 3 weeks after the onset of paroxysms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Diphtheria</td>\n<td>Up to 4 weeks after disease onset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Meningococcal meningitis</td>\n<td>Till meningococci are absent from nasal/throat swabs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Influenza</td>\n<td>1 to 2 days before and 1 to 2 days after onset of symptoms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tetanus</td>\n<td>Not communicable</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1037, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2160. Indicators for Body fat', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>The indicators for body fat are:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Body weight</strong>: +3SD (standard deviations) from the median weight for height as a cut-off point for obesity. For adults, some people calculate various other indicators such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Body mass index (Quetelets index)</strong>: Weight (kg) / Square of height in metres</li>\n<li><strong>Ponderal index</strong>: Height(cm) / cube root of body weight (kg)</li>\n<li>Corpulence index: Actual weight /desirable weight.(Should not exceed 1.2)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Brocas index</strong>&nbsp;= Height (cm) - 100 .&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Lorentzs formula</strong>&nbsp;<br>Ht (cm) - 100 - [ (Ht (cm) - 150) / 2 for women or 4 for men ]</p>\n<p><strong>Skinfold thickness:</strong>&nbsp;Four sites mid-triceps, biceps, subscapular and suprailiac regions. The sum of the measurements should be less than 40 mm in boys and 50 mm in girls.</p>\n<p><strong>Waist circumference and waist-hip ratio</strong>: At the mid point between the lower border of the rib cage and the iliac crest. There is an increased risk of metabolic complications for men with a waist circumference~ 102 cm, and women with a waist circumference~ 88 cm. A high WHR (&gt; 1.0 in men and&gt; 0.85 in women) indicates abdominal fat accumulation.</p>\n<p><strong>Total body water</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Total body potassium</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Body density&nbsp;</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1038, 'Medicine,', 'PM2065. Body mass index', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Recent update for Asian population:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Classification</td>\n<td>Global population (kg/m<sup>2</sup>)&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Indian population</p>\n<p>(kg/m<sup>2</sup>)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Underweight</td>\n<td>&lt;18.5</td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;18.5</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Normal&nbsp;</td>\n<td>18.5-24.99</td>\n<td>18.5-22.99</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Overweight</td>\n<td>25-29.99</td>\n<td>23-24.99 (and At risk)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Obesity</td>\n<td><span>&gt;</span>30</td>\n<td><span>&gt;</span>25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Class I obesity</td>\n<td>30.0-34.9</td>\n<td>&nbsp;25- 29.9</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Class II Obesity</td>\n<td>35.0 to 39.9</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<span>&gt;</span>30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Class III Obesity (severe, extreme, massive)</td>\n<td>≥40</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Note:</p>\n<p>Lethal BMI:</p>\n<p class=\p1\>BMI Value of 13 is considered as “Lethal” in men.</p>\n<p class=\p1\>Females withstand and survive even at lower BMI rate upto 11.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1039, 'Community Medicine,', 'PM2024. Syndromic Management of Sexually Transmitted Infections', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/9e7908befff94f9a85b4a7b751999821x1280x1742.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Partner Management when <strong>asymptomatic</strong> is not required for <strong>Gardenella vaginalis, Candida and Herpes infections</strong>.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/60da7b1257d04ca5938ef3340533e6b9x1280x2974.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1040, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1778. HIV and AIDS (Prevention and Control) Act, 2017', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The Govt. of India on 21<sup>st</sup> April 2017, enacted the human immunodeficiency virus and acquired immune deficiency syndrome (prevention and control) act, 2017</p>\n<p><strong>Key highlights of the HIV and AIDS (Prevention and Control) Act, 2017</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prohibition of discrimination against HIV positive persons: </strong>The Bill sets various grounds on which discrimination against HIV positive persons is prohibited.&nbsp; These include the denial, termination, discontinuation or unfair treatment with regard to employment, educational establishments, health care services, residing or renting property, among others.</li>\n<li><strong>Informed consent and disclosure of HIV status: </strong>The Bill requires that no HIV test, medical treatment, or research will be conducted on a person without his informed consent.</li>\n<li><strong>Role of the Union and State Governments: </strong>The Union and State Governments shall take measures to prevent the spread of HIV or AIDS, provide anti-retroviral therapy and infection management for persons with HIV or AIDS, and facilitate their access to welfare schemes especially for women and children, and others.</li>\n<li><strong>Role of the Ombudsman: </strong>An ombudsman shall be appointed by each state government to inquire into complaints related to the violation of the Act and the provision of health care services.</li>\n<li><strong>Guardianship: </strong>A person between the age of 12 to 18 years who has sufficient maturity in understanding and managing the affairs of his HIV or AIDS affected family shall be competent to act as a guardian of another sibling below 18 years of age.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared residence: </strong>Every protected HIV positive person has the right to reside in a shared household, and enjoy the facilities of the household.</li>\n<li><strong>Court proceedings: </strong>Cases relating to HIV positive persons shall be disposed of by the court on a priority basis.&nbsp; In any legal proceeding, if an HIV infected or affected person is a party, the court may pass orders that the proceedings be conducted (a) by suppressing the identity of the person, (b) in camera, and (c) to restrain any person from publishing information that discloses the identity of the applicant.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1041, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1682. Malaria in the National Vector Borne Disease Control Programme (NVBDCP)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>National Framework for Malaria Elimination in India (2016-2030)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Goals:</strong> To eliminate malaria and maintain malaria-free status.</li>\n<li><strong>Objectives:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>By 2022, transmission of malaria interrupted and zero indigenous cases.</li>\n<li>By 2024, incidence of malaria to be reduced to &lt;1 case per 1000 population.</li>\n<li>By 2030, malaria to be eliminated throughout the country.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Classification of states/UTs according to the Annual Parasite Index (API):</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Criteria&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Major measures:</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Category 0&nbsp;</td>\n<td>States/UTs with zero indigenous cases&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Detect re-introduced cases and notify and maintain malaria-free status.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Category 1&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Elimination phase –</strong> States/UTs with API &lt;1 and all their districts reporting API &lt;1&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Interruption of local transmission.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Category 2&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Pre-elimination phase –</strong> States/UTs with API &lt;1 but some districts reporting API&nbsp;≥1.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Screening.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Setting up one-stop mobile centres/clinics.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Category 3&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Intensified control phase –</strong> States/UTs with API&nbsp;≥1.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Same as category 2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>National Strategic Plan (NSP) for Malaria Elimination&nbsp;</strong>(2017-22) was launched by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare under NVBDCP, which is based on the <strong>National Framework for Malaria Elimination </strong>(2016 – 2030).</li>\n<li>The <strong>NSP</strong> focuses mainly on the <strong>districts</strong> which function as the <strong>operational units.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accordingly, all the districts are classified into the following <strong>four</strong> categories:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category of districts</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Definition</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category 0</strong>: Prevention of re-establishment phase</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Includes all districts in which no incidence of malaria was reported in the last 3 years.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category 1:</strong> Elimination phase</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Districts with API &lt;1 per 1000 population.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category 2: </strong>Pre elimination phase</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Districts with API in between 1-2 per 1000 population.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category 3:</strong> Intensified control phase</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Districts with API &gt;2 per 1000 population.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>The above classification is more operational than the classification mentioned in the <strong>NFME</strong> which is <strong>state</strong> focussed.</p>\n<p>The goal of&nbsp;<strong>NSP strategy </strong>is the phased elimination of malaria in India. The National Framework for Malaria Elimination (<strong>NFME</strong>) in India has set <strong>2030</strong> as the goal for eliminating malaria, and the goals of NSP in consonance with overall goals.</p>\n<p><strong>The goals of NSP 2017 – 2022 are:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eliminate malaria in <strong>category 1</strong> (API &lt; 1) districts by <strong>2020</strong>, and <strong>category 2</strong> (API 1-2) districts by <strong>2022</strong>.</li>\n<li>Reduce transmission in <strong>category 3</strong> districts to stabilize API at&nbsp;<strong>&lt;1 </strong>by <strong>2022</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1042, 'Community Medicine,', 'PM0341. WHO proposed Multi Drug Therapy (MDT) for the treatment of Leprosy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>WHO proposed Multi-Drug Therapy (MDT) for the treatment of Leprosy</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Age group</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Drug</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Duration of Treatment</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Adult</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Rifampicin 600 mg</strong> once a month</p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p><strong>Clofazimine 300 mg</strong> once a month and <strong>50 mg daily</strong></p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p><strong>Dapsone 100 mg</strong> daily</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>12 months (MB)</p>\n<p>6 months (PB)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Children (10–14 years)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rifampicin <strong>450 mg</strong> once a month</p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p>Clofazimine <strong>150 mg</strong> once a month and 50 mg <strong>alternate days</strong>.</p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p>Dapsone <strong>50 mg</strong> daily&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;\n<p>12 months (MB)</p>\n<p>6 months (PB)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Children &lt;10 years old or &lt;40 kg</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rifampicin <strong>10 mg/kg</strong> once a month</p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p>Clofazimine <strong>100mg</strong> once a month, 50mg <strong>twice weekly</strong></p>\n<p>+</p>\n<p>Dapsone <strong>2 mg/kg</strong> daily</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>12 months (MB)</p>\n<p>6 months (PB)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1043, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0166. Health Planning Committees of India', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p><strong>Year</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p><strong>Name</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<p><strong>Concepts and Programmes</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1946</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Bhore committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also called Health Survey and <strong>Development</strong> Committee</li>\n<li>1 PHC for 40,000 population</li>\n<li><strong>3 million plan</strong></li>\n<li>3 months training in PSM for physicians</li>\n<li>Preventive and curative services at all administrative levels&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1962</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Mudaliar committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also known as Health Survey and <strong>Planning</strong> Committee</li>\n<li>District hospitals to have specialists</li>\n<li>1 PHC for not more than 40,000 people</li>\n<li>Constitution of <strong>All India Health Service</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1963</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Chadah committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Outlined responsibility of PHCs in the National Malaria Eradication Programme</li>\n<li>One <strong>basic health worker</strong> for 10,000 population&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1965</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Mukerji committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Delinked malaria activities from family planning activities.</li>\n<li><strong>Family planning assistants</strong> were for family planning work and basic health workers for other activities.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1966</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Mukerji committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also called committee of Health Secretaries.</li>\n<li>Detailed the <strong>Basic Health Service</strong> to be given at block level&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1967</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Jungalwalla committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also called <strong>Committee on Integration of Health Services</strong></li>\n<li>Ban of private practice by government doctors</li>\n<li>Equal pay for equal work and special pay for specialized work</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1973</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Kartar Singh committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also called <strong>Committee on Multipurpose Workers under Health and Family Planning</strong></li>\n<li>Recommended <strong>male and female health workers</strong></li>\n<li>1 PHC for 50,000 population</li>\n<li>Each PHC to have 16 sub-centres</li>\n<li>Each sub-centre to have one male and one female health worker</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1975</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Shrivastav committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li>Also called <strong>Group on Medical Education and Support Manpower</strong></li>\n<li>Referral Services Complex</li>\n<li>Rural Health Infrastructure of&nbsp;Sub centre, PHC and CHC</li>\n<li><strong>ROME</strong> scheme – Reorientation of health education</li>\n<li><strong>Establishment of Medical and Health Education Commission</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Village Health Guide scheme</strong></li>\n<li>Bands of semi–professional and Para-professional Health workers&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1983</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Krishnan committee</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Urban Revamping Scheme</strong></li>\n<li>Integration of PHC &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p>1986</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\168\>\n<p>Bajaj committee</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\337\>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Formulation</strong> of National Medical and Health Education Policy.</li>\n<li>Formulation of National Manpower Policy.</li>\n<li>Health Manpower cells</li>\n<li>Education commission.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1044, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0163. Management Methods in Health Programmes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\564\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p><strong>Methods based on behavioral sciences</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\354\>\n<p><strong>Quantitative methods</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\210\>\n<p>Organisational design</p>\n<p>Personnel management</p>\n<p>Communication</p>\n<p>Information systems</p>\n<p>Management by objectives(MBO)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\354\>\n<p>Cost–Benefit analysis</p>\n<p>Cost-Effective analysis</p>\n<p>Cost–Accounting</p>\n<p>Input–Output analysis</p>\n<p>Model</p>\n<p>Systems analysis</p>\n<p>Network analysis- Includes Programme Evaluation and Review Technique(PERT) and Critical Path Method(CPM)</p>\n<p>Planning–Programming–Budgeting System (PPBS)</p>\n<p>Work sampling</p>\n<p>Decision making</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1045, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0162. The Planning Cycle', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The planning cycle for health programmes consists of:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Analysis of the health situation</li>\n<li>Establishment of objectives and goals</li>\n<li>Assessment of resources</li>\n<li>Fixing priorities</li>\n<li>Write up of formulated plan</li>\n<li>Programming and implementation</li>\n<li>Monitoring</li>\n<li>Evaluation</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The planning cycle has been summarized in the following image:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b369b2910cee4095990b201b988f7f5ex1280x2558.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1046, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0155. Levels of Healthcare System in India', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e039424256924d55891c73b8e1a95878x1280x1130.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1047, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2505. Sex Ratio', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>It is the number of<strong> females per 1000 males</strong>.</li>\n<li>According to NFHS-5 (2019-21), the sex ratio in India was <strong>1020&nbsp;females</strong> per <strong>1000 males.</strong></li>\n<li>As per Census 2011, India had a sex ratio of 940 females per 1000 males. Hence, we can see the sex ratio has improved.</li>\n<li><strong>Kerala</strong> was the only state to hold a favourable sex ratio in the last census. It currently holds a sex ratio of <strong>1121 females per 1000 males. </strong>(NFHS-5 data)</li>\n<li><strong>Puducherry</strong> was the only union territory that had a favourable sex ratio in the last census. It currently has a sex ratio of <strong>1112 females per 1000 males</strong>. (NFHS-5 data)</li>\n<li>The sex composition of the population is affected by <strong>the differentials in mortality conditions of males and females</strong>, sex-selective migration and the sex ratio at birth.</li>\n<li>A very low sex ratio indicates male-child favoritism.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1048, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1715. Pearl index and couple protection rate:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Pearl Index</strong>&nbsp;is defined as the <strong>number </strong>of <strong>contraceptive failures</strong> per 100 woman-years of exposure (<strong>HWY).</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/da0fc9aa2dee499fb8ab86afa8cbe537x1280x667.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>In this formula, the total accidental pregnancies that are used as the numerator must include every known conception, irrespective of its outcome.</li>\n<li>In the denominator, total months of exposure is obtained by deducting, 10 months for full-term deliveries and 4 months for abortion, from the total period under review.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Couple Protection Rate:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is an indicator of <strong>couple protection practice</strong> in the community.</li>\n<li>It is defined as the percentage of <strong>eligible couples</strong> effectively <strong>protected against childbirth</strong> by one or the other approved methods of family planning.</li>\n<li>Attaining a <strong>60% CPR</strong> would mean <strong>restricting all third </strong>or<strong> higher-order births.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
