(1117, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1598. Chlorination of Water', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Chlorination is widely used for the&nbsp;<strong>large-scale purification</strong>&nbsp;of<strong>&nbsp;drinking water.</strong></li>\n<li>It is bactericidal and moderately virucidal but not <strong>sporicidal</strong>, except in high doses.</li>\n<li>It oxidizes<strong>&nbsp;iron, manganese, and hydrogen sulphide</strong>. It also destroys some taste and odour&nbsp;producing components. It <strong>controls algae and slime</strong> organisms and <strong>aids in coagulation</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>The action of chlorine:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hydrochloric acid and hypochlorous acid </strong>are formed when chlorine is added to water. <strong>Hypochlorous acid</strong> ionizes to form <strong>hydrogen and hypochlorite ions.</strong></li>\n<li>H<sub>2</sub>O + Cl<sub>2</sub> → HCl + HOCl<br> HOCl → H + OCl</li>\n<li>The disinfecting action of chlorine is predominantly due to <strong>hypochlorous acid</strong>. <strong>Hypochlorous acid</strong>&nbsp;is&nbsp;the most<strong>&nbsp;effective</strong> form of chlorine and it is <strong>almost 70 – 80 times</strong>&nbsp;more effective than<strong>&nbsp;hypochlorite ions</strong>.</li>\n<li>Chlorine acts best in <strong>water</strong> that has a <strong>pH of around 7</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Principles of chlorination:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>The water to be disinfected must be <strong>clear of turbidity</strong> as turbidity <strong>impedes efficient chlorination</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>chlorine demand</strong> of water is the <strong>difference between the amount of chlorine added to the water</strong> and the <strong>amount of residual chlorine</strong> remaining at the end of a specific period of contact (usually 60 minutes) at a given temperature and pH of the water. This has to&nbsp;be estimated<strong> before&nbsp;</strong>chlorination is done.</li>\n<li>The <strong>point</strong>&nbsp;at which<strong>&nbsp;the chlorine demand </strong>of&nbsp;water&nbsp;is met is called the <strong>breakpoint</strong>. It is beyond this that<strong> residual free chlorine</strong> begins to appear.</li>\n<li><strong>Contact period</strong>&nbsp;of free chlorine for at least<strong>&nbsp;one hour</strong> is required to kill bacteria and viruses.</li>\n<li>&nbsp;<strong>Minimum recommended concentration</strong>&nbsp;of free chlorine is<strong>&nbsp;0.5 mg/litre</strong>&nbsp;for<strong>&nbsp;one hour</strong>. Free residual chlorine provides a margin of <strong>safety</strong> against <strong>microbial contamination</strong> that occurs in storage or transport.</li>\n<li>The <strong>sum</strong> of the <strong>chlorine demand</strong> of the specific water plus <strong>free residual chlorine</strong>&nbsp;of 0.5<strong> mg/litre</strong> constitutes the <strong>correct dose of chlorine</strong> to be applied.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Methods of chlorination:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Chlorine gas</strong>: It is the <strong>first choice</strong> as it is <strong>cheap, quick and efficient</strong> in action, and easy to apply. Special <strong>chlorinating equipments</strong> like <strong>Paterson’s chloronome</strong> are used for the application of chlorine gas.</li>\n<li><strong>Chloramines</strong>: These<strong>&nbsp;loose compounds of chlorine and ammonia</strong> give more persistent forms of residual chlorine. They have <strong>slow action</strong> and thus are not widely used.</li>\n<li><strong>Perchloron</strong> or <strong>high test hypochlorite (H.T.H.)</strong>: It is a <strong>calcium compound</strong> that has <strong>60 – 70% of available chlorine</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Break point chlorination:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>The point at which the <strong>chlorine demand of water</strong>&nbsp;is met is called<strong>&nbsp;the breakpoint. </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Free chlorine</strong> (HOCl and OCl) appears when <strong>chlorine is added beyond the breakpoint</strong>.</li>\n<li>In other words, at the breakpoint, if chlorine is added, then <strong>all the combined chlorines</strong>&nbsp;would have been completely<strong>&nbsp;destroyed</strong> and <strong>free residual chlorines </strong>begin to&nbsp;<strong>appear</strong>.</li>\n<li>This corresponding dosage to achieve the appearance of free residual chlorine is called <strong>breakpoint dosage</strong> and this method is called <strong>breakpoint chlorination</strong>.</li>\n<li>It is also called <strong>controlled superchlorination</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Superchlorination </strong>followed by <strong>dechlorination </strong>is used to disinfect highly polluted waters whose quality fluctuates greatly.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Orthotolidine (OT) test:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>It is a <strong>test for chlorination</strong> and determines <strong>free and combined chlorine</strong> in water, rapidly and accurately.</li>\n<li>The reagent used is <strong>analytical grade Orthotolidine</strong> dissolved in a 10% solution of hydrochloric acid.</li>\n<li>When added to water that contains chlorine, it turns <strong>yellow</strong> with varying intensity. This is <strong>faster</strong> in the presence of <strong>free chlorine</strong> and <strong>slower</strong> in the presence of <strong>combined chlorine</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Orthotolidine - arsenite (OTA) test:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>This is a <strong>modification of the OT test</strong> which <strong>nullifies the errors</strong>&nbsp;due to interfering substances<strong>&nbsp;</strong>like <strong>iron, nitrites, manganese</strong>, etc.</li>\n<li>It determines <strong>free</strong>&nbsp;and<strong>&nbsp;combined chlorine separately.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1118, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1596. Rapid Sand Filters', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>They are also called <strong>mechanical filters</strong> and are another method of <strong>large scale </strong>purification of water.</li>\n<li>The two types of rapid sand filters are <strong>gravity type </strong>(e.g. Paterson’s filter) and <strong>pressure type</strong> (e.g. Candy’s filter).</li>\n<li>Steps in the purification of water by rapid sand filters are:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Coagulation</strong> – Raw water is first treated with a <strong>chemical coagulant like alum</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Rapid mixing</strong> – The treated water then undergoes <strong>violent agitation</strong> in a <strong>mixing chamber</strong> which allows <strong>complete dissemination of alum</strong> throughout the bulk of the water.</li>\n<li><strong>Flocculation</strong> – <strong>Slow </strong>and<strong> gentle mixing</strong> of water in a <strong>flocculation chamber</strong> is done for <strong>30 minutes</strong>.&nbsp;This results in a thick, copious flocculate of<strong> aluminium hydroxide</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Sedimentation</strong> – The coagulated water is moved into <strong>sedimentation tanks</strong> where detaining it for 2 – 6 hours will result in the <strong>settling down </strong>of the <strong>flocculent</strong> along with <strong>impurities</strong> and <strong>bacteria</strong>. This is to be removed before the filtration takes place.</li>\n<li><strong>Filtration</strong> – The partly purified water is then subjected to rapid sand filtration.\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Filter beds</strong>:&nbsp;The <strong>effective size</strong> of the sand particles/grains is about <strong>0.4 to 0.7 mm</strong>. The <strong>depth</strong> of the sand bed is about <strong>1 metre</strong> and has graded gravel below it.</li>\n<li>As the filtration is done, the alum-floc which has not precipitated is held back by the sand bed. This forms a layer which adsorbs bacteria and other impurities. When the <strong>loss of head</strong> in a rapid sand filter approaches <strong>7 – 8 feet</strong>, the <strong>filter needs to be cleaned</strong> by a process known as <strong>backwashing</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Backwashing</strong> is done by <strong>reversing </strong>the<strong> flow of water </strong>through the sand bed. It dislodges the impurities and cleans the bed. <strong>Skilled labor </strong>is needed for this purpose.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Advantages</strong> of rapid sand filter:\n<ul>\n<li>Rapid sand filter <strong>does not need storage </strong>of water before it is treated.</li>\n<li>It occupies <strong>less space</strong> when compared to slow sand filters.</li>\n<li>Filtration is much<strong> more rapid</strong> than slow sand filters.</li>\n<li>It is <strong>easy </strong>to wash and clean.</li>\n<li>There is more <strong>flexibility</strong> in its operation.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1119, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1595. Slow Sand Filters', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>These are also called <strong>biological filters</strong>.</li>\n<li>They are accepted as the <strong>standard method </strong>of<strong> large scale </strong>water purification.</li>\n<li>Essentially, elements of a slow sand filter include\n<ul>\n<li>Supernatant (raw) water</li>\n<li>Bed of graded sand</li>\n<li>Under-drainage system</li>\n<li>System of filter control valves</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/57efa9f1e6a34873a4a4b8c5996958c9x800x449.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Supernatant water:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>It lies <strong>above </strong>the<strong> sand bed</strong> and its depth varies from <strong>1 – 1.5 metres</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>level of supernatant or raw water</strong> is always kept <strong>constant</strong> and this helps in <strong>overcoming </strong>the<strong> resistance </strong>of filter bed, promoting the downward flow of water through the sand bed.</li>\n<li>It also provides for a<strong> waiting period</strong> during which the water undergoes <strong>partial purification</strong> by sedimentation, oxidation and particle agglomeration.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Sand bed:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>This is the <strong>most important part</strong> of a slow sand filter.</li>\n<li>Its <strong>thickness</strong> is generally around <strong>1 metre</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>sand grains</strong> must be <strong>rounded</strong> and have an effective diameter of <strong>0.2 – 0.3 mm</strong>. They must be clean and free from organic matter.</li>\n<li>A layer of <strong>supporting, graded gravel</strong>, <strong>30 – 40 cm deep</strong>, prevents the grains from being carried into drainage pipes.</li>\n<li>The sand bed filters the water as it percolates slowly through it through processes like mechanical straining, oxidation, sedimentation and adsorption.</li>\n<li><strong>Vital layer</strong>: In a new filter, the bed merely acts as a mechanical strainer. But over time the sand bed get covered with a <strong>Schmutzdecke</strong>/<strong>vital layer/zoogleal layer/biological layer</strong>. This is a <strong>slimy </strong>and<strong> gelatinous layer</strong> that contains algae, diatoms and plankton. The <strong>formation</strong> of such a layer is the <strong>ripening</strong> of the filter and this layer is the <strong>heart of a slow sand filter</strong>. It removes organic matter, prevents bacteria from flowing through and oxidizes ammoniacal nitrogen into nitrates, thus rendering the water<strong> bacteria-free</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Under-drainage system:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>A system of <strong>porous and perforated pipes</strong>, at the bottom of the filter bed, is part of the under-drainage system.</li>\n<li>They provide an <strong>outlet </strong>for the<strong> filtered water</strong> and a support to the filter medium above.</li>\n<li>The <strong>under-drainage system</strong> along with the <strong>supernatant water</strong> and sand <strong>bed</strong> is kept in a<strong> filter box</strong>, which is usually <strong>2.5 to 4 metres</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Filter control:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>outlet-pipe system</strong> is provided with <strong>valves </strong>and other devices which maintain a constant rate of filtration.</li>\n<li>The <strong>Venturi meter</strong> measures the <strong>bed resistance</strong> or the <strong>loss of head</strong>.</li>\n<li>When the resistance builds up, the operator opens the <strong>regulatory valve</strong> to maintain a steady-state of filtration.</li>\n<li>When the loss of head <strong>exceeds 1.5 metres </strong>(4 feet), it is <strong>uneconomical</strong> to run the filter.</li>\n<li>If the regulatory <strong>valve has to be kept fully open</strong> as the <strong>bed resistance is very high</strong>, the <strong>filter needs to be cleaned</strong>.</li>\n<li>This is done by <strong>scraping</strong> the <strong>sand bed</strong>, which doesn’t need to be done by skilled labor. After several years of operation (say 20 to 30 scrappings) the sand bed can be changed as it would have diminished in size.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Advantages</strong> of slow sand filters:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Simple </strong>to construct and operate.</li>\n<li>Cost of construction is<strong> cheap</strong> compared to rapid sand filters.</li>\n<li>Physical, chemical and bacteriological <strong>quality</strong> of the water is <strong>very high</strong> which is partially owed to the <strong>long duration</strong> taken for filtration.</li>\n<li>Bacteria are cleared <strong>more effectively</strong> than rapid filters.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1120, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1594. Purification of Water', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Purification of water can be done on a <strong>large scale</strong> or <strong>small scale.</strong></p>\n<p>I)&nbsp;Purification of water on a <strong>large scale </strong>is done by one or more of the following measures:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Storage</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Filtration:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Slow sand filters</li>\n<li>Rapid sand filters</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Disinfection:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Chlorination</li>\n<li>Ozonation</li>\n<li>UV radiation</li>\n<li>Membrane processes like <strong>reverse osmosis</strong>,<strong> nanofiltration</strong>,<strong> ultrafiltration </strong>and<strong> microfiltration</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>II)&nbsp;Purification of water on a <strong>small scale:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Household</strong> purification of water:\n<ul>\n<li>Boiling</li>\n<li>Chemical disinfection using <strong>bleaching powder</strong>, chlorine solution, <strong>high test hypochlorite</strong>, chlorine tablets, iodine and potassium permanganate.</li>\n<li>Filtration using <strong>Pasteur Chamberland </strong>filter,<strong> Berkefeld </strong>filters or<strong> Katadyn </strong>filters.</li>\n<li>UV radiation</li>\n<li>Multi-stage reverse osmosis</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Disinfection of wells</strong> with bleaching powder</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1121, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1593. Wells', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Wells </strong>are a source of <strong>ground water</strong> and are widely used across India.</li>\n<li>The two main types of wells are the <strong>shallow</strong> and <strong>deep wells</strong>, the difference between which are:</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Shallow Wells</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Deep Wells</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Description</td>\n<td>They tap subsoil water, i.e., water from above the first impervious layer in the ground</td>\n<td>They tap water from the water-bearing stratum which is below the first impervious layer of the ground</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chemical quality</td>\n<td>Moderately hard water</td>\n<td>Very hard water</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Contamination</td>\n<td>Very often grossly contaminated and liable to pollution</td>\n<td>Low contamination levels and purer than water from shallow wells</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Yield</td>\n<td>Generally dry in summer</td>\n<td>Provides constant water supply</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Prevalence in India</td>\n<td>Very common</td>\n<td>Less common than shallow wells</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>An <strong>artesian well</strong> is a type of <strong>deep well</strong> in which the <strong>water rises to the surface</strong> due to the <strong>pressure</strong> with which it is held between <strong>two impervious/impermeable layers</strong>. There is <strong>no pump or other manual methods</strong> needed to bring the water to the surface. These are not common in India.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/757cd3b056ba491baacf879379998e83x734x425.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Wells can also be classified according to the method of <strong>construction</strong> as <strong>dug wells </strong>and<strong> tube wells</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>i)&nbsp;</strong><strong>Dug wells:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>They are the <strong>most common type</strong> of wells in India.</li>\n<li>In rural India, two types of dug wells exist, namely the <strong>unlined katcha wells</strong> and the <strong>masonry or pucca wells</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>katcha wells </strong>are just big holes dug into the sand.</li>\n<li>The <strong>pucca wells</strong> are well built with walls or linings made of brick or stones.</li>\n<li><strong>Step wells </strong>are types of <strong>pucca dug wells</strong> that have steps. These steps can be used by people to descend into the well and come in contact with water. This increases the risk of water contamination.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>ii)&nbsp;Tube wells:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Shallow tube wells</strong> are also called <strong>driven wells</strong> and&nbsp;<strong>deep tube wells</strong> are called <strong>bore wells</strong>.</li>\n<li>They are safer sources of water compared to other wells, relatively cheaper to build and maintain.</li>\n<li>Tube wells use <strong>strainers at the bottom</strong> and <strong>hand pumps at the top</strong> attached by a <strong>pipe</strong> in between.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The following are the considerations for building a safe and sanitary well:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>Must be at least 15 m away from sources of contamination. Must not be &gt;100 m from households.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lining</strong></td>\n<td>Must be made of brick or stones set in cement to a depth of 6 m, so that water enters from bottom and not sides. Height of lining above ground level must be 60 – 90 cm.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Parapet Wall</strong></td>\n<td>Must be at least 70 – 75 cm (28 inches) from the ground level.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Platform</strong></td>\n<td>Should stretch at least 1 m around the well in all directions.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Drain</strong></td>\n<td>It should be a pucca drain to carry spilled water to a public drain beyond the <strong>cone of filtration </strong>of the well.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Covering</strong></td>\n<td>There should be a cement concrete covering over the well.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hand-pump</strong></td>\n<td>Should be able to withstand rough handling.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Consumer responsibility</strong></td>\n<td>Consumers must practice basic precautions before handling the well.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Quality</strong></td>\n<td>The water standards in terms of quality must be conformed to.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1122, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1592. Sources of Water', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>i) Rain</strong></p>\n<p><strong>ii) Surface water</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Impounding reservoirs</li>\n<li>Rivers and streams</li>\n<li>Tanks, ponds and lakes</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>iii)&nbsp;Ground water</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Shallow wells</li>\n<li>Deep wells</li>\n<li>Springs</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1123, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1590. Adequate Intake of Water for Different Age Groups (WHO)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age Group</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Daily Adequate Water Intake (Litres/Day)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>0 – 6 months</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>0.7, assumed to be from <strong>human milk.</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>7 – 12 months</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>0.8, assumed to be from human milk and complementary foods and beverages</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>1 – 3 years</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1.3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>3 – 8 years</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1.7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>9 – 13 years</strong></p>\n<p>Boys</p>\n<p>Girls&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>2.4</p>\n<p>2.1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>14 – 18 years</strong></p>\n<p>Boys</p>\n<p>Girls&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>3.3</p>\n<p>2.3&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>19 – 70+ years</strong></p>\n<p>Men</p>\n<p>Women&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>3.7</p>\n<p>2.7</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1124, 'Dermatology,', 'PM0366. Difference between classic and neonatal scabies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Classic scabies</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Neonatal scabies</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Site of involvement</td>\n<td>Interdigital webs, trunk, genitals, flexors, sparing of palms and soles, and skin above neck</td>\n<td>Face, scalp, palm, and soles</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Morphology of Lesion</td>\n<td>Papules, pustules, excoriation, eczematization, burrow</td>\n<td>Vesicles, pustules, bullae, erosions, and ulcerations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Burrows</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Usually absent</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1125, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2444. Biomedical Waste (BMW) Management -COVID 19', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>In addition to the current BMW Management rules, the following measures are proposed</p>\n<ul>\n<li>To report opening/operation of COVID 19 Ward/ICU/Lab/Collection Centre to <strong>SPCB</strong> (State Pollution Control Board) and <strong>CBWTF</strong> (Common Biomedical Waste Treatment Facility) in that area</li>\n<li>Dedicated sanitation workers deputed only to collect COVID 19 BMW</li>\n<li>It is mandatory for all BMW bags and containers from COVID 19 areas to carry <strong>\COVID 19 WASTE\</strong> label</li>\n<li>Keep separate colour coded bins with <strong>foot operated lids</strong></li>\n<li>The inner and outer surfaces of these containers must be disinfected daily with <strong>1% sodium hypochlorite</strong> solution</li>\n<li>To ensure no leaks, <strong>double layers&nbsp;</strong>(2 bags) are used</li>\n</ul>\n<table width=\433\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>COLOUR OF THE BIN</strong></td>\n<td><strong>PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT(PPE)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>OTHER WASTE</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Red Bin</strong></td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Goggles</li>\n<li>Face shield&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Splash-proof apron</li>\n<li>Plastic coverall</li>\n<li>Hazmat suit</li>\n<li>Nitrile gloves</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Used gloves</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Laboratory waste</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pre-treated viral transport media</li>\n<li>Plastic vials and cryovials</li>\n<li>Vacutainers</li>\n<li>Eppendorf tubes</li>\n<li>Pipette tips</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Yellow Bin</strong></td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Used mask(triple layer mask, N95 mask)</li>\n<li>Head cover/Cap, Shoe cover</li>\n<li>Disposable linen gown&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Non-plastic/Semi-plastic coverall</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Diapers with feces of immobile COVID 19 patients&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1126, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0128. Triage Colour Coding', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/515d17fd0b684f8b9cd1fd57ef97b7e6x454x304.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;<strong>Triage system </strong>consists of <strong>four colour codes:</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Color code</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Type of patients</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Examples</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Red (High priority)<br></span></td>\n<td>\n<p>Need for<strong> immediate resuscitation or surgery</strong> in the next<strong> 6 hours</strong> or transfer.</p>\n<p>May survive if timely medical intervention can be given</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Tension pneumothorax</li>\n<li>Airway obstruction</li>\n<li>Hemothorax</li>\n<li>Cardiac tamponade</li>\n<li>Acute circulatory arrest</li>\n<li>Major intra-abdominal bleed etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Yellow (Medium priority)<br></span></td>\n<td>\n<p>Possible <strong>resuscitation or surgery</strong> in the <strong>next 24 hours</strong>.</p>\n<p>Likely to survive if prompt treatment is given.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Compound fractures</li>\n<li>Degloving injuries</li>\n<li>Pelvic fracture</li>\n<li>Spinal injuries</li>\n<li>Moderate head injury</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span>Green (Low priority)<br></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Ambulatory patients</strong> or minor illnesses.</p>\n<p>Likely to survive if treatment is slightly delayed.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Simple fractures</li>\n<li>Minor lacerations etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Black (Least priority)</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Dead or moribund</strong> patients.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Severe brain injury</li>\n<li>Major damage / disruption to chest wall and abdominal structures</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1127, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2488. Post-exposure management of healthcare personnel in Hepatitis B exposure', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Healthcare personnel status</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Post-exposure testing</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Post-exposure prophylaxis</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Post-vaccination serological testing</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Source</strong><br><strong>patient (HbsAg)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>HCP testing (anti-HBs)</strong></td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>HBIG</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Vaccination</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Documented<br>responder (after 3 doses)</td>\n<td colspan=\5\>No action needed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Documented non-responder (after 6 doses)</td>\n<td>Positive/&nbsp;<br>Unknown</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>HBIG x 2 <br>1 month apart</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>No&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\4\>No action needed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\3\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Response unknown (after 3 doses)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>Positive/<br>Unknown</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 214\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>&lt;10 mIU/ml</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>HBIG x 1</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Initiate re-<br>vaccination</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Yes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>&lt;10 mIU/ml</td>\n<td>None</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Any result</td>\n<td>≥10 mIU/ml</td>\n<td colspan=\3\>No action needed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\>Unvaccinated/ incompletely vaccinated or vaccine refusers</td>\n<td>Positive/<br>Unknown</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>HBIG x 1</td>\n<td>Complete&nbsp;<br>vaccination</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>None</td>\n<td>Complete&nbsp;<br>vaccination</td>\n<td>Yes&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1128, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2165. The Factories act, 1948 and The Maternity Act, 2017', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>The Factories act</strong>,<strong>1948</strong></p>\n<p>The act defines a factory as an establishment employing 10 or more workers where power is used, and 20 or more workers where power is not used.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Provisions in the age of employment are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Children <strong>&lt;14 years</strong> are <strong>prohibited</strong> from working.</li>\n<li>Adolescents between <strong>15-18</strong> years:\n<ul>\n<li>Can be employed only in certain industries.</li>\n<li>They can work only between <strong>6 AM – 7 PM</strong>.</li>\n<li>They should not be made to work for more than <strong>four and a half hours.</strong></li>\n<li>They are allowed to take <strong>leave once</strong> every <strong>15 days</strong> and have an <strong>accumulated</strong> leave of up to <strong>40</strong> days.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For adults, the&nbsp;<strong>maximum</strong> hours of work for an industrial worker should be not more than <strong>48 hours</strong> <strong>per week</strong>, not exceeding 9 hours a day. If working <strong>overtime,</strong> then it should be no more than <strong>60 hours</strong> <strong>per week</strong> including overtime.</p>\n<p><strong>Per capita space</strong> availability: For factories established&nbsp;after 1948 – min 500cuft / person</p>\n<p>Safety and welfare measures include the provision of the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>&gt; 1000 Workers – Safety officer</li>\n<li>&gt; 500 Workers – Welfare officer</li>\n<li>&gt; 250 Workers – Canteen</li>\n<li>&gt; 50 employees - Crèche</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The Maternity Act, 2017</strong> is a landmark law that has enhanced the&nbsp;duration of paid maternity leave:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Working mothers -&nbsp;12-26 weeks</li>\n<li>Working mothers, with 2 surviving children - 12 weeks</li>\n<li>Adopting mother and commissioning mothers-&nbsp;12 weeks from the date on which the child is being handed over to the mother.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>According to <strong>Indian Maternity Benefit (Amendment) Act, 2017</strong>: Effective as of the 1st of July 2017, mandatory <strong>crèche</strong> (daycare) facilities for every establishment employing <strong>50 or more employees&nbsp;</strong>(inclusive of <strong>men</strong> and <strong>women</strong>).</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1129, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0022. ESI ACT, 1948', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Employees State Insurance Act, 1948 (Revised in 2019)</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Scope:</strong> It is applicable to all factories in India <strong>excluding</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Defence&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Railway&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Mines&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Finance Contribution</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It covers all employees getting income up to Rs.21,000/- per month.</li>\n<li>Employee –<strong> 0.75%</strong> of his daily wage.</li>\n<li>Employer –<strong> 3.25%</strong> of the employees daily wage.</li>\n<li>Medical benefit – 1/8th by the state government and 7/8th by the ESI Corporation.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Benefits</strong></p>\n<p><strong>To the Employees</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Medical</strong> Benefit- full medical care is provided free of cost in case of sickness, employment injury, and maternity.</li>\n<li><strong>Sickness</strong> Benefit- is given at <strong>70%</strong> of average daily wages for a duration of <strong>91 days</strong> in one year.&nbsp;In order to qualify for sickness benefit, the worker is required to contribute for 78 days in a period of 6 months.\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Extended</strong> sickness benefit – <strong>80%</strong> of the daily wages for a duration of<strong> 2 years,</strong> for 34 specified diseases such as TB, leprosy, malignant diseases, diabetes, Parkinsons, myasthenia gravis, glaucoma, coronary artery disease, etc.</li>\n<li><strong>Enhanced</strong> sickness benefit – at <strong>full</strong> <strong>wages</strong> for sterilization procedure; for a duration of 7 days post-vasectomy and 14 days post tubectomy.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>The total amount payable is double the standard sickness benefit rate, that is, equal to full wages.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Maternity</strong> Benefit&nbsp;– benefit is payable at full wages for 26 weeks (6.5 months) for pregnancy, 6 weeks following a miscarriage, and 30 days for sickness arising out of pregnancy. It also covers the premature birth of a child born to an insured woman.</li>\n<li><strong>Dependance</strong> Benefit– in case of death, as a result of employment injury, the dependents of an insured person are eligible for periodical payments. Pension at the rate of <strong>90%</strong> of the wages is payable, shared by dependants in a fixed ratio, on monthly basis in accordance with the prescribed share. An eligible son or daughter is entitled to the dependants benefit up to the age of 18; the benefit is withdrawn if the daughter marries earlier.</li>\n<li><strong>Disablement</strong> Benefits–\n<ul>\n<li>Temporary disability- at 90% daily wages as long as the person is disabled.</li>\n<li>Permanent disability- lifetime pension. It also covers occupational diseases.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Funeral</strong> Benefit&nbsp;– a maximum of Rs.15,000/-.</li>\n<li><strong>Rehabilitation</strong> Benefit- on payment of Rs.10, the insured person and his/her family continue to get medical treatment after permanent disablement or retirement.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>To the Employers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Exemption from Workman Compensation Act.</li>\n<li>Exemption from Maternity Benefit Act.</li>\n<li>Income tax rebate on the amount contributed towards the scheme.</li>\n<li>Exemption from payment of medical allowance to employees and their dependants, or arranging for their medical care.</li>\n<li>Healthy-work force.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1130, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0021. Notifiable occupational diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;There are 29 diseases notifiable to the government under the Indian Factories Act 1948, some important ones are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Anthracosis</li>\n<li>Asbestosis</li>\n<li>Byssinosis</li>\n<li>Noise induced hearing loss</li>\n<li>Occupational dermatitis</li>\n<li>Occupational cancers</li>\n<li>Silicosis</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1131, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0019. Consequences of different dust particle sizes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Size</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Consequence</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&gt; 10 microns</td>\n<td>Settles down</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&lt;10 microns</td>\n<td>Suspended in air</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5-10 microns</td>\n<td>Trapped at upper respiratory tract</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3-5 microns</td>\n<td>Trapped in the mid respiratory tract</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1-3 microns</td>\n<td>Settles in alveoli</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&lt; 1micron</td>\n<td>Shows Brownian movement</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1132, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0174. Methods of Health Communication', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/48ba5eb0215744d389fb6f353dbe3813x538x361.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1133, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0173. Principles of Health Education', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>(Mnemonic: <strong>PLS, G</strong>ood <strong>F</strong>riend, <strong>CLICK MoRe</strong>!)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>P</strong>articipation</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>earning by doing</li>\n<li><strong>S</strong>etting an example</li>\n<li><strong>G</strong>ood human relations</li>\n<li><strong>F</strong>eedback</li>\n<li><strong>C</strong>redibility</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>eaders</li>\n<li><strong>I</strong>nterest</li>\n<li><strong>C</strong>omprehension</li>\n<li><strong>K</strong>nown to unknown</li>\n<li><strong>M</strong>otivation</li>\n<li><strong>R</strong>einforcement</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1134, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0167. Evaluation of a Health Program', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Steps of evaluation:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Determine what is to be evaluated:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>structure, process or outcome</li>\n<li>Establish standards and criteria</li>\n<li>Plan the methodology to be applied</li>\n<li>Gather information</li>\n<li>Analyze the results</li>\n<li>Take action</li>\n<li>Re-evaluate</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Components of evaluation</strong></p>\n<p>(Mnemonic: <strong>R</strong>yan <strong>A</strong>lways <strong>A</strong>te <strong>A</strong>n <strong>E</strong>gg <strong>E</strong>very <strong>E</strong>vening)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>R</strong>elevance</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>dequacy</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>ccessibility</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>cceptability</li>\n<li><strong>E</strong>ffectiveness</li>\n<li><strong>E</strong>fficiency</li>\n<li><strong>E</strong>ffect or impact</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1135, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0164. Network Analysis in Health Management', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>A network is a <strong>graphic plan</strong> of all events and activities to be completed in order to reach an end objective.<br> <br> Two types of network analysis: <strong>PERT </strong>and <strong>CPM</strong></p>\n<p>1. Programme Evaluation and Review Technique (PERT)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An arrow diagram of all events in logical sequence is drawn.</li>\n<li>Time to finish each activity can be calculated and critical activities can be identified.</li>\n<li>It aids in planning, scheduling and monitoring of the project.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/173aa5799bb5492e8a01d82bdda0f6d2x1280x1447.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>2. Critical Path Method (CPM)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The longest path of the network is called the critical path.</li>\n<li>A delay in the critical path will cause a delay in the entire project.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1136, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0845. The Family as a Social Organization', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>A family is a group of biologically related individuals living together under the same roof and eating from a common kitchen.</li>\n<li>It is the most primary and basic unit of all societies.</li>\n<li>The basic and arbitrary model of a family cycle has six phases:</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p><strong>Phase</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p><strong>Beginning</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p><strong>End</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Formation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>Marriage</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>Birth of 1<sup>st</sup> child</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Extension</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>Birth of 1<sup>st</sup> child</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>Birth of last child</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>3</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Complete extension</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>Birth of last&nbsp;child</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>1<sup>st</sup> child leaves home</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>4</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Contraction</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>1<sup>st</sup> child leaves home</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>Last child leaves parental home</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>5</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Completed contraction</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>Last child leaves parental home</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>Death of 1<sup>st</sup> spouse</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\66\>\n<p>6</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\167\>\n<p>Dissolution</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\146\>\n<p>Death of 1<sup>st</sup> spouse</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\138\>\n<p>Death of survivor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Types </strong>of families:\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>nuclear family</strong> or <strong>elementary family</strong> consists of only the married couple and their offspring while they are dependants.</li>\n<li>The term <strong>new family</strong> is applied when nuclear families <strong>are younger than 10 years</strong> and consist of parents and children.</li>\n<li>A <strong>joint</strong> family or <strong>extended family</strong> consists of a number of married couples and their children who live together in the same household with usually the men being related by blood. All <strong>property</strong> in joint families is <strong>held in common</strong> with the family income going into a common pocket. A <strong>senior male member</strong> is usually the <strong>head of the family</strong> who makes decisions.</li>\n<li>A <strong>three generation family</strong> is one where there are representatives from three different generations in one house.</li>\n<li>A <strong>communal family</strong> is one in which all the <strong>members play a part</strong> in its <strong>management</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Functions </strong>of the family:\n<ul>\n<li>Residence (patrilocal and matrilocal)</li>\n<li>Division of labour</li>\n<li>Reproduction and raising children</li>\n<li>Socialization and social care</li>\n<li>Economic functions</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Problems families</strong> are those that <strong>lag behind</strong> the rest of the community in terms of standard and quality of life of its members.</li>\n<li><strong>Broken families </strong>are those in which the parental or family system has been disrupted by separation, divorce or death.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1137, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0172. Health Education vs. Propaganda', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Health education&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Health propaganda</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Knowledge</td>\n<td>Actively acquired</td>\n<td>Instilled in the mind</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Skills</td>\n<td>Actively acquired</td>\n<td>Instilled</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Primitive desires</td>\n<td>Disciplined</td>\n<td>Aroused</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Action</td>\n<td>Reflective behaviour; trained to use judgement before acting</td>\n<td>Reflexive behaviour;Aims at impulsive action&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Emotion&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Does not appeal to emotion but appeals to reason</td>\n<td>Appeals to emotion</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Behaviour</td>\n<td>Process is behaviour centered</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Process is information centered</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
