(1177, 'Community Medicine', 'PM0141. Hardy-Weinberg Law', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>The Hardy-Weinberg Law is related to <strong>population genetics</strong>.</li>\n<li>It is based on the principle founded by G.H. Hardy and Wilhelm Weinberg.</li>\n<li>The law states that the relative <strong>frequencies of each gene allele</strong>&nbsp;tends to remain <strong>constant</strong> from generation to generation in the absence of other evolutionary influences.</li>\n<li>It is also called the Hardy-Weinberg<strong> equilibrium</strong> or principle.</li>\n<li>It is only applicable for <strong>infinitely large, static</strong> populations which <strong>randomly mate</strong>.</li>\n<li>This law fails in the following conditions:\n<ul>\n<li>Small and dynamic populations</li>\n<li>Non random or assortative mating</li>\n<li>Mutations</li>\n<li>Gene outflow and genetic drift</li>\n<li>Migration</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1178, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1688. Pesticide Toxicity Labels', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Extremely toxic</strong></td>\n<td>Bright <strong>red</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Highly toxic</strong></td>\n<td>Bright <strong>yellow</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Moderately toxic</strong></td>\n<td>Bright <strong>blue</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Slightly toxic</strong></td>\n<td>Bright <strong>green</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/ba1415f5a3b84d668208be25942661aax278x267.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1179, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2503. Rabies vaccines and immunoglobulins schedules', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>According to the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, Government of India:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f49dfa01d9bd424db725e4ebf600cb98x1280x3397.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>WHO category <strong>II</strong> or <strong>III</strong> exposures should receive&nbsp;<strong>post-exposure prophylaxis&nbsp;</strong>(PEP)<strong>&nbsp;immediately.</strong></p>\n<p>One <strong>intradermal&nbsp;</strong>(ID)&nbsp;dose is <strong>0.1 mL</strong> of vaccine and one <strong>intramuscular</strong> (IM) dose is an <strong>entire vial</strong> of vaccine, irrespective of the vial size.</p>\n<p>Should a vaccine dose be delayed for any reason, the PEP schedule should be resumed (not restarted).</p>\n<p><strong>Rabies Immunoglobulin(RIG):&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Passive immunization</li>\n<li><strong>Single-dose</strong>; after initiation of PEP and not beyond 7 days after the first dose of vaccine</li>\n<li>Max dose: <strong>hRIG - 20IU/kg ,&nbsp;</strong><strong>eRIG</strong><strong>&nbsp;- 40IU/kg </strong>body weight</li>\n<li>Vaccines should never be withheld regardless of the availability of RIG.</li>\n<li><strong>Alternatives</strong> for RIG- WHO recommends&nbsp;<strong>m</strong><strong>onoclonal antibodies&nbsp;</strong>(mAb)&nbsp;as a cocktail containing at least <strong>two antibodies</strong> against the rabies virus.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Administration of RIG:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>RIG should be administered&nbsp;<strong>into</strong> or <strong>around</strong> the <strong>wound site</strong> or sites.</li>\n<li>The&nbsp;<strong>remaining</strong> RIG, if any, should be injected <strong>IM</strong> at a site <strong>distant</strong> from the <strong>site</strong> of vaccine administration.</li>\n<li>RIG may be diluted to a volume sufficient for all wounds to be effectively and safely infiltrated.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Prioritization&nbsp;of RIG allocation (numbered according to priority order):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Multiple bites</li>\n<li>Deep wounds</li>\n<li>Bites to head, neck, and hands</li>\n<li>Patients with severe immunodeficiency</li>\n<li>Confirmed/probable rabies in biting animal</li>\n<li>Bites, scratches, and exposure of mucous membranes caused by a bat</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Pre-exposure prophylaxis&nbsp;(PrEP)</strong></p>\n<p>PrEP is considered in the following conditions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>High-risk groups- laboratory staff, wildlife wardens, veterinarians, animal handlers, and travelers to endemic regions.</li>\n<li>Remote, rabies-endemic areas where access to PEP is difficult</li>\n<li>Areas where&nbsp;dog bite incidence is &gt;5% per year</li>\n<li>Areas where vampire bat rabies is known to be present.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Pre-exposure rabies vaccination consists of <strong>3&nbsp;intramuscular (IM) or 3 intradermal (ID)</strong>&nbsp;doses. These are given on <strong>days 0, 7 and 21 or 28.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adults - the vaccine should always be administered in the deltoid area of the arm</li>\n<li>Young children (under 1 year of age)- Administration into the anterolateral area of the thigh is recommended.</li>\n<li><strong>Rabies vaccine </strong>should<strong> never</strong> be administered in the<strong> gluteal area.</strong>&nbsp;Administration in this manner will result in <strong>lower neutralizing antibody titers.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>For exposed or re-exposed patients who can document previous completion of PEP the following guidelines would be applicable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Proper wound management should be done.</li>\n<li>There is no need for the administration of RIG.</li>\n<li>One site ID or IM vaccine administration on days 0 and 3.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Only adequate wound washing would be required in case of re-exposure where the animal bite victim has documented proof of complete PEP&nbsp;<strong>within the last three months.</strong></p>\n<p>The following cases are treated as fresh cases and given full PEP:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Those who have previously received full post-exposure treatment with neural tissue vaccines (NTV) or vaccines of unproven potency</li>\n<li>Those who cannot document complete PEP or PrEP treatment&nbsp;</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1180, 'Community Medicine', 'PM2502. GOBI–FFF Strategy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>This strategy was proposed by the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>G </strong>– Growth monitoring with growth charts</li>\n<li><strong>O </strong>– Oral rehydration therapy for diarrhoea and dehydration</li>\n<li><strong>B</strong> – Breastfeeding</li>\n<li><strong>I</strong> – Immunization of children</li>\n<li><strong>F</strong> – Family planning and birth spacing</li>\n<li><strong>F </strong>– Food supplementation</li>\n<li><strong>F </strong>­– Female literacy promotion</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1181, 'Community Medicine', 'PM1144. Survival Analysis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Survival analysis </strong>is a technique used to analyze data about binomial or dichotomous outcomes, like death vs. survival, etc.</li>\n<li>One of the simplest methods used in survival analysis is the <strong>life table analysis</strong>.</li>\n<li>Another is the <strong>Kaplan-Meier</strong> analysis which involves calculating the <strong>survival function</strong> which is given as, <strong>survival function at time t = Number of patients surviving longer than times t / Total number of patients.</strong></li>\n<li>Life tables and survival functions are graphically represented in a <strong>Kaplan-Meier plot or curve</strong>.</li>\n<li>Tests which are used to compare the <strong>survival curves</strong> or <strong>Kaplan-Meier curves</strong> are <strong>Mantel-Haenszel test </strong>or <strong>log rank test</strong> and the <strong>Cox regression</strong> or <strong>Cox proportional hazards analysis.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1182, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0059. Medico-legal importance of age', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\430\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Age&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Medico-legal importance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>7 months period of gestation</strong></td>\n<td>Attainment of viability by fetus – <strong>infanticide</strong> can’t be charged if fetus is proved to be less than 7 months of age.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&gt;5 years</strong></td>\n<td>Criminal responsibility as per <strong>railways act</strong>. &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&lt;7 years</strong></td>\n<td>No criminal responsibility as per <strong>Section 82 IPC</strong>. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>10 years</strong></td>\n<td>Abducting a child below 10 years for the sake of moveable property amounts to <strong>kidnap</strong> (369 IPC)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>7 – 12 years</strong></td>\n<td>Criminal responsibility if he/she is of sufficient maturity to understand and judge the nature and consequences of the act <strong>(Section 83 IPC)</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&lt;12 years</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Consent</strong> by the <strong>parent</strong> or <strong>guardian</strong> is needed before examination of the patient.</p>\n<p>Not punishable under the <strong>Railway Act</strong>.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&lt;14 years </strong></td>\n<td>Cannot be employed in factory jobs.&nbsp;(<strong>Factory Act</strong>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>14 – 15 years</strong></td>\n<td>Can be employed in nonhazardous factory jobs in the daytime.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&gt;15 years</strong></td>\n<td>Can be employed in any job</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&lt;16 years</strong></td>\n<td>Taking away a <strong>boy</strong> without consent of parent or guardian amounts to&nbsp;<strong>kidnapping</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&lt;18 years</strong></td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Juvenile (boy and girl)&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Taking away a <strong>girl </strong>without consent of parent or guardian amounts to<strong>&nbsp;kidnapping</strong></li>\n<li>Sexual intercourse with a girl with or without her consent amounts to rape (<strong>Section 375 IPC</strong>)</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&gt;/=18 years</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Attainment of <strong>majority</strong>&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Can give <strong>valid consent</strong> to suffer any harm not known to cause death or grievous hurt.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Valid consent given by a girl for <strong>sexual intercourse.</strong>&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Can make <strong>valid will</strong>.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Legal age of <strong>marriage for girls</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1183, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0058. Ossification centres appearing before birth', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>7 weeks in utero - Tibial Shaft</li>\n<li>8 weeks in utero - Femoral &amp; Fibular Shaft</li>\n<li>9 weeks in utero - metatarsals</li>\n<li>6 months in utero – Calcaneum</li>\n<li>7 months in utero – talus</li>\n<li>9 months in utero– Cuboid</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1184, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0057. Appearance of ossification centres of carpal bones', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Capitate – 2 months (1-3 months)</li>\n<li>Hamate – 3 months (2-4 months)</li>\n<li>Triquetrum – 3 years</li>\n<li>Lunate, Scaphoid, trapezoid, Trapezium –&nbsp;4 years in females and 5 years in males</li>\n<li>Pisiform –&nbsp;9 or 10 years in females and 12 years in males</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1185, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0056. Fusion of skull sutures and closure of fontanelles', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Fusion of skull sutures and closure of fontanelles:</p>\n<table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Lateral &amp; occipital&nbsp;fontanelles&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&lt;2months</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Posterior&nbsp;fontanelles</td>\n<td>6-8 weeks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Anterior&nbsp;fontanelles</td>\n<td>1.5-2 years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Metopic suture</td>\n<td>9 Months</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Basiocciput with basisphenoid</td>\n<td>18-21 years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sagittal suture:<br>\n<ul>\n<li>Posterior 1/3rd</li>\n<li>Anterior 1/3rd</li>\n<li>Middle 1/3rd</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>30-40 years<br>40-50 Years<br>50-60 years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Coronal suture:<br>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower half</li>\n<li>Upper half</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>40-50 years<br>50-60years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lambdoid suture</td>\n<td>45 years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Squamous temporal suture</td>\n<td>&gt;80 years</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1186, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0055. Permanent dentition', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>First molar - 6 years</li>\n<li>Central incisor - 7 years</li>\n<li>Lateral incisor - 8 years</li>\n<li>First premolar - 9 years</li>\n<li>Second premolar -10 years</li>\n<li>Canine - 11&nbsp; years</li>\n<li>Second molar -12-14 years</li>\n<li>Third molar -17-25 years</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Mnenomic: Mumma Is In Pain, Paapa Can Make Medicine</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1187, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0054. Temporary dentition', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Lower central incisor - 6 months</li>\n<li>Upper central incisor - 7 months</li>\n<li>Upper lateral incisor - 8 months</li>\n<li>Lower lateral incisor&nbsp; - 9 months</li>\n<li>First molar-1 year</li>\n<li>Canine- 1 ½&nbsp;years</li>\n<li>Second molar– 2 years</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1188, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0053. Indices for determination of race and sex of an individual', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>To determine the sex of an individual -</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/6c5339f818154bd5a2224da77db2ecc7x377x228.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Krogmans degree of accuracy in sexing adult skeletal remains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Entire skeleton – 100%</li>\n<li>Pelvis alone – 95%</li>\n<li>Skull alone – 90%</li>\n<li>Pelvis plus skull – 98%</li>\n<li>Long bones alone – 80%</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>To determine the race of an individual -&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/149e51cb37a046d5b49316bbc90fcb6fx435x252.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1189, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0050. Cephalic index', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type of skull</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Cephalic Index</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dolicocephalic</td>\n<td>70-75</td>\n<td>Pure aryans, Aborigines, Negroes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mesaticephalic</td>\n<td>75-80</td>\n<td>Europeans &amp; Chinese</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Brachycephalic</td>\n<td>80-85</td>\n<td>Mongolians</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1190, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM2391. Contributory negligence', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Contributory negligence</strong> occurs when a <strong>patient</strong> or his <strong>personal attendant</strong> shows unreasonable conduct or absence of ordinary care, which when combined with the negligence of the doctor, has contributed to the injury. In this case, the patient’s or attendant’s negligence should be the direct, proximate cause and without which the injury would not have occurred.</p>\n<p>So, contributory negligence occurs when <strong>both the doctor and patient are negligent</strong>. The direct or proximate cause of the injury should be the patient’s negligence, which means that if the patient was not negligent, the injury could have been prevented.</p>\n<p>Contributory negligence usually occurs when the doctor is negligent and the<strong> patient:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fails to give an accurate medical history, and as a result, the doctor may misdiagnose or mistreat the patient.</li>\n<li>Fails to follow the doctor’s instructions</li>\n<li>Refuses to take the treatment</li>\n<li>Leaves the hospital against doctor’s advice</li>\n<li>Does not inform the doctor or seek further medical assistance if the symptoms persist or worsens.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Contributory negligence is a defence </strong>for doctor’s negligence in civil cases. However, from case to case, the liability of a doctor may vary from complete non-liability to substantial liability for the damages. Under the <strong>doctrine of comparative negligence</strong>, the court has the right to hold both parties liable for their negligent actions.</p>\n<p><strong>Limitations / Exceptions to contributory negligence:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>A. The doctor will be held guilty in the following conditions:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>1. The doctor failed to provide proper instructions to the patient</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Ex: </strong>Doctor applies a tight plaster cast (<strong>doctor is</strong> <strong>negligent</strong>) to the patient’s leg and did not tell the patient to inform if he develops any numbness (<strong>no</strong> <strong>proper</strong> <strong>instruction</strong>). The patient develops numbness and has not informed the doctor (<strong>patient is negligent</strong>). After few days patient developed a permanent injury.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;2.&nbsp;<strong>Last clear chance doctrine: </strong>It is applicable when the doctor fails to take necessary action to prevent damage due to a negligent act of the patient, even after getting a clear chance to take such action.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Ex: </strong>Doctor applies a tight plaster cast (<strong>doctor is</strong> <strong>negligent</strong>) to the patient’s leg and told the patient to inform if he develops any numbness (<strong>gave proper</strong> <strong>instruction</strong>). The patient developed numbness and has not informed the doctor (<strong>patient is</strong> <strong>negligent</strong>). Next day patient informed the doctor, but the doctor did not remove the cast and said he was busy (<strong>There was a clear last chance, but the doctor neglected again</strong>). After few days patient developed a permanent injury.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>B. The doctor/person will not be held guilty in the following conditions:</strong></p>\n<p>1.&nbsp;<strong>Avoidable consequences rule: </strong>It occurs when an injury is caused due to doctor’s negligence, and the patient has done a negligent act, which further aggravated the injury caused by the doctor, and the patient could have avoided the consequence by not doing such act. In such cases, the<strong> doctor need not pay anything</strong>, and the<strong> patient will be held guilty</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Ex:</strong> A patient had a lacerated wound. The doctor examined the patient and had not done any dressing or provided any antibiotics (the doctor is negligent). However, the doctor instructed the patient to avoid contamination and asked him to visit the clinic next week. When the patient went home, he applied cow dung on his wound every day thinking that the wound would heal faster and didnt visit the doctor after one week. The wound got infected and developed pus and aggravated the injury.</span></li>\n<li><span>Here, <strong>despite the doctor being negligent </strong>in the first instance, the <strong>patient is responsible for his injury</strong> as he <strong>performed an unnecessary, avoidable act</strong>, which aggravated the injury. The doctor need not pay anything.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>2.&nbsp;<strong>Good Samaritan doctrine: </strong>A person who assists another person who is in serious danger cannot be charged with contributory negligence. unless such assistance is reckless or rash.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Ex:</strong> A person was travelling on a road and saw a car accident, where the victim was unconscious and was stuck inside the car. He called the ambulance. The paramedical staff instructed him not to mobilize the victim until they arrived. Meanwhile, the car was caught in fire (<strong>serious danger</strong>), and the person tried to remove the victim carefully out of the car <strong>(assisted the victim and was not reckless)</strong>. However, the victim already had a cervical bone fracture due to the accident, which got mobilized while he was being removed out of the car and as a result, suffered an injury to the spine that led to paralysis (<strong>victim’s injury was aggravated</strong>). In such a case, the good samaritan doctrine would apply and the person who tried to help, <strong>will not be charged under contributory negligence.</strong></span></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1191, 'Forensic Medicine,', 'PM2131. Medical Termination of Pregnancy Act - MTP Act 1971', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>MTP Act with 2021 amendments&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Indications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Therapeutic </strong>- to save the life of the mother</li>\n<li><strong>Eugenic </strong>- to prevent the&nbsp;risk of the child being born with serious mental or physical abnormality i.e. first-trimester viral infections, teratogenic drug intake, radiation exposure</li>\n<li><strong>Humanitarian </strong>-&nbsp;pregnancy resulted from rape or incest</li>\n<li><strong>Social </strong>-&nbsp;pregnancy resulted from failure of contraceptives&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Rules:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Only a <strong>registered medical practitioner</strong> who is qualified (one who has assisted in the performance of 25 cases of MTP in a recognized hospital) can terminate a pregnancy.</li>\n<li>MTP should be carried out in a government or <strong>government-recognized hospital</strong>.&nbsp;Private hospitals may take up MTP if they obtain a license from the chief medical officer of the district.</li>\n<li>The termination of pregnancy by a person, who is not a registered medical practitioner (the person concerned), or in an unrecognised hospital (administrative head) shall be punished with rigorous imprisonment for a term not less than <strong>2 years</strong>, but which may extend to 7 years.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Consent</strong>:</p>\n<p>The consent of the woman is required for conducting an abortion. The written consent of the guardian is required if the woman is minor or mentally ill. Consent of the husband or partner is not necessary.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If the woman is not willing, abortion cannot be performed at the request of the husband alone. The woman need not produce proof of her age.&nbsp;It is enough for the woman to say that she was raped, and it is not necessary that a complaint was lodged with the police.</p>\n<p><strong>Opinion of doctors:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Till 20 weeks - 1 doctors opinion</li>\n<li>20 to 24 weeks - 2 doctors opinion</li>\n<li>For substantial fetal anomalies - approval from the medical board consisting of obstetrician, paediatrician, radiologist and a person appointed by the state</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Upper limit of MTP:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Up to <strong>24 weeks</strong> of gestation in victims of <strong>rape</strong> and incest, fetal anomalies, or congenital malformations</li>\n<li>Up to <strong>20 weeks</strong> in case of <strong>contraception failure</strong> (any female with her partner)</li>\n<li>At <strong>any gestational age</strong> for substantial <strong>fetal anomalies</strong> decided by the medical board</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Confidentiality:</strong></p>\n<p>A <strong>register</strong> for recording the details of MTP must be kept for at least <strong>5 years</strong>. The patients name must not be entered, only the reference number is used.&nbsp;Unlawful disclosure of patients details is punishable with 1-year imprisonment&nbsp;± fine.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1192, 'Forensic Medicine,', 'PM2059. IPC Sec 84, MNaghtens rule', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>MNaghtens rule,&nbsp;Section 84 IPC:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Criminal responsibility of the insane.</p>\n<p>It states that an accused is not criminally responsible if he was suffering from:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Defect of reason and </strong><strong>unsoundness of mind:&nbsp;</strong>the law&nbsp;recognizes only those diseases which impair the thinking abilities of the mind. So, not all medically insane people are legally insane, as emotional disturbances that affect the mind are not considered if they do not directly affect cognition.</li>\n<li><strong>That he did not know the nature and the quality of the act he is doing:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;the law needs the unsoundness of mind to exist at the time of the act to such a degree that the person is not aware of what he is doing and whether it is right or wrong to do. Absence of a motive or forethought is also considered as a criteria for determining unsoundness of mind.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1193, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1027. Sexual Offences', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>IPC section</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Section it deals with</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Punishment</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Type of offense</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>375</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Definition of Rape</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\3\>\n<p>376</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>376A</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Punishment for Rape</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment of not less than 10 years which may extend to imprisonment for life.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; non-bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Persons committing the offense of rape on a woman under 16 years of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment of not be less than 20 years which may extend to imprisonment for life.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; Non-Bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>The person committing&nbsp;an offense of rape and inflicting injury which causes death or causes the woman to be in a persistent vegetative state.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment of not less than 20 years may extend to imprisonment for life or with death.&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; non-bailable</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376AB</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>The person committing an offense of rape on a woman under 12 years of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment of not less than 20 years but which may extend to imprisonment for life with fine or with death</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; Non-Bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376B</p>\n</td>\n<td>Sexual intercourse by the husband upon his wife during separation</td>\n<td>\n<p>Imprisonment for not less than 2 years but which may extend to 7 years and with a fine.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable(only on a complaint of the victim); Bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376C</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Sexual intercourse by a person in authority (police officer, public servant, member of armed forces, management or staff of a jail, remand home or other places of custody and management or staff of a hospital) who&nbsp;<strong>induces or seduces</strong> any female inmate of such jail, remand home, place, or institution to have sexual intercourse with him, such sexual intercourse not amounting to the offense of rape.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment for not less than 5 years but which may extend to 10 years and with a fine.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; non-bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376D</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gang Rape</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment for not less than 20 years which may extend to imprisonment for life with fine</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; non-bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376DA</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gang rape on a woman under 16 years of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rigorous imprisonment for life and with fine</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cognizable; Non-Bailable</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376DB</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gang rape on a woman under 12 years of age</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Imprisonment for life with fine or with death</p>\n</td>\n<td>Cognizable; Non-Bailable</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>376E</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Repeat offenders</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Imprisonment for life or with death</p>\n</td>\n<td>Cognizable; Non-Bailable&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>354</p>\n</td>\n<td>Indecent assault /Outrage of modesty</td>\n<td>Imprisonment for up to 2 years, or with fine.</td>\n<td>Cognizable; Non-Bailable&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<p>The above sections are in accordance with The Criminal Law (Amendment) Bill, 2018.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1194, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1025. Doctor and The Court', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\0\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>IPC section</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Deals with</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>191</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Giving false evidence (perjury)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>192</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Fabricating false evidence</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>193</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Punishment for false evidence</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Judicial proceedings: up to 7 yrs of imprisonment and fine</li>\n<li>Any other case: up to 3 yrs of imprisonment and fine</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>196</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Using evidence known to be false</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>197</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Issuing or signing a false certificate</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>201</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Causing disappearance of evidence of offense or giving false information to screen offender</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1195, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1024. Consent', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>IPC Section</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Provisions under the Act</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>87</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Act not intended and not known to be likely to cause death or grievous hurt, done by consent is not an offense.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>88</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>An act done by consent in good faith for a person’s benefit is not an offense.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>89</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>An act done in good faith for the benefit of a child under 12 years of age or an insane person, with the consent of a parent or guardian is not an offense.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>90</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Consent is invalid if</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Given under fear or misconception.</li>\n<li>Given by an insane person</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>92</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>The act is done in good faith without consent in&nbsp;the following situations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Emergency (No need to take consent during emergencies)</li>\n<li>The person is incapable of giving consent</li>\n<li>The person has no guardian to give consent</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>95</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Act causing slight harm is not an offense</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1196, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1023. Criminal Responsibilities', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>IPC Section</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Deals with</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>82</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>A child under 7 years is not liable for the act.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>83</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Child of 7–12 years if not attained proper mental maturity is not liable for the act.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>84 &nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>McNaughtens rule -&nbsp;</strong>A person of unsound mind is not liable for the act.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>85</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>A person who under involuntary intoxication has commited an act is not liable for the act.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>86</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>A person who under voluntary intoxication commits an act is liable for the act.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1197, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM2132. Hyperthermic disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\408\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Hyperthermic disorders</td>\n<td>Mechanisms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heat edema</td>\n<td>Cutaneous vasodilation and pooling of interstitial fluid leads to swelling of hands, feet, and ankles</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heat syncope</td>\n<td>Vasodilation and volume depletion(from sweating) following exercise or prolonged standing&nbsp;with consequent systemic and cerebral hypotension</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heat cramps</td>\n<td>Deficiency of sodium, potassium, and water at an intracellular level, leading to intermittent, painful, and involuntary spasmodic contractions of skeletal muscles</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heat exhaustion</td>\n<td>\n<p>Results from prolonged strenuous activity. There is water or salt depletion, but thermoregulatory mechanisms are maintained.&nbsp;Temperature &lt;&nbsp;40.5° C</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heatstroke</td>\n<td>\n<p>Thermoregulatory mechanisms are lost</p>\n<p>Temperature &gt; 40.5° C</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1198, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0761. Difference between ante mortem and post-mortem abrasion', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Trait</td>\n<td>Ante mortem wounds &nbsp;</td>\n<td>Post-mortem wounds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Site</td>\n<td>Anywhere on the body</td>\n<td>Usually over bony prominences &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Colour</td>\n<td>Bright reddish brown</td>\n<td>Yellowish, translucent, Parchment like&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Exudation</td>\n<td>More</td>\n<td>Less&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Microscopic</td>\n<td>Intravital reaction and congestion seen</td>\n<td>\n<p>No intravital reaction</p>\n<p>No congestion&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1199, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0074. Order of Putrefaction', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Larynx and trachea – first organ to putrify</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>Stomach, intestine, and spleen</li>\n<li>Liver and lungs</li>\n<li>Brain</li>\n<li>Heart</li>\n<li>Kidney and bladder</li>\n<li>Prostate and uterus – virgin uterus resists putrefaction whereas uterus soon after delivery putrefies rapidly.</li>\n<li>Skin, muscle, tendon</li>\n<li>Bones</li>\n</ul>\n<p><br><strong>NOTE</strong>: This is only a generalised order of putrefaction, as each case must be assessed as per the attending factors, both endogenous and exogenous.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1200, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0073. Difference between Cadaveric Rigidity (Rigor mortis) and Cadaveric Spasm (Instantaneous rigor)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trait</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Cadaveric rigidity</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Cadaveric spasm</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Production</strong></td>\n<td>Freezing and exposure to a temperature above 65<sup>0</sup>C will produce rigor</td>\n<td>Cannot be produced by any method after death</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>\n<td>Reduction of ATP</td>\n<td>Not clear</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Predisposing factors</strong></td>\n<td>Nil</td>\n<td>Sudden death, excitement, fear, etc</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Time of onset</strong></td>\n<td>1 – 2 hours after death</td>\n<td>Instantaneous</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Muscles involved</strong></td>\n<td>All muscles – both voluntary and involuntary</td>\n<td>Single group of voluntary muscles</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Muscle stiffening</strong></td>\n<td>Not marked: can be overcome by moderate force</td>\n<td>Marked: Great force is required to overcome</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Molecular death</strong></td>\n<td>Occurs</td>\n<td>Doesnt occur</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Body heat</strong></td>\n<td>Cold</td>\n<td>Warm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Electrical stimuli</strong></td>\n<td>Muscles do not respond</td>\n<td>Muscles respond</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Muscular reaction</strong></td>\n<td>Acidic</td>\n<td>Alkaline</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Medicolegal importance</strong></td>\n<td>Indicates the time of death</td>\n<td>Indicates manner of death</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1201, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0072. Color of Postmortem Hypostasis in Various Conditions', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Poisoning/Condition</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Postmortem staining</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Carbon monoxide&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cherry red</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cyanides &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Brick red/dark pink</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Potassium chlorate</p>\n</td>\n<td>Chocolate brown&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Phosphorous&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Dark brown&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nitrites &nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Red-brown</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Hydrogen sulphide</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Bluish-green</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Opium&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Greyish/black</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Asphyxia</td>\n<td>Dark purple</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hypothermia</td>\n<td>Bright pink</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Septic abortion (Cl. Perfringens infection)</td>\n<td>Pale bronze</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1202, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0071. Tests for Confirming Cessation of Breathing', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The recommended method is thorough auscultation for breath sounds by a stethoscope. <strong>No audible breath sounds</strong> on continuous auscultation of upper part of chest and in front of or on the larynx <strong>for minimum of 5 minutes</strong>, confirms cessation of breathing.</p>\n<p>Other tests: &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feather test </strong>– no movement of a feather held in front of the nose. &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Mirror test </strong>– mirror held in front of the nose does not turn dim due to any moisture of breath. &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Winslow’s test </strong>– no movement of surface of water in bowl kept on the chest.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1203, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0070. Tests for Confirming Cessation of Circulation', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>No audible heart sounds</strong> on continuous auscultation on precordial area of chest for a <strong>minimum of 5 minutes</strong>&nbsp;is suggestive of cessation of circulation and a <strong>flat ECG recording for 5 minutes</strong> confirms this.</p>\n<p><strong>Other tests:</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Magnus’s test (Ligature test)—</strong>fingers fail to show congestion distal to a ligature applied at their base. &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Diaphanous test (Transillumination test)</strong>—Failure to show redness in the web space between the fingers on transillumination from behind. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Icard’s test</strong>—fluorescent dye on being injected at a given site in a dead body fails to produces any discolouration.</li>\n<li><strong>Fingernail test</strong>—no blanching and filling of blood in the fingernail on application of pressure and release.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1204, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0069. Suspended animation and its causes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Suspended animation </strong>is a condition where<strong> signs of life are absent as functions are interrupted for sometime or are reduced to minimum.</strong></p>\n<p>It can be produced voluntarily by yoga practitioners. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>It is seen in following conditions</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>After anaesthesia</li>\n<li>Cholera</li>\n<li>Concussion</li>\n<li>Drowning</li>\n<li>Electrocution</li>\n<li>Hypothermia</li>\n<li>Insanity</li>\n<li>Newborn</li>\n<li>Narcotics</li>\n<li>Shock</li>\n<li>Sunstroke</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1205, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0068. Harvard criteria for brain death', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Unreceptivity and unresponsivity &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>No movements &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>Apnoea &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>Absence of elicitable reflexes &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>Isoelectric EEG (confirmatory)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1206, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1458. Autopsy Techniques', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Virchows</strong>&nbsp;<strong>technique</strong>: Organs are removed <strong>one by one</strong> from the body to be examined. Here the cranial cavity is opened first, then the spinal cord, followed by thoracic, cervical, and abdominal organs in that order.</li>\n<li><strong>Ghons technique</strong>: Here the organs are removed<strong> en bloc</strong>. The thoracic, cervical, pelvic, and abdominal organs are removed as organ blocks.</li>\n<li><strong>Rokitanskys technique</strong>: This is characterized by <strong>in situ</strong> dissection in part combined with<strong><em> en bloc</em>&nbsp;</strong>removal like Ghons technique. The dissection begins at the neck and slowly works its way down the body and the organ is removed as a bloc. A cut is first made at the larynx to separate the esophagus from the pharynx. The larynx and trachea are pulled downward and using a scalpel, the chest organs are cut. The diaphragm is cut to expose the abdominal organs. Other organs like the bladder and rectum are separated from the body by using a scalpel to cut the pelvic ligaments.</li>\n<li><strong>Letulles technique</strong>: Thoracic, cervical, abdominal, and pelvic organs are removed <strong>en masse</strong> meaning as one big organ block. It allows the body to be made available for examination in less than 30 minutes as the process of removing the organs is much quicker.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1207, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1457. Autopsy: Types Of Incision', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type of incision</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Procedure</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Indication</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Advantage</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>I-Shaped Incision</strong></td>\n<td>Extends from <strong>symphysis menti to symphysis pubis</strong>, taking a curve towards the left around the umbilicus.</td>\n<td>It is used routinely in practice</td>\n<td>It is <strong>simple and convenient</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Y-Shaped Incision</strong></td>\n<td>Commences at the <strong>anterior axillary fold</strong> on the chest on either side, runs downwards and anteriorly <strong>beneath the breasts</strong> as to meet at the xiphisternum and then run downwards as in the \I\-shaped incision&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Preferred in <strong>females</strong></td>\n<td>It <strong>prevents cutting of the chest</strong> skin in the midline.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Modified Y-Shaped Incision</strong></td>\n<td>Commences at the <strong>angle of mandible</strong> on either side, brought forwards, downwards to meet at the suprasternal notch and then run downwards as in the “I” shaped incision.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Preferred when a <strong>detailed study of neck structures</strong> required, e.g. asphyxial death due to neck compression.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>It has better exposure and allows the study of neck structures.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Elongated X-shaped Incision</strong></td>\n<td>Used to dissect out <strong>subcutaneous structures</strong> in the back to identify and evaluate the extent of blunt injuries.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Should be practiced in cases of custodial death.&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Helpful in the&nbsp;<strong>reconstruction of events</strong> prior to death.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b50f95de210f4d069f005b0844c8e10ex1264x1306.JPEG\><img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/49bf2290516345ddbf128a1ea88ec8e3x1267x1297.JPEG\><img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f798ddeaaa0f45c292cb0be7ab3f3a40x1262x1293.JPEG\><img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e036f4fc17f1412ca5f8b027908a66a8x1261x1287.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1208, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM2193. Differences between antemortem and postmortem burns', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p class=\p1\>&nbsp;</p>\n<table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Characteristics</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Antemortem burns</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Postmortem burns</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Line of redness</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Vital sign</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Vesication / Blister</td>\n<td>Present and true, contains serous fluid</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Present but are false, contains PM gases +/- thin clear fluid</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Reparative process</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Internal organs</td>\n<td>Congested</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Usually burnt+emits peculiar odor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Blood colour</td>\n<td>Cherry red due to CO</td>\n<td>Normal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Curling’s ulcer</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Inflamed Payer’s patches</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Carbon/ soot particles in the trachea, bronchus</p>\n</td>\n<td>Present</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Peripheral zone of burn&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>Shows an increase in enzyme reaction</td>\n<td>Does not show an increase in enzyme reaction</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1209, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM2129. Most common injuries in a Road Traffic Accident', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>Scenario</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Injury</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Unrestrained driver</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Face and head injury</p>\n<p>Cervical spine injury</p>\n<p>Steering wheel impact - Thoracic injuries</p>\n<p>Pelvic fracture</p>\n<p>Leg fracture</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Seatbealt injury</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Bruising</p>\n<p>Rupture of the mesentery or small intestine</p>\n<p>Abdominal aorta injury</p>\n<p>Lumbar spine fracture</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Airbag injury</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Facial bruising</p>\n<p>Amputation of fingers</p>\n<p>Fractures arms</p>\n<p>Cervical spine and head injury</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Front-seat passenger&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>The pattern of injuries is similar to that of the driver, but this position in the car is even more dangerous.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rear-seat passenger</strong></td>\n<td>The injuries occurring are more fatal compared to front-seat passengers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Motorcyclist&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Basal skull fracture - Hinge fracture</p>\n<p>Brush abrasions</p>\n<p>Tailgating</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pedestrian</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Lower limb injuries</p>\n<p>Head injuries</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1210, 'Radiology,', 'PM2128. Diffuse Axonal Injury', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>The mechanism of diffuse axonal injury (DAI) is primarily a non-impact rotational acceleration-deceleration injury. This leads to the deformation of the axons by stretching them.</p>\n<p>Pathology of DAI:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Changes in permeability of the axolemma</li>\n<li>Axonal swelling</li>\n<li>Intracellular calcium accumulation</li>\n<li>Proteolysis</li>\n<li>The collapse of the cytoskeleton</li>\n<li><strong>Retraction balls</strong> or globes - bulbous and clubbed axons. Seen earliest at 12-18 hours.&nbsp;The number of retraction balls begins to decrease<strong> after 2-3 weeks after injury</strong> and a cluster of microglial cells appears followed by astrocytosis and demyelination.</li>\n<li>Immuno-histochemistry shows beta-amyloid precursor protein - the <strong>most reliable</strong> indicator of axon damage. Seen earliest at 2-3 hours.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Image shows scattered axonal retraction balls stained with Congo Red:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/cf55a5006e2e477ebb43d97d7e373764x1280x1139.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1211, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM1808. Types of bullets:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>1. Ricochet bullet: </strong>Bullet first strikes an <strong>intermediate object</strong> and then after being <strong>reflected strikes the target.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/c162353ba8714028bacb6d2cd96989b4x304x191.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>2.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Yawning bullet: </strong>Travels in an <strong>irregular fashion</strong> and produces a key<strong> hole entry wound</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/56007c1b13db447580f082614e2dd2b0x300x81.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>3.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Tandem (Piggy Back) Bullet Effect: Two bullets are ejected one after the other</strong>; first bullet failed to leave the barrel and is ejected by subsequently fired bullet. This occurs due to <strong>defect in the weapon</strong> or due to <strong>faulty ammunition</strong> or with <strong>loaded firearms unused for several years.&nbsp;</strong><strong>Tandem cartridge</strong> (also called duplex cartridge) is a single cartridge containing two bullets.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/09c02e2f5842489795a6ea1a2aaa411ex312x135.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>4.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Frangible bullet: Fragments </strong>on hitting the target.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/bcc46f8a8a87488594e05754d8eed4f0x290x152.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>5.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Dum Dum bullet: Tip is chiseled out, fragments extensively on impact.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/3b142ec1047d4358a842fef7639d67e4x283x152.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>6.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Tumbling bullet: &nbsp;Rotates end on end </strong>during its motion.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/5850c87b5a6c4dbea3d9b14ac43e01e4x290x130.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>7.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Souvenir bullet: &nbsp;</strong>Bullet <strong>left in the body</strong> for a long time and <strong>covered with dense fibrous connective tissue.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/61f5ab7bf3924308b3122719651e4919x290x138.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>8.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Tracer bullet: </strong>This type of bullet <strong>leaves a visible mark or trace </strong>while in flight so that the gunner can observe the strike of shot. Rear portion of bullet is filled with <strong>mixture of barium nitrate, strontium nitrate and powdered magnesium </strong>which is ignited by the burning powder. Mixture burns and sheds red sparks which makes the projectile visible to naked eye which enables shooter to make aiming corrections.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/3cbe6e1a20774317b382f79f78bfa917x1280x697.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>9.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Incendiary bullet: </strong>It is filled with<strong> white phosphorous </strong>and<strong> ignites the target.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>From left to right : Blank with frangible wooden bullet, ball, tracer and incendiary bullets</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/376e0233099242b9a43903052e22c60fx800x600.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1212, 'Forensic Medicine,', 'PM1185. Whiplash Injury (Cervical Acceleration-Deceleration Injuries)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Mechanism of injury</strong>:&nbsp;Collision causing the occupant’s body to be forced against the car seat, while the head flips backwards causing&nbsp;<strong>hyperextension</strong> and then recoil into&nbsp;<strong>flexion</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Clinical features</strong>: Neck pain and stiffness are common symptoms. Less commonly,&nbsp;headache, dizziness, blurring of vision, paraesthesia in the arms, temporomandibular discomfort and tinnitus.</p>\n<p><strong>Examination findings</strong>: Tenderness of neck muscles, restriction of neck movements.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Clinical presentation can be <strong>graded</strong> using the&nbsp;<strong>Quebec Task Force</strong> grading system:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>0 - No neck symptoms or signs</li>\n<li>1 - Neck pain, stiffness and tenderness</li>\n<li>2 - Neck symptoms and musculoskeletal signs</li>\n<li>3 - Neck symptoms and neurological signs</li>\n<li>4 - Neck symptoms and fracture or dislocation</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Investigations</strong>: X-ray may be normal or show loss of cervical lordosis due to muscle spasm. <strong>MRI&nbsp;</strong>is done if there are neurological signs.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Treatment</strong>: Simple pain-relieving measures, including NSAIDs during the first few weeks.&nbsp;Graded exercises and isometric strengthening exercises after the pain subsides.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b9d35b51d252478a87c2f5659b58de31x1158x622.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1213, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0980. Kronlein Shot', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>This is a condition wherein a large portion of the brain is thrown out (herniated) of the exit wound but still intact/attached to the wound</strong>.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/0029452971af49589763aec2e12a6726x623x417.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1214, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0979. Types of Blast Injuries', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Blast injury type</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Mechanism of injury</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\245\>\n<p><strong>Health impact</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Primary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Rapid crushing over pressure</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\245\>\n<p>Tympanic membrane (<strong>most common), </strong>Lung (2<sup>nd</sup> most common), eyes, GIT</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Secondary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Flying debris</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\245\>\n<p><strong>MARSHAL’s triad </strong>(triad of abrasions, contuisions, lacerations)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Tertiary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Blast wind</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\245\>\n<p>Victim is thrown in air and strikes other objects leading to fracture and blunt trauma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Quaternary</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Any complicating factor not in the other three categories</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\245\>\n<p>Burns, histotoxicanoxia, and crush injuries</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>The specific pulmonary injury of air blast is known as blast lung.</li>\n<li>When the explosion is in the water the pressure changes are called underwater blast. <strong>Intestinal damage</strong> is very common in underwater blast injuries.</li>\n<li>Solid blast refers to the wave of energy that spreads through the rigid structure when an explosive is detonated near it and people in contact with its structure can be injured.</li>\n<li>Caecum is most sensitive to intestinal blast injury.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1215, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0977. Rayalaseema Phenomenon', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>This is an <strong>artifact</strong>.</li>\n<li>Here, a victim <strong>was first killed by stab injury</strong> and then to mislead the investigating officer, the <strong>criminal stuffed the stab wound with a bullet manually</strong>.</li>\n<li>This was <strong>unraveled only after a meticulous autopsy examination</strong>.</li>\n<li>Since the <strong>whole incident occurred in the Rayalaseema, a geographic region of Andhra Pradesh State</strong> in India, the terminology for the phenomenon was coined accordingly.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1216, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0976. Difference between Wound of Entry and Exit', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p><strong>Characteristics</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p><strong>Wound of entry</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p><strong>Wound of exit</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Size</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Smaller than the diameter of the bullet.</p>\n<p>In close discharge, skin is torn, hence size is increased.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Bigger than the diameter of the bullet.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Margin</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Inverted</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Everted</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Soiling of wound</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Abrasion collar</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Contusion collar</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Grease collar</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Bleeding</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Less</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>More</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Foreign bodies</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Dispersion of pallets (shotgun)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Protrusion of fat</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Bright red (Carboxy Hb)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve (Near shot)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>X-ray Metallic Ring</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Muzzle impression</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve (contact shot)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Blast effect</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>+ve (contact shot)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>-ve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1217, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0975. Summary of Wound of entry for Rifled Firearm at different Ranges', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Characteristics</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Contact shot</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Close shot</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Near shot</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Distant shot</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Range</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>In-touch with skin</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>2.5-7.5 cm</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>30-60 cm</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&gt;60 cm</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Size</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Largest size</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Bullet size</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Smaller</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Smallest</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Shape</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Stellate</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Circular</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Circular</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Circular</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Muzzle end imprint</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive </strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Edge eversion</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Blackening</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Tattooing</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Singeing</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Positive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Abrasion collar</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Grease collar</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Positive</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Contact shot:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/60d9c33411084d6ebb4206179e5ab21fx453x432.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>This is a contact gunshot entrance wound. Since the barrel contacts the skin, the gases released by the fired round go into the subcutaneous tissue and cause the star-shaped laceration. Note also the grey-black discoloration from the soot, as well as the faint abrasion ring.</p>\n<p><strong>Close shot:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/74a1ae8e4ced4b14ab1c3e64fc3c1f86x515x509.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>The wound has been washed and there is stippling. This indicates a close-range gunshot wound because both stippling and fouling are present.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Distant shot:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Distant range entrance gunshot wound with eccentric abrasion rim.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/e6ba1b7acac54301a1df10c6d5639536x551x413.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1218, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0974. Products of firing and their effects', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Components</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Distance traveled</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Effects produced</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Gun flame</p>\n<p>Gunsmoke</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>15 cm (6”)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Heat combustion effect-&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Burning and singeing</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Soot Particles/</p>\n<p>Gunpowder</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>30 cm (12”)</p>\n&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Blackening/\n<p>Smudging</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Fine or coarse particles</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>90 cm (36”)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tattooing/peppering/ powder stippling-&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Become impregnated into the skin and cannot be washed or scrubbed off.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Gases</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Contact shot</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Blast effects</p>\n<p>Facial distortion</p>\n<p>Cherry red discoloration</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Bullet</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Variable</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Abrasion collar</p>\n<p>Grease collar</p>\n<p>Wound of entry</p>\n<p>Wound of exit</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Medicolegal importance</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Smudging and tattooing effects can help to assess the range of firing, as below\n<ul>\n<li>If both are present, the range of firing is close or near shot.</li>\n<li>If both are absent, the range of firing is a distant shot.</li>\n<li>If both are found deeper, i.e. on the inner aspect of the wound, the range is contact shot.</li>\n<li>If only tattooing is present, the range is near shot.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Thus as the range increases, blackening fades first, followed by tattooing, the reason being their causative agents cannot travel beyond a fixed distance.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1219, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0973. Products of Firing and its Effects', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Flame and hot air</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Smoke/soot (completely burnt powder)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Partially burnt and unburnt powder particle</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Bullet</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Scorching</p>\n<p>Burning and singeing</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Blackening /smudging</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Tattooing</strong>/peppering/powder strippling</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Wound of entry</p>\n<p>Grease collar</p>\n<p>Abrasion collar</p>\n<p>Wound of exit</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Soiling of the Wound:</p>\n<p>Smudging/blackening:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is due to the deposition of smoke particles, lead or metal of which the missile is made of.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/b541a09e4730441aac9449fb519c0ad4x408x416.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Tattooing/peppering</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>It is due to deposition of fine or coarse gunpowder particles, which become truly impregnated into and mark the skin, and cannot be washed or scrubbed off</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/fd70e021746945e6860ffe7cf9af61c5x387x390.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Medicolegal importance</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Smudging and tattooing effects can help to assess the range of firing, as below\n<ul>\n<li>If both are present, the range of firing is close or near shot.</li>\n<li>If both are absent, the range of firing is a distant shot.</li>\n<li>If both are found deeper, i.e. on the inner aspect of the wound, the range is contact shot.</li>\n<li>If only tattooing is present, the range is near shot.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Thus as the range increases, blackening fades first, followed by tattooing, the reason being their causative agents cannot travel beyond a fixed distance.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1220, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0969. Various types of gunpowder', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Smokeless powder:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Nitrocellulose (single base)</li>\n<li>Nitrocellulose &amp; Nitroglycerine (double base)</li>\n<li>Nitrocellulose, Nitroglycerine, and Nitroguanidine (triple base)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Smoke producing powders contain</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Black Powder:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Potassium nitrate</li>\n<li>Charcoal</li>\n<li>Sulphur</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Semi-smokeless powder</strong>:\n<ul>\n<li>Mixture of 80% black and 20% of the smokeless powder</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1221, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0966. Difference between Epidural Hematoma due to Burns and Blunt Force', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Trait </strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Epidural hematoma due to burns</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Epidural hematoma due to blunt force </strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Cause</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Charring of skull due to intense heat</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Blunt force to the head</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Situation</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Anywhere usually bilateral</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Usually adjacent to Sylvian fissure</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Distribution</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Diffuse</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Localised</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Characters</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Thin, granular, soft friable clot of light chocolate color honeycomb appearance; evenly distributed or sickle-shaped</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Discoid shape, localized more rubbery in consistency, reddish purple</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Skull</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Maybe fractured</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Associated fracture in temporal area</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>CNS</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No injury</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Frequently injured</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Carboxyhaemoglobin</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Present</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Absent</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1222, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0965. Difference between Ante-mortem Burns and Post-mortem Burns', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Trait</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Ante-mortem burns</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Post-mortem burns</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Line of redness</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Present</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Absent</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Blister</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Contains serous fluid with proteins and chlorides</p>\n<p>Base is inflamed</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Contains air only</p>\n<p>Base is dry, hard and yellow.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Vital reaction</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Present</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Absent</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Enzymes</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Peripheral zone of burn shows increase in enzyme reaction</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\154\>\n<p>Peripheral zone of burn does not show increase in enzyme reaction</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1223, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0829. Types of impact injuries', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Primary impact injuries:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is caused due <strong>to initial impact b/w vehicle and pedestrian</strong>. These are seen on the part of the body facing the vehicle and help in identifying the offending vehicle.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Secondary impact injuries:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is caused due to <strong>subsequent second impact of same vehicle</strong>. These injuries are also seen on the same side as the primary impact injuries.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Tertiary impact injuries/secondary injuries</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is caused<strong> by person violently falling on ground or on other stationary objects</strong>. Found on parts opposite to primary impact <strong>or on head<em>.</em></strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Rolling/Run over/degloving injuries:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is caused by wheel of vehicle running or rolling over the victim. Children are often involved.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>Types of impact injuries on pedestrian</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/3df0f261ba824803a86e21445237a218x386x335.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1224, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0822. Types of skull vault fracture', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Diastatic</strong> fracture/ <strong>sutural</strong> fracture - It involves the separation of sutures due to blow with a blunt weapon or from cerebral edema.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/ba0902e972ff42d08d29c34cc50c1f54x327x150.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Fissured</strong> fracture/ <strong>linear</strong> fracture:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>They are breaks in the bone that traverse the full thickness of the skull from the outer to inner table.</li>\n<li>They are usually fairly straight with no bone displacement.</li>\n<li>The common cause of injury is blunt force trauma where the impact energy transferred over a wide area of the skull.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Pond</strong> fracture/ <strong>indented</strong> fracture - It occurs in children due to elasticity of bones.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/ed4f9a37343641e59bcc73eda4ecffd1x167x176.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Depressed</strong> fracture/ <strong>signature</strong> fracture - It is caused by a heavy weapon with a small striking surface. Its shape indicates the type of weapon which is produced (signature fracture).</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b493f5278c3d460d906209a6d1462fbex1200x797.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Comminuted</strong> fracture/ <strong>spider-web</strong> fracture - It has a stellate appearance where there is no displacement of the fracture.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/2090d8cd7b744d2d9e9136e65cdd7069x526x382.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Ring</strong> fracture - It is usually caused due to a fall from height landing on feet.&nbsp;These occur in the&nbsp;posterior fossa&nbsp;around the&nbsp;foramen magnum.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/cfbc6a495f5f47f6b1be0a6dc8651bd3x1279x1477.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1225, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0763. Difference between incised, lacerated and stab wound', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trait</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Incised wound</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Lacerated wound</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Stabwound</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Manner of production </strong></td>\n<td>By sharp objects or weapons</td>\n<td>By blunt&nbsp; objects or weapons&nbsp;</td>\n<td>By pointed sharp or blunt weapons</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Site </strong></td>\n<td>Anywhere</td>\n<td>Usually over the bony prominences</td>\n<td>Anywhere, usually chest and abdomen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>margins</strong></td>\n<td>Smooth, even, clean cut and everted</td>\n<td><strong>Irregular and often undermined</strong></td>\n<td>Cleancut, parallel edges, lacerated if weapon is blunt pointed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Abrasion and edges </strong></td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n<td>Usually present</td>\n<td>Absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bruising </strong></td>\n<td>No adjacent bruising of soft tissues</td>\n<td>Bruising of surrounding and underlying tissue</td>\n<td>rare</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>shape</strong></td>\n<td>Linear or spindle shaped</td>\n<td>Varies usually irregular</td>\n<td>Linear or irregular</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Depth of wound</strong></td>\n<td>Structures cleanly cut to the depth of the wound</td>\n<td>Small strands of tissue at the bottom bridge across margins</td>\n<td>Structures cleanly cut</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1226, 'Forensic Medicine', 'PM0762. Age of bruise and abrasion', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Age and color change of bruise/contusion</strong>:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Colour</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Due to</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Duration &nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Red</td>\n<td>Haemoglobin (fresh blood)</td>\n<td>Fresh <em>&nbsp;</em></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Blue</td>\n<td>Deoxygenated haemoglobin</td>\n<td>Few hours to 3 days<em>&nbsp;</em></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bluish black/ brown</td>\n<td>Hemosiderin</td>\n<td>4<sup>th</sup> day &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Green</td>\n<td>Hematoidin</td>\n<td>5 to 6 days&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Yellow</td>\n<td>Bilirubin</td>\n<td>7 to 12 days&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Normal colour</td>\n<td>Pigment removed by phagocytes&nbsp;</td>\n<td>2 weeks</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The image given below shows the age and colour change of bruise:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/108b99181eaa4f5d8900121410157a90x1280x3975.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-2 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Age of abrasion</strong>:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Colour of scab</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Duration </strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bright red</td>\n<td>12-24 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Reddish brown</td>\n<td>2-3 days</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dark brown to brownish black</td>\n<td>4-7 days</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Scab dries shrinks and falls off</td>\n<td>After 7 days</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
