(1469, 'Dermatology', 'PM1914. Different types of miliaria', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Miliaria</strong>&nbsp;is a common acute or subacute skin condition that arises due to the&nbsp;<strong>occlusion</strong>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<strong>disruption</strong>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<strong>eccrine sweat ducts</strong>&nbsp;in hot humid conditions.</p>\n<p>Based on the <strong>level of blockade</strong> it is differentiated into</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Miliaria Crystallina-&nbsp;</strong>Stratum corneum</li>\n<li><strong>Miliaria Rubra</strong>&nbsp;- Malpighian Layer</li>\n<li><strong>Miliaria profunda</strong>&nbsp;- Dermoepidermal junction</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Pathophysiology:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The first event may be an<strong>&nbsp;increase in the skin flora</strong>, perhaps with Staphylococcus epidermidis being responsible for producing an extracellular polysaccharide substance or slime that&nbsp;<strong>blocks the lumen</strong>&nbsp;of the sweat duct.</li>\n<li>The&nbsp;<strong>parakeratotic plugs</strong>, a notable feature of the later stages of the disease, are not the primary cause of the obstruction but arise in the<strong>&nbsp;repair process</strong>, and further aggravate the obstruction.</li>\n<li><strong>Leakage of sweat into the epidermis</strong>&nbsp;is responsible for the final production of the lesions, and for their further aggravation.</li>\n<li>Miliaria crystallina occurs commonly in infants due to a delay in the development of patency in the sweat ducts.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Clinical features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Miliaria crystallina:</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Clear, thin‐walled vesicles, 1–2 mm</strong>&nbsp;in diameter&nbsp;<strong>without an inflammatory areola</strong>, are usually&nbsp;<strong>symptomless</strong>&nbsp;and develop in&nbsp;<strong>crops</strong>, mainly on the trunk. In persistent febrile illnesses, recurrent crops may occur. The vesicles soon rupture and are followed by&nbsp;<strong>superficial, branny desquamation</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/aa0deef4a0d14ef3bcfc937904ab0af5x600x413.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Miliaria rubra:</strong>&nbsp;Typical lesions develop on the body, especially in areas of<strong>&nbsp;friction with clothing, and in flexures</strong>. The lesions are uniformly&nbsp;<strong>minute erythematous papules</strong>, which may be present in very large numbers. Characteristically, the lesions produce intense discomfort in the form of an&nbsp;<strong>unbearable pricking sensation.</strong>&nbsp;Relief is often instantaneous when the stimulus to sweating is abolished by a cool shower. In infants, lesions commonly appear on the occluded skin of the neck, groins and axillae, but also occur elsewhere.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/35d93e9e18cd4f19b2a0df77cb0c2896x448x496.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Miliaria profunda:</strong>&nbsp;This nearly always&nbsp;<strong>follows repeated attacks of miliaria rubra</strong>, and is common only in the tropics. The&nbsp;lesions are&nbsp;<strong>easily missed</strong>. The affected skin is covered with&nbsp;<strong>pale, firm papules 1–3 mm across</strong>, especially on the body, but sometimes also on the limbs. There is&nbsp;<strong>no itching or discomfort </strong>from the lesions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>First line</strong><br> • Control local environment (remove excess bedding, fans, air<br> conditioning)<br> • Cool the skin (damp compresses, cool showers)<br> • Avoid tight or excessive clothing</li>\n<li><strong>Second line</strong><br> • Menthol (e.g. 0.5% menthol in aqueous cream)<br> • Topical antibiotics if there is secondary infection<br> • Mild topical steroids</li>\n<li><strong>Third line</strong><br> • Removal to cooler climate<br> • Prophylactic oral vitamin C</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1470, 'Dermatology', 'PM1913. Fordyce Spots', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Fordyce spots/Fordyce granules:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Fordyce spots are&nbsp;<strong>heterotopic&nbsp;sebaceous glands&nbsp;</strong>wherein&nbsp;the duct is connected&nbsp;<strong>directly</strong>&nbsp;to the overlying&nbsp;<strong>skin or mucosal surface&nbsp;</strong>unlike other sebum glands which open into the follicle.</li>\n<li>They are called&nbsp;<strong>ectopic/free-lying sebaceous glands</strong>.</li>\n<li>They occur commonly on the vermilion border of&nbsp;<strong>upper lip(m/c)</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>buccal mucosa</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>skin over penile shaft and areolar of the breast.</strong></li>\n<li>They are commonly&nbsp;<strong>multiple</strong>&nbsp;and appear as&nbsp;<strong>symmetrical discrete yellow papules.</strong></li>\n<li>Fordyce spots on penis are called&nbsp;<strong>Tyson glands.</strong></li>\n<li>They are&nbsp;<strong>asymptomatic</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Treatment ladder</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>First line</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Reassurance</li>\n<li><strong>Second line</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Local destruction with superficial cautery or electrodessication</li>\n<li>Topical trichloracetic acid&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Image:&nbsp;</strong>Fordyce spots on the&nbsp;vermilion border of both lips in A, upper lip in B, and buccal mucosa in&nbsp; C.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/2759a4f8bc9e4098b54c8308c4a26e5ex512x108.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1471, 'Dermatology', 'PM0243. Global Alliance Algorithm for Acne Treatment', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Global Alliance Algorithm for Acne Treatment</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Image: </strong>Global Alliance Algorithm for Improving Outcomes in acne</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/d0c11e3325124df49bac9104eabccaebx686x530.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>BPO - Benzoyl peroxide</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1472, 'Dermatology', 'PM0240. Important Syndromes Related to Acne', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Important Syndromes Related to Acne</strong></p>\n<p><strong>I. SAPHO syndrome</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Synovitis</li>\n<li>Acne</li>\n<li>Pustulosis</li>\n<li>Hyperostosis</li>\n<li>Osteitis</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>II. HAIR-AN syndrome</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Hyperandrogenism (HA)</li>\n<li>Insulin Resistance (IR)</li>\n<li>Acanthosis Nigricans(AN)</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>III. SAHA syndrome</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Seborrhoea</li>\n<li>Acne</li>\n<li>Hirsutism</li>\n<li>Androgenetic alopecia</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>IV. PAPA syndrome</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Pyogenic Arthritis (PA)</li>\n<li>Pyoderma gangrenosum (P)</li>\n<li>Acne(A)</li>\n</ol></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1473, 'Dermatology', 'PM1897. Causes of scarring and non-scarring alopecia- Mnemonic', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Alopecia or hair loss can be classified as :</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Non-Scarring/Non-Cicatricial alopecia</li>\n<li>Scarring/Cicatricial alopecia&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Mnemonic</strong> for causes of<strong> non-scarring </strong>alopecia<strong>: THATS STD!</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>T</strong>inea capitis(Non-Inflammatory Type&nbsp; - grey patch and black dot types )</li>\n<li><strong>H</strong>ormonal - Hypothyroidism, Androgenetic alopecia</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>nagen effluvium,&nbsp;<strong>A</strong>lopecia areata</li>\n<li><strong>T</strong>richotillomania</li>\n<li><strong>S</strong>econdary syphilis (moth-eaten alopecia)</li>\n<li><strong>S</strong>LE(predominantly causes non-scarring alopecia but also can cause scarring alopecia)</li>\n<li><strong>T</strong>elogen effluvium</li>\n<li><strong>D</strong>eficiency of Zinc, Iron&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Mnemonic</strong> for causes of <strong>scarring</strong> alopecia: <strong>SF<sub>2</sub>L<sub>3</sub></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>S</strong>cleroderma - Linear scalp morphea (en coup de sabre)</li>\n<li><strong>F</strong>avus and Kerion (Inflammatory Type of Tinea capitis)</li>\n<li><strong>F</strong>olliculitis decalvans</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>ichen planopilaris</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>upus vulgaris</li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>upus erythematosis - discoid (DLE)</li>\n<li>Pseudopelade of Brocq</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1474, 'Dermatology', 'PM0182. Hair Cycle', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Hair follicles</strong> undergo a repetitive sequence of growth and the rest is known as the <strong>hair cycle</strong>. Hair Cycle is usually described under <strong>three phases</strong>: Anagen, Catagen, and Telogen.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/4e7b67b1c3c646fda4224ac2fbca4337x936x718.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>1. Anagen</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>period of active hair growth</strong> is known as <strong>anagen</strong> and the duration of this phase is responsible for determining the final length of the hair.</li>\n<li>The entry of a resting hair follicle into anagen is heralded by the <strong>onset of mitotic activity in epithelial cells</strong> overlying the dermal papilla at the base of the follicle (the secondary epithelial germ).</li>\n<li>Under normal circumstances, <strong>80–90% of hair follicles</strong> on the human scalp are in anagen at any one time.</li>\n<li>Anagen can continue for several years.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Fig 1.</strong>&nbsp;Scalp hair follicle in the anagen II stage of development</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/ee859cd3c39c47b4a7f639dfeb33f278x404x601.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Fig 2.</strong>&nbsp; Anagen hair bulb. <strong>Co</strong>, hair cortex; <strong>Cu</strong>, hair cuticle; <strong>DP</strong>, dermal papilla; <strong>DS</strong>, dermal sheath; <strong>He</strong>, Henle layer; <strong>HM</strong>, hair matrix; <strong>Hu</strong>, Huxley layer; <strong>IRSCu</strong>, inner root sheath cuticle; <strong>Me</strong>, melanocyte; <strong>ORS</strong>, outer root sheath</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/5231bb585714455d9ada9c1ddc365512x400x482.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>2. Catagen</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>At the end of anagen, <strong>epithelial cell division declines and ceases</strong>, and the follicle enters an <strong>involutionary phase</strong> known as <strong>catagen</strong>.</li>\n<li>During catagen, the proximal end of the <strong>hair shaft keratinizes</strong> to form a <strong>club-shaped structure</strong> and the lower part of the follicle involutes by apoptosis.</li>\n<li>The basement membrane surrounding the follicle becomes thickened and corrugated to form the ‘<strong>glassy membrane’</strong>.</li>\n<li>It lasts for about 10 days.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Fig 3.&nbsp; </strong>Human hair follicle in mid-catagen. There is a prominent glassy membrane surrounding the regressing epithelial column. The dermal papilla is rounded and condensed.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/c270087a4c224c20a09ed0369eddf177x400x600.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>3. Telogen</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is the time period between catagen and the next anagen.</li>\n<li>It lasts for about 3 months.</li>\n<li><strong>Club hair is eventually shed</strong> through an active process called <strong>exogen</strong>.</li>\n<li>In the human scalp, hair follicles may remain in a <strong>state of latency</strong>, also known as <strong>kenogen</strong>, for a pro­longed period after the club hair is shed.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1475, 'Dermatology,', 'PM0180. Nail findings and associated systemic conditions', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Nail finding</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Associated systemic condition</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Clubbing</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Inflammatory bowel disease</li>\n<li><span>Lung cancer</span></li>\n<li>Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis</li>\n<li><span>Complicated tuberculosis</span></li>\n<li><span>Suppurative lung disease (lung abscess, empyema, bronchiectasis, cystic fibrosis)</span></li>\n<li>Mesothelioma</li>\n<li>Cirrhosis</li>\n<li>Congenital heart disease, Endocarditis</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Koilonychia</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Iron-deficiency anemia, hemochromatosis, Raynaud’s disease</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Onycholysis</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Psoriasis, onychomycosis, hyperthyroidism, sarcoidosis, trauma, amyloidosis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Pitting</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Psoriasis, Reiter’s syndrome, Alopecia areata</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Beau’s lines</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Any severe systemic illness that disrupts nail growth, Raynaud’s disease, pemphigus, trauma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Yellow nail</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Lymphedema, pleural effusion, immunodeficiency, bronchiectasis, sinusitis, rheumatoid arthritis, nephrotic syndrome, thyroiditis, tuberculosis, Raynaud’s disease</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Nail Pterygium</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dorsal: Lichen Planus</p>\n<p>Ventral: trauma, systemic sclerosis, Raynaud phenomenon, lupus erythematosus</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p class=\heading\>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Nail finding</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Associated systemic condition</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Terry’s (white) nails</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hepatic failure, cirrhosis, diabetes mellitus, CHF, hyperthyroidism, malnutrition</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Azure lunula</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hepatolenticular degeneration (Wilson’s disease), silver poisoning, quinacrine therapy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Half-and-half nails</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Specific for renal failure</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Muehrcke’s lines</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Specific for hypoalbuminemia</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Mees’ lines</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Arsenic poisoning, Hodgkin’s disease, CHF, leprosy, malaria, chemotherapy, carbon monoxide poisoning, other systemic insults</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Dark longitudinal streaks</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Melanoma, benign nevus, chemical staining, normal variant in darkly pigmented people</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Splinter hemorrhage</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Subacute bacterial endocarditis, SLE, rheumatoid arthritis, antiphospholipid syndrome, peptic ulcer disease, malignancies, oral contraceptive use, pregnancy, psoriasis, trauma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Telangiectasia</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Rheumatoid arthritis, SLE, dermatomyositis, scleroderma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1476, 'Dermatology', 'PM1911. Algorithm for the differential diagnosis of Hypomelanosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/76d12e9fdf3e477fa5ca155bed1ddaacx657x456.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1477, 'Dermatology', 'PM1948. Erythema multiforme vs. Stevens-Johnson syndrome/Toxic epidermal necrolysis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Erythema multiforme major</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Stevens-Johnsons Syndrome</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis (Lyell syndrome)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>% Body Surface-area</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;10%</p>\n</td>\n<td>&lt;10%</td>\n<td><strong>&gt;30%</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Causes</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Herpes simplex</strong>&gt; Mycoplasma infection</td>\n<td>Drug induced e.g. cephalosporins, sulfa drugs, allopurinol</td>\n<td>Drug induced e.g. cephalosporins, sulfa drugs, allopurinol</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Associated Symptoms</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Less</strong> fever and other constitutional symptoms</td>\n<td>Fever, malaise and headache</td>\n<td>Fever, malaise and headache</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mucosal Lesions</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Milder</strong> mucosal lesions</td>\n<td>Severe mucosal involvement</td>\n<td>Severe mucosal involvement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lesions</strong></td>\n<td>Erythematous papules, <strong>Target lesions</strong>, <strong>raised atypical target</strong> lesions, occasional bullous lesions</td>\n<td>\n<p>Vesicles on erythematous base, erosions, <strong>purpuric macules, Flat atypical target lesions</strong></p>\n<p>Nikolsky Sign Positive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Diffuse, generalized epidermal detachment</p>\n<p><strong>TEN with spots</strong> - with widespread purpuric macules and flat atypical target lesions</p>\n<p><strong>TEN without spots</strong>-&nbsp;loss of large epidermal sheets without purpuric macules or target lesions</p>\n<p>&nbsp;Nikolsky Sign Positive</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Distribution</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Acral</strong> – distal extremities</td>\n<td><strong>Variable</strong> distribution</td>\n<td><strong>Extensive</strong> distribution</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Histo-pathology</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Interface dermatitis</strong> – Basal cell vacuolization, apoptotic bodies and inflammatory cells at Dermo-epidermal junction</td>\n<td>Dermo-epidermal separation, Intense inflammatory cell infiltrates in dermis, some areas of epidermal detachment&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Epidermal necrosis</strong>, Dermo-epidermal separation, minimal dermal inflammatory cell infiltrate, large areas of epidermal detachment.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Recurrence</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Common</strong>, related to Herpes infections</td>\n<td>Uncommon, drug-related</td>\n<td>Uncommon, drug-related</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mortality</strong></td>\n<td>Rare – recovery in 1 to 4 weeks</td>\n<td>Elevated mortality</td>\n<td><strong>Highest mortality</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note:&nbsp;<strong>Overlap SJS-TEN:</strong>&nbsp;There is detachment of <strong>10–30%</strong>&nbsp;body surface area, plus widespread purpuric macules or flat atypical targets.</p>\n<p><strong>Erythema Multiforme</strong> is regarded as a <strong>self‐limiting cytotoxic dermatitis</strong> resulting from cell‐mediated hypersensitivity most commonly to&nbsp;infection or drugs.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/c83d335429494d2eb09a17fd553fe4c2x600x796.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1478, 'Dermatology', 'PM0232. Characteristic features of various types of Angioedema', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Characteristic Features of Various Types of Angioedema</strong></p>\n<table border=\all sides\ width=\671\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ width=\340\>\n<p><strong>Clinical Presentation</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\85\>\n<p><strong>C4 Level</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\2\ width=\95\>\n<p><strong>C1-INH Function by Chromogenic Assay</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p><strong>C1-INH Level</strong></p>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p><strong>C1q Level</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Hereditary Angioedema (HAE)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\6\ width=\548\>\n<p><strong>Inherited defect in the gene for</strong> <strong>C1-esterase inhibitor. Autosomal dominant: patients have one normal, one abnormal gene</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Type I</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\217\>\n<p>Recurrent episodic angioedema and abdominal attacks without urticaria. Onset in childhood or young adulthood. 75% have family history. Note that attacks may be oestrogen dependent in this group as well as the Type III form.</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\4\ width=\255\>\n<p>Usually LOW</p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\3\ width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Type II</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\3\ width=\180\>\n<p>Usually LOW</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL or HIGH</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Type III</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Family history present in most cases, onset after childhood. Female patients predominate and attacks often appear to be estrogen-dependent.</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\4\ width=\255\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Acquired Angioedema (AAE)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\6\ width=\548\>\n<p><strong>Condition not inherited but due to other underlying disease. C1-esterase inhibitor is low due to consumption</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Type I</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Onset age variable; symptoms same as HAE. No family history, may be associated with underlying lymphoproliferative disease.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\2\ width=\180\>\n<p>Usually LOW</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p>LOW</p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\76\>\n<p>Usually LOW, May be NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Type II</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Onset at variable age; symptoms indistinguishable from HAE. No family history, often associated with an autoantibody that binds to C1-INH.</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Drug-induced Angioedema</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\6\ width=\548\>\n<p><strong>Angioedema occurs through allergic mechanism and does not involve C1-INH.</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>ACE Inhibitors</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\217\>\n<p>Pseudoallergic (NSAID) or non-allergic (ACE) inhibitors Angioedema may start at first use. Acute onset of well-demarcated subcutaneous non-pitting edema of the face or hands</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\4\ rowspan=\2\ width=\255\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>NSAIDs</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Angioedema with Urticaria</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\6\ width=\548\>\n<p><strong>Angioedema is accompanied by urticaria. Does not usually involve C1-INH.</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Allergic AE</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Exposure to food, venom, latex, drug, or environmental allergen. May include anaphylaxis</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\3\ width=\90\>\n<p>May be LOW or NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\3\ width=\165\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL OR LOW</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>AE with Vasculitis</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Long-lasting urticaria with tenderness. Vascular Damage. With Hypocomplementemic Urticarial Vasculitis, the CH5O is usually LOW and so are classical pathway components.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\123\>\n<p><strong>Idiopathic AE</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\217\>\n<p>Frequently chronic and relapsing, often occurs with urticarial. Consider test for chronic urticarial (CD203c)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\76\>\n<p>NORMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1479, 'Dermatology', 'PM0206. UK refinement of Hanifin & Rajka’s diagnostic criteria of atopic dermatitis (eczema)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>In order to qualify as a case of <strong>atopic dermatitis</strong> (<strong>eczema</strong>) with the <strong>UK&nbsp; diagnostic criteria</strong>, the child <strong>must have</strong>&nbsp;<strong>an itchy skin condition</strong> (or parental report of scratching or rubbing in a child).</p>\n<p><strong>Plus three or more of the following:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Onset below age of 2 years (not used if child is under 4 years)</li>\n<li>History of skin crease involvement (including cheeks in children under 10 years)</li>\n<li>History of a generally dry skin</li>\n<li>Personal history of other atopic disease (or history of any atopic disease in a first-degree relative in children under 4 years)</li>\n<li>Visible flexural dermatitis (or dermatitis of cheeks/forehead and outer limbs in children under 4 years)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1480, 'Dermatology', 'PM1956. Koebner phenomenon', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Koebner or isomorphic Phenomenon</strong> is the development of new lesions <strong>along the line of trauma</strong> in a previously normal skin. The new lesions have iso (same) and morphic (morphology) as the existing lesions.</p>\n<p>The trauma may include mechanical trauma, thermal trauma, allergic or irritant reactants or any treatment procedures.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>True</strong> Koebners phenomenon</td>\n<td>In immune-mediated conditions</td>\n<td>\n<p>Psoriasis</p>\n<p>Vitiligo</p>\n<p>Lichen planus</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>False</strong> Koebners phenomenon</td>\n<td>In infectious diseases</td>\n<td>\n<p>Viral warts</p>\n<p>Molluscum contagiosum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Remote reverse</strong> Koebner phenomenon</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Spontaneous repigmentation</strong> of vitiligo patches <strong>distant</strong> from the autologous skin graft sites (trauma)</p>\n<p>Generalized granuloma annulare</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Vitiligo</p>\n<p>Psoriasis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Some <strong>rare causes</strong> of True Koebner Phenomenon are : Dariers disease, Hailey-Hailey disease, Erythema multiforme, Kaposis Sarcoma and Lichen sclerosus.</p>\n<p><strong>Image:</strong>&nbsp;Koebner phenomenon with linear psoriasis patch on the abdomen</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/d31270bf5e5f4b709adfe08cf50556d9x131x217.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1481, 'Dermatology', 'PM1954. Drug of choice for different types of psoriasis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Drug of choice</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chronic Plaque Psoriasis</td>\n<td>Methotrexate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Erythrodermic Psoriasis</td>\n<td>Methotrexate&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Psoriatic Arthritis</td>\n<td>Methotrexate / Apremilast</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pustular Psoriasis</td>\n<td>Acitretin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Psoriasis in HIV patients</td>\n<td>Acitretin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Impetigo Herpetiformis</td>\n<td>\n<p>1. Systemic Corticosteroids</p>\n<p>2. Cyclosporine</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Erythrodermic Psoriasis in Pregnancy</td>\n<td>Systemic Corticosteroids&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1482, 'Dermatology', 'PM0294. Drugs Inducing or Exacerbating Psoriasis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Drugs Inducing or Exacerbating Psoriasis</strong></p>\n<p>The following drugs are implicated in the exacerbation of psoriasis:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beta blockers</strong></li>\n<li>Synthetic antimalarials</li>\n<li>NSAIDS</li>\n<li><strong>Lithium</strong></li>\n<li><strong>ACE inhibitors </strong>&amp; angiotensin receptor blockers</li>\n<li></li>\n<li>Interferon alpha</li>\n<li>Tetracycline</li>\n<li>Terbinafine</li>\n<li>Gemfibrozil</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1483, 'Dermatology', 'PM0292. Papulosquamous Disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Lichen planus</li>\n<li>Psoriasis</li>\n<li>Parapsoriasis</li>\n<li>Pityriasis rubra pilaris</li>\n<li>Pityriasis rosea</li>\n<li>Seborrheic dermatitis</li>\n<li>Secondary Syphilis</li>\n<li>Drug Reactions</li>\n<li>Reiter’s disease</li>\n<li>Eczema</li>\n<li>Neoplasms (Mycosis fungoides, Squamous cell carcinoma, &nbsp;Bowen’s disease)</li>\n<li>Tinea infections</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1484, 'Dermatology', 'PM0259. Types of scales associated with dermatological conditions', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Types of Scales and Associated Diseases</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Type of Scale</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Associated Disease</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Collarette scale</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>It is a fine, peripherally attached, and centrally detached scale at the edge of an inflammatory lesion. It is seen in <strong>pityriasis rosea</strong>.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Fish-like scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>They are seen in <strong>ichthyosis</strong> <strong>vulgaris</strong> (<em><strong>ichthyos</strong></em>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<strong>fish</strong>). Ichthyotic scales are large and polygonal.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Silvery scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>They are characteristic of processes involving parakeratosis, especially <strong>psoriasis</strong>. The silvery color is due to the reflection of light at several air–keratin interfaces.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Mica-like scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 659\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>They are seen in <strong>Pityriasis lichenoides.&nbsp;</strong>The lesions are polymorphic with some showing hemorrhagic crusting and adherent scales.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Yellow / greasy scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Seborrheic dermatitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Leaf-like scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Pemphigus foliaceous</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Powdery, branny, fine scales</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Pityriasis versicolor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b6af559a05704578a2cf494258896e78x1280x8136.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1485, 'Dermatology', 'PM2085. Differences between pemphigus vulgaris and bullous pemphigoid', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Pemphigus vulgaris</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Bullous pemphigoid</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Age</td>\n<td>30-40 years</td>\n<td>70-80 years</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Antibody</td>\n<td>Anti-desmoglein</td>\n<td>Anti-hemidesmosome</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Location of target antigens</td>\n<td>Intraepidermal</td>\n<td>Subepidermal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Immuno-fluorescence</td>\n<td>Fish-net pattern</td>\n<td>Linear, shoreline pattern</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bullae</td>\n<td>Thin and fragile</td>\n<td>Deep and tense</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mouth involved</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nikolsky’s sign</td>\n<td>Positive</td>\n<td>Negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Symptom</td>\n<td>Painful</td>\n<td>Pruritic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Severity</td>\n<td>Life threatening</td>\n<td>Resolves</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1486, 'Dermatology', 'PM0363. Classification of Vesiculobullous Disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>According to Pathology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Immunobullous disorders/ Primary blistering disease: </strong>occur due to autoimmunity</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Intraepidermal</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Subepidermal</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Pemphigus vulgaris</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Bullous pemphigoid</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Pemphigus foliaceous</p>\n</td>\n<td>Dermatitis herpetiformis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Pemphigus vegetans</p>\n</td>\n<td>Epidermolysis bullous acquisita</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;Pemphigus erythematosus</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mechanobullous disorders:</strong> Due to defect in the structure of epidermis\n<ul>\n<li>Epidermolysis bullosa</li>\n<li>Bullous ichthyosiform erythroderma</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Other disorders</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Infections - VZV, HSV, Bullous impetigo, SSSS</li>\n<li>Metabolic - Porphyria, Diabetes, Hemodialysis</li>\n<li>Drug eruptions - Fixed drug eruption, Steven Johnson Syndrome, Erythema Multiforme</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>According to Site</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Intraepidermal</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Sub-epidermal (Dermo-epidermal)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>1. Subcorneal (granular layer)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pemphigus foliaceous &amp; erythematosus</li>\n<li>Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome</li>\n<li>Miliaria crystalina</li>\n<li>Bullous impetigo</li>\n<li>Friction blister</li>\n<li>Subcorneal pustular dermatosis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>2. Spinous layer</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eczematous (atopic) dermatitis</li>\n<li>HSV/VZV infection</li>\n<li>Molluscum contagiosum</li>\n<li>Familial benign pemphigus (Hailey-hailey disease)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>3. Suprabasal</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pemphigus vulgaris</li>\n<li>Darrier’s disease</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>4. Basal layer</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Erythema multiforme</li>\n<li>Epidermolysis bullosa simplex</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>1. Junctional (at basal lamina)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Junctional epidermolysis bullosa</li>\n<li>Bullous pemphigoid</li>\n<li>Toxic epidermal necrolysis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>2. Dermolytic (below basal lamina)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Epidermolysis bullosa acquisita</li>\n<li>Epidermolysis bullosa dystrophicans</li>\n<li>Deep burns</li>\n<li>Porphyria cutanea tarda</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1487, 'Dermatology', 'PM1995. Nail changes in lichen planus', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Nail involvement in lichen planus</strong> occurs in up to<strong>&nbsp;</strong>10%&nbsp;of the cases but is usually a minor feature of the disease.</p>\n<p><strong>Dorsal Nail Pterygium&nbsp;</strong>is the<strong> most specific</strong>&nbsp;nail change in Lichen planus. The fusion<strong>&nbsp;of dorsal nail fold</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>nail bed</strong>&nbsp;leads to&nbsp;<strong>pterygium</strong>.</p>\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>most frequent</strong>&nbsp;nail change is the exaggeration of longitudinal lines and linear depressions due to a slight&nbsp;<strong>thinning of the nail plate</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Pup-tent sign</strong>&nbsp;- elevation of nail in shape of tent</p>\n<p><strong>Trachyonychia</strong>&nbsp;- 20 nail dystrophy</p>\n<p><strong>Subungual Hyperkeratosis</strong>&nbsp;and Onycholysis</p>\n<p><strong>Longitudinal Melanonychia</strong>&nbsp;in Lichen Planus of the nail bed</p>\n<p><strong>Permanent destruction</strong>&nbsp;of several toenails with ulceration of soles (rare variant)</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/3131aa9be4124cbe906d8d8975d39f08x800x533.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image shows&nbsp; Nails in Lichen planus presented with irregular longitudinal grooves and ridges .</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/7e2934a4486d4ac28a14dbccffc37ed9x512x476.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image :&nbsp;<strong>Dorsal Nail Pterygium</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e7c66d7b46b5468b8850c33722e61737x512x478.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image :&nbsp;<strong>Pup-tent sign</strong>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/5775473480c84dc3939adb6d5b2b1d3cx512x287.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image:&nbsp;<strong>Trachyonychia</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1488, 'Dermatology', 'PM1994. Nail changes in psoriasis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Nail changes in psoriasis</strong> are present in about<strong>&nbsp;40%&nbsp;</strong>of the cases at any point in time. Nail psoriasis is associated with more&nbsp;extensive&nbsp;psoriasis, longer disease duration,&nbsp;family history&nbsp;of psoriasis, and the presence of&nbsp;psoriatic arthritis.</p>\n<p><strong>Subungal oil drop sign or Salmon Patch</strong>&nbsp;is a<strong>&nbsp;highly specific&nbsp;</strong>pathognomonic sign seen in Nail psoriasis. It is a yellow-red discoloration in the nail bed resembling a drop of oil.</p>\n<p><strong>Nail pitting</strong>&nbsp;however is the most<strong>&nbsp;frequent sign.&nbsp;</strong>Individual pits are uniformly sized,&nbsp;<strong>deep and irregular</strong>&nbsp;in nature. These nail pits are also known as <strong>Thimble pits</strong>&nbsp;and are due to the involvement of the proximal nail matrix.</p>\n<p>Nail Bed disease also causes&nbsp;<strong>subungual hyperkeratosis</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>splinter hemorrhages,</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>distal onycholysis</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Leuconychia</strong>&nbsp;may also be present.</p>\n<p><strong>Trachonychia</strong>&nbsp;or Twenty Nail dystrophy may be present in severe cases.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f0da378ee7f743efbfc9081ff7287a61x512x340.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image :&nbsp;&nbsp;Pitting is the commonest manifestation of nail psoriasis.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f09a662cc05e4c4f995a7ee68a24d4bbx512x334.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image:&nbsp;oil drops visible in the nail bed.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/3aa273571f484fe380d4efe7476efa4ex512x348.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image:&nbsp;pitting and salmon patches in fingernails.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b553a94f74764bffb051362172637611x512x341.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Image:&nbsp;Leukonychia in a patient with psoriasis.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Features of Nail Psoriasis – Mnemonic</strong></p>\n<p>“Nail – <strong>POLISH</strong>”</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>P – P</strong>itting</li>\n<li><strong>O – O</strong>il drop sign<strong>, O</strong>nycholysis</li>\n<li><strong>L – L</strong>euconychia</li>\n<li><strong>I – I</strong>rregular pitting pattern</li>\n<li><strong>S – S</strong>plinter Hemorrhage</li>\n<li><strong>H – H</strong>yperkeratosis (Subungual)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1489, 'Dermatology', 'PM1971. Classification of cutaneous tuberculosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The classification of cutaneous tuberculosis is based on the mode of acquisition.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Pathophysiology</strong></td>\n<td><strong>AFB</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p><strong>Exogenous</strong></p>\n<p>Through broken skin or mucosa</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tuberculous chancre</td>\n<td>Occurs in individuals with no previous sensitization to TB</td>\n<td>Multibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tuberculosis verrucosa cutis</td>\n<td>Occurs in previously sensitized individuals with strong immunity</td>\n<td>Paucibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p><strong>Endogenous</strong></p>\n<p>Direct spread from a focus of infection</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Scrofuloderma</td>\n<td>Contiguous spread from affected parts like lymph nodes, joints</td>\n<td>Multibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Periorificial tuberculosis</td>\n<td>Autoinoculation at mucocutaneous borders from infected secretions</td>\n<td>Multibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p><strong>Hematogenous</strong></p>\n<p>Spread from a distant primary focus of TB</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acute cutaneous miliary tuberculosis</td>\n<td>Occurs in severe disseminated TB</td>\n<td>Multibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lupus vulgaris</td>\n<td>Occurs in previously sensitized individuals with strong immunity. Mostly hematogenous spread, sometimes exogenous.</td>\n<td>Paucibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tuberculous gumma/ abscess</td>\n<td>Occurs in immunocompromised patients</td>\n<td>Multibacillary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p><strong>Tuberculids</strong></p>\n<p>Hypersensitivity reaction</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lichen scrofulosorum (micropapular)</td>\n<td rowspan=\3\>Hematogenous spread of <em>M. tuberculosis </em>antigens to the skin causes type III hypersensitivity which triggers type IV reaction with granuloma formation</td>\n<td rowspan=\3\>Very rarely seen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Papulonecrotic tuberculid</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Erythema induratum of Bazin (nodular)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1490, 'Dermatology', 'PM1967. Characteristics of Ridley Jopling Classification in Leprosy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>TT (Tuberculoid Leprosy)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>BT (Borderline Tuberculoid)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>BB (Borderline)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>BL(Borderline Lepromatous)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>LL (Lepromatous Leprosy)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Number and Type of lesions</strong></td>\n<td><strong>1-3</strong> <strong>well</strong><br><strong>defined</strong>&nbsp;hypopigmented macule(s) or plaque(s) with elevated sloping borders&nbsp; -<strong>saucer right side up</strong> lesion. Asymmetrical distribution.</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypopigmented macules or plaques, variable in number, up to <strong>10</strong>.</p>\n<p>Occasionally showing fingerlike extensions<br>(<strong>pseudopodia</strong>) or&nbsp;<strong>satellite lesions</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypopigmented macules or plaques with annular, ‘<strong>swiss&nbsp;</strong><strong>cheese’</strong>&nbsp;/inverted saucer/punched out appearance</p>\n<p>Variable in number<br><strong>(10–30)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Numerous</strong> hypopigmented macules, papules, plaques, and some nodules, lesions with&nbsp;<strong>swiss&nbsp;</strong><strong>cheese’</strong>&nbsp;/inverted saucer/punched out appearance&nbsp;<strong>almost symmetrical</strong> in<br>distribution</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypopigmented macules, plaques,<br>and nodular lesions</p>\n<p><strong>Innumerable</strong> lesions<br>showing&nbsp;<strong>perfect&nbsp; symmetrical&nbsp;</strong>distribution</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Size of Lesion</strong></td>\n<td>Variable size,<strong>usually</strong><br><strong>large</strong></td>\n<td>Variable size, some lesions are large</td>\n<td>Variable</td>\n<td>Variable, usually small</td>\n<td><strong>Small</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Surface of Lesion</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Dry, scaly and infiltrated</strong></td>\n<td>Dry, scaly infiltrated (but less than TT)</td>\n<td>Dry, scaly and slightly shiny</td>\n<td>Shiny (less than LL)</td>\n<td><strong>Shiny</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sensations</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Absent.&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td>Markedly diminished</td>\n<td>Moderately diminished</td>\n<td>Slightly diminished</td>\n<td><strong>May be normal</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Peripheral Nerves</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Asymmetrical, single nerve</strong><br>enlargement.</p>\n<p>Nerve to patch may<br>be palpable</p>\n</td>\n<td>Asymmetrical enlargement of few nerves</td>\n<td>Asymmetrical involvement of several nerves</td>\n<td><strong>Increasingly symmetric</strong> enlargement of nerves</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Symmetrical</strong><br><strong>involvement</strong> of<br>nerve trunks with<br>‘<strong>glove and stocking</strong><br><strong>anesthesia’</strong>.</p>\n<p>Nerves may feel normal on<br>palpation or may be<br>thickened.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hair</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Absent</strong></td>\n<td>Markedly diminished</td>\n<td>Moderately diminished</td>\n<td>Slightly diminished</td>\n<td><strong>Almost normal (initially)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bacteriology on Split Skin Smear</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Negative</strong></td>\n<td>Negative or Scanty Bacilli</td>\n<td>Moderate number of AFB present</td>\n<td>Large number of AFB&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Plenty of AFB including <strong>Globi</strong> are seen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Typical Lepra Reaction</strong></td>\n<td>Type 1</td>\n<td>Type 1</td>\n<td>Type 1/Type 2</td>\n<td>Type 1/Type 2</td>\n<td>Type 2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lepromin Reactivity</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Strongly Positive</strong></p>\n<p>(+++)</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Weakly Positive</p>\n<p>(+ or ++)</p>\n</td>\n<td>Negative/ Weakly positive</td>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td><strong>Negative</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Histopathology</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Dermal Tuberculoid granulomas</strong> (arranged around nerves)</p>\n<p><strong>No bacilli are seen</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Fewer Tuberculoid granulomas</p>\n<p><strong>Grenz clear zone</strong> in upper papillary dermis <strong>starts to form</strong></p>\n<p>Nerves are<br>replaced by granulomas</p>\n<p>Fragmented<br>bacilli are seen with AFB stain</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tuberculoid granulomas less prominent</p>\n<p>Grenz zone is more prominent</p>\n<p>Transverse section of the nerve shows&nbsp;<strong>cut onion appearance</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Prominent foam cells</p>\n<p>Prominent Grenz zone</p>\n<p>Nerves show concentric perineural cell infiltration<br>and <strong>more conspicuous cut onion appearance</strong>.</p>\n<p>AFB are plentiful, including<br><strong>small globi</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Most prominent Grenz zone</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Expansive and loose granulomas</strong></p>\n<p>Plenty of macrophages<br>loaded with AFB- <strong>Virchow cells or Lepra cells</strong></p>\n<p>AFB are seen in endothelial cells and Schwann cells as clumps - <strong>globi</strong></p>\n<p>Nerves are minimally<br>involved.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1491, 'Dermatology', 'PM0342. Differentiating features between Tuberculoid Leprosy (TT) and Lepromatous Leprosy (LL)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Differentiating features between Tuberculoid Leprosy (TT) and Lepromatous Leprosy (LL)</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Tuberculoid</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Lepromatous</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Number of lesions</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>1 -10</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Hundreds, confluent</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Distribution</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Asymmetrical, anywhere</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Symmetrical, avoiding ‘soared’ areas</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Definition and clarity</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Defined edge, markedly hypopigmented</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Vague edge, slight hypopigmented</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Anaesthesia</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Early, marked, defined, localized to skin lesions or major peripheral nerve</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Late, initially slight, ill- defined, but extensive, over ‘cool’ areas of body</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Autonomic loss</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Early in skin and nerve lesions</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Late, extensive as for anesthesia</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Nerve enlargement</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Marked, in a few nerves</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Slight but widespread</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Mucosal and systemic</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Absent</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Common, severe during type 2 reactions</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p><strong>Number of <em>Mycobacterium leprae</em></strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Not detectable</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\150\>\n<p>Numerous in all affected tissue</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1492, 'Dermatology', 'PM2489. Cutaneous lesions of Tuberous sclerosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Tuberous sclerosis (TS)&nbsp;is also known as&nbsp;tuberous sclerosis complex&nbsp;or&nbsp;Bourneville disease. It is a neurocutaneous disorder (<strong>phakomatosis</strong>) characterized by the development of&nbsp;<strong>multiple benign tumors&nbsp;</strong>of the<strong>&nbsp;embryonic ectoderm</strong>&nbsp;(e.g. skin, eyes, and nervous system). It is an&nbsp;<strong>autosomal dominant&nbsp;</strong>condition.&nbsp;&nbsp;The mutations are involved in the&nbsp;<strong>TSC1</strong>&nbsp;gene that encodes&nbsp;<strong>hamartin</strong>&nbsp;on&nbsp;<strong>chromosome 9</strong>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<strong>TSC2 gene&nbsp;</strong>that&nbsp;encodes a protein&nbsp;<strong>tuberin</strong>&nbsp;on&nbsp;<strong>chromosome 16.</strong></p>\n<p>Tuberous sclerosis presents in childhood with a triad (<strong>Vogt triad</strong>). The triad comprises of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Seizures</li>\n<li>Mental retardation</li>\n<li>Adenoma sebaceum</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Skin lesions in tuberous sclerosis</strong>:</p>\n<p><strong>Shagreen patch</strong> consists of a roughened, raised lesion with an orange-peel consistency, located primarily in the lumbosacral region. Shagreen is shark skin used as a decorative material present in the right image given below.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/0cee876a9f6240469fbeeec41caa125ex1280x523.0933333333334.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The typical <strong>hypomelanotic ash leaf–type macules</strong> on the trunk and extremities are&nbsp;seen in 90% of the patients. It is visualized by the use of a wood ultraviolet lamp.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/181f1c6703df48e0b459ef3224c79828x973x697.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Facial angiofibromas (<strong>adenoma sebaceum</strong>) develop between 4 and 6 years of age; they appear as tiny red nodules over the nose and cheeks and are sometimes confused with acne. Later, they enlarge, coalesce, and assume a fleshy appearance.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/7dd9904adb764d4492cce469f6b0ce88x800x525.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Periungual fibroma</strong> are small fibromas or nodules of skin, which form around fingernails or toenails in some adolescent patients</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/d7eeecb16bbf4cfaa451b24185d0ab43x569x629.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Confetti skin lesions</strong>&nbsp;are seen less commonly as a minor feature of tuberous sclerosis.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1d30bdf16a3a42079eaa18cadb32ad7fx1280x521.892071952032.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1493, 'Dermatology,', 'PM2483. Skin rashes (Erythemas)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Erythema marginatum</strong>&nbsp;is an&nbsp;<span>evanescent</span>, non-pruritic rash over the trunk and extremities seen in&nbsp;<strong>rheumatic fever.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/31d3dceee51b4984b72a7db26d7a909ax1280x960.0.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Erythema nodosum&nbsp;</strong>is an acute, nodular, erythematous, painful eruption, occurring probably due to a delayed hypersensitivity reaction to a variety of antigens. Lesions are usually seen over the extensor aspects of the legs. Its causes include infections (tuberculosis), autoimmune (IBD and&nbsp;<strong>sarcoidosis</strong>), idiopathic.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/25992b6578f94152a91386ff3bf217e0x800x562.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Erythema migrans</strong>&nbsp;has a bulls-eye appearance (central erythema and necrosis) and is seen in&nbsp;<strong>Lyme disease.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/98f6b0c0b2ed4191ba8b8d02006ef8f6x1280x1881.077752117013.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Erythema multiforme&nbsp;</strong>lesions usually have a&nbsp;<strong>target appearance</strong>; it is mediated by the deposition of immune complexes in the superficial microvasculature of the skin and oral mucosal membrane. It is usually triggered by certain infections (<strong>herpes simplex virus</strong>) and drugs.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/c2541fbf6c18417aaae813fd00078246x758x600.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1494, 'Dermatology,', 'PM0297. Types of Psoriatic Arthritis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Types of Psoriatic Arthritis - Mnemonic</strong></p>\n<p><strong>“SODA”</strong></p>\n<p><strong>S &nbsp;— &nbsp;S</strong>ymmetrical Polyarthritis</p>\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;S</strong>pondylitis<strong>/S</strong>acroiliits</p>\n<p><strong>O — &nbsp;O</strong>ligoarticular Asymmetrical&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>D — &nbsp;D</strong>IP(Distal Interphalangeal/Classic Type)</p>\n<p><strong>A — &nbsp;A</strong>rthritis Mutilans</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1495, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0353. Defense mechanisms that operate in various diseases', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>OCD</strong> - reaction formation, undoing</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Phobia</strong> - displacement</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Neurosis</strong> - repression</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Grief</strong> - denial</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Borderline personality</strong> - Splitting</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Schizophrenia</strong> - projection</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Enuresis</strong> - Regression</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1496, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0346. Contributions by Sigmund Freud', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Contributions of Sigmund Freud to the field of psychiatry</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Free association</li>\n<li>Interpretation of dreams</li>\n<li>Psychoanalysis</li>\n<li>Psycho-sexual development&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Psychodynamic theory&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Topographic theory of the mind-unconscious, preconscious, conscious</li>\n<li>Structural theory of mind- id, ego, superego</li>\n<li>Cocaine in psychiatry</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1497, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2384. Classification of disorders of thought', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/5245e029dd5b4d2d8711bef5bf3b05eex1280x1809.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1498, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2383. Disorders of thought and perception', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><span><strong>DISORDERS OF THOUGHT</strong></span></p>\n<table width=\431\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>DISORDER OF STREAM OF THOUGHT</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>(A) Disorder of tempo</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(i) Flight of Ideas</span></p>\n<p><span>Continuous flow of rapid speech that jumps from topic to topic</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I like mangoes, the weather is nice, India is great\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(ii) Retardation of thinking</span></p>\n<p><span>Slow speed of speech and a prolonged latent period before a response</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I went to the market (pause)......... the shop was closed\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iii) Circumstantialities</span></p>\n<p><span>Inclusion of irrelevant details and going on in a roundabout manner, but their thought ultimately reaches the answer</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>Doctor: \How did you get that bruise?\</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><span>Patient: \I woke up and had a cup of coffee, read the newspaper and went for a walk. It was a wonderful day in the park. I returned home and watched the TV. I took a nap in the afternoon after lunch. I slipped and fell in the bathroom. The fall gave me this bruise.\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iv) Clang associations</span></p>\n<p><span>Jumping from one word to another irrelevant rhyming word</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>I am Sam...I like jam...I travel in a tram\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>(B) Disorder of continuity</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(i) Perseveration</span></p>\n<p><span>Repetition of out of context words, phrases, or ideas beyond the point of relevance.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>Q1. Whats your name?: \Rahul\</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><span>Q2. Where are you from?: \Rahul\</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><span>Q3. How old are you?: \Rahul\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(ii) Thought blocking</span></p>\n<p><span>A sudden disruption of thought or a break in the flow of ideas</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I went to the market (extreme silence)....................\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width=\429\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>DISORDER OF FORM OF THOUGHT</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(i) Tangentiality</span></p>\n<p><span>In response to a question, the patient gives a reply that is appropriate to the general topic but does not answer the question exactly. The speech moves away from the actual answer.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Doctor: \Have you had any trouble sleeping lately?\</span></li>\n<li><span>Patient: \I usually sleep in my bed, but now Im sleeping on the sofa\</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(ii) Derailment</span></p>\n<p><span>A breakdown in both the logical connection between ideas and the overall sense of goal-directedness. The words make sentences, but the sentences do not make sense.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>\Some people just dont understand why I had breakfast in America during the first world war\</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iii) Neologisms</span></p>\n<p><span>Bringing in new words that do not exist.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>The world is not gooder for people like me\</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iv) Desultory thoughts</span></p>\n<p><span>Speech is grammatically correct, however, sudden unrelated ideas force their way in from time to time.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>My actual problem is that the people never understand me and my stomach feels like an empty bucket\</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(v) Word salad</span></p>\n<p><span>Using a mixture of unintelligible meaningless words and sentences</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Tree bus rain food home car tiger\</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width=\430\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>DISORDER OF POSSESSION OF THOUGHT</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>A. Thought alienation</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(i) Thought insertion</span></p>\n<p><span>Thoughts are being inserted into the patients mind and they recognize them as being foreign and coming from without any stimulus</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I have repeated thoughts of killing my neighbors and I believe aliens are putting these ideas into my head at night\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(ii) Thought withdrawal</span></p>\n<p><span>Delusion that someone or something is removing from ones mind and the patient has no power over this.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\Lately, I am losing all my memories and I believe that the government agents are stealing them when I go to sleep\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iii) Thought broadcasting</span></p>\n<p><span>Belief that ones thoughts are quietly escaping from ones mind and that other people might be able to access them and hear or see them.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I believe my exact thoughts appear on the TV and the internet and I think I can broadcast them globally\&nbsp;</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iv) Thought echo</span></p>\n<p><span>Patient hears the echo of his own thoughts in the form of a voice after he has made the thought.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I thought of making a sandwich in the morning and surprisingly a voice, from nowhere, told me to make a sandwich out loud\</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width=\430\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>&nbsp;<strong>B.&nbsp;</strong><strong>Obsessions and Compulsions</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>1. Obsessions</span></p>\n<p><span>Recurrent and persistent thoughts, impulses. or images that cause distress to oneself.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Fear of dirt or contamination</span></li>\n<li><span>Fear of becoming ill</span></li>\n<li><span>Constant thoughts of a certain number</span></li>\n<li><span>Need for symmetry or exactness</span></li>\n<li><span>Worry about whether something has been done \right\</span></li>\n<li><span>Forbidden sexual or religious thoughts</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span>2. Compulsions</span></p>\n<p><span>Repetitive behaviors or actions that the person feels driven to perform in response to an obsession</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Washing hands</span></li>\n<li><span>Blinking eyes</span></li>\n<li><span>Counting items, such as currency</span></li>\n<li><span>Checking to see if doors are locked</span></li>\n<li><span>Arranging items in a certain way</span></li>\n<li><span>Requiring constant approval from people around them</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;<span><strong>DISORDER OF CONTENT OF THOUGHT</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(i) Phobias</span></p>\n<p><span>Persistent fear of an object or situation, typically disproportional to the actual danger posed, in which the sufferer goes to great lengths in avoiding it</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<div><span>Arachnophobia - fear of spider</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Barophobia - fear of gravity</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Cynophobia - fear of dogs</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Hemophobia - fear of blood</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Nosocomephobia - fear of hospitals</span></div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(ii) Religious preoccupations</span></p>\n<p><span>Thoughts involving religious themes or subject matter.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I get instructions from God on how to make my country great\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iii) Ideas of hopelessness</span></p>\n<p><span>Thoughts of complete despair where the patient strongly believes that the circumstances will never get better for him.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I am never going to pass my final exams, no matter how hard I study\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(iv) Antisocial urges</span></p>\n<p><span>Thoughts of indulging in some behaviors or actions that harm or lack consideration for the well being of others.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span>\I have these urges to go rob a bank or blackmail my neighbors for their money\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span>(v) Delusions</span></p>\n<p><span>False beliefs that are strongly held and unchangeable in the face of refuting evidence and that are not consistent with the persons educational, social and cultural background.</span></p>\n<p><span>The three main criteria for a belief to be considered a delusion are:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<div><span>Certainty (held with complete confidence)</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Incorrigibility (not changeable by proof to the contrary)</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>Impossibility or falsity of content (implausible, bizarre or patently untrue)</span></div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width=\429\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;<span><strong>DISORDERS OF PERCEPTIONS</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span><strong>Illusion</strong>: Misinterpretation of real external stimuli.</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><span><strong>Hallucination</strong>: False sensory perception, externally.</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><span><strong>Pseudohallucination</strong>: False sensory perception from within and having an insight.</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong><span>Depersonalization:</span></strong><span> Feeling as if one is disconnected from reality, feeling detached from ones own thoughts and ones own physical body.</span><strong><span><br></span></strong></p>\n<p><span>\I sometimes drift into a dream-like state where I lose contact with my own self\</span></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong><span>Derealization: </span></strong><span>Alteration in the perception or experience of the external world so that it seems unreal.</span><strong><span><br></span></strong></p>\n<p><span>\The world and everything around is nothing but just a dream\</span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1499, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2323. ECT versus TMS', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\20\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Electroconvulsive Therapy</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Principle</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Seizures are induced by applying an electric current</span></td>\n<td><span>Induction of eddy currents in the cortex by applying magnetic fields</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Mechanism</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Neuroplasticity; induced seizures promote new synapse formation</span></td>\n<td><span>Neuronal stimulation by eddy currents</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Advantages</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>More effective</span></li>\n<li><span>Faster response</span></li>\n<li><span>Shorter treatment course</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Non-invasive</span></li>\n<li><span>Enables focal stimulation of cortical areas</span></li>\n<li><span>No significant memory loss</span></li>\n<li><span>Does not induce seizures</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Disadvantages</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Invasive</span></li>\n<li><span>Requires anesthesia</span></li>\n<li><span>Significant cognitive impairment</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Less effective</span></li>\n<li><span>Slower response</span></li>\n<li><span>Prolonged treatment course</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1500, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2116. Neurotransmitters', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\1103\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Neuro-transmitters</strong></td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Major source</strong></td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Function</strong></td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Increased in</strong></td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Decreased in</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Serotonin</strong></td>\n<td><span>Midline Raphe Nucleus</span>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Inhibitory</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Regulation of mood, sleep, appetite, sexual behavior, decreases anxiety</span></p>\n<p><span>Inhibits the dopaminergic function</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Serotonin syndrome</span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Depression</span></p>\n<p><span>OCD</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dopamine</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<span>Substantia Nigra</span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Inhibitory</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Motor movement and alertness</span></p>\n<p><span>Reward seeking, pleasure, motivation</span></p>\n<p><span>Major neurotransmitter in the basal ganglia</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Schizophrenia</span></p>\n<p><span>OCD</span></p>\n<p><span>Mania</span></p>\n<p><span>Delirium</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Parkinsons disease</span></p>\n<p><span>Depression</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Endorphins</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<span>Pituitary gland</span></td>\n<td><span>Pain control, feelings of pleasure, stress reduction, \natural opium\</span></td>\n<td><span>Addiction</span></td>\n<td><span>Inability to combat pain</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Acetylcholine</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<span>Nucleus Basalis (of Meynert)</span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Excitatory</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Motor movement, learning and memory</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Parkinsons disease</span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Alzheimers disease</span></p>\n<p><span>Delirium</span></p>\n<p><span>Dementia</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>GABA</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Inhibitory</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Decreases anxiety and reduces insomnia</span></p>\n<p><span>Interacts with dopamine, inhibits dopaminergic neurons</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Anxiety</span></p>\n<p><span>Seizure disorder</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Norepinephrine</strong></td>\n<td><span>Locus ceruleus</span>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Excitatory:</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>\Fight or flight\</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Mania</span></td>\n<td><span>Lack of energy, anhedonia in Schizophrenia,&nbsp;</span><span>Depression</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Glutamate</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Excitatory</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Links between neurons for learning and long term memory</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Seizures</span></td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1501, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2046. The Mental Health Care Act, 2017 and The Mental Health Act, 1987', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The <strong>Mental Health Care Act</strong>, <strong>2017</strong>, was passed to provide for health care and services for persons with mental illness and to protect, promote and fulfill their rights during the delivery of mental health care.</p>\n<p>Its main provisions are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Patient autonomy</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>The mentally ill patient has the right to make an advance directive about their treatment and their nominated representative.</li>\n<li>If the mental health professional/care-giver does not wish to follow the <strong>advance directive</strong> made by the patient, they can send an application to the Mental Health Board to review/alter/cancel the advance directive.</li>\n<li><strong>Decriminalization of suicide</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Mental Health Review Commission and Mental Health Authority&nbsp;</strong>set up.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong class=\ng-binding\>The Mental Health Act, 1987:</strong></p>\n<div class=\panel-body ng-scope\>\n<p class=\ng-binding ng-scope\>The&nbsp;Mental Health Act, 1987 deals with the care of the mentally ill, makes provisions with respect to their property and affairs and states the law for psychiatric hospitals .<sup class=\reference\></sup></p>\n<p>Important provisions under it for the diagnosis of mental illness are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For the diagnosis of mental illness, an individual can be kept in a psychiatric hospital for&nbsp;<strong>10 days</strong>.</li>\n<li>If the mental health professional needs further time, the magistrate can permit an extension of&nbsp;<strong>10 more days.</strong></li>\n<li>This extension can be permitted only&nbsp;<strong>twice</strong>.</li>\n<li>Thus, an individual can be detained in a psychiatric hospital for a maximum period of&nbsp;<strong>30 days only</strong>.</li>\n<li>If a mentally ill person is detained against these provisions, the responsible authority can be punished with an imprisonment of upto&nbsp;<strong>2 years.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1502, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1607. Tests for evaluating attention, concentration and memory', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Memory</strong>:</p>\n<p>Memory is of 3 types:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Immediate memory and recall</strong> are usually tested by digit span/ digit repetition test.\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Digit span test</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Digits spelled at the rate of <strong>1 digit per second.&nbsp;</strong>It is of two types: Digit forward and Digit backward.</li>\n<li><strong>Digit forward</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Reproduction of increasingly longer digits. E.g., Examiner says 2 - 4 –8 –1 –5 –7 - 9. The person has to repeat in the same order 2 – 4 – 8 –1 –5 –7 –9.</li>\n<li><strong>Digit backward</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Reproduction of longer digits in the backward direction. Eg: Examiner says 2 - 4 –8 –1 –5 –7 - 9. The person has to repeat it backward. 9 -7 -5 -1 -8- 4- 2.</li>\n<li>The above tests should<strong> be stopped</strong> when there are <strong>2 successive failures</strong>. Hence <strong>2 skips are not allowed</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Recent memory</strong>:&nbsp;Ask them how they reached the hospital or what they ate for breakfast.</li>\n<li><strong>Remote memory</strong>:&nbsp;Relevant questions from the past like close relatives birth dates.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Attention</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Is the patients attention easily aroused and sustained?</li>\n<li><strong>Digit span </strong>test.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Concentration</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Is the patient easily distractable or can they concentrate?</li>\n<li><strong>Serial subtraction test</strong>: Minimum of five subtractions done serially is taken into account</li>\n<li>Count backward from 20.</li>\n<li>Enumerate the months in reverse order.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1503, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0498. Key points on electroconvulsive therapy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Produces grand mal seizure in an anesthetized patient.</p>\n<p>Mechanism of action:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Neuroplasticity</strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Ability of the brain to form and reorganize synaptic connections.</li>\n<li>Increases levels of Brain-Derived Growth Factor and Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Indications</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Treatment-resistant depression</li>\n<li>Severe depression with suicidal risk (most common indication)</li>\n<li>Depression with psychotic features</li>\n<li>Depressed suicidal pregnant women</li>\n<li>Refusal to eat or drink</li>\n<li>Imminent risk for suicide</li>\n<li>Neuroleptic malignant syndrome</li>\n<li>Catatonia and catatonic schizophrenia</li>\n<li>Severe agitated depression</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Electrode placement: <strong>Bifrontotemporal</strong>, <strong>right unilateral</strong>.</p>\n<p>Anesthetic agent: <strong>Methohexital</strong> (most common)</p>\n<p>Adverse effects:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Retrograde amnesia (most common)</li>\n<li>Partial anterograde amnesia</li>\n<li>Disorientation</li>\n<li>Temporary headache</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Memory disturbances recover within 1-6 months. <strong>Safe in pregnancy</strong>.&nbsp;ECT can reverse extrapyramidal symptoms of neuroleptics.</p>\n<p>Contraindications: <strong>No absolute contraindication</strong> (raised intracranial tension is considered as a relative contraindication).</p>\n<p>Increased risk of adverse effects in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Severe cardiovascular disease, recent myocardial infarction</li>\n<li>Space occupying brain lesion</li>\n<li>Recent stroke, unstable aneurysm</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1504, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0397. Timeline in psychiatry', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Condition</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Duration</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Manic episode</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>At least 1 week</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Hypomania</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>At least 4 consecutive days</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Major depressive disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Lasts 6 to12 months with episodes for 2 or more weeks</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Cyclothymia</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>At least 2 years</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Dysthymia</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>At least 2 years</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Maternal blues</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Starts 2–3 days after delivery and usually resolves within 10 days</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Postpartum mood disturbances</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Onset within 4 weeks of delivery</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Brief psychotic disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &lt; 1 month, usually stress-related</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizophreniform disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts 1-6 months</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizophrenia</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 6 months</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizoaffective disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 2 weeks</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Delusional disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 1 month</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Panic disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>An episode followed by 1 month of concern of additional attacks&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Specific phobia</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 6 months</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Generalized anxiety disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 6 months&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Acute stress disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts between 3 days and 1 month&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>PTSD</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 1 month&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Adjustment disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Symptoms occur within 3 months of the stressor and last &lt; 6 months</span></p>\n<p><span>May last &gt; 6 months in presence of chronic stressor</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Bulimia nervosa</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>At least 3 months</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Somatic symptom disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Lasts &gt; 6 months</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Separation anxiety disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Common onset at 7–9 years&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Tourette syndrome</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Onset &lt; age 18 years</span></p>\n<p><span>Tics that persist for &gt; 1 year&nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>ADHD</strong></span></td>\n<td><span>Symptoms for &gt; 6 months&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1505, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0264. Types of delusions', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>THE TYPES OF DELUSIONS</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of control</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>False belief that a person’s will, thoughts, or feelings are being controlled by external forces.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of grandeur </strong>or<strong> Megalomania</strong>&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span>Exaggerated conception of one’s importance, power, or identity.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of infidelity </strong>or morbid jealousy or <strong>Othello syndrome</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>False&nbsp;belief that one’s lover is unfaithful.&nbsp;Sometimes called pathological jealousy.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion of love </strong>or<strong> erotomania</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>False belief that another person is in love with them. In<strong> De Clerambault</strong> syndrome, the woman believes that a man, frequently older and of higher status, is in love with her.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion of misidentification</strong>&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Capgras syndrome</strong>: Belief that a familiar person has been replaced by an exact double i.e. an <strong>impostor</strong>.</span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Fregoli syndrome</strong>: Person holds a delusional belief that different people are in fact a single person who changes his or her appearance or is in <strong>disguise</strong>.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Nihilistic delusion</strong>&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span>False belief that oneself, others or the world, is non-existent or about to end. When nihilistic delusion is accompanied by ideas concerning bodily function failure e.g. putrefaction of intestine etc, it is called <strong>Cotard syndrome.</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion of infestation</strong>&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span>False belief that one is infested with small but visible organisms. As a monosymptomatic delusional disorder, this is called <strong>Ekbom syndrome.&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of persecution</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>The most<strong>&nbsp;common delusion</strong>.<strong>&nbsp;</strong>False&nbsp;belief of being harassed or persecuted.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of poverty</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>The person&nbsp;strongly believes they are financially incapacitated.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion of reference</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>False belief that the behavior of others has a particular and unusual significance, usually of a negative nature. The person may falsely feel that others are talking about them (e.g. the people on television are talking to or about the person). &nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delusion&nbsp;of self-accusation</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>False&nbsp;feeling of remorse and guilt.&nbsp;Seen in depression with psychotic features.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1506, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0239. Tests for intelligence', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 277\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Omnibus Intellectual and Ability Tests:</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale (WAIS) - 16 yrs to 90 yrs</li>\n<li>Stanford-Binet test - 2 yrs to 89 yrs</li>\n<li>Binet-Kamat test of intelligence</li>\n<li>Bhatia’s battery test of intelligence</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Infant and Child Tests:</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<ul>\n<li class=\ng-binding\>Gesell schedule - 1month to 36 months</li>\n<li>Bayley scale - 1 month to 42 months</li>\n<li>Mullen scale - 0 months to 68 months&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1507, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0237. Neuropsychological tests', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1132\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>The neuropsychiatric evaluation combines information from neurological, neuropsychological testing, and mental status examinations.</p>\n<p>The following are some common neuropsychological screening tests and test batteries:&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Wisconsin card sorting test</li>\n<li>Wechsler memory scale</li>\n<li>PGI memory scale</li>\n<li>Bender Gestalt test or&nbsp;BG test</li>\n<li>Benton visual retention test or&nbsp;BVRT</li>\n<li>Luria-Nebraska neuropsychological battery</li>\n<li>Halstead-Reitan neuropsychological test battery</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1508, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2377. The 5 stages of grief model by Kübler-Ross', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>D</strong>enial - Patients may become numb and dazed at the news of their own imminent death and refuse to accept the diagnosis.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>nger - Patients may get angry towards God or themselves.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>B</strong>argaining - Patients may start to bargain with God or friends and doctors for a cure to buy some more time.</li>\n<li><strong>D</strong>epression - Patients may go into depression.</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>cceptance - Patients finally accept that their death is inevitable and make further preparations (eg., making a will, etc).&nbsp;</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1509, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1861. Neurotransmitters in Psychiatry', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Neurotransmitter</strong></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Source</strong></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Disorder</strong></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Dopamine</strong></div>\n&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Substantia Nigra</div>\n&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Decrease</strong>:</div>\n<div>Parkinson’s disease</div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Increase</strong>:&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Mania, Delirium</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Acetylcholine</strong></div>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<div>Nucleus Basalis (of Meynert)</div>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Decrease</strong>:</div>\n<div>Delirium, Dementia</div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Increase</strong>:</div>\n<div>Parkinson’s disease</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Norepinephrine</strong></td>\n<td>Locus Coeruleus</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Decrease</strong>:</div>\n<div>Depression</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Serotonin</strong></td>\n<td>Midline Raphe nucleus</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Decrease</strong>:</div>\n<div>Depression</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1510, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0528. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Neuroleptic Malignant syndrome</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Signs/ symptoms</td>\n<td>\n<p>Fever (sometimes &gt; 40<sup>o</sup> C)</p>\n<p>Mental status changes</p>\n<p>Motor symptoms:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Muscular rigidity </strong>(generalised)</li>\n<li>Dystonia</li>\n<li>Akinesia</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Autonomic symptoms: &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia/arrhythmias</li>\n<li>Labile blood pressure &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Tachypnea</li>\n<li>Diaphoresis</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Mutism, obtundation, and agita­tion.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Precipitating factors</td>\n<td>\n<p>Antipsychotics (typical and atypical)</p>\n<p>Antiemetics (ex: Promethazine, Metoclopramide)&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Withdrawal of Antiparkinsonian drugs (dopamine agonists)&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Infection&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Surgery</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Investigations</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Elevated WBC count,</strong> creatinine phosphokinase (<strong>CPK</strong>), myoglobin, and liver enzymes.</p>\n<p>Myoglobinuria may be seen in patients who develop acute renal failure.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Treatment&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Stop neuroleptic agents and start dopaminergic agonists</li>\n<li>Supportive care (hydration, cooling)</li>\n<li>Dantrolene or Bromocriptine</li>\n<li>Amantadine may be used in some cases.</li>\n<li>Electroconvulsive therapy may also be used.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1511, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0263. Difference between psychotic and neurotic illness', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Psychosis</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Neurosis</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Insight absent</td>\n<td>Insight present</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Personality changed</td>\n<td>Personality maintained</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Impaired judgment</td>\n<td>Judgment normal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Loss of contact with reality</td>\n<td>Contact with reality is present</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>An organic cause may be present</td>\n<td>Absence of organic causative factor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hallucination, delusion present</td>\n<td>Not present</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ex: Schizophrenia,&nbsp; acute psychotic disorder</td>\n<td>Ex: Anxiety, OCD, conversion disorder</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1512, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2172. Symptoms of schizophrenia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Positive symptoms</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Negative symptoms</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>Hallucination</div>\n<div>Delusion</div>\n<div>Bizarre motor acts</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Flattening of affect</div>\n<div>Anhedonia</div>\n<div>Alogia</div>\n<div>Apathy</div>\n<div>Paucity of thought</div>\n<div>Poverty of speech</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Common in <strong>acute schizophrenia</strong></td>\n<td>Common in <strong>chronic schizophrenia</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hyperactivity of the dopaminergic system in the <strong>mesolimbic</strong> system</td>\n<td>Hypoactivity of the dopaminergic system in the <strong>mesocortical</strong> system</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Respond to most&nbsp;<strong>typical and atypical</strong> antipsychotics</td>\n<td>Respond better to&nbsp;<strong>atypical</strong> antipsychotics</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1513, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0445. Psychiatric conditions and associated neurotransmitter activity', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Psychiatric Condition</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Associated Neurotransmitter Activity</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Depression</strong></td>\n<td>Decrease in serotonin, norepinephrine and dopamine</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mania</strong></td>\n<td>Increase in dopamine and decrease in GABA</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Schizophrenia</strong></td>\n<td>Increase in dopamine and serotonin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Anxiety</strong></td>\n<td>Increase in norepinephrine and decrease in GABA ad serotonin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Alzheimers disease</strong></td>\n<td>Decrease in Norepinephrine and decrease&nbsp;in Acetylcholine</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1514, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0339. Clozapine treatment guidelines', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Clozapine treatment guidelines:</strong></p>\n<p>Indications:&nbsp; Treatment resistant schizophrenia, schizophrenia associated with suicidality.</p>\n<p>Adverse effects:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Agranulocytosis</li>\n<li>Seizures</li>\n<li>Myocarditis</li>\n<li>Metabolic syndrome</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1515, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0336. Psychotic disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Differential diagnosis of DSM-5 psychotic disorders</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Psychotic disorder</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span><strong>Criteria for diagnosis</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Brief psychotic disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Sudden onset and a full return to function</span></p>\n<p><span>Duration: &gt; 1 day and &lt; 1 month</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizophreniform disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Same symptoms as schizophrenia and functional decline not required</span></p>\n<p><span>Duration: &gt; 1 month &amp; &lt; 6 months</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizophrenia</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Requires functional decline</span></p>\n<p><span>At least 6 months (includes at least 1 month of active symptoms, can include prodromal and residual periods)</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Schizoaffective disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>With concurrent mood episode.&nbsp;</span><span>Active-phase symptoms of schizophrenia with at least a 2 weeks of lifetime history of delusions or hallucinations in absence of prominent mood symptoms</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Delusional disorder</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>One or more delusions for &gt; 1 month</span></p>\n<p><span>No other psychotic symptoms and normal functioning apart from the direct impact of delusions</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Shared psychotic disorder (folie a deux)</strong></span></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Development of delusions in a person who is in a close relationship (ex: spouse, child) with someone who has a delusional disorder (the inducer)</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1516, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0333. Prevalence of schizophrenia in specific population', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\15\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Populations</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Prevalence</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>General population</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>One schizophrenic parent</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>12%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Two schizophrenic parents</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>40%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Monozygotic twin</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>47%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Dizygotic twin</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>12%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>First-degree relative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>12%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Second-degree relative</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>5–6%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1517, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1864. Differential diagnosis of dementia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Condition</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Features</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Alzheimer’s disease</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Insidious onset</span></li>\n<li><strong><span>Short-term memory loss</span></strong></li>\n<li><span>Language deficits and spatial disorientation</span></li>\n<li><span>Later, personality changes</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Vascular Dementia</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Stepwise decline</span></li>\n<li><strong><span>Early executive dysfunction</span></strong></li>\n<li><span>Cerebral infarction &amp;/or deep white matter changes on neuroimaging</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Frontotemporal dementia</strong></span></div>\n<div><span><strong>(Pick’s disease)</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Early <strong>personality changes</strong></span></li>\n<li><span>Apathy, disinhibition &amp; compulsive behaviors</span></li>\n<li><span>Frontotemporal atrophy on neuroimaging</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Dementia with Lewy bodies</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Visual Hallucination</strong></span></li>\n<li><span>Spontaneous parkinsonism</span></li>\n<li><span>Fluctuating cognition</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Normal-pressure hydrocephalus</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Gait abnormalities&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span>Urinary Incontinence</span></li>\n<li><span>Dementia</span></li>\n<li><strong><span>Dilated ventricles on neuroimaging</span></strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease</strong></span></div>\n<div><span><strong>(Prion disease)</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><span>Behavioral changes</span></strong></li>\n<li><span>Rapidly progressive</span></li>\n<li><span>Myoclonus and/or seizures</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1518, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1862. Clinical subtypes of delirium', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\p1\><strong>Hyperactive Delirium</strong></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Hypoactive Delirium</strong></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><strong>Mixed delirium</strong></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\p1\>Increased</div>\n<div class=\p1\>Psychomotor activities like restlessness, hyperarousal and increased speech</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Decreased Psychomotor activities like withdrawal, apathy and diminished speech&nbsp;</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Presence of both either simultaneously or sequentially</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\p1\>Easily identified</div>\n<div class=\p1\>due to dramatic symptoms</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Overlooked&nbsp; and often mistaken for depression</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Confusion in diagnosis due to varying presentations</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\p1\>Common in drug withdrawal/ intoxication</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Common in metabolic encephalopathies</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>Multiple etiologies</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1519, 'Medicine,', 'PM0404. Alzheimer’s disease', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Alzheimer’s disease:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Age of onset &gt; 60 years</li>\n<li>Mini-mental state examination (MMSE) &lt; 24</li>\n<li>Diagnosis: Clinical\n<ul>\n<li>2 or more areas of cognitive deficits</li>\n<li>Progressive worsening of memory and other cognitive function</li>\n<li>No disturbance in consciousness</li>\n<li>Other systemic causes must be ruled out&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Risk Factors:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Most important risk factor: Old age</li>\n<li>Other risk factors – Family history, presenilin-1, presenilin-2, Apolipoprotein E4&nbsp;<strong><strong>(ApoE ε4 allele)</strong></strong>,&nbsp;Ubiquitin, Down syndrome and smoking.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Protective factors:</strong> NSAIDs and Apolipoprotein <strong>E2</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Causes: </strong>Decrease in <strong>acetylcholine</strong> causing depletion&nbsp;of the&nbsp;cholinergic neurons&nbsp;in the <strong>nucleus basalis of Meynert</strong> resulting in short-term memory defects.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Early findings:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Anterograde</strong> memory loss (immediate recall affected, distant memories preserved)</li>\n<li><strong>Visuospatial deficits</strong> (lost in own neighborhood)</li>\n<li><strong>Language difficulties</strong> (difficulty finding words)</li>\n<li><strong>Cognitive impairment</strong> with a progressive decline</li>\n<li>Anosognosia&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Visual processing dysfunction (posterior cortical atrophy syndrome)</li>\n<li>Difficulties with naming and repetition (logopenic aphasia)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Late findings:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Psychotic symptoms: <strong>delusions</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Apraxia</strong>: Difficulty to perform learned motor tasks</li>\n<li><strong>Lack of insight</strong> regarding deficits</li>\n<li>Non-cognitive neurologic deficits: Pyramidal and extrapyramidal, myoclonus and seizures</li>\n<li>disrupted sleep - wake pattern.</li>\n<li><strong>Urinary incontinence.</strong></li>\n<li>Loss of procedural memory</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Histopathology:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Senile plaques</strong> (amyloid deposits), <strong>neurofibrillary tangles</strong> (composed of <strong>tau</strong> proteins), neuronal loss, synaptic loss, and granulovacuolar degeneration of neurons.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The image below shows neurofibrillary tangles in&nbsp;Alzheimers disease.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e5db3b220b5c4a6fb0a82d0c724c68c5x640x784.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>CT/MRI:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Later stages: Cortical and subcortical atrophy prominent in parietal and temporal lobes, particularly <strong>hippocampus</strong>.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>NMDA antagonist: <strong>memantine</strong></li>\n<li>Cholinesterase inhibitors: <strong>donepezil</strong>, <strong>galantamine</strong>, <strong>rivastigmine</strong>.</li>\n<li>Monoclonal antibody against the N-terminus of the Aβ peptide - <strong>aducanumab</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1520, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0401. Delirium vs Dementia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Features</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Delirium</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Dementia</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Presentation</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Hallmark is impaired consciousness</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Loss of memory and intellectual abilities</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong><span>Commonly seen in&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Children and elderly&nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Elderly&nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Associated physical findings</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Acute medical illness&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span>Autonomic dysfunction</span></li>\n<li><span>Abnormal EEG&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span>Carphologia or&nbsp;floccillation&nbsp;(picking movements at cover-sheets and clothes)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>No medical illness</span></li>\n<li><span>Little autonomic dysfunction</span></li>\n<li><span>Normal EEG&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Psychological findings</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Impaired consciousness</span></li>\n<li><span>Illusion, delusion&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span>Sundowning (symptoms much worse at night)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Normal consciousness</span></li>\n<li><span>Depressed mood&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span>Personality changes in early stages in Pick’s disease&nbsp;<br></span></li>\n<li><span>Sundowning (symptoms much worse at night)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Course</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Develops quickly</span></li>\n<li><span>Fluctuating course with lucid intervals (waxing and waning)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Insidious-onset</span></li>\n<li><span>Progressive downhill course</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;\n<p><span><strong>Etiology</strong></span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>CNS disease (E.g: Huntington or Parkinson disease)</span></li>\n<li><span>CNS trauma</span></li>\n<li><span>CNS infection (E.g: Meningitis)</span></li>\n<li><span>Systemic disease (E.g., hepatic, cardiovascular)</span></li>\n<li><span>Substance abuse/withdrawal</span></li>\n<li><span>HIV infection</span></li>\n<li><span>Prescription drug overdose (E.g: atropine)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Alzheimers disease</span></li>\n<li><span>Vascular disease (15-30% of all dementias)</span></li>\n<li><span>CNS disease (E.g., Huntingtons or Parkinsons disease)</span></li>\n<li><span>CNS infection (HIV, Prion diseases)</span></li>\n<li><span>Lewy body dementia</span></li>\n<li><span>Picks disease (Frontotemporal dementia)&nbsp;</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;\n<p><span><strong>Treatment:</strong></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Treat the underlying medical cause</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors&nbsp;(donepezil, rivastigmine) and&nbsp;</span><span>NMDA antagonist (memantine)</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1521, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1983. Patterns of Mood Disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/6ab1892272934b0792b8745017664ccfx1280x6841.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1522, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1904. Mania Vs Hypomania', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mania</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Hypomania</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Symptoms for at least 1 week</td>\n<td>Symptoms for at least 4 days</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Marked impairment in social or occupational functioning</td>\n<td>No impairment in social or occupational functioning</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>May need hospitalization</td>\n<td>Doesnt need hospitalization</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1523, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0500. Treatment of acute manic episode', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>There is no single drug of choice for the treatment of acute mania.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If the patient is <strong>on anti-depressants</strong>: Stop antidepressants.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If the patient is <strong>already on anti-manic medication</strong>:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If already on lithium or valproate: increase the dose of lithium or valproate and consider adding an antipsychotic.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Consider adding short-term benzodiazepines for all patients.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the patient is <strong>not on anti-manic medication</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Consider an antipsychotic if symptoms are severe and behavior is disturbed (or)</li>\n<li>Consider valproate, but avoid in women of reproductive age (or)</li>\n<li>Consider lithium if future adherence is likely&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Consider adding short-term benzodiazepines for all patients.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1524, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0499. Bipolar disorder', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong> Bipolar &amp; related disorders </strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Manic episode</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Symptoms more <strong>severe</strong></span></li>\n<li><span><strong>1 week</strong> unless hospitalized</span></li>\n<li><span><strong>Marked impairment</strong> in social or occupational functioning or <strong>hospitalization</strong> necessary</span></li>\n<li><span>May have <strong>psychotic features</strong>; makes episode manic by definition</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Hypomanic episode</strong> &nbsp;</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Symptoms <strong>less severe</strong></span></li>\n<li><span><strong>4 days&nbsp;</strong>to less than 7 days</span></li>\n<li><span>Unequivocal, observable change in functioning from patients baseline</span></li>\n<li><span>Symptoms not severe enough to cause marked impairment or necessitate hospitalization</span></li>\n<li><span><strong>No psychotic features</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Bipolar I</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Manic episode(s)</strong></span></li>\n<li><span>Depressive episodes common (but not required for diagnosis)</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Bipolar II</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Hypomanic episode(s)</strong></span></li>\n<li><span>Major depressive episodes (required for diagnosis)</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Cyclothymic disorder</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>At least <strong>2 years</strong> of fluctuating, mild hypomanic &amp; depressive symptoms that </span><br><span>do not meet criteria for hypomanic episodes or major depressive episodes</span></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1525, 'Obstetrics & Gynaecology,', 'PM0497. Postpartum mood disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span><strong>Disorders and features</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Incidence and timeline</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Harmful thoughts</strong></span></td>\n<td><span><strong>Treatment</strong></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Postpartum blues</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Depressed affect, tearfulness and fatigue</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>30-75%</span></p>\n<p><span>Starts&nbsp;2-3 days after delivery. Resolves within 10 days.</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>No thoughts of harming the baby</span></td>\n<td><span>Support and follow up</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Postpartum depression</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Depressed affect, anxiety, and poor concentration</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>10-15%</span></p>\n<p><span>Starts within 4 weeks from delivery (DSM 5) or 6 weeks (ICD 11) and persists for ≥ 2 weeks.&nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Thoughts of harming the baby often present</span></td>\n<td><span>CBT and SSRIs&nbsp;</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><span><strong>Postpartum psychosis</strong>:</span></p>\n<p><span>Mood-congruent delusions, hallucinations</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><span>0.1-0.2%</span></p>\n<p><span>Onset within 4 weeks postpartum (DSM 5) or 6 weeks (ICD 11)</span></p>\n</td>\n<td><span>Thoughts of harming the baby or self</span></td>\n<td><span>Hospitalization, atypical antipsychotics and ECT for refractory cases</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Note: Zuranolone is the first-ever oral drug to be FDA-approved specifically for the treatment of postpartum depression. It is a neuroactive steroid that enhances the action of GABA in the brain and regulates mood.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1526, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0496. Signs and symptoms of depression', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Mnemonic \<strong>SIGECAPS</strong>\</p>\n<p><strong>S</strong>leep disorder (increased or decreased)</p>\n<p><strong>I</strong>nterest deficit (anhedonia): loss of interest in previously pleasurable activities</p>\n<p><strong>G</strong>uilt (worthlessness, hopelessness, regret)</p>\n<p><strong>E</strong>nergy deficit</p>\n<p><strong>C</strong>oncentration deficit</p>\n<p><strong>A</strong>ppetite disorder (increased or decreased)</p>\n<p><strong>P</strong>sychomotor retardation or agitation</p>\n<p><strong>S</strong>uicidal tendency</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1527, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0418. Acute drug intoxication', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Acute Drug Intoxication</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Drug</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Class</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Clinical Features</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Phencyclidine (PCP)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hallucinogen</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Hypertension</li>\n<li>Ataxia</li>\n<li>Hallucinations</li>\n<li>Violent behavior</li>\n<li>Dissociation</li>\n<li>Amnesia</li>\n<li><strong>Nystagmus</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>LSD</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hallucinogen</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Hypertension</li>\n<li>Ataxia</li>\n<li><strong>Visual hallucinations</strong></li>\n<li>Euphoria</li>\n<li>Dysphoric/panic</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Cocaine</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Stimulant&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia</li>\n<li>Hypertension</li>\n<li>Agitation</li>\n<li>Euphoria</li>\n<li><strong>Chest pain</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Seizures</strong></li>\n<li>Mydriasis</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Methamphetamine</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Stimulant</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia</li>\n<li>Hypertension</li>\n<li>Violent behavior</li>\n<li>Psychosis</li>\n<li>Diaphoresis</li>\n<li>Choreiform movements</li>\n<li>Tooth decay</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Marijuana (THC, Cannabis)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Psychoactive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Increased appetite</strong></li>\n<li>Euphoria</li>\n<li>Dysphoria/panic</li>\n<li><strong>Impaired time perception</strong></li>\n<li>Dry mouth</li>\n<li><strong>Conjunctival injection</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Heroin</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Opioid</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Euphoria</li>\n<li><strong>Depressed mental status</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Miosis</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Respiratory depression</strong></li>\n<li>Constipation</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1528, 'Psychiatry', 'PM2336. Differential diagnosis of Trauma and Stress related disorder', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span>&nbsp;</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>PTSD</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Adjustment disorder</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Bereavement</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Stressor</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Extreme traumatic events like rape or accident</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Financial/ Illness/ Relationship issues</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Death of a loved one</span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Time</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div><span>Symptoms</span></div>\n</div>\n<div><span><strong>develop</strong><strong>&nbsp;within 6 months</strong> and persist more than 1 month</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div><span>Symptoms</span></div>\n</div>\n<div><span><strong>develop</strong><strong>&nbsp;within 3 months</strong> and resolve in 6 months if stressor eliminated</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Symptoms <strong>develop within 2 months</strong> and resolve within 2 months</span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Symptoms</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Flashbacks and nightmares</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Mostly depressive and anxiety</span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Mostly depressive</span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1529, 'Psychiatry', 'PM1874. Anxiety disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Disorder&nbsp;</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Feature</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Panic disorder</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>1. Recurrent and unexpected panic attacks with ≥ 4 of the following:</span></div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Dyspnea</span></li>\n<li><span>Tachypnea</span></li>\n<li><span>Palpitations</span></li>\n<li><span>Sweating</span></li>\n<li><span>Dizziness</span></li>\n<li><span>Chest pain</span></li>\n<li><span>Tightness</span></li>\n<li><span>Paresthesias</span></li>\n<li><span>Emotional and cognitive</span><br><span>symptoms</span></li>\n<li><span>Feeling that something catastrophic is</span><br><span>about to happen.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>2. At least 1 attack followed by one or both of the following &gt; 1 month:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Worry about an additional panic attack or consequences</li>\n<li>Changes in behaviour related to attacks (ex: avoidance)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>3. Panic attack not attributable to substance abuse or another medical condition.</p>\n<p>4. Panic attack not explained by another mental disorder.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Treatment of Panic disorder:</p>\n<p>Immediate: Benzodiazepines <br>Long term: SSRI/ SNRI and or cognitive behavioural therapy</p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Phobias</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Exaggerated anxiety responses that occur</span><br><span>during exposure to relatively innocuous stimuli or situations.</span></div>\n<div><span>Specific phobias entail phobic responses to</span><br><span>particular stimuli or situations.</span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Social</strong></span><br><span><strong>anxiety disorder (Social phobia)</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Phobic responses to specific social situations.</span></div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><span><strong>Generalized anxiety disorder</strong></span></div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div><span>Excessive worry about</span><br><span>a variety of topics (job, health, finances, etc.) &gt; 6 months.</span></div>\n<div><span>&nbsp;</span></div>\n<div><span>3 or more of the following symptoms:</span></div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Restlessness</span></li>\n<li><span>Fatigue</span></li>\n<li><span>Difficulty concentrating</span></li>\n<li><span>Irritability</span></li>\n<li><span>Muscle tension</span></li>\n<li><span>Sleep disturbance</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><span>Treatment:</span></p>\n<p><span>First line: CBT, SSRIs or SNRIs</span></p>\n<p><span>Second-line: Benzodiazepines, Buspirone</span></p>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div><span>&nbsp;</span></div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1530, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0552. Obsessive-compulsive disorder', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Key points:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Most common:\n<ul>\n<li>Obsession: <strong>Contamination</strong></li>\n<li>Compulsion: <strong>Checking, cleaning</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Treatment: Exposure and Response prevention - 1st line, Cognitive Behavioural Therapy(CBT), CBT with ERP, Pharmacotherapy.</li>\n<li>Drug of choice:&nbsp;High dose <strong>SSRI</strong></li>\n<li>Treatment in nonresponsive patients:&nbsp;Clomipramine or antipsychotic augmentation</li>\n<li>Treatment of severe or refractory cases:&nbsp;<strong>Deep brain stimulation</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1531, 'Psychiatry', 'PM0550. Specific phobia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Present in 10% of the population.</p>\n<p>Clinical features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Marked anxiety about a specific object</strong> or situation (the phobic stimulus) for &gt; 6 months</li>\n<li>Usually develops in childhood, can develop after a traumatic event</li>\n<li>Avoidance behavior</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Treatment:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Behavioral therapy</strong> (exposure-based, systematic desensitization) is the <strong>treatment of choice</strong></li>\n<li>Short-acting <strong>benzodiazepines</strong> may help acutely</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\257\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Phobia</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Object</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acarophobia</td>\n<td>Small objects</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acrophobia</td>\n<td>High places</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Agoraphobia</td>\n<td>Open or crowded places, leaving familiar setting of home</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Aichmophobia</td>\n<td>Pointed objects</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ailurophobia</td>\n<td>Cats</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Algophobia</td>\n<td>Pain</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Androphobia</td>\n<td>Men</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Astraphobia or astrapophobia</td>\n<td>Thunder and lightning</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Autophobia</td>\n<td>Being alone, or of self</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bathophobia</td>\n<td>Depths</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Claustrophobia</td>\n<td>Closed or confined places</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Coprophobia</td>\n<td>Excreta</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cynophobia</td>\n<td>Dogs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Demophobia</td>\n<td>Crowds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Erythrophobia</td>\n<td>Blushing</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gynophobia</td>\n<td>Women</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Haphephobia</td>\n<td>Being touched</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hematophobia</td>\n<td>Sight of blood</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hydrophobia</td>\n<td>Water</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hypnophobia</td>\n<td>Sleep</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lalophobia or glossophobia</td>\n<td>Speaking</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mysophobia</td>\n<td>Dirt, contamination</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Necrophobia</td>\n<td>Dead bodies</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nyctophobia</td>\n<td>Darkness, night</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Panphobia</td>\n<td>Everything</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pathophobia or nosophobia</td>\n<td>Disease, suffering</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Peccatophobia</td>\n<td>Sinning</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pedophobia</td>\n<td>Children</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Phonophobia</td>\n<td>Speaking aloud</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Photophobia</td>\n<td>Strong light</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sitophobia</td>\n<td>Eating</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Taphophobia</td>\n<td>Being buried alive</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Thanatophobia</td>\n<td>Death</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Toxophobia</td>\n<td>Being poisoned</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Xenophobia</td>\n<td>Strangers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Zoophobia</td>\n<td>Animals</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
