(1738, 'Medicine', 'PM1665. Nerve Fiber Types And Sensory Neuropathies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Depending on the nerve fibers involved (Large or Small), the sensory neuropathies are classified as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>A. Small fiber</strong> (Painful neuropathies: dissociated sensory loss)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lepromatous leprosy</li>\n<li>Amyloidosis</li>\n<li>Diabetic small fiber neuropathy</li>\n<li>HIV and antiretroviral therapy neuropathy</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>B. Large fiber </strong>(Ataxic neuropathies)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sjogren’s syndrome</li>\n<li>Vitamin B12 neuropathy</li>\n<li>Pyridoxine toxicity</li>\n<li>Cisplatin neuropathy</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>C. Mixed </strong>(small &amp; large fiber) (Global sensory loss)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Diabetic sensory neuropathy</li>\n<li>Hereditary sensory neuropathies</li>\n<li>Carcinomatous sensory neuropathy</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1739, 'Medicine', 'PM1637. Patterns of Neuropathic Disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p><strong>Pattern</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p><strong>Consideration</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p>Symmetric proximal and distal weakness with sensory loss</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p>Inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (GBS and CIDP)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p>Symmetric distal sensory loss with or without distal weakness</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p>Cryptogenic or idiopathic sensory polyneuropathy (CSPN)</p>\n<p>Diabetes mellitus and other metabolic disorders</p>\n<p>Drugs, toxins, familial (HSAN)</p>\n<p>Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease</p>\n<p>Amyloidosis, and others</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p>Symmetric sensory loss and distal areflexia with upper motor neuron findings</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p>Vitamin B12, vitamin E, and copper deficiency with combined system degeneration with peripheral neuropathy, hereditary leukodystrophies (e.g., adrenomyeloneuropathy)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p>Asymmetric proprioceptive sensory loss without weakness</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p>Causes of a sensory neuronopathy &nbsp;(ganglionopathy):</p>\n<p>Cancer (paraneoplastic)</p>\n<p>Sjögren’s syndrome</p>\n<p>Idiopathic sensory neuronopathy (possible GBS variant)</p>\n<p>Cisplatin and other chemotherapeutic agents</p>\n<p>Vitamin B6 toxicity</p>\n<p>HIV-related sensory neuronopathy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\2\ width=\253\>\n<p>Asymmetric distal weakness with sensory loss</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p><strong>With involvement of multiple nerves:</strong></p>\n<p>Multifocal CIDP</p>\n<p>Vasculitis</p>\n<p>Cryoglobulinemia</p>\n<p>Amyloidosis, sarcoid</p>\n<p>Infectious (leprosy, Lyme, hepatitis B, C, or E, HIV, CMV), HNPP, tumor infiltration</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p><strong>With involvement of single nerves/regions:</strong></p>\n<p>May be any of the above but also could be compressive mononeuropathy, plexopathy, or radiculopathy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\253\>\n<p>Asymmetric proximal and distal weakness with sensory loss</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\363\>\n<p>Polyradiculopathy or plexopathy due to diabetes mellitus</p>\n<p>Meningeal carcinomatosis or lymphomatosis</p>\n<p>Hereditary plexopathy (HNPP, HNA), idiopathic</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1740, 'Medicine', 'PM1628. Mechanism of Immunopathogenesis of Guillain-Barre Syndrome', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The following sequence of events, takes into consideration, the development of Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS) associated with <em>Campylobacter jejuni</em><strong> infection</strong>.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>B cells</strong> recognize glycoconjugates on <strong> jejuni (Cj)</strong> that cross-react with <strong>ganglioside</strong> present on <strong>Schwann cell surface</strong> and <strong>subjacent peripheral nerve myelin</strong>.</li>\n<li>Most of the B cells are activated via a partially T cell–dependent route and secrete primarily <strong>IgG autoantibodies</strong>. Some B cells, activated via a T cell–independent mechanism, secrete primarily IgM</li>\n<li><strong>The</strong> <strong>activated B cells</strong> escape from Peyer’s patches into regional lymph nodes.</li>\n<li><strong>Activated T cells</strong> also function to assist in the opening of the blood-nerve barrier, facilitating penetration of pathogenic autoantibodies.</li>\n<li>The earliest changes in myelin consist of <strong>edema between myelin lamellae</strong> and <strong>vesicular disruption</strong> of the outermost myelin layers.</li>\n<li>These effects are associated with activation of the <strong>C5b-C9 membrane attack complex</strong> and mediated by <strong>calcium entry</strong>; it is possible that the macrophage cytokine tumor necrosis factor (TNF) also participates in <strong>myelin damage</strong>.</li>\n</ol></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b40cb513616a452c90a928eb9e4fc6d7x1280x1987.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1741, 'Medicine', 'PM0908. Aphasias and Related Conditions', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\0\ width=\320\ cellspacing=\0\ cellpadding=\0\><colgroup><col span=\5\ width=\64\> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl63\ height=\80\>&nbsp;</td>\n<td class=\xl65\><strong>Comprehension</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl65\><strong>Repetition of Spoken language</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl65\><strong>Naming</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl65\><strong>Fluency</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\40\><strong>Wernickes</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\40\><strong>Brocas</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Decreased</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\40\><strong>Global</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Decreased</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\40\><strong>Conduction</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\100\><strong>Anterior (nonfluent) transcortical</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\80\><strong>Posterior (fluent) transcortical</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\xl65\ height=\80\><strong>Isolation</strong></td>\n<td class=\xl64\>Impaired</td>\n<td class=\xl64\>E