d>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Perforator</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>An</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No venous location identified</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Patho-physiologic&nbsp;classification (P)</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pr</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Reflux</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Po</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Obstruction, thrombosis</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pr,o</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Reflux and obstruction</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pn</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No venous pathophysiology identified</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1027\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The descriptor A (asymptomatic) or S (symptomatic) is placed after the C clinical class.</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Telengiactesia refers to tiny intradermal venules &lt;1 mm in diameter.</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Reticular veins refer to small dilated subdermal blue veins of 1 to 2.9 mm</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Varicose veins refer to dilated tortuous veins &gt;3 mm in diameter</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1761, 'Surgery', 'PM2166. Complications of total parenteral nutrition', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>A. Related to nutrient deficiency</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hypoglycemia/hypocalcaemia/hypophosphatemia/hypomagnesaemia (<strong>refeeding syndrome</strong>)</li>\n<li>Chronic deficiency syndromes (essential fatty acids,&nbsp;<strong>zinc</strong>, mineral and trace elements)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>B. Related to overfeeding</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Excess glucose:</strong>&nbsp;Hyperglycemia, hyperosmolar dehydration, hepatic steatosis, hypercapnia, increased sympathetic activity, fluid retention, electrolyte abnormalities</li>\n<li><strong>Excess fat:</strong>&nbsp;Hypercholesterolemia and formation of lipoprotein X, hypertriglyceridemia, hypersensitivity reactions</li>\n<li><strong>Excess amino acids:</strong>&nbsp;Hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis, hypercalcemia, aminoacidemia, uremia</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>C. Related to sepsis</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Catheter-related sepsis</li>\n<li>Possible increased predisposition to systemic sepsis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>D. Related to IV line</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>On insertion:</strong>&nbsp;Pneumothorax, damage to adjacent artery, air embolism, thoracic duct damage, cardiac perforation or tamponade, pleural effusion, hydro mediastinum</li>\n<li><strong>Long-term use:</strong>&nbsp;Occlusion, venous thrombosis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>E. Related to motility</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cholestasis</li>\n<li><strong>Gallstones</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1762, 'Surgery', 'PM2147. Modified Gilberts classification of hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Type 1</strong> <strong>Indirect</strong> hernia with&nbsp;peritoneal sac passing through an intact internal ring that will not admit 1 fingerbreadth (ie,&lt;1 cm.); the posterior wall is intact.</p>\n<p><strong>Type 2 Indirect</strong> hernia (the most common indirect hernia) with peritoneal sac coming through a 1-fingerbreadth internal ring (ie, ≤2 cm.); the posterior wall is intact.</p>\n<p><strong>Type 3 Indirect</strong> hernia with peritoneal sac coming through a 2-fingerbreadth or wider internal ring (ie, &gt;2 cm.).They are frequently complete and often have a <strong>sliding</strong> component. They begin to break down a portion of the posterior wall just medial to the internal ring.</p>\n<p><strong>Type 4 Direct</strong> hernia with full floor posterior wall breakdown or multiple defects in the posterior wall. The internal ring is intact, and there is no peritoneal sac.</p>\n<p><strong>Type 5 Direct</strong> hernia with a <strong>diverticular</strong> defect. There is no peritoneal sac and the internal ring remains intact.</p>\n<p><strong>Type 6</strong>&nbsp;Both <strong>direct and indirect</strong> inguinal hernia (a <strong>pantaloon</strong> hernia)</p>\n<p><strong>Type 7</strong>&nbsp; <strong>Femoral</strong> hernia.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1763, 'Surgery', 'PM2142. Complications of enteral nutrition', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>1.&nbsp;<strong>Tube-related </strong>(most common)<strong>:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Malposition</li>\n<li>Displacement</li>\n<li>Blockage</li>\n<li>Breakage/leakage</li>\n<li>Local complications (e.g. erosion of skin/mucosa)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>2. <strong>Gastrointestinal:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Diarrhoea</li>\n<li>Bloating, nausea, vomiting</li>\n<li>Abdominal cramps</li>\n<li>Aspiration</li>\n<li>Constipation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>3. <strong>Metabolic/biochemical:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Electrolyte disorders</li>\n<li>Vitamin, mineral, trace element deficiencies</li>\n<li>Drug interactions</li>\n</ul>\n<p>4. <strong>Infective:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Exogenous (handling contamination)</li>\n<li>Endogenous (patient)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1764, 'Surgery', 'PM2120. Brilliantly Transilluminating Swellings', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Vaginal hydrocele</li>\n<li>Epididymal cyst</li>\n<li>Cystic hygroma</li>\n<li>Ranula</li>\n<li>Meningocele</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1765, 'Surgery', 'PM2114. Types of transplants', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Definition</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Orthotopic</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Organ implanted in the same anatomic location in the recipient as it was in the donor.&nbsp;Diseased organ is removed. Eg: heart, lung, liver, intestine</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Heterotopic</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Organ implanted in a different anatomic location. Diseased organ is left in place. Eg: Kidney, pancreas</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Auxiliary transplantation</strong></td>\n<td>Partial tissue from the donor is used which acts as temporary support for the recipients injured organ, which remains in place. Eg: left lobe of liver</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Autotransplant&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td>Transfer of cells/tissues/organs within the same person.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Allotransplant</strong></td>\n<td>Transfer of cells/tissues/organs within the same species.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Xenotransplant</strong></td>\n<td>Transfer of cells/tissues/organs in a different species.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Isograft</strong></td>\n<td>Transfer of organ or tissue within genetically identical individuals. Eg: Identical twins</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1766, 'Surgery', 'PM2087. Lasers used in various specialities', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\520\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Laser</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Major indications</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nd:YAG</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Ophthalmology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Posterior capsulotomy</li>\n<li>Iridotomy</li>\n<li>Vitreolysis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Urology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Bladder cancer</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><strong>GIT</strong></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fragmentation of gall stones</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Holmium YAG</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Urology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lithotripsy</li>\n<li>Benign prostatic hyperplasia</li>\n<li>Urethral stricture</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Carbon dioxide&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>ENT</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Stapedectomy</li>\n<li>Tympanomastoid surgery</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Excimer (argon fluoride)</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Ophthalmology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>LASIK</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Argon green</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Ophthalmology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Retinal photocoagulation</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>ENT</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Middle ear surgery</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pulsed dye laser (PDL)</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Dermatology</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Port-wine stain</li>\n<li>Strawberry birthmarks</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1767, 'Surgery', 'PM2082. Damage Control Surgery', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><h3>Five stages of damage control surgery:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Patient selection</li>\n<li>Control of haemorrhage and control of contamination</li>\n<li>Resuscitation continued in the intensive care unit</li>\n<li>Deﬁnitive surgery</li>\n<li>Abdominal closure</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Indications for damage control surgery:</h3>\n<h4>Anatomical</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Inability to achieve haemostasis</li>\n<li>Complex abdominal injury, e.g. liver and pancreas</li>\n<li>Combined vascular, solid and hollow organ injury, e.g. aortic or caval injury</li>\n<li>Inaccessible major venous injury, e.g. retrohepatic vena cava</li>\n<li>Demand for non-operative control of other injuries, e.g. fractured pelvis</li>\n<li>Anticipated need for a time-consuming procedure</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Physiological (decline of physiological reserve)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Temperature &lt;34ºC</li>\n<li>pH &lt;7.2</li>\n<li>Serum lactate &gt;5 mmol/L (normal is &lt;2.5 mmol/L)</li>\n<li>Prothrombin time (PT) &gt;16 s</li>\n<li>Partial thromboplastin time (PTT) &gt;60 s</li>\n<li>Blood transfusion approaching 15 units</li>\n<li>Systolic blood pressure &lt;90 mmHg for &gt;60 min</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Environmental</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Operating time &gt;60 min</li>\n<li>Inability to approximate the abdominal incision</li>\n<li>Desire to reassess the intra-abdominal contents (directed relook)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1768, 'Surgery', 'PM1953. Diathermy/Cautery:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Features</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Monopolar</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Bipolar</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Flow of current</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cautery pencil –&gt; tissue –&gt; cautery pad –&gt; machine/ground</p>\n<p>Hence <strong>more</strong> chance of burns</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Only between tips of the instrument</p>\n<p>Hence <strong>less</strong> chance of burns</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Modes</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Cutting</strong> – Low voltage, high amplitude, continuous waveforms</p>\n<p><strong>Coagulation</strong> – Alternate waveforms (Bursts)</p>\n<p><strong>Dessication</strong> – Low power</p>\n<p><strong> Fulguration</strong> – High power</p>\n</td>\n<td>Only coagulation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dissipation</td>\n<td>\n<p>More thermal dissipation of current</p>\n<p>Hence can cause <strong>damage</strong> to nerves and other vital structures</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Less lateral dissipation of current</p>\n<p>Hence<strong> safer</strong> in procedures closer to vital structures</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1a2ad85d0c4b467ba6f98641c22ef684x554x1180.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1769, 'Surgery', 'PM1769. Trauma Scoring Systems', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Revised Trauma Score&nbsp; </strong>- Total score 0-12 :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Glasgow coma scale</li>\n<li>Respiratory rate</li>\n<li>Systolic BP</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Glasgow coma scale&nbsp; -</strong> Total score 3-15 :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eye-opening</li>\n<li>Verbal response</li>\n<li>Motor response</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Abbreviated Injury Scale:&nbsp;</strong>AIS severity code – 1(minimal severity) to 6 (presumably fatal)</p>\n<p><strong>Injury Severity Score –</strong> Total score 3 to 75. Calculated summing the squares of the AIS severity codes for the three most severely injured body regions</p>\n<table width=\199\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Score</td>\n<td>Severity of injury</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3-8</td>\n<td>Minor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9-16</td>\n<td>Moderate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16-24</td>\n<td>Serious</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&gt;25</td>\n<td>Severe/ Critical</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Mangled Extremity Severity score: </strong>Mnemonic -<strong> ELiSA</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>E</strong>nergy that caused the injury, skeletal and soft tissue injury</li>\n<li><strong>Li</strong>mb ischemia</li>\n<li><strong>S</strong>hock</li>\n<li>Patient’s <strong>a</strong>ge</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>TRISS (Trauma</strong><strong> and Injury Severity Score</strong><strong>) : </strong>Mnemonic - <strong>IRMA</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>I</strong>njury Severity Score</li>\n<li><strong>R</strong>evised Trauma Score</li>\n<li><strong>M</strong>echanism of Injury (blunt/penetrating)</li>\n<li><strong>A</strong>ge</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1770, 'Surgery', 'PM1768. Response to surgical stress / trauma :', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Factors that are altered in cases of trauma or surgical stress:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Increased levels</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Decreased levels</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ACTH</strong></li>\n<li>Cortisol</li>\n<li>Adrenaline</li>\n<li>Glucagon</li>\n<li><strong>GH</strong></li>\n<li><strong>TNF α</strong></li>\n<li>IL-1</li>\n<li>IL-6</li>\n<li>IL-8</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Insulin (ebb phase)</strong></li>\n<li>IGF-1</li>\n<li>Testosterone</li>\n<li>T3</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Metabolic changes seen include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>↑ Adipocyte lipolysis</li>\n<li>↑ Hepatic gluconeogenesis</li>\n<li>↑ Skeletal muscle protein degradation</li>\n<li>↑ Hepatic acute phase protein synthesis</li>\n<li>Pyrexia</li>\n<li>Hypermetabolism</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1771, 'Surgery', 'PM1716. Classification of Kaposi sarcoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Classic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Older men of eastern European and Meditteranean origin</li>\n<li>Not associated with HIV</li>\n<li>Skin plaques and nodules</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Endemic African</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Seen in HIV seronegative individuals</li>\n<li>Predominant lymph node and visceral involvement</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Transplant associated</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Solid organ transplant recipients</li>\n<li>Involves lymph nodes, mucosa, and viscera</li>\n<li>Cutaneous lesions may be absent</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>AIDS-associated epidemic KS</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>HIV infected individuals</li>\n<li>Involves lymph nodes</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1772, 'Surgery', 'PM1615. Triads in Surgery', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Triad</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Seen in</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Components</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Borchardt’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gastric Volvulus</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Epigastric pain + Inability to vomit + Inability to pass a nasogastric tube</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Cushing’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Intracranial hypertension</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypertension&nbsp;+ Bradycardia + Irregular respiration</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Dieulafoy’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Acute appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypersensitiveness of skin + Reflex muscular contraction + Tenderness at Mc Burney’s point</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Galezias Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dupuytren’s contracture + Retroperitoneal fibrosis + Peyronie’s disease of the penis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Hutchison’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Congenital syphilis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hutchison’s teeth (notched upper incisors) + Interstitial keratitis + Nerve deafness</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Mackler’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Boerhaave’s syndrome</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Thoracic pain + Vomiting + Cervical subcutaneous emphysema</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Quinckes Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hemobilia</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gastrointestinal hemorrhage + Biliary colic + Jaundice</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Rigler’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Gallstone ileus</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Small bowel obstruction + Pneumobilia + Ectopic gallstone</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Saints Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hiatus hernia + Gallstones+ Colonic diverticulosis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Tillaux’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Mesenteric cyst</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Soft fluctuant swelling in umbilical region + Freely mobile perpendicular to mesentery + Zone of resonance all around</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Trotter’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Nasopharyngeal Carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Conductive hearing loss + Immobility of homolateral soft palate + Trigeminal neuralgia</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Virchow’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Thrombosis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Hypercoagulability + Stasis + Endothelial injury</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Whipple’s Triad</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Insulinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Symptoms of hypoglycemia + Serum&nbsp;glucose &lt;50 mg/dL + Symptomatic relief on glucose ingestion</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1773, 'Surgery', 'PM1600. Indications and contraindications of puncture, aspiration, injection, and re-aspiration (PAIR) in hydatid cyst', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Indications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Relapse cyst, infected cyst, cyst &gt;5 cm in different liver segments</li>\n<li>Patients who refuse surgery or where surgery is contraindicated</li>\n<li>Pregnant women, children &lt; 3 years of age</li>\n<li>WHO - type CE1 and type CE3a (transitional cyst)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Contraindications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cysts in lung</li>\n<li>Cysts communicating with bile duct</li>\n<li>Cysts with multiple septae—honeycomb cysts</li>\n<li>Inaccessible cysts</li>\n<li>Hyperechogenic cysts</li>\n<li>Calcified cysts</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1774, 'Surgery', 'PM1512. Identification of Surgical Retractors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Deavers Retractor:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1bdb9c3f1d64405eb0ba5d6b7f14c373x800x600.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Doyens retractor:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/ba4b0fd005ca49eb9e1bd9f3a014a99dx1280x960.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Morris retractor:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/20f77217c4f6464189079798ee63679fx714x340.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Czerny’s retractor:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/f080538ebecb4e22bb229bfcafd32caax720x390.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1775, 'Surgery,', 'PM1500. Gurds criteria for diagnosing fat embolism syndrome', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\ng-scope\><strong>Major criteria</strong></div>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<ul>\n<li>Petechial rash</li>\n<li>Respiratory symptoms with radiographic changes</li>\n<li>CNS depression.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<p class=\ng-binding\><strong>Minor criteria</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tachycardia</li>\n<li>Pyrexia</li>\n<li>Retinal changes (fat or petechiae)</li>\n<li>Renal abnormalities (oliguria, anuria, or lipiduria)</li>\n<li>Acute thrombocytopenia</li>\n<li>Acute decrease in hemoglobin</li>\n<li>Fat globules in sputum</li>\n<li>Increased ESR</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>2 major criteria</strong> OR <strong>one major criteria</strong> + <strong>four minor criteria</strong> suggest a diagnosis of fat embolism syndrome.</p>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1776, 'Surgery', 'PM1492. Complications of a Massive Transfusion', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Massive transfusion (MT)</strong>&nbsp;is defined as the replacement by transfusion of <strong>10 units of pRBCs</strong>&nbsp;in <strong>24 hours&nbsp;</strong>or more than <strong>4 units of pRBCs</strong> in <strong>one hour</strong>.</p>\n<p>Complications from massive transfusion include:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Complication</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hypothermia</td>\n<td>As blood products are normally stored between 1°C and 6°C</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Coagulopathy</td>\n<td>\n<p>MT with PRBCs alone causes a <strong>dilutional coagulopathy&nbsp;</strong>(vs&nbsp;consumptive coagulopathy caused by&nbsp;massive hemorrhage)</p>\n<p>Can be prevented by starting early transfusion of FFP, platelets, pRBCs in a <strong>1:1:1 ratio</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acidosis/ Alkalosis</td>\n<td>\n<p>Mild acidosis - increased CO2 levels in stored blood by 21-35 days</p>\n<p>Metabolic alkalosis -&nbsp;citrate gets metabolized to bicarbonate</p>\n<p>Metabolic acidosis - due to tissue hypoperfusion</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hyperkalemia/ Hypokalemia</td>\n<td>\n<p>Initially - Hyperkalemia, as stored blood has high K+ levels due to inactivated Na/K/ATPase pump</p>\n<p>Later - Hypokalemia, due to intracellular potassium uptake and metabolic alkalosis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hypocalcemia</td>\n<td>Stored blood is anticoagulated with citrate, which binds calcium.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hypomagnesemia</td>\n<td>Infusion of large volumes of magnesium-poor fluids and&nbsp;binding of magnesium to citrate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Impaired O2-carrying capacity of hemoglobin</td>\n<td>Decreased 2, 3 DPG</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Volume overload</td>\n<td>Due to massive transfusion</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1777, 'Surgery', 'PM1486. Classification of hemorrhagic shock', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table class=\scrollable bordered\ border=\0\ cellspacing=\0\ cellpadding=\0\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\rowsep\>Parameters</th>\n<th class=\rowsep\>Class I</th>\n<th class=\rowsep\>Class II</th>\n<th class=\rowsep\>Class III</th>\n<th class=\rowsep\>Class IV</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Blood loss in %</td>\n<td>&lt;15</td>\n<td>15–30</td>\n<td>30–40</td>\n<td>&gt;40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pulse rate</td>\n<td>&lt;100</td>\n<td>100–120</td>\n<td>120–140</td>\n<td>&gt;140</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Blood pressure</td>\n<td>Normal</td>\n<td>Normal</td>\n<td>Decreased</td>\n<td>Greatly decreased</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pulse pressure</td>\n<td>Normal or increased</td>\n<td>Decreased</td>\n<td>Decreased</td>\n<td>Decreased</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Respiratory rate</td>\n<td>14–20</td>\n<td>20–30</td>\n<td>30–40</td>\n<td>&gt;35</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mental status</td>\n<td>Slightly anxious</td>\n<td>Mildly anxious</td>\n<td>Anxious, confused</td>\n<td>Confused, lethargic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Urine output (mL/hr)</td>\n<td>&gt;30</td>\n<td>20–30</td>\n<td>5–15</td>\n<td>Minimal</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1778, 'Surgery', 'PM1112. Marjolin’s Ulcer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Low-grade squamous cell carcinoma</strong> arising from:\n<ol>\n<li>Long-standing ulcers like a venous ulcer</li>\n<li>Post-burn scar</li>\n<li>Chronic osteomyelitis</li>\n<li>Post-radiation ulcer</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Slow growing</strong> since it is relatively <strong>avascular</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Painless</strong> due to the <strong>absence of nerves</strong> in scar tissue</li>\n<li><strong>No secondary deposits</strong> since there are <strong>no lymphatics</strong> in scar tissue</li>\n<li><strong>Radioresistant</strong> due to avascularity</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1779, 'Surgery', 'PM1047. The triangle of pain/Electrical hazard zone:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>The triangle of pain</strong>/Electrical hazard zone:</p>\n<p>It is bounded</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Superio-medially by gonadal vessels</li>\n<li>Laterally by peritoneum</li>\n<li>Inferio-laterally by the iliopubic tract</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Contents:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve</li>\n<li>Anterior femoral cutaneous nerve</li>\n<li>Femoral branch of the genitofemoral nerve</li>\n<li>Femoral nerves</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/833ca430d54d417da2cf19e702148c98x1280x1369.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1780, 'Surgery', 'PM0794. Types of microcalcification indicating malignancy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>In decreasing order of risk of malignancy-</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cluster microcalcification (maximum risk)</li>\n<li>Linear microcalcification</li>\n<li>Segmental microcalcification</li>\n<li>Diffuse microcalcification (minimum risk)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1781, 'Surgery', 'PM0787. Clinical signs and symptoms of phaeochromocytoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Feature</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Prevalance</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Hypertension</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Paroxysmal<br><br></li>\n<li>Continuous</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>80–90</p>\n<p>50–60</p>\n<p>30</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Headache</strong></td>\n<td>60–90</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sweating</td>\n<td>50–70</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Palpitation</td>\n<td>50–70</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pallor</td>\n<td>40–45</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Weight loss</td>\n<td>20–40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hyperglycaemia</td>\n<td>40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nausea</td>\n<td>20–40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Psychological effects</td>\n<td>20–40</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1782, 'Surgery', 'PM0478. Surgical wound classifications as defined by ACS NSOP', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Clean</strong>:&nbsp;Uninfected operative wounds in which no inflammation is encountered and the respiratory, alimentary, genital, and uninfected urinary tracts are not entered</li>\n<li><strong>Clean/Contaminated</strong>:&nbsp;Operative wounds in which the respiratory, alimentary, genital, or urinary tract is entered under controlled conditions and without unusual contamination</li>\n<li><strong>Contaminated</strong>:&nbsp;Open, fresh, accidental wounds; operations with major breaks insterile technique or gross spillage from the gastrointestinal tract and incisions in which acute, nonpurulent inflammation is encountered</li>\n<li><strong>Dirty</strong>:&nbsp;Old traumatic wounds with retained devitalized tissue and wounds that involve existing clinical infection or perforated viscera</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1783, 'Surgery', 'PM0476. Staging of Pressure Sores', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stage</strong></td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 50\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Description</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td><strong>Non-blanchable erythema</strong> without a breach in the epidermis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Partial thickness skin loss</strong> involving the epidermis and dermis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Full thickness skin loss</strong> extending into the subcutaneous tissue but <strong>not</strong> through underlying <strong>fascia</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td><strong>Full thickness skin loss</strong> through fascia with extensive tissue destruction, maybe involving <strong>muscle, bone, tendon or joint</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/5101f11adf164ca39aa80464ba864044x1280x4990.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1784, 'Surgery', 'PM0466. Causes of Burns and their Likely Depth', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\455\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Cause of burn</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Probable depth of burn</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Scald</td>\n<td>Superficial, but with deep dermal patches in the absence of good first aid. Will be deep in a young infant</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Fat burns</td>\n<td>Deep dermal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Flame burns</td>\n<td>Mixed deep dermal and full thickness</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Alkali burns, including cement</td>\n<td>Often deep dermal or full thickness</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Acid burns</td>\n<td>Weak concentrations superficial; strong concentration deep dermal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Electrical contact burn</td>\n<td>Full thickness</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1785, 'Surgery', 'PM0457. White cell peaks during wound healing', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\213\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Cell</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Peak (day)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Neutrophils</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Macrophages</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lymphocytes</td>\n<td>7</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1786, 'Surgery', 'PM0192. Important Tumor Classifications', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Name of classification</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Associated tumors</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bloom–Richardson grading</td>\n<td>Carcinoma breast</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Butchart staging</td>\n<td>Mesothelioma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chang staging</td>\n<td>Medulloblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Duke staging</td>\n<td>Colorectal carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gleason</td>\n<td>Prostate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jackson</td>\n<td>Carcinoma penis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Masaoka staging</td>\n<td>Thymoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Noguchi</td>\n<td>Adenocarcinoma lung</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nevine staging</td>\n<td>Carcinoma gall bladder</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Robson staging</td>\n<td>Renal cell carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>Reiss and Ellsworth classification</div>\n<div>Esson prognostic index</div>\n</td>\n<td>Retinoblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shimda index</td>\n<td>Neuroblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sullivan modification of Macfarlane system</td>\n<td>Adrenocortical carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1787, 'Surgery', 'PM0161. Important tumor classifications', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;<strong>Important tumor classifications:</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Bloom Richardson grading</td>\n<td>Carcinoma breast</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Butchart staging</td>\n<td>Mesothelioma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chang staging</td>\n<td>Medulloblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Duke staging</td>\n<td>Colorectal carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gleason</td>\n<td>Prostate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jackson</td>\n<td>Carcinoma penis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Masaoka staging</td>\n<td>Thymoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Noguchi</td>\n<td>Adenocarcinoma lung</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nevins staging</td>\n<td>Carcinoma gall bladder</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Robson staging</td>\n<td>Renal cell carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Reiss and Ellsworth classification</p>\n<p>Esson prognostic index</p>\n</td>\n<td>Retinoblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shimada index</td>\n<td>Neuroblastoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sullivan modification of Macfarlane system&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Adrenocortical carcinoma</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1788, 'Surgery', 'PM2218. Characteristics of in situ ductal (DCIS) and lobular (LCIS) carcinoma of the breast', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 548\>\n<table border=\1\><colgroup><col><col><col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>LCIS</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>DCIS</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Age (years)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>44–47</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>54–58</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Incidence</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>2%–5%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>5%–10%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Clinical signs</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Mostly incidental finding.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Usually asymptomatic but mass, pain, nipple discharge may also be seen.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Mammographic signs</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>None</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Microcalcifications</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Premenopausal</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>2/3</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>1/3</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Incidence of synchronous invasive carcinoma</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>5%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>2%–46%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Multicentricity</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>60%–90%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>40%–80%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Bilaterality</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>50%–70%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>10%–20%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Axillary metastasis</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>1%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>1%–2%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Subsequent carcinomas:</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>Incidence</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>25%–35%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>25%–70%</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>Laterality</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Bilateral</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ipsilateral</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>Interval to diagnosis</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>15–20 y</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>5–10 y</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>Histologic type</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ductal</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ductal</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1789, 'Surgery', 'PM2216. Discharge from the Nipple', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>From the surface:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Paget’s disease</li>\n<li>Skin diseases (eczema, psoriasis)</li>\n<li>Rare causes (e.g., chancre)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>From a single duct:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blood-stained:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Intraductal papilloma (M/C cause)</li>\n<li>Intraductal carcinoma</li>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Serous (any colour):</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Fibrocystic disease</li>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n<li>Carcinoma</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>From multiple ducts:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blood-stained:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Carcinoma (M/C cause)</li>\n<li>Ectasia</li>\n<li>Fibrocystic disease</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Black or green:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Purulent:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Infection</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Serous:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Fibrocystic disease (M/C cause)</li>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n<li>Carcinoma</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Milk:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Lactation</li>\n<li>Rare causes (hypothyroidism, pituitary tumour)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1790, 'Surgery', 'PM1850. Newer drugs in chemotherapy for metastatic breast cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Treatment of metastatic breast cancer by targeting PI3k/AKT/mTOR pathways has led to newer chemotherapeutic drugs, which are as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>Cyclin-dependent kinase 4/6 inhibitor</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Palbociclib:</strong>&nbsp;Approved for use with aromatase inhibitor (Letrozole) or SERD (Fulvestrant)</li>\n<li>Ribociclib: Approved for use with aromatase inhibitor (Letrozole)</li>\n<li>Abemaciclib: Approved for use with SERD (Fulvestrant)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>mTOR pathway inhibitors</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Everolimus:</strong>&nbsp; Approved for treatment of advanced/metastatic hormone receptor–positive, HER-2-negative breast cancer</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Phophatidyl-inositol 3 kinase (PI3k) inhibitors</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Buparlisib – </strong>Not approved, but trials are underway for treatment of metastatic breast carcinoma</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>AKT (Protein kinase B) inhibitors</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ipatasertib:</strong>&nbsp;Not approved, but found beneficial for metastatic triple-negative breast cancer&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1791, 'Surgery', 'PM1849. Newer molecular tests in breast cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Newer molecular tests for breast cancer have been developed, which help in predicting the advantage of adding <strong>chemotherapy</strong>.&nbsp;These are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Oncotype Dx (21-geneassay)</li>\n<li>Mammaprint (70-gene assay)</li>\n<li>EndoPredict (12-gene assay)</li>\n<li>PAM50 (50-gene assay)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Oncotype Dx </strong>can only be used in<strong> hormone (ER, PR) receptor-positive&nbsp;cancers, </strong>while <strong>mammaprint </strong>can be used in<strong> both </strong>hormone receptor (ER, PR) positive&nbsp;and hormone receptor-negative&nbsp;cancers.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>These tests are used for T<sub>1,2 </sub>N<sub>0</sub> M<sub>0</sub> breast cancers – (<strong>node-negative, metastasis-negative</strong>). Using these molecular tests, a <strong>recurrence score</strong> (0 – 100) is calculated.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the score is <strong>low</strong>, then there <strong>is no advantage</strong> of adding chemotherapy</li>\n<li>If the score is <strong>high</strong>, then chemotherapy should be <strong>added</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1792, 'Surgery', 'PM0885. Indications and contraindications for radical mastectomy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Indications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Large, bulky tumor involving pectoralis major muscle and fascia.</li>\n<li>Axillary lymph node involvement</li>\n<li>Interpectoral lymph node involvement</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Contraindications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Non-palpable or small tumors</li>\n<li>Advanced disease with distant metastasis</li>\n<li>Patients who need improved cosmetic result</li>\n<li>Patients who need reconstructive surgery</li>\n<li>Coexisting severe systemic diseases like DM, CHF, CRF</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1793, 'Surgery', 'PM0884. Contraindications for Breast Conservative Surgery', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Absolute contraindications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>1st-trimester pregnancy</li>\n<li>Diffuse microcalcifications</li>\n<li>Persistently positive pathologic margin</li>\n<li>Multicentric tumor</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Relative contraindications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Connective tissue disorders like systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE),&nbsp; scleroderma and&nbsp;rheumatoid arthritis</li>\n<li>Large lump-to-breast ratio, i.e., a big lump in small breast</li>\n<li>Lump beneath the nipple-areola complex</li>\n<li>Multifocal&nbsp;tumor</li>\n<li>History of therapeutic radiation exposure to the chest wall</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>NOTE : Some authorities do not consider Rheumatoid Arthritis as a relative contraindication as the data on radiation toxicity in RA is sparse.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1794, 'Surgery', 'PM0880. Important surgeries for breast cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Tylectomy:&nbsp;Excision of lump</li>\n<li><strong>Breast conservation surgery (BCS)/WLE (wide local excision)</strong>: Tumour removal with a 3D clearance of a 1 mm margin of normal tissue</li>\n<li><strong>Simple mastectomy:</strong>&nbsp;Palpable extent of breast +&nbsp;Nipple–areola complex + overlying skin.</li>\n<li>Extended simple mastectomy: Simple mastectomy + removal of level I axillary lymph nodes.</li>\n<li>Skin-sparing mastectomy: Mastectomy with breast envelope preservation and nipple-areola complex removal</li>\n<li>Skin+ nipple/areola-sparing mastectomy: Mastectomy with breast envelope and nipple-areola complex preservation</li>\n<li><strong>Total mastectomy:</strong>&nbsp;All breast tissue + Nipple–areola complex + skin.</li>\n<li><strong>Level I oncoplasty (volume displacement surgery):</strong> Tumour excision with wide margins followed by defect repair via dual-plane mobilisation of the breast parenchyma to maintain shape and symmetry</li>\n<li><strong>Level II oncoplasty (volume replacement surgery):</strong> Skin excision and glandular mobilisation involving &gt;20% resection of breast volume</li>\n<li><strong>Modified radical mastectomy:</strong>&nbsp; Entire breast tissue + Nipple–areola complex + skin + axillary lymph nodes (levels I + II ± III) dissection\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Patey’s:</strong> Pectoralis minor is removed</li>\n<li><strong>Scanlon’s</strong>: Pectoralis minor incised</li>\n<li><strong>Auchincloss</strong>: Pectoralis minor only retracted</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Halsted’s radical mastectomy:</strong>&nbsp;Entire breast tissue + Nipple–areola complex + skin + Levels I + II+ III Axillary lymph nodes + Pectoralis major and minor</li>\n<li>Extended radical (Urban) - Halsted’s + internal mammary lymph nodes dissection</li>\n<li>Extended radical (Dahl-Iverson) mastectomy: Halsted’s + internal mammary and supraclavicular lymph nodes dissection</li>\n<li>Super radical mastectomy: Halsted’s + internal mammary, supraclavicular and mediastinal lymph nodes dissection.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>*Dual-plane mobilisation of breast parenchyma: Mobilisation of the dermoglandular plane and plane between breast parenchyma and pectoralis muscle.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1795, 'Surgery', 'PM0877. TNM Staging of Carcinoma Breast', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Tumor (T)</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Description</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tx</td>\n<td>\n<p>Primary tumor cannot be assessed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T0</td>\n<td>\n<p>No evidence of primary tumor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Tis (DCIS)</strong></td>\n<td>Ductal carcinoma in situ</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Tis (Paget)</strong></td>\n<td>Paget disease not associated with invasive carcinoma or DCIS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T1</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>≤</strong><strong>2 cm</strong> in greatest dimension</p>\n<p><strong>1mic</strong>&nbsp;≤ 0.1 cm</p>\n<p>1a &gt;0.1 to 0.5 cm</p>\n<p>1b &gt;0.5 to 1 cm</p>\n<p>1c &gt;1 to 2 cm</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T2</td>\n<td><strong>&gt;2 but ≤5 cm</strong> in greatest dimension</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T3</td>\n<td><strong>&gt;5 cm</strong> in greatest dimension</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T4</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor of<strong> any size&nbsp;</strong>and -</p>\n<p><strong>4a</strong> – chest wall involvement (except pectoralis major)<strong>#</strong>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>4b </strong>– skin involvement in the form of ulceration, peau d’orange, satellite nodules &nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>4c </strong>– 4a + 4b &nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>4d</strong> – Inflammatory breast carcinoma (typical skin changes involving <span>&gt;</span>1/3rd of breast)<strong>*</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Nodes (N)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N1 mic</td>\n<td>Refers to micrometastasis to Lymph node</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N1</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral <strong>mobile</strong> axillary lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N2A</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral<strong> fixed or matted</strong> axillary lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N2B</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral internal mammary <strong>without axillary lymph node</strong> involvement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N3A</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral infraclavicular lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N3B</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral internal mammary and axillary lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N3C</td>\n<td>Ipsilateral supraclavicular lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Distant metastasis (M)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>M0</td>\n<td>Metastasis absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>M1</td>\n<td>Metastasis present</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Stages</strong></td>\n<td><strong>T, N</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>M</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage 0</td>\n<td>T<sub>is</sub>N<sub>0</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IA</td>\n<td>T<sub>1</sub>N<sub>0</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IB</td>\n<td>T<sub>0,1</sub>N<sub>1mic</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IIA</td>\n<td>T<sub>0,1</sub>N<sub>1</sub> (or) T<sub>2</sub>N<sub>0</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IIB</td>\n<td>T<sub>2</sub>N<sub>1</sub> (or) T<sub>3</sub>N<sub>0</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IIIA</td>\n<td>T<sub>0,1,2,3</sub>N<sub>2 </sub>(or) T<sub>3</sub>N<sub>1</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IIIB</td>\n<td><strong>T</strong><sub><strong>4</strong>&nbsp;</sub>N<sub>0,1,2</sub></td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IIIC</td>\n<td>\n<p>Any T,<strong> N<sub>3</sub></strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>M<sub>0</sub></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IV</td>\n<td>\n<p>Any T, Any N</p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>M<sub>1</sub></strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>#&nbsp;</strong>Chest wall includes Serratus anterior, Intercostal muscles, Ribs.&nbsp;Pectoralis muscle is <strong>not</strong> a part of the chest wall.</p>\n<p><strong>*&nbsp;</strong>Inflammatory breast carcinoma (stage 4d) is characterized by the skin changes of&nbsp;<strong>brawny induration, erythema</strong> with a raised edge, and edema (<strong>peaud’orange</strong>) involving <span>&gt;</span>1/3rd of the breast.</p>\n<p>Note: LCIS (lobular carcinoma in situ) is considered a benign condition and not included under Tis.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/2202ec4c95df457eb86eaf658395ea5dx1280x943.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Prefixes for TNM staging:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>c:</strong>&nbsp;clinical staging (e.g. cT1b)</li>\n<li><strong>p:</strong>&nbsp;pathological (histological) staging</li>\n<li><strong>y:</strong>&nbsp;stage following systemic or radiation therapy (either prior to surgery or as a primary treatment)</li>\n<li><strong>r:</strong>&nbsp;staging at the time of retreatment or recurrence for disease progression</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Suffix for TNM staging:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>m:</strong>&nbsp;multiple primary tumours of the same histology in the same organ, e.g. T2(m) or T2(5), the latter meaning that there are five primary tumours</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1796, 'Surgery', 'PM0872. Relative risk of invasive breast carcinoma based on pathological examination of benign breast tissue', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>No increased risk </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Adenosis, sclerosing or florid</li>\n<li>Apocrine metaplasia</li>\n<li>Cysts, macro and/or micro</li>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n<li>Fibroadenoma</li>\n<li>Fibrosis</li>\n<li>Hyperplasia</li>\n<li>Mastitis (inflammation)</li>\n<li>Periductal mastitis</li>\n<li>Squamous metaplasia</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Slightly increased risk (1.5–2 times)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hyperplasia</strong>, moderate or <strong>florid, solid, or papillary</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Papilloma</strong> with a fibrovascular core</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Moderately increased risk (5 times)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Atypical hyperplasia (ductal or lobular)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Insufficient data to assign a risk</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Solitary papilloma of lactiferous sinus</li>\n<li>Radial scar lesion</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1797, 'Surgery', 'PM0870. Breast Cancer Screening', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Breast Cancer Screening</strong></p>\n<p>Individuals are encouraged to conduct a <strong>risk assessment by 25 years of age</strong>. This helps classify them into <strong>average risk</strong> or <strong>increased risk groups</strong>.</p>\n<p>Recommendations<strong>:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li aria-level=\1\><strong>Average-risk</strong>&nbsp;(no known genetic or family history of breast cancer)</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>25-39 years of age: clinical breast examination every 1-3 years;&nbsp;</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>≥ 40 years of age: clinical breast examination and mammogram annually</li>\n</ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\><strong>High-risk </strong>(positive family or genetic history of breast cancer)</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>Consult a healthcare professional&nbsp;every <strong>6-12 months</strong> <strong>after 21 years of age</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\2\><strong>Annual mammogram or MRI</strong> from 25 years of age or 10 years prior to the age at which the youngest family member was diagnosed with breast cancer (whichever is earliest)</li>\n</ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\><strong>Asymptomatic women</strong> with <strong>previously treated breast cancer</strong></li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>Consult a healthcare professional&nbsp;every <strong>6-12 months</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\2\><strong>Annual mammogram</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>Annual MRI to be considered</li>\n</ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Mammogram and USG are&nbsp;<strong>not contraindicated</strong> in <strong>pregnant and breastfeeding</strong> women</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>High-risk patients</strong> for breast cancer:</p>\n<ol>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Women (or a first-degree relative) with a known BRCA1 or BRCA2 mutation or TP53 or PTEN genes</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Two first-degree relatives with breast cancers with or without gene mutations</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Women with a history of chest irradiation between the ages of 10 and 30</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Women with previously biopsy-proven breast cancer</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Women with ≥ 20% lifetime risk for breast cancer based on breast cancer risk models</li>\n</ol>\n<p>*According to <strong>NCCN 2022 guidelines</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1798, 'Surgery', 'PM0869. Risk Factors and Protective Factors for Breast Carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Risk factors:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Age: Incidence increases with increasing age.</li>\n<li>Sex: more common in females.</li>\n<li>Family history of breast cancer</li>\n<li>Race, ethnicity (white women have increased risk compared to women of other races)</li>\n<li>History of radiation exposure</li>\n<li>Mammographically dense breast</li>\n<li>Genetic factors:</li>\n<li>Mutations in tumor suppressor genes:\n<ul>\n<li><em><strong>BRCA 1</strong></em></li>\n<li><em><strong>BRCA 2</strong></em></li>\n<li><em>TP53</em></li>\n<li><em>CHEK2</em></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Hereditary syndromes:\n<ul>\n<li>Li Fraumeni syndrome</li>\n<li>Cowden’s syndrome</li>\n<li>HNPCC syndrome</li>\n<li>Peutz-Jegher’s syndrome</li>\n<li>Ataxia telangiectasia</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Hormonal factors (hyperestrogenemia is the risk factor):\n<ul>\n<li>Early menarche</li>\n<li>Late menopause</li>\n<li>First full-term pregnancy &gt;30 years</li>\n<li>Nulliparity</li>\n<li>Obesity (postmenopausal)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Higher socioeconomic status, high fat diet, alcohol intake</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Protective factors:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Early age at first pregnancy</li>\n<li>Multiparity</li>\n<li>Breastfeeding</li>\n<li>Oophorectomy</li>\n<li>Exercise</li>\n<li>Tamoxifen and Aromatase inhibitors</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1799, 'Surgery', 'PM0802. Relative risk of invasive breast carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Relative risk of invasive breast carcinoma based on pathological examination of benign breast tissue (American College of Pathologists Consensus Statement):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>No increased risk</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Adenosis, sclerosing or florid</li>\n<li>Apocrine metaplasia</li>\n<li>Cysts, macro and/or micro</li>\n<li>Duct ectasia</li>\n<li>Fibroadenoma</li>\n<li>Fibrosis</li>\n<li>Hyperplasia</li>\n<li>Mastitis (inflammation)</li>\n<li>Periductal mastitis</li>\n<li>Squamous metaplasia</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Slightly increased risk (1-5 - 2times)</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Hyperplasia, moderate or florid, solid or papillary</li>\n<li>Papilloma with a fibrovascular core</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Moderately increased risk (5 times)</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Atypical hyperplasia (ductal or lobular)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Insufficient data to assign a risk</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Solitary papilloma of lactiferous sinus</li>\n<li>Radial scar lesion</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1800, 'Surgery', 'PM0796. Differentiating features of benign and malignant breast lump on USG', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\403\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Benign lump</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Malignant lump</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hyper echoic</td>\n<td>Hypo echoic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Oval, well circumscribed lump</td>\n<td>Lump will be taller than wider</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Thin echogenic pseudocapsule</td>\n<td>Ill defined echogenic halo</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Peripheral vascularity</td>\n<td>Central vascularity</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>Most sensitive and most common finding of malignancy on USG – Lump will be taller than wider.</li>\n<li><strong>Most specific finding</strong> of malignancy on USG – <strong>Central vascularity</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1801, 'Surgery', 'PM0194. Breast Lump Evaluation', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/7c86e5c970864792a60c24c28018aec0x1280x2445.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1802, 'Surgery', 'PM2223. TNM staging of oral cavity cancer -  AJCC 8th edition', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\ width=\708\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>Primary Tumour (T)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TX</td>\n<td>Cannot be assessed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tis</td>\n<td>Carcinoma in situ</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T1</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor ≤2 cm,&nbsp;<strong>depth of invasion (DOI)&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>≤5 mm</strong> (DOI is depth of invasion and not tumor thickness)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T2</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor ≤2 cm, DOI &gt;5 mm and ≤10 mm;</p>\n<p>or tumor &gt;2 cm but ≤4 cm, and ≤10 mm DOI</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T3</td>\n<td>Tumor &gt;4 cm or any tumor &gt;10 mm DOI</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T4</td>\n<td>Moderately advanced or very advanced local disease</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T4a</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Moderately advanced local disease</strong>:</p>\n<p>Tumor&gt; 4 cms with DOI &gt;10 mm</p>\n<p>or tumor invades adjacent structures only (through cortical bone of the mandible or maxilla or involves the maxillary sinus or skin of the face.</p>\n<p>Note that superficial erosion of bone/tooth socket (alone) by a gingival primary is not sufficient to classify a tumor as T4</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T4b</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Very advanced local disease</strong>; tumor invades the masticator space, pterygoid plates, or skull base and/or encases the internal carotid artery</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table class=\table article-section__table\ border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\ colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 785\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Regional lymph nodes (N) - Clinical</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>NX</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Cannot be assessed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N0</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>No regional lymph node metastasis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N1</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Single ipsilateral, <span>&lt;</span>3 cm and <strong><strong>ENE (</strong></strong><strong>extranodal extension)‐</strong>negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N2</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>&nbsp;Single ipsilateral lymph node larger than 3 cms but not greater than 6 cms, ENE - negative;&nbsp;Multiple ipsilateral lymph nodes, &lt;6 cm and ENE ‐negative ;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bilateral or contralateral lymph nodes, &lt;6 cm and ENE‐negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N2a</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Single ipsilateral lymph node larger than 3 cms but not greater than 6 cms, ENE - negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N2b</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Multiple ipsilateral lymph nodes, &lt;6 cm and ENE ‐negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N2c</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Bilateral or contralateral lymph nodes, &lt;6 cm and ENE‐negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N3</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>\n<p>Metastasis in a lymph node larger than 6 cms and ENE -negative or metastasis in any lymph node and clinically over ENE +positive</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N3a</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>Metastasis in a lymph node &gt;6 cms and ENE‐negative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\right-bordered-cell left-aligned\>N3b</td>\n<td class=\left-aligned\>\n<p>Metastasis in any lymph node(s) and clinically overt ENE +positive.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><br>Note:<br>ENE is as determined by physical examination (e.g., invasion of the skin, infiltration of musculature/dense tethering to adjacent structures, or dysfunction of a cranial nerve, the brachial plexus, the sympathetic trunk, or the phrenic nerve) and supported by radiological evidence, should be present to assign a status of ENE‐positive.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1803, 'Surgery', 'PM2183. Indications for splenectomy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1206\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Trauma (most common)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Accidental</li>\n<li>Operative</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Oncological</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Part of en bloc resection</li>\n<li>Diagnostic</li>\n<li>Therapeutic</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Haematological</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Spherocytosis</li>\n<li>Purpura (idiopathic/immune thrombocytopenic purpura)</li>\n<li>Hypersplenism</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Portal hypertension</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Variceal surgery</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1804, 'Surgery', 'PM2153. TNM staging of Gallbladder Carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>TNM staging of gallbladder carcinoma according to the AJCC guidelines, 8<sup>th</sup> edition</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>T: Primary tumor</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>x</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Main tumor cannot be assessed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>0</sub></strong></td>\n<td>No sign of a primary tumor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>is</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Cancer is only in the epithelium and has not grown into deeper layers of the gallbladder</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades the lamina propria or the muscle layer (muscularis)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>1a</sub></strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades the lamina propria</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>1b</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades the muscular layer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>2a</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades the <strong>muscle layer</strong> into the <strong>fibrous tissue on the side of the peritoneum</strong> (the lining of the abdominal cavity)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>2b</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades&nbsp;the <strong>muscle layer</strong> into the <strong>fibrous tissue on the side of the liver</strong>&nbsp;but has not invaded the liver</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>3</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades the serosa and/or it has grown directly into the liver and/or one nearby structure like the stomach, duodenum, colon, pancreas, or bile ducts outside the liver.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>T<sub>4</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor invades&nbsp;the main blood vessels leading into the liver (portal vein or hepatic artery) or it has grown into 2 or more structures outside the liver</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>N: Lymph nodes involvement&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>N<sub>X</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>N<sub>0</sub></strong></td>\n<td>No spread to nearby lymph nodes&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>N<sub>1</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Spread to <span>&lt;</span> 3 nearby lymph nodes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>N<sub>2</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Spread to <span>&gt;</span>4 nearby lymph nodes&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>M: Distant metastasis&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>M<sub>0</sub></strong></td>\n<td>No spread to distant sites</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>M<sub>1</sub></strong></td>\n<td>Tumor spread to distant sites such as the liver, peritoneum, or the lungs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\347\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>AJCC Stage</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Stage grouping</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>TisN0M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>I</td>\n<td>T1N0M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IIA</td>\n<td>T2aN0M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IIB</td>\n<td>T2bN0M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IIIA</td>\n<td>T3N0M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IIIB</td>\n<td>T1-3N1M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IVA</td>\n<td>T4N0 or N1M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IVB</td>\n<td>Any TN2M0&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1805, 'Surgery', 'PM2148. Lauren Classification System of gastric carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\366\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1241\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Intestinal(type l)</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Diffuse (type ll)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1241\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Environmental</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>Familial</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Gastric atrophy, intestinal metaplasia</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Blood type A</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Men &gt; women</td>\n<td>Women &gt; Men</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Increasing incidence with age</td>\n<td>Younger age group</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gland formation</td>\n<td>Poorly differentiated, signet ring cells&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hematogenous spread</td>\n<td>Transmural, lymphatic spread</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Microsatellite instability</p>\n<p>APC gene mutations</p>\n</td>\n<td>Decreased E-cadherin</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>p53, p16 inactivation</td>\n<td>p53, p16 inactivation</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1806, 'Surgery', 'PM1963. Indication for Cholecystectomy in Gallbladder Polyp', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>All symptomatic patients</li>\n<li>All asymptomatic patients &gt;50 years</li>\n<li>Polyp of size &gt;10 mm</li>\n<li>Evidence of polyp growth on serial ultrasonography</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1807, 'Surgery', 'PM1924. Liver tumors - commons', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Most common tumor overall: Metastatic&nbsp;tumor</li>\n<li>Most common <strong>primary benign</strong> tumor: Cavernous hemangioma</li>\n<li>Most common <strong>primary malignant</strong> tumor: Hepatocellular carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common <strong>primary malignant</strong> liver tumor of early <strong>childhood</strong>: Hepatoblastoma</li>\n<li>Most common tumor associated with <strong>arsenic / vinyl chloride</strong>: Angiosarcoma</li>\n<li>Most common tumor associated with <strong>oral contraceptive / anabolic steroid</strong>: Hepatic adenoma</li>\n<li>Most common tumor rupture spontaneously causing <strong>hemoperitoneum</strong>: Hepatic adenoma</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1808, 'Surgery', 'PM1803. Rockall score for risk stratificatison of UGI bleed:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>NOTE:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The total Rockall score amounts to <strong>0 to 11</strong></li>\n<li>The Rockall score has both clinical and complete scores</li>\n<li>The factors like Age, shock and coexisting illness are combined together as <strong>CLINICAL ROCKALL SCORE (Age + Shock + Coexisting illness)</strong></li>\n<li>When the endoscopic features are taken into consideration along with CLINICAL SCORE, then it is called as <strong>COMPLETE ROCKALL SCORE (Clinical score + endoscopic features)</strong></li>\n<li>A score of less than 3 carries good prognosis but total score more than 8 carries a high risk of mortality</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Factors</td>\n<td>Value</td>\n<td>Score</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;60 y</p>\n<p>60-79 y</p>\n<p>≥80 y</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>0</p>\n<p>1</p>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shock</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Heart rate &gt;100 beats/min</p>\n<p>Systolic blood pressure &lt;100 mm Hg&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1</p>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Coexisting Illness</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Ischemic heart disease, heart disease, congestive heart failure, other major illness</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>2</p>\n<p>3</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Endoscopic diagnosis</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>No lesions observed, Mallory-Weiss syndrome</p>\n<p>Peptic ulcer, erosive disease, esophagitis</p>\n<p>Cancer of the upper GI tract</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>0</p>\n<p>1</p>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Endoscopic stigmata of recent haemorrhage</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Clean base ulcer, flat pigmented spot</p>\n<p><strong>Blood in upper GI tract, active bleeding, visible vessels, clot</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>0</p>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1809, 'Surgery', 'PM1772. Physiological Consequences of Increased Intra-abdominal Pressure', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Decreased :</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cardiac output</li>\n<li><strong>Venous return</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Visceral blood ﬂow</strong></li>\n<li>Renal blood ﬂow</li>\n<li>Glomerular filtration</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Increased :</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Cardiac rate</strong></li>\n<li>Pulmonary capillary wedge pressure</li>\n<li>Peak inspiratory pressure</li>\n<li><strong>Central venous pressure</strong></li>\n<li>Intrapleural pressure</li>\n<li><strong>Systemic vascular resistance</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1810, 'Surgery', 'PM1771. Criteria for evaluation of peritoneal lavage fluid', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Positive</strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>Intermediate<br></strong></td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>Negative</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong><br> </strong>\n<ul>\n<li>&gt; <strong>100,000 red cells/μL<br> &gt; 500 white cells/μL<br> = 175 units amylase/dL</strong></li>\n<li>Bacteria on Gram-stained smear</li>\n<li><strong>Bile</strong></li>\n<li>Food particles</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Pink fluid on free aspiration</li>\n<li><strong>50,000–100,000 red</strong> cells/μL in blunt trauma</li>\n<li>100–500 white cells/μL</li>\n<li>75–175 units amylase/dL</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td><strong><br> </strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Clear aspirate</li>\n<li>&lt; 100 white cells/μL</li>\n<li>&lt; 75 units amylase/dL</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1811, 'Surgery', 'PM1646. Tests for Exocrine Pancreas', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Directly measuring<strong> pancreatic secretion </strong>in response to a standardized<strong> stimulus</strong>.\n<ul>\n<li>The stimulus to secretion can be\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Physiological, </strong>e.g., ingestion of a test meal, as in the <strong>Lundh test</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Pharmacological, </strong>e.g., intravenous injection of a hormone, such <strong>as secretin or cholecystokinin&nbsp;(CCK).</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Duodenal intubation</strong> has to be performed with a triple-lumen tube so that the gastric and duodenal juices can be aspirated, and a non-absorbable marker, such as polyethylene glycol, is used to assess the completeness of the aspiration.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The<strong> nitroblue tetrazolium–para-aminobenzoic acid (NBT–PABA) test </strong>provides an <strong>indirect measure</strong> of pancreatic function\n<ul>\n<li>The substance is administered orally and degraded in the gut by a pancreatic enzyme, and the breakdown product (PABA) is absorbed by the intestine and excreted in the urine; its urinary level is measured.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>pancreolauryl test</strong> works on a similar principle.\n<ul>\n<li>These tests are <strong>cheap and easy to perform</strong>, but are <strong>non-specific</strong>, especially following gastrectomy and in conditions that may alter gastrointestinal transit and intestinal absorptive capacity.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Measurement of the fecal elastase 1 in the stool</strong> is simple, specific, and now widely used.\n<ul>\n<li>Interpretation:\n<ul>\n<li>Above 200 μg/g feces is normal</li>\n<li>Between 100 and 200 μg/g:&nbsp;mild to moder­ate pancreatic insufficiency</li>\n<li>Below 100 μg/g: establishes the diagnosis of severe pancreatic exocrine insufficiency</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The <strong>fecal fat and weight estimation test </strong>measures the stool content of fat after a nutritional intake of 100 g of fat per day during 3 days. If the stool fat content exceeds 7 g/day, the diag­nosis of steatorrhea is established.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1812, 'Surgery', 'PM1634. Glasgow scale for assessment of severity of acute pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Within 48 hours</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Age &gt;55 years</li>\n<li>White blood cell count &gt;15 × 10<sup>9</sup>/L</li>\n<li>Blood glucose &gt;10 mmol/L (no history of diabetes)</li>\n<li>Serum urea &gt;16 mmol/L (no response to intravenous fluids)</li>\n<li>Arterial oxygen saturation (<em>P</em>aO2) &lt;8 kPa (60 mmHg)</li>\n<li>Serum calcium &lt;2.0 mmol/L</li>\n<li>Serum albumin &lt;32 g/L</li>\n<li>LDH &gt;600 units/L</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1813, 'Surgery', 'PM1621. Differentiating features between hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) and fibrolamellar carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Parameter</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>HCC</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Fibrolamellar carcinoma</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Male-to-female ratio</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>2:1&nbsp; to&nbsp;8:1</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No gender predilection</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Median age</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>55 years</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>25 years</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Invasive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;Well circumscribed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Resectability</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;25%</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>50%–75%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Cirrhosis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>90%</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>AFP positive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>80%</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Hepatitis B positive</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>65%</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>AFP: alpha-fetoprotein&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1814, 'Surgery', 'PM1614. Classification of Choledochal Cysts', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Type</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Feature</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Type I</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>The most common choledochal cyst type; it involves only the extrahepatic biliary tree and is generally a fusiform dilation.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Type II</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Saccular diverticulum off the common bile duct and may be mistaken for an accessory gallbladder.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Type III</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>A cystic dilation of the intramural common bile duct, within the wall of the duodenum, known as choledochoceles.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Type IV</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Type IVa: Cysts involving the intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary tree</p>\n<p>Type IVb: Multiple cysts limited to the extrahepatic biliary tree.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Type V</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Also known as Caroli disease, involve the intrahepatic ducts only.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/cb8a9fd06ff049cf8d8471ff68af11dcx1280x6315.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1815, 'Surgery', 'PM1609. Complications following Pancreaticoduodenectomy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Complication</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Frequency (%)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Delayed gastric emptying</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>18</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Pancreas fistula</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>12</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Wound infection</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>7</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Intra-abdominal abscess</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>6</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Cardiac events</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>3</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Bile leak</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>2</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Overall reoperation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>3</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1816, 'Surgery', 'PM1608. Presenting symptoms of periampullary tumors of pancreas', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Presenting symptom</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Frequency (%)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Jaundice</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>75</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Weight loss</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>51</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Abdominal pain</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>39</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Nausea/vomiting</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>13</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Pruritus</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>11</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Fever</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>3</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Gastrointestinal bleeding</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1817, 'Surgery', 'PM1602. Child-Turcotte-Pugh Score', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The Child–Turcotte–Pugh (CTP) score was originally developed to <strong>evaluate the risk of portocaval shunt procedures </strong>performed for<strong> portal hypertension.</strong>&nbsp;It is also useful in predicting the surgical risks of other intra-abdominal operations performed in cirrhotic patients.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Variable</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>1 Point</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>2 Points</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>3 Points</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Bilirubin level</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;2 mg/dL</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>2–3 mg/dL</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&gt;3 mg/dL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Albumin level</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&gt;3.5 g/dL</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>2.8–3.5 g/dL</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&lt;2.8 g/dL</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Prothrombin time (increased seconds)</p>\n<p>International normalized ratio</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>1–3</p>\n<p>&lt;1.7</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>4–6</p>\n<p>1.7–2.3</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&gt;6</p>\n<p>&gt;2.3</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Encephalopathy</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>None</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Controlled</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Uncontrolled</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Ascites</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>None</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Controlled</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Uncontrolled</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Child-Turcotte-Pugh class and overall surgical mortality rates:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Class A = 5–6 points - Well-compensated - 10% mortality</li>\n<li>Class B = 7–9 points - Decompensated and significant&nbsp; functional compromise - 30% mortality</li>\n<li>Class C = 10–15 points - Severerly decompensated - 75-80% mortality</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Prognosis of the various CTP classes:</strong></p>\n<table width=\429\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td><strong>1-year survival rate &nbsp;%</strong></td>\n<td><strong>2-year survival rate %</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A</td>\n<td>100</td>\n<td>85</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>B</td>\n<td>80</td>\n<td>60</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>C</td>\n<td>45</td>\n<td>35</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1818, 'Surgery', 'PM1588. Barium studies in GI tuberculosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Earliest feature </strong>is <strong>spasm </strong>and <strong>hypermotility,&nbsp;</strong>with <strong>edema of the valve.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Thickening of the valve lips,&nbsp;</strong>with <strong>narrowing </strong>of the <strong>terminal ileum:&nbsp;</strong><strong>Fleischner </strong>or <strong>inverted</strong>&nbsp;<strong>umbrella sign </strong>is <strong>characteristic of TB</strong>.</li>\n<li>In advance disease, the characteristic deformity includes <strong>symmetric, annular, napkin-ring stenosis </strong>and obstruction or shortening and pouch formation.</li>\n<li><strong>The cecum is</strong>&nbsp;<strong>shrunken </strong>and <strong>retracts&nbsp;</strong>out of the iliac fossa due to contraction of the mesocolon: <strong>Pulled-up cecum</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Loss of ileocecal angle </strong>with <strong>dilated terminal ileum:</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Gooseneck deformity </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Narrowing of the terminal ileum </strong>due to irritability, along with shortened rigid cecum: <strong>Sterlein sign</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Persistent narrow stream </strong>of <strong>barium </strong>in the bowel indicates stenosis:&nbsp;<strong>String sign</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1819, 'Surgery', 'PM1586. Factors Preventing Spontaneous Fistula Closure', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>High output (</strong><strong>&gt;</strong><strong>500 mL/24 hours)</strong></li>\n<li>Severe disruption of intestinal continuity (&gt;50% of bowel circumference)</li>\n<li>Active inflammatory bowel disease of bowel segment</li>\n<li>Cancer</li>\n<li>Radiation enteritis</li>\n<li><strong>Distal obstruction</strong></li>\n<li>Undrained abscess cavity</li>\n<li>Foreign body in the fistula tract</li>\n<li><strong>Fistula tract </strong><strong>&lt;2.5</strong><strong> cm long</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Epithelialization of fistula tract</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1820, 'Surgery', 'PM1585. Rule of two’s in Meckels diverticulum', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>2% prevalence</li>\n<li>2:1 male predominance</li>\n<li>Located approx 2 feet (60 cm) proximal to the ileocecal valve in adults</li>\n<li>Approx 2 inches in length</li>\n<li>Half of those who are symptomatic are under 2 years of age.</li>\n<li>2 types of heterotopic mucosa (gastric &amp; pancreatic)</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1821, 'Surgery', 'PM1578. Replacement conduits after esophagectomy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Best conduit after esophagectomy – <strong>Stomach</strong></li>\n<li>Best conduit of choice after carcinoma esophagus resection – Stomach</li>\n<li>Best conduit of choice after benign disorders – Colon</li>\n<li>Best conduit of choice after short segment replacement – Jejunum</li>\n<li><strong>Gastric conduit </strong>is based on <strong>right gastric and gastroepiploic arteries</strong></li>\n<li>Left colon conduit is based on left colic artery</li>\n<li>The <strong>posterior mediastinal route</strong> is preferred for placement of conduit as it is the shortest route.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1822, 'Surgery', 'PM1576. Types of Fundoplication', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Types of fundoplication</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Degree of wrap</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Dor</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>anterior 180–200° fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Thal</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>270° anterior fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Lind</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>300° posterior fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Toupet</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>posterior 180 - 270°&nbsp;fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Belsey Mark IV</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>270° anterior transthoracic</strong> fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Nissen</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>360°</strong> fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Watson</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>90<strong>°&nbsp;anterior </strong>fundoplication</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1823, 'Surgery', 'PM1575. Manometric classification of esophageal motility disorders', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\727\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Types</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Definition</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Disorders of EGJ obstruction</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type I achalasia<br>(classic)</td>\n<td>Abnormal IRP<br>100% failed peristalsis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type II<br>(with panesophageal pressurization)</td>\n<td>Abnormal IRP<br>100% failed peristalsis<br>Panesophageal pressurization</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type III<br>(spastic)</td>\n<td>Abnormal IRP<br>100% failed peristalsis<br>Spastic contractions<br>Panesophageal pressurization or normal presurization<br>DCI &gt; 450mmHg</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Disorders of peristalsis&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DES (Diffuse esophageal spasm)</td>\n<td>Normal IRPN<br>Non-peristaltic (spastic) contractions or premature contractions.<br>DCI&gt;450mmHg</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nutcracker’s esophagus</td>\n<td>Normal IRP<br>Increased duration of peristalsis<br>Normal peristalsis<br>DCI&gt;8000mmHg</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p class=\p1\><em>DCI (distal contractile integral) is an <strong>index of contractile vigor</strong>&nbsp;and is calculated as the product of amplitude, duration, and span of the distal esophageal contraction, (mmHg·s·cm).</em></p>\n<p><em>IRP (integrated relaxation pressure) corresponds to the <strong>mean pressure</strong>&nbsp;of greatest post deglutitive relaxation in a 10 seconds gap, triggered at the beginning of a swallow, (mmHg).</em></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1824, 'Surgery', 'PM1540. Charcot and Reynolds Triad', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Charcots triad - </strong>in <strong>acute cholangitis</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Right upper quadrant pain</li>\n<li>Fever with chills</li>\n<li>Jaundice</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Reynolds pentad - </strong>in<strong> acute suppurative cholangitis</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Charcot’s triad + Altered mental status + Hypotension&nbsp;</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1825, 'Surgery', 'PM1530. Mirizzi’s syndrome', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Gallstone becomes impacted in the <strong>cystic duct or neck of the gallbladder</strong>&nbsp;producing&nbsp;<strong>CBD obstruction and jaundice.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/e49b34e6f474441a9f74f858fa5cdb28x245x222.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ERCP, PTC, MRCP</strong> will usually demonstrate the characteristic extrinsic compression of the CBD.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Surgery consists of <strong>removing the cystic duct, diseased gallbladder, and the impacted stone.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1826, 'Surgery', 'PM1374. Non-functioning Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>These <strong>do not cause any clinical symptoms</strong>.</p>\n<p>Account for <strong>30-50%</strong> of all neuroendocrine tumors.</p>\n<p>Usually <strong>larger (&gt;5cm), solitary, mostly in head, malignant and metastatic</strong>.</p>\n<p>Diagnosis: Positive for Immunohistochemical markers such as <strong>synaptophysin, chromogranin A (CgA), and neuron-specific enolase.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Chromogranin A – </strong>used as<strong> serum marker to monitor response to treatment and to detect recurrence.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Treatment is mainly surgical - </strong>partial pancreaticoduodenectomy as well as the synchronous or metachronous resection of liver metastases<strong>.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1827, 'Surgery', 'PM1373. Diagnosis of Zollinger Ellison syndrome/Gastrinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Gastric pH below 2.5 </strong>and a <strong>serum gastrin concentration above 1000 pg/mL</strong> (normal &lt;100 pg/mL) confirms the diagnosis of Zollinger Ellison syndrome.</p>\n<p><strong>BAO &gt;15 mEq/h or &gt;5 mEq/h</strong> if they have had a previous procedure for peptic ulcer.</p>\n<p>Provocative tests when diagnosis is in doubt:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Secretin stimulation test – </strong>Increase in serum gastrin &gt; 200pg/ml&nbsp;(over the pretreatment value ) following an IV bolus of secretin (2U/kg).</li>\n<li>Calcium stimulation test</li>\n<li>Secretin plus calcium stimulation test</li>\n<li>Bombesin test</li>\n<li>Protein meal test</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1828, 'Surgery', 'PM1372. Clinical features of gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Most common symptom: <strong>Abdominal pain</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Gastrin hypersecretion</strong> stimulates <strong>gastric acid secretion,</strong> leading to <strong>peptic ulcers </strong>that&nbsp;occur at atypical sites like the duodenum and jejunum and are&nbsp;<strong>refractory</strong> and <strong>multiple.</strong></p>\n<p>Diarrhea&nbsp;is due to</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Acid-induced injury to the small intestine mucosa</li>\n<li>Inability of the intestinal tract to absorb large volumes of fluids secreted by the stomach</li>\n<li>Inactivation of pancreatic lipase by low pH</li>\n<li>Precipitation of bile salts.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The unique characteristic of <strong>acid-induced diarrhea</strong> is that it is controlled by <strong>nasogastric aspiration of gastric secretions.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1829, 'Surgery', 'PM1368. American Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Spleen Injury Scale', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/304d125090cf41f5b2ac0b5561d350dfx1280x2558.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1830, 'Surgery', 'PM1320. Appendicular tumors and their characteristics', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Appendicular tumor</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Characteristics</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Carcinoid</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>10 times more common than any other tumor of appendix</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Goblet cell carcinoid tumor</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>More aggressive</p>\n<p>Endocrine and glandular differentiation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Primary adenocarcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Usually of mucinous type</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Mucinous cystadenoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Can present as pseudomyxoma peritonei</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1831, 'Surgery', 'PM1319. Complications of Appendicectomy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Wound infection</strong>:<strong> 5–10%</strong></li>\n<li>Intra-abdominal abscess: 8%</li>\n<li>Post operative ileus</li>\n<li>Respiratory complications</li>\n<li>Venous thrombo-embolism</li>\n<li>Portal pyemia- septicemia in portal venous system, can lead to hepatic abscess.</li>\n<li><strong>Adhesive intestinal obstruction</strong>:<strong> 1–3% (MC late post op complication)</strong></li>\n<li>Fecal fistula</li>\n<li>Port site hernias.</li>\n<li>Appendico-cutaneous fistula or appendico-vesical fistula: rare</li>\n<li>Mortality after appendicectomy is less than 1%</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1832, 'Surgery', 'PM1318. Oshner Sherren Regimen', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Principle</strong> :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The inflammatory process is already localised and that inadvertent surgery is difficult and may be dangerous.</li>\n<li>It may be impossible to find the appendix and, occasionally, a faecal fistula may form.</li>\n<li>Antibiotic therapy should be given after performing CECT abdomen</li>\n<li>Abscess if present can be drained radiologically.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Outcome</strong> :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Improvement in 24–48 h</li>\n<li>90% cases resolve</li>\n<li>Failure should raise suspicion of Crohn’s disease and carcinoma.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Criteria for stopping conservative treatment of Appendicular mass:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rising pulse rate</li>\n<li>Increasing or spreading abdominal pain</li>\n<li>Increasing size of the mass</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1833, 'Surgery', 'PM1317. Alvarado Scoring System', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Findings</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p><strong>Points</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Migratory right iliac fossa pain</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Anorexia</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Nausea / vomiting</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Tenderness in right iiliac fossa</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p><strong>2</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Rebound tenderness right iliac fossa</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Elevated temperature ≥ 37.3°C</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Leukocytosis ≥ </strong>10⨯10<sup>9</sup><strong> cells/L</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p><strong>2</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Shift to the left of neutrophils</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\78\>\n<p>1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A score of 4-5 or below&nbsp;rules out the diagnosis of acute appendicitis in children, and in adults, a score of 8-9 or higher&nbsp;rules in the diagnosis.</p>\n<p>If the score is 4-6, an&nbsp;an adjunctive CT scan would be recommended to confirm the diagnosis.</p>\n<p>If the score is 7 or higher, surgery is recommended.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1834, 'Surgery', 'PM1315. Signs in appendicitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Sign</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Characteristic</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Seen in</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Dunphy’s sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Pain on coughing</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Acute appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p><strong>Rovsing sign</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Pain in the right lower quadrant during palpation of the left lower quadrant</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Acute appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Obturator sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Pain on internal rotation of hip</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Pelvic appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Ilio-Psoas sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Pain on extension of hip</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Retrocaecal appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Aaron sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Pain or pressure in epigastrium or anterior chest with persistent firm pressure applied to McBurney’s point</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Acute appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Basseler sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Sharp pain created by compressing appendix between abdominal wall and iliacus</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Chronic appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Blumberg’s sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Transient abdominal wall rebound tenderness</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Peritoneal inflammation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\213\>\n<p>Ten Horn sign</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\213\>Pain caused by gentle traction of right testicle</td>\n<td>\n<p>Appendicitis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1835, 'Surgery', 'PM1276. Chemotherapy for GI Tumours', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\0\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p><strong>GI malignancy</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p><strong>Chemotherapy</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p>Esophageal carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p>ECF (Epirubicin + Cisplatin + 5-FU)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p>Gastric carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p>ECF (Epirubicin + Cisplatin + 5-FU)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p>Small intestine adenocarcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p>5-FU</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p>Colorectal carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p>FOLFOX-IV (5-FU + Leucovorin + Oxaliplatin)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\265\>\n<p>Carcinoma of the anal canal</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\408\>\n<p>Nigro Regimen: Chemoradiation (5-FU + Mitomycin C) + Radiation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1836, 'Surgery', 'PM1269. Parks classification of fistula–in–ano', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Type of Fistula</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Arises due to&nbsp;</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Begins from</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Track</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Ends in</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Inter-sphincteric</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Perianal abscess</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dentate line</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>In inter-sphincteric space</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Perianal skin or perineum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Trans- sphincteric</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Ischiorectal Fossa abscess</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dentate line</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Crosses the internal and external sphincters&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Perineal skin or perineum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Supra- sphincteric</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Supra-levator abscess</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dentate line</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Penetrates the inter-sphincteric space, continues above puborectalis, and penetrates levator ani</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Perineal skin or perineum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Extra- sphincteric</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Penetrating injury</p>\n<p>Crohn’s disease</p>\n<p>Carcinoma rectum</p>\n</td>\n<td>Rectum or sigmoid colon&nbsp;</td>\n<td>\n<p>Outside the external sphincter, penetrating the levator ani&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>Peri-anal skin via ischio-rectal&nbsp; fossa.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/42a24c416b354e1eb349609162b1dce0x1280x1480.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1837, 'Surgery', 'PM1267. Grading of hemorrhoids', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p><strong>GRADE</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p><strong>SYMPTOMS AND SIGNS</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>First degree</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Bleeding; no prolapse</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Second degree</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Prolapse with spontaneous reduction</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Third degree</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Prolapse requiring manual reduction</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Fourth degree</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\295\>\n<p>Prolapsed, cannot be reduced</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1838, 'Surgery', 'PM1266. Differences between internal and external hemorrhoids', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Internal hemorrhoids</strong></td>\n<td><strong>External hemorrhoids</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Located&nbsp;<strong>proximal</strong> to&nbsp;the dentate line</td>\n<td>\n<p>Located&nbsp;<strong>distal </strong>to the dentate line</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Covered by&nbsp;<strong>transitional&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>columnar epithelium</strong></td>\n<td>Covered by richly innervated<strong>&nbsp;squamous epithelium</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Caused by pressure on <strong>superior rectal veins</strong></td>\n<td>Caused by pressure on <strong>inferior rectal veins</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Painless,&nbsp;</strong>can be&nbsp;<strong>ligated</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Painful, not ligated</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Banding&nbsp;</strong>is&nbsp;<strong>preferred</strong></td>\n<td>Excision is done</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1839, 'Surgery', 'PM1264. Risk Factors for Colorectal Cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The risk factors for colorectal cancer are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dietary: </strong>\n<ul>\n<li>High-animal-fat diet</li>\n<li>Low-fiber diet</li>\n<li>Alcohol</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Hereditary syndromes:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>FAP</li>\n<li>HNPCC</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Inflammatory bowel disease</li>\n<li>Cholecystectomy: increased right colon cancer due to exposure to bile acids</li>\n<li>Ureterosigmoidostomy</li>\n<li>Smoking</li>\n<li>Acromegaly</li>\n<li>Pelvic irradiation</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1840, 'Surgery', 'PM1263. Haggitt’s classification for polyps containing cancer according to the depth of invasion', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Level 0:</strong> Carcinoma does not invade the muscularis mucosae (<strong>carcinoma in situ or intramucosal carcinoma</strong>)</li>\n<li><strong>Level 1</strong>: Carcinoma invades through the muscularis mucosae into the submucosa but is limited to the <strong>head</strong> of the polyp</li>\n<li><strong>Level 2</strong>: Carcinoma invades the level of the <strong>neck</strong> of the polyp (junction between the head and stalk)</li>\n<li><strong>Level 3</strong>: Carcinoma invades <strong>any part of the stalk</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Level 4</strong>: Carcinoma invades into the <strong>submucosa of the bowel wall below the stalk of the polyp but above the muscularis propria</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/81ca1351b12d443d9d4e991af0c4c62dx1280x1413.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1841, 'Surgery', 'PM1260. Peutz–Jeghers Syndrome', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Autosomal-dominant disease</li>\n<li>Germline defects in the <strong>tumor suppressor </strong>serine-threonine kinase 11 (<strong><em>STK11</em></strong>) gene on<strong> chromosome 19.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Features</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hyperpigmentation</strong> of the buccal mucosa, lips, and digits</li>\n<li><strong>Hamartomatous polyps</strong> of the intestinal tract</li>\n<li>Increased (2% to 10%) risk for <strong>cancer</strong> of the<strong> intestinal tract</strong>&nbsp;(stomach - rectum).</li>\n<li>Increased risk for <strong>extraintestinal malig­nant neoplasms</strong>, including cancer of the breast, ovary, cervix, fallopian tubes, thyroid, lung, gallbladder, bile ducts, pancreas, and testicles.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Screening</strong>:&nbsp;Baseline colonoscopy and upper endoscopy at age 20 years, followed by annual flexible sigmoidoscopy thereafter.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/eff8622ebbed495bb2c50bb2544cdb48x450x600.JPEG\><img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1160ec99452648149a62ef6cadaef74ex418x532.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Histologic image</strong> showing the characteristic arborizing network of connective tissue, smooth muscle, lamina propria, and glands lined by normal-appearing intestinal epithelium:</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/e7f25b73d84249949d85119e7bd2cc28x1280x1863.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1842, 'Surgery', 'PM1259. Features of Familial Adenomatous Polyposis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Gastrointestinal manifestations</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Colon </strong>and<strong> rectum</strong>:<strong> Multiple adenomatous polyps</strong> usually <strong>&gt;100</strong></li>\n<li>Gastric and duodenal polyps are present</li>\n<li><strong>Gastric polyp: </strong>fundal gland polyp, gastric adenoma</li>\n<li><strong>Duodenal polyp</strong> usually in the<strong> ampullary </strong>region: Adenomatous and premalignant</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Extraintestinal manifestations</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium (<strong>CHRPE</strong>) is seen. It is detected by indirect ophthalmoscopy.</li>\n<li><strong>Epidermoid cysts</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Desmoid tumors </strong>in the abdomen</li>\n<li><strong>Osteoma </strong>in the skull, mandible, and tibia</li>\n<li><strong>Brain tumors</strong></li>\n<li>Tumors of the thyroid, adrenal, liver, pancreas, gallbladder, and bile duct</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1843, 'Surgery', 'PM1258. Characteristic features of colorectal carcinoma in Hereditary Non-polyposis Colorectal Cancer (HNPCC)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Onset of cancer at a <strong>relatively young age </strong>(mean, 44 years)</li>\n<li>Proximal distribution (70% of cancers located in the <strong>right colon)</strong></li>\n<li>Predominance of <strong>mucinous or poorly differentiated (signet cell) adenocarcinoma</strong></li>\n<li>Increased number of <strong>synchronous and metachronous cancers</strong></li>\n<li>Relatively <strong>good outcome after surgery</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1844, 'Surgery', 'PM1257. Types of Lynch syndromes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Lynch I syndrome</strong> is characterized by <strong>cancer of the proximal colon</strong> occurring at a relatively young age.</li>\n<li><strong>Lynch II syndrome</strong> is characterized by <strong>fami­lies at risk for both colorectal and extracolonic cancers</strong>, including cancers of endometrial, ovarian, gastric, small intestinal, pancre­atic, and ureteral and renal pelvic origin.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1845, 'Surgery', 'PM1256. Amsterdam Criteria II - Revised Criteria for HNPCC', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The <strong>diagnostic criteria for HNPCC</strong> are referred to as the <strong>Amsterdam criteria</strong><em>&nbsp;</em>or the <strong>3-2-1-0 rule</strong><em>.</em></p>\n<p>It includes the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Three or more relatives</strong> with HNPCC-associated cancer (colorectal cancer, endometrial cancer, cancer of the small bowel, ureter, or renal pelvis), <strong>one </strong>of whom is a<strong> first-degree relative of the other two</strong></li>\n<li>At least <strong>two successive generations</strong> affected</li>\n<li>At least <strong>one case </strong>diagnosed<strong> before </strong>the age of<strong> 50 years</strong></li>\n<li>Familial adenomatous polyposis excluded.</li>\n<li>Tumors verified by pathologic examination.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>All of the above</strong> must be applicable for a presumptive diagnosis of HNPCC to be made in a family.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\p1\>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1846, 'Surgery', 'PM1254. Fearon-Vogelstein adenoma-carcinoma multistep model of colorectal neoplasia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/36a7ff35752b47cb923b911ff3c3e18bx1280x1486.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1847, 'Surgery', 'PM1253. Sites of carcinoma colon and rectum', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Site of carcinoma</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Frequency</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Rectum (most common)</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>38%</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Sigmoid colon</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>21%</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>Caecum</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p><strong>12%</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Transverse colon</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>5.5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Ascending colon</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Descending colon</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>4%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Splenic flexure</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>3%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>Hepatic flexure</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\319\>\n<p>2%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/925f8d8fa9b34218846e9970ec217bbdx1280x1150.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1848, 'Surgery', 'PM1252. Virtual/CT Colonoscopy', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>CT colonography (virtual colonoscopy)</strong></p>\n<p>It uses helical CT and three-dimensional reconstruction to detect <strong>intraluminal colonic lesions</strong>.</p>\n<p>Oral bowel preparation, oral and rectal contrast, and colon insufflation have been used to <strong>maximize sensitivity</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Noninvasive, less time consuming</li>\n<li>Sensitivity may be as good as colonoscopy</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Requires bowel preparation</li>\n<li>Insensitive for small polyps</li>\n<li>Minimal experience and data</li>\n<li>Colonoscopy required for positive result</li>\n</ul>\n<p>False positive results from retained stool, diverticular disease, haustral folds, motion artifacts, and an inability to detect flat adenomas.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/65cd04b932ff460a940784e3636b0a2cx512x182.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1849, 'Surgery', 'PM1251. Dukes’ staging for colorectal cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Stage A</strong> - Invasion of but <strong>not breaching the muscularis propria</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Stage B</strong> <strong>- Breaching the muscularis propria</strong> but not involving lymph nodes</li>\n<li><strong>Stage C - Lymph nodes involved</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dukes himself never described a <strong>stage D</strong>, but this is often used to describe <strong>metastatic disease</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1850, 'Surgery', 'PM1183. Cowden Disease', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Autosomal dominant</strong></p>\n<p>Mutation of <strong>PTEN</strong> gene on chromosome <strong>10q23.3</strong></p>\n<p>Components:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hamartomas of all three embryonal cell layers\n<ul>\n<li>Intestinal hamartomatous polyp – usually <strong>ectodermal</strong>, most common in <strong>colon</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Facial trichilemmomas – most common feature.</strong></li>\n<li>Cancer of the\n<ul>\n<li>Breast (30–50%)</li>\n<li>Thyroid (10% - <strong>Mainly </strong><strong>FTC</strong>, rarely PTC and Hurthle cell tumors)</li>\n<li>Endometrium</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>CNS – 2<sup>nd</sup> most commonly involved system\n<ul>\n<li>Megalencephaly, ataxia, epilepsy, dysplastic gangliocytoma of cerebellum – <strong>Lhermitte Duclos syndrome.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Developmental anomalies – high arched palate</strong>, adenoid facies, prominent forehead, Hypoplastic mandible.</li>\n<li><strong>Skin disease – acral keratosis.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1851, 'Surgery', 'PM1177. Classification of colorectal polyps', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Colorectal polyps can be classified as:</p>\n<p><strong>Neoplastic </strong></p>\n<p>Adenomatous polyps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tubular adenoma (Most common)</li>\n<li>Tubulovillous adenomas</li>\n<li>Villous adenoma (highest risk of malignancy)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Non-neoplastic: </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hyperplastic</li>\n<li>Hamartomatous\n<ul>\n<li>Juvenile polyp(solitary)-benign</li>\n<li>Juvenile polyposis syndromes (multiple)-premalignant</li>\n<li>Peutz-Jeghers syndrome- occasionally carcinoma may develop.</li>\n<li>Cronkite-Canada syndrome*</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Inflammatory\n<ul>\n<li>Pseudopolyp</li>\n<li>Benign lymphoid polyp</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Note:</p>\n<p>*Cronkite-Canada syndrome: Cancer occurs in the stomach, colon, and rectum, but it remains controversial whether these polyps&nbsp; possess malignant potential. As many as 15% of patients with Cronkite- Canada syndrome have a malignant tumor at the time of diagnosis</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1852, 'Surgery', 'PM1074. TNM staging of gastric carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table class=\datatable xwidetable\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<p><strong>Primary tumor (T)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>TX</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Primary tumor cannot be assessed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T0</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No evidence of primary tumor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Tis</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Carcinoma in situ: intraepithelial tumor without invasion of the lamina propria</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T1</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades lamina propria, muscularis mucosae, or submucosa</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T1a</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades lamina propria or muscularis mucosae</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T1b</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades submucosa</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T2</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades muscularis propria</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T3</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor penetrates subserosal connective tissue without invasion of visceral peritoneum or adjacent structures</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T4</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades serosa (visceral peritoneum) or adjacent structures</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T4a</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades serosa (visceral peritoneum)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>T4b</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Tumor invades adjacent structures</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<p><strong>Regional lymph nodes (N)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>NX</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Regional lymph node(s) cannot be assessed</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N0</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No regional lymph node metastasis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N1</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Metastasis in 1-2 regional lymph nodes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N2</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Metastasis in 3-6 regional lymph nodes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N3</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Metastasis in seven or more regional lymph nodes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N3a</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Metastasis in 7-15 regional lymph nodes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>N3b</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Metastasis in 16 or more regional lymph nodes</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<p><strong>Distant metastasis (M)</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>M0</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>No distant metastasis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>M1</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Distant metastasis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1853, 'Surgery', 'PM1072. Borrmann’s classification of stomach cancer', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/cdf8171797864909bcbfd5d019fc4ec6x1280x1766.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1854, 'Surgery', 'PM1070. Siewert-Stein classification of adenocarcinomas of the esophago-gastric junction', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Siewert</td>\n<td>Description</td>\n<td>Surgical approach</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>I</td>\n<td>Tumour center located between 5 and 1 cm proximal to the anatomical cardia</td>\n<td>Approached as esophageal or EGJ cancer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>II</td>\n<td>Tumour center located between 1 cm proximal and 2 cm distal to the anatomical cardia</td>\n<td>Approached as esophageal or EGJ cancer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>III</td>\n<td>Tumour center located between 2 and 5 cm distal to the anatomical cardia</td>\n<td>Approached as gastric cancer</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/340014f8d74f4927a93edc2b769e8d7cx1279x1588.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1855, 'Surgery', 'PM1069. Most common site of gastric malignancies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Most common site of <strong>Ca. Stomach</strong> : <strong>Proximal Stomach (Western countries)</strong></p>\n<p>Most common site of <strong>Ca. Stomach in Pernicious anaemia</strong> :&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;Fundus</strong></p>\n<p>Most common site of <strong>diffuse variety of&nbsp;Ca. Stomach</strong> :&nbsp;<strong>Fundus</strong></p>\n<p>Most common site of&nbsp;<strong>Gastric lymphoma</strong> :<strong> Antrum</strong></p>\n<p>Most common site of&nbsp;<strong>Burkitt’s lymphoma/EBV</strong> : <strong>Cardia / Body</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1856, 'Surgery', 'PM1068. Risk factors for carcinoma stomach', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Risk factors for carcinoma stomach:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dietary\n<ul>\n<li>Low fat or protein consumption</li>\n<li>Consumption of <strong>salted meat</strong> or fish with <strong>high nitrate content</strong></li>\n<li>High complex carbohydrate consumption</li>\n<li>Smoking,&nbsp;<strong>alcohol </strong>consumption</li>\n<li>Spicy food, high salt diet</li>\n<li>Lack of fresh fruits and vegetables</li>\n<li>Dietary anti-oxidant deficiency</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Genetic and familial</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>E cadherin</strong> – hereditary diffuse type of gastric cancer</li>\n<li><strong>Blood group A</strong></li>\n<li>FAP</li>\n<li>Li-Fraumeni syndrome</li>\n<li>HNPCC</li>\n<li>BRCA 2 mutation</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Premalignant lesions</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Chronic atrophic gastritis</strong></li>\n<li>Adenomatous polyp (FAP)</li>\n<li>Pernicious anemia</li>\n<li><strong>Intestinal metaplasia (H. pylori)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Menetrier’s disease</strong></li>\n<li>Stump carcinoma from stomach remnants in Billroth II GJ or vagotomy GJ</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Others\n<ul>\n<li>Low socioeconomic status</li>\n<li>Male gender</li>\n<li>Rubber and coal workers</li>\n<li><strong>EBV infection</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1857, 'Surgery', 'PM1067. Desmoid tumor', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Unencapsulated fibroma </strong>arising from<strong> musculoaponeurotic structures </strong>usually below the umbilicus.</li>\n<li>Females&gt;males</li>\n<li><strong>Extraabdominal (65%) </strong>&gt; abdominal (25%) &gt; intraabdominal (15%)</li>\n<li>Associated with FAP (Gardner syndrome)</li>\n<li>Infiltrates surrounding tissues but no metastasis and <strong>no sarcomatous change</strong>.</li>\n<li>Investigation of choice – <strong>MRI</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Treatment</strong>:\n<ul>\n<li>Wide local excision with negative margin</li>\n<li>More <strong>prone for recurrence</strong> – treated by surgery and radiotherapy</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1858, 'Surgery', 'PM1066. Moore’s classification of Omphalocele:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Type</td>\n<td>Diameter of defect</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type I</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&lt;2.5cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type II</td>\n<td>2.5 - 5 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Type III</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt;5cm</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1859, 'Surgery', 'PM1057. Lumbar triangles and hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Acquired</strong>&gt;congenital</li>\n<li><strong>Left side</strong>&gt; right side</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Superior lumbar triangle (Grynfelt triangle) -&nbsp;</strong>Bounded by the</p>\n<ul>\n<li>12th rib</li>\n<li>Paraspinal muscles</li>\n<li>Internal oblique muscle.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Inferior lumbar triangle (Petit triangle) -&nbsp;</strong>Bounded by the</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Iliac crest</li>\n<li>Latissimus dorsi muscle</li>\n<li>External oblique muscle.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dowd’s operation is done for lumbar hernia</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/a6a8d905893446aab2c86694c553af86x1280x1211.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1860, 'Surgery', 'PM1054. Spigelian hernia/Hernia of linea semilunaris:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Occurs through the <strong>spigelian fascia</strong>, which is the aponeurosis of transversus abdominis.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>This aponeurotic layer is&nbsp; between the <strong>rectus muscle medially and semilunar line laterally</strong>.</li>\n<li>Occur <strong>at or above the arcuate line</strong>.</li>\n<li>Often <strong>interparietal</strong>, with the hernia sac dissecting <strong>pos­terior to the external oblique aponeurosis.</strong></li>\n<li>In subumbilical region and is due to defect in internal oblique.</li>\n<li><strong>Clinical feature:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Often present with <strong>localized pain in the area without a bulge</strong> because the hernia lies beneath the intact external oblique aponeurosis.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Diagnosis: Ultrasound or CT of the abdomen.</strong></li>\n<li>Treatment – surgery</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1861, 'Surgery', 'PM1053. Variants of femoral hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Laugier’s femoral hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Through a gap in <strong>lacunar (Gimbernat) ligament.</strong></li>\n<li>Always strangulated</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Narath’s femoral hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Seen in patients with <strong>congenital dislocation of hip</strong></li>\n<li>It is <strong>behind the femoral vessels</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cloquet’s hernia</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sac lies <strong>under pectineus fascia.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Hesselbach’s hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lateral to femoral artery</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Serafinis hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Behind the femoral vessels</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Velpeau(Prevascular/Teales) hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Infront of femoral vessels</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Beclard’s hernia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Through saphenous opening</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1862, 'Surgery', 'PM1052. Surgeries for femoral hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Lockwood’s low inguinal surgery</li>\n<li>McEvedy’s high inguinal surgery – preferred in emergency where risk of bowel infarction is high</li>\n<li>Lotheissen’s inguinal surgery</li>\n<li>Henry procedure – Mid abdominal Extraperitoneal Femoral Hernioplasty</li>\n<li>McVay – for both femoral and inguinal hernia</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1863, 'Surgery', 'PM1042. Types of indirect inguinal hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Bubonocele</strong> – Hernia limited to the <strong>inguinal canal.</strong></li>\n<li>Funicular – Hernia stops just above the testis.</li>\n<li>Complete/scrotal – Hernia reaches bottom of scrotum.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1cff780fee0d413389d14744a7f8ff0bx1280x1156.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1864, 'Surgery', 'PM1040. Nyhus classification of groin hernia', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Type I - Indirect inguinal hernia: internal inguinal ring normal (e.g., pediatric hernia)</li>\n<li>Type II - Indirect inguinal hernia: internal inguinal ring dilated but posterior inguinal wall intact; inferior deep epigastric vessels not displaced</li>\n<li>Type III - Posterior wall defect\n<ul>\n<li>A- Direct inguinal hernia</li>\n<li>B - Indirect inguinal hernia: internal inguinal ring dilated, medially encroaching on or destroying the transversalis fascia of Hesselbach&nbsp;triangle (e.g., scrotal, sliding, or pantaloon hernia)</li>\n<li><strong>C - Femoral hernia</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Type IV - Recurrent hernia\n<ul>\n<li>A - Direct</li>\n<li>B - Indirect</li>\n<li>C - Femoral</li>\n<li>D - Combined</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1865, 'Surgery', 'PM0788. Pheochromocytoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When pheochromocytoma is associated with the MEN syndrome it is rarely malignant.</li>\n<li>Phaeochromocytomas are greyish-pink on the cut surface and are usually highly vascularised.</li>\n<li><strong>Zellbalen cells and nuclei with salt and pepper chromatin </strong>are seen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Factors indicating more chances of malignancy:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>An increased PASS (phaeochromocytoma of the adrenal gland scale score)</li>\n<li>High number of Ki-67-positive cells</li>\n<li>Vascular invasion or a breached capsule</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Measurement of the plasma metanephrines is the most sensitive screening test.</li>\n<li><strong>MRI is the IOC.</strong></li>\n<li>Biopsy and CT Contrast scans are contraindicated in order to avoid a hypertensive crisis.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Adrenalectomy i</strong>s preferred TOC.</li>\n<li>Size&lt;5 cm -&nbsp; Laparoscopic adrenalectomy</li>\n<li>Preop Alpha blockers should be given</li>\n<li>Mitotane should be started as adjuvant or palliative treatment</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1866, 'Surgery', 'PM0578. Early Dumping vs. Late Dumping', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Early dumping</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Late dumping</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Incidence</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>5–10%</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>5%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Relation to meals</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Almost immediate</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Second hour after meal</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Duration of attack</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>30–40 mins</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>30–40 mins</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Relief</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Lying down</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Food</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Aggravated by</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>More food</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Exercise</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Precipitating factor</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Carbohydrate-rich food</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Carbohydrate-rich food</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p><strong>Major symptoms</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Epigastric fullness, sweating, light headedness, tachycardia, colic, sometimes diarrhoea</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\208\>\n<p>Tremor, faintness, prostration</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1867, 'Anatomy,', 'PM0561. Abdominal muscles and their nerve supplies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Muscles</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p><strong>Nerve supply</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>External oblique and rectus abdominis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>T7-11 intercostal nerves and subcostal nerve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Internal oblique&nbsp;and transversus abdominis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>T7-11 intercostal nerves, subcostal nerve and L1</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Pyramidalis</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Subcostal nerve (the anterior division of T12)&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Cremaster&nbsp; (efferent for cremasteric reflex)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\239\>\n<p>Genital branch of genitofemoral nerve</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1868, 'Surgery', 'PM0312. Opacities on a Plain Abdominal Radiograph that may be Confused with Renal Calculus', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Opacities on a plain abdominal radiograph that may be confused with renal calculus</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Calcified Mesenteric Lymph Node</li>\n<li>Gallstones or concretion in the appendix</li>\n<li>Tablets or Foreign bodies in the Alimentary canal (e.g., cyclopenthiazide (Navidrex-K))</li>\n<li>Phleboliths - calcification in the walls of veins, especially in the veins</li>\n<li>Ossified tip of the 12th rib</li>\n<li>Calcified tuberculous lesion in the kidney</li>\n<li>Calcified adrenal gland</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1869, 'Surgery', 'PM1041. Difference between Direct and Indirect inguinal hernias:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Indirect hernia</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Direct hernia</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>Young</td>\n<td>Elderly</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Herniation</strong></td>\n<td>Through the deep inguinal ring</td>\n<td>Through the posterior wall of the inguinal canal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shape</strong></td>\n<td>Pyriform/oval</td>\n<td>Globular/round</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Descent</strong></td>\n<td>Obliquely and downwards</td>\n<td>Directly forwards</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Descent to scrotum</strong></td>\n<td>Complete – descends till the bottom of the scrotum</td>\n<td>Rarely complete</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Neck</strong></td>\n<td>Narrow</td>\n<td>Wide</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sac</strong></td>\n<td>Lateral to the inferior epigastric artery</td>\n<td>Medial to the inferior epigastric artery</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Zieman’s test</strong></td>\n<td>Cough impulse on the index finger</td>\n<td>Cough impulse on the middle finger</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Invagination test</strong></td>\n<td>Tip of finger</td>\n<td>Pulp of finger</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Ring occlusion test</strong></td>\n<td>Doesn’t bulge</td>\n<td>Bulges medial to occluding finger</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Coverings</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Extraperitoneal tissue</p>\n<p>Internal spermatic fascia</p>\n<p>Cremasteric fascia</p>\n<p>External spermatic fascia</p>\n<p>Skin</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Extraperitoneal tissue</p>\n<p>Fascia transversalis</p>\n<p>Conjoint tendon</p>\n<p>External spermatic fascia</p>\n<p>Skin</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Obstruction/strangulation</strong></td>\n<td>Common</td>\n<td>Rare</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sac</strong></td>\n<td>Should be opened during surgery</td>\n<td>Not necessary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td>Usually unilateral</td>\n<td>Usually bilateral</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1870, 'Surgery', 'PM2252. Causes of Hydronephrosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1306\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1306\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Unilateral hydronephrosis</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Extramural obstruction</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tumor from adjacent structures, e.g., cervix, prostate, rectum, colon, or cecum</li>\n<li>Retrocaval ureter</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Aberrant renal vessels</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Idiopathic retroperitoneal fibrosis (Ormond’s disease)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Intramural obstruction</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Congenital PUJ obstruction</strong> - most common congenital cause</li>\n<li>Congenital stenosis</li>\n<li>Ureterocele</li>\n<li>Ureteric stricture - iatrogenic/ inflammatory</li>\n<li>Neoplasm of the ureter or bladder involving the ureteric orifice</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Intraluminal obstruction</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Renal stones</strong> - most common acquired unilateral cause</li>\n<li>Sloughed papilla in papillary necrosis (especially, in patients with diabetes, analgesic abuse, or sickle cell disease)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong><span><span>Bilateral hydronephrosis</span></span></strong></p>\n<p><strong><span><span>Congenital</span></span></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><span>Posterior urethral valves (associated with pulmonary hypoplasia)</span></span></li>\n<li><span><span>Urethral atresia</span></span></li>\n<li><span><span>PUJ obstruction</span></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Acquired &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Benign prostatic hypertrophy or carcinoma of the prostate</li>\n<li>Idiopathic retroperitoneal fibrosis <span><span>(Ormonds disease)</span></span></li>\n<li>Postoperative bladder neck scarring</li>\n<li>Urethral stricture</li>\n<li>Phimosis</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1871, 'Surgery', 'PM2238. American Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Kidney Injury Scale', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>GRADE&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>INJURY</td>\n<td>DESCRIPTION</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>I</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Contusion</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Microscopic or gross hematuria, urologic studies normal</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Hematoma</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Subcapsular, nonexpanding, without parenchymal laceration</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>II</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Hematoma</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Nonexpanding perirenal hematoma confined to renal retroperitoneum</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Laceration</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>&nbsp;&lt;1 cm parenchymal depth of renal cortex without urinary extravasation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>III</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Laceration&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>&gt;1 cm depth of renal cortex, without collecting system rupture or urinary extravasation</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV</td>\n<td>Laceration</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Parenchymal laceration extending through the renal cortex, medulla, and collecting system</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Vascular</td>\n<td>\n<p class=\p1\>Main renal artery or vein injury, with contained hemorrhage</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>V</td>\n<td>Laceration</td>\n<td>Completely shattered kidney</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Laceration&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Avulsion of renal hilum, which devascularizes kidney</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/7b401ef41a614376a0bf729998a717a5x1280x2560.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1872, 'Surgery', 'PM2149. TNM staging of testicular tumour: American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) and Union Internationale Contre le Cancer (UICC)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1175\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Primary tumor (T)</strong></p>\n<p>The extent of the primary tumor is usually classified after radical orchiectomy (except for pTis and pT4) and, for this reason, a pathologic (p) stage is assigned.</p>\n<p>pTx - Primary tumor cannot be assessed</p>\n<p>pT0 - No evidence of primary tumor (e.g., a histologic scar in testis)</p>\n<p>pTis -&nbsp; Germ-cell neoplasia in situ</p>\n<p>pT1 - Tumor limited to the testis and epididymis <strong>without</strong> <strong>vascular/lymphatic invasion</strong>; tumor may invade into tunica albuginea but <strong>not&nbsp;</strong><strong>tunica vaginalis</strong></p>\n<p>pT2 - Tumor limited to testis and epididymis <strong>with vascular/lymphatic invasion</strong> or tumor extending through the tunica albuginea, with the&nbsp;<strong>involvement of tunica vaginalis</strong></p>\n<p>pT3 - Tumor <strong>invades spermatic cord</strong> with or without vascular/lymphatic invasion</p>\n<p>pT4 - Tumor <strong>invades the scrotum</strong> with or without vascular/lymphatic invasion</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1175\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Regional lymph nodes (N)</strong></p>\n<p>NX - Regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed</p>\n<p>N0 - No regional lymph node metastasis</p>\n<p>N1 - Metastasis with lymph node mass <strong>≤2 cm</strong> in greatest dimension; or multiple lymph nodes, none more than 2 cm in greatest dimension</p>\n<p>N2 - Metastasis with lymph node mass,&nbsp;<strong>2–5 cm</strong> in greatest dimension; or multiple lymph nodes, anyone mass &gt;2 cm but not more than 5 cm in greatest dimension</p>\n<p>N3 - Metastasis with lymph node mass <strong>&gt;5 cm</strong> in greatest dimension</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1176\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Distant metastasis (M)</strong></p>\n<p>MX - Distant metastasis cannot be assessed</p>\n<p>M0 - No distant metastasis</p>\n<p>M1 - Distant metastasis</p>\n<p>M1a - Nonregional nodal or pulmonary metastasis</p>\n<p>M1b - Distant metastasis at site other than nonregional lymph nodes or lung</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1176\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Serum tumor markers (S)</strong></p>\n<p>SX - Marker studies unavailable or not performed</p>\n<p>S0 - Marker study levels within normal limits</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>S1</td>\n<td>S2</td>\n<td>S3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>LDH</td>\n<td>&lt;1.5 × N</td>\n<td>1.5–10 × N</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt;10×N</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>hCG(MIU/mL)</td>\n<td>&lt;5000</td>\n<td>5000–50,000</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt;50,000&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>AFP(ng/mL)</td>\n<td>&lt;1000</td>\n<td>1000–10,000</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt;10,000</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1176\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>N indicates the upper limit of normal for the LDH assay</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1873, 'Surgery', 'PM2119. Most common testicular tumors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\508\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Pre-pubertal age group</td>\n<td>Yolk sac tumor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15–34 years</td>\n<td>Germ-cell tumors</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Adults</td>\n<td>Seminomatous and non-seminomatous</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Elderly age group</td>\n<td>Lymphoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Germ-cell testicular tumor</td>\n<td>Seminoma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bilateral testicular tumor</td>\n<td>Lymphoma</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1874, 'Surgery', 'PM2081. Histologic subtypes of renal cell carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1866\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Clear-cell type:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Most common type</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Originates from proximal convoluted tubules</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Caused by deletion of chromosomes 3p &amp; 6p&nbsp;</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Associated with von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease and tuberous sclerosis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Papillary type:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Originates from proximal/distal convoluted tubules</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Caused by c-met mutation</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Histology shows <strong>Psammoma bodies</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Associated with hereditary papillary renal cell carcinoma</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Micropapillary variant is associated with long term dialysis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Chromophobe type:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\><strong>Best prognosis</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Originates from intercalated cells of collecting duct</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Caused by <strong>loss of multiple chromosomes</strong> (1, 2, 6, 10, 13) and extreme hypodiploidy</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Associated with <strong>Birt-Hogg- Dubé syndrome</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Histology shows plant-like cells/ resin like nucleus</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Cytokeratin positive on IHC&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Collecting (Bellini duct) type:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Worst prognosis</strong></li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Originates from collecting tubules</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Caused by deletion of 1q &amp; monosomy of multiple chromosomes</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Medullary type:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Poor prognosis</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Originates from distal nephron</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Associated with <strong>sickle cell anemia</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Note:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Sarcomatoid change can occur infrequently in all types of renal cell carcinoma (RCC) and is an ominous feature.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1875, 'Surgery', 'PM1220. Surgical shunts for ischaemic priapism', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\379\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shunt site</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><strong>Example&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Corpora&nbsp;glanular&nbsp;shunt&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Winter / Al-Ghorab&nbsp;shunt&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Corpora&nbsp;spongiosal&nbsp;shunt&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Quackel&nbsp;/ Sacher shunt&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Corpora Saphenous shunt&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Grayhack&nbsp;shunt&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Corpora dorsal vein shunt&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Barry shunt&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1876, 'Surgery', 'PM0310. Management of renal and ureteric calculi', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/4cfbb28a9c864211aae21deaebd2fc99x1280x2912.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>ESWL: Extracorporeal Shock Wave Lithotripsy</p>\n<p>PCNL:&nbsp;Percutaneous nephrolithotomy</p>\n<p>URS: Ureteroscopic retrieval of stones</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1877, 'Surgery', 'PM0309. Radiolucent Renal Stones', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Radiolucent Renal Stones</strong></p>\n<p>Mnemonic: <strong>X UTI</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>X</strong>anthine</li>\n<li><strong>U</strong>ric Acid (most common)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Drug induced renal stones</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>T</strong>riamterene</li>\n<li><strong>I</strong>ndinavir</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1878, 'Surgery', 'PM2499. ATLS Primary Survey', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The steps in the ATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Primary</strong>&nbsp;survey with simultaneous resuscitation – identify and treat what is killing the patient</li>\n<li><strong>Secondary</strong>&nbsp;survey – proceed to identify all other injuries</li>\n<li><strong>Definitive care&nbsp;</strong>– develop a definitive management plan</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Primary Survey: ABCDEs</strong>&nbsp;of trauma care:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A</strong>irway assessment and protection (maintain <strong>cervical spine stabilization</strong> when appropriate) - If airway obstruction is identified, jaw thrust in cervical injury patients or chin lift is performed.</li>\n<li><strong>B</strong>reathing and ventilation assessment - maintain adequate <strong>oxygenation,&nbsp;</strong>consider non-invasive or invasive ventilation when indicated</li>\n<li><strong>C</strong>irculation assessment (<strong>control hemorrhage, </strong>maintain circulating volume and adequate end-organ perfusion)<strong> -&nbsp;</strong><strong>Two wide-bore (14G to 16G) cannulae</strong> are inserted for intravenous fluid resuscitation.</li>\n<li><strong>D</strong>isability assessment - perform a&nbsp;<strong>basic neurologic evaluation&nbsp;</strong>(AVPU/GCS-P), blood glucose levels</li>\n<li><strong>E</strong>xposure with environmental control - undress the patient and examine thoroughly for possible injuries, prevent hypothermia</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Adjuncts</strong>&nbsp;to the primary survey:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blood</strong> collection - CBC, urea and electrolytes, clotting screen, glucose, toxicology, cross-match</li>\n<li>ECG, pulse oximetry, ventilatory rate, capnography, ABG analysis</li>\n<li>Urinary and gastric catheters</li>\n<li>Radiographs of the chest and pelvis are done as a part of the primary survey preferably with a portable x-ray unit. When required, all these x-rays must also be done on pregnant women.</li>\n<li>(e)FAST</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Other more&nbsp;<strong>specialized</strong>&nbsp;forms of&nbsp;<strong>imaging,</strong>&nbsp;such as ultrasound, computerized tomography, angiography, and diagnostic peritoneal lavage, should be considered after the&nbsp;<strong>secondary survey</strong>&nbsp;and only when the patient is&nbsp;<strong>stable after initial resuscitation.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1879, 'Surgery', 'PM2504. Two-level deep vein thrombosis (DVT) Wells score', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table width=\508\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Clinical features</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Points</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Active cancer (treatment ongoing within 6 months or palliative)</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>paralysis, paresis, or recent plaster immobilization of the lower extremities&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Recently bed ridden for 3 days or more or major surgery within 12 weeks requiring general or regional anaesthesia&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Localised tenderness along the distribution of deep venous system</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Entire leg swollen</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>calf swelling atleast 3 cm larger than asymptomatic side&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pitting edema confined to the symptomatic leg</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Collateral superficial veins (Non varicose)</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Previously documented DVT</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>An alternative diagnosis is atleast as likely as DVT</td>\n<td>-2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Clinical probability simplified score</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Points</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DVT Likely</td>\n<td>2 points or more</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DVT Unlikely&nbsp;</td>\n<td>1 points or less&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1880, 'Surgery', 'PM1968. Pancreas - Most Commons', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>M/C cause of <strong>acute</strong> pancreatitis: Gallstones</p>\n<p>M/C cause of <strong>chronic </strong>pancreatitis: Alcohol</p>\n<p>M/C cause of <strong>chronic</strong> pancreatitis <strong>in children</strong>: Cystic fibrosis</p>\n<p>M/C cause of <strong>pancreatic calcification</strong>: Alcohol</p>\n<p>M/C <strong>congenital</strong> variant: Pancreas divisum</p>\n<p>M/C site of <strong>thrombosis</strong> in <strong>chronic</strong> pancreatitis: Splenic vein&nbsp;</p>\n<p>M/C site of <strong>pseudoaneurysm</strong> in <strong>chronic</strong> pancreatitis: Splenic artery&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1881, 'Surgery', 'PM1649. Surgical procedures for chronic pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Duval procedure:</strong> Distal pancreatectomy with Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/6db05009daf44dd486f989ee8dd8c275x1280x1971.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Puestow procedure: </strong>Resection of tail followed by longitudinal pancreaticojejunostomy</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/c3679bb15aee4f2985f0f23302681a84x1280x1966.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Partington and Rochelle modification of Puestow procedure: </strong>Elimination of resection of the pancreatic tail</p>\n<p>A <strong>longitudinal pancreatotomy</strong>&nbsp;shows&nbsp;<strong>segmental stenosis</strong> of the pancreatic duct and the presence of intraductal calculi in a patient with chronic<strong> calcific </strong>pancreatitis<strong>.&nbsp;</strong>Following mobilization of a Roux limb of the jejunum, a <strong>longitudinal pancreaticojejunostomy</strong> is performed to permit extensive drainage of the pancreatic duct system.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/ff11f76c414b445cb95de206adeab5e1x1280x2335.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1882, 'Surgery', 'PM1647. Resection and Hybrid Surgical Procedures for Chronic Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Beger’s procedure: Duodenum-preserving pancreatic head resection (DPPHR)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The completed resection after <strong>transection of the pancreatic neck and subtotal removal of the pancreatic head,</strong> with <strong>preservation of the distal common bile duct and duodenum (Marked A).</strong></li>\n<li>Completion of the reconstruction of the anastomosis to the distal pancreas and to the proximal pancreatic rim by the same Roux limb of the jejunum.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/15f8041170e141ac85eacb95bdf7511ax356x333.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/c37ecdf4dc964e78aebbc6c7fcbdae4bx373x307.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Frey’s procedure:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>local resection of the pancreatic head</strong> with <strong>longitudinal pancreaticojejunostomy (LR-LPJ)</strong> provides complete decompression of the entire pancreatic ductal system. Reconstruction is performed with a <strong>side-to-side Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy.</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/bbf335e03bfb4f64b431288b5a21f580x819x674.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Warren’s modification of Beger’s procedure:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Berne modification (Beger + Frey)&nbsp;</strong>involves excavation of the central portion of the head without formal division of the neck.</p>\n<p>(image below)</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/8530a422baf14d83a64364457f218197x422x497.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Hamburg modification of Frey’s procedure</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/7ebc00f0c14949269afefb8493648225x479x418.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Note:</strong></p>\n<p>Surgical treatments for chronic pancreatitis</p>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1207\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Resection</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pancreaticoduodenectomy (Kausch–Whipple procedure)</li>\n<li>Pylorus-preserving pancreaticoduodenectomy (Traverso–Longmire)</li>\n<li>Beger procedure</li>\n<li>Near-total or total pancreatectomy</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Decompression/Drainage</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Duval procedure</li>\n<li>Puestow–Gillesby procedure</li>\n<li>Partington–Rochelle procedure (Puestow)</li>\n<li>Izbicki procedure</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Hybrid (resection+decompression)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Frey procedure</li>\n<li>Hamburg modification</li>\n<li>Berne modification</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1883, 'Surgery', 'PM1645. Chronic pancreatitis and pancreatic exocrine insufficiency: TIGAR-O classification system', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Toxic-metabolic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Alcoholic</li>\n<li>Tobacco smoking</li>\n<li>Hypercalcemia</li>\n<li>Hyperlipidemia</li>\n<li>Chronic renal failure</li>\n<li>Medications—phenacetin abuse</li>\n<li>Toxins—organotin compounds (e.g., dibutyltin dichloride, DBTC)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Idiopathic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Early onset</li>\n<li>Late onset</li>\n<li>Tropical</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Genetic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cationic trypsinogen (<em><strong>PRSS1</strong></em>)</li>\n<li>Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene (<em><strong>CFTR</strong></em>)</li>\n<li>Calcium-sensing receptor (<em><strong>CASR</strong></em>)</li>\n<li>Chymotrypsin C gene (<em><strong>CTRC</strong></em>)</li>\n<li>Pancreatic secretory trypsin inhibitor gene (<em><strong>SPINK1</strong></em>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Autoimmune</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Type 1 autoimmune chronic pancreatitis</li>\n<li>IgG4 systemic</li>\n<li>Type 2 autoimmune chronic pancreatitis</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Recurrent and severe acute pancreatitis</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Postnecrotic (severe acute pancreatitis)</li>\n<li>Recurrent acute pancreatitis</li>\n<li>Vascular diseases/ischemia</li>\n<li>Radiation-induced</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Obstructive</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pancreas divisum</li>\n<li>Duct obstruction (e.g., tumor)</li>\n<li>Periampullary duodenal wall cysts</li>\n<li>Posttraumatic pancreatic duct scars</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1884, 'Surgery', 'PM1644. Rosemont’s criteria for the diagnosis of chronic pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Parenchymal features</td>\n<td>Ductal features</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Major criteria</td>\n<td><strong>Major A criteria:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Hyperechoic foci with post-acoustic shadowing</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Major B criteria:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Honeycombing lobularity</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Major A criteria:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Main pancreatic duct calculi</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Minor criteria</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Hyperechoic, non-shadowing foci ≥3 mm in length and width</li>\n<li>Lobularity including three or more noncontiguous lobules in the body or tail</li>\n<li>Pancreatic cysts ≥2 mm in short axis</li>\n<li>At least three strands*</li>\n</ul>\n<p><sup>&nbsp;&nbsp; *</sup>Strands are defined as hyperechoic lines ≥3 mm in length seen in at least two different directions in the body or tail of the pancreas.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Irregular main pancreatic duct (MPD) contour</li>\n<li>Dilated side branches<sup>+</sup></li>\n<li>Main pancreatic duct dilation (≥3.5 mm in the body or ≥1.5 mm in the tail)</li>\n<li>Hyperechoic MPD margin &gt;50% of the main pancreatic duct in the body and tail.</li>\n</ul>\n<br>&nbsp;<sup>+</sup>≥3 tubular anechoic structures, each one ≥1 mm in width, budding from MPD</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td colspan=\2\>Diagnosis of Chronic Pancreatitis:<br>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Consistent with chronic pancreatitis</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>1 major A criterion + ≥3 minor criteria</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>1 major A criterion + major B criterion</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>2 major A criteria</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Suggestive of chronic pancreatitis (requires imaging for confirmation)</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>1 major A criterion + &lt;3 minor criteria</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>1 major B criterion + ≥3 minor criteria</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>≥5 minor criteria</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Indeterminate for chronic pancreatitis (requires imaging for confirmation)</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>3-4 minor criteria in the absence of major criteria</li>\n<li aria-level=\2\>Major B criterion + &lt;3 minor criteria</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>&nbsp;Normal</li>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\2\>&lt;3 minor criteria</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1885, 'Surgery', 'PM1641. Clinical Features of Chronic Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Abdominal pain</strong>: <strong>most common symptom</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Site:\n<ul>\n<li>If infectious foci are in the <strong>head of the pancreas</strong>, then <strong>epigastric and right subcostal pain</strong> is common;</li>\n<li>If the infection is limited to the <strong>left side of the pancreas, left subcostal and back pain</strong> are seen.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Precipitated by food intake, thus <strong>weight loss </strong>is also seen.</li>\n<li>Associated with nausea, vomiting</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Exocrine insufficiency:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Precedes endocrine insufficiency</strong></li>\n<li>Correlates with morphological changes</li>\n<li>Manifests with <strong>malabsorption symptoms</strong>: steatorrhea, diarrhea.</li>\n<li>Manifests with signs and symptoms of <strong>fat-soluble vitamin deficiency, </strong>such as <strong>bleeding, osteopenia, and osteoporosis: </strong>Severe cases</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Endocrine insufficiency: Diabetes mellitus</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1886, 'Surgery', 'PM1640. Pancreatic necrosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Presence of nonviable pancreatic paren­chyma or peripancreatic fat</li>\n<li>20% of patients with AP</li>\n<li>Suspected in patients with prolonged fever, elevated white blood cell count, or progres­sive clinical deterioration</li>\n<li><strong>CECT – investigation of choice</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Low attenuation areas and presence of <strong>air in parenchyma</strong> (diagnostic feature)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Most common complication is the <strong>infection</strong> (proportional to the amount of necrosis) – usually by <strong>translocation of gut bacteria</strong> and subsequent <strong>multi-organ failure.</strong></li>\n<li>Treatment:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>IV antibiotics – carbapenems</strong> are the first option of treatment because of good penetration into the pancreas and spec­trum coverage. Alternative therapy includes quinolones, metronidazole, third-generation cephalosporins, and piperacillin.</li>\n<li>Definitive treatment of infected pancreatic necrosis is surgical <strong>debridement with necrosectomy, closed con­tinuous irrigation, or open packaging.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1887, 'Surgery', 'PM1639. Vascular complications of pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Arterial pseudoaneurysm:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is caused by damage to the vessel wall by <strong>pancreatic elastase</strong></li>\n<li>The most common vessel affected is <strong>the splenic artery</strong>, but the superior mesenteric artery (SMA), cystic artery, and&nbsp;gastroduodenal artery (GDA) may also be affected</li>\n<li><strong>Spontaneous rupture</strong> results in <strong>massive bleeding</strong></li>\n<li>Clinical manifestations include sudden onset of abdominal pain, tachycardia, and hypotension.</li>\n<li><strong>CT angiography</strong> is the investigation of choice</li>\n<li>Treatment\n<ul>\n<li>Arterial embolization</li>\n<li>Ligation of the affected vessel in refrac­tory cases</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Vascular thrombosis:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The vessel usually affected is the <strong>splenic vein</strong>, but in severe cases, it can extend into the portal venous system</li>\n<li>Clinical features include splenomegaly, gastric varices, and splenic vein occlusion</li>\n<li>Treatment:\n<ul>\n<li>Mostly conservative</li>\n<li>Throm­bolytics in the acute early phase</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1888, 'Surgery', 'PM1636. SOFA and qSOFA Scores', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Sepsis</strong>&nbsp;is defined as a state of&nbsp;<strong>life-threatening organ dysfunction</strong>&nbsp;that occurs&nbsp;<strong>due to</strong>&nbsp;an unregulated host&nbsp;<strong>immune response to an infection</strong>. To objectively define the beginning of organ dysfunction, <strong>sequential organ failure assessment (SOFA) scoring</strong> is used. The variables in the SOFA score include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\><strong>Circulation</strong>&nbsp;- Systolic BP &amp; need for vasopressors and platelet count</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\><strong>Respiration</strong>&nbsp;- PaO2/FiO2 &amp; need for mechanical ventilation</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\><strong>Mentation</strong>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<strong>Glasgow coma score </strong>(GCS)</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\><strong>Hepatic function</strong>&nbsp;-<strong>&nbsp;Bilirubin</strong></span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\><strong>Renal function</strong>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<strong>Creatinine</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\6\>Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (SOFA) score</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Cardiovascular</strong></p>\n<p>Hypotension</p>\n</td>\n<td>No hypotension</td>\n<td>\n<p>MAP &lt;70 mmHg</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Dopamine <span>&lt;</span>5 or <span>epi/norepi ≤0.1¤&nbsp;</span></p>\n</td>\n<td>Dopamine &gt;5 or epi/norepi ≤0.1¤</td>\n<td>Dopamine &gt;15 or epi/norepi &gt;0.1¤&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Coagulation</strong></p>\n<p>Platelets (×10<sup>3</sup> per&nbsp;μL)</p>\n</td>\n<td>&gt;150</td>\n<td>≤150</td>\n<td>≤100</td>\n<td>≤50</td>\n<td>&nbsp;≤20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Respiration</strong></p>\n<p>(PaO<sub>2/</sub>FIO<sub>2</sub>) (mm Hg)</p>\n</td>\n<td>&gt;400</td>\n<td>≤400</td>\n<td>≤300</td>\n<td>≤200 with respiratory support</td>\n<td>≤100 with respiratory support</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Mentation</strong></p>\n<p>GCS</p>\n</td>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>13–14</td>\n<td>10–12</td>\n<td>6–9</td>\n<td>&lt;6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Liver</strong></p>\n<p>Bilirubin(μmol/L)</p>\n</td>\n<td>&lt;20</td>\n<td>20–32</td>\n<td>33–101</td>\n<td>102–204</td>\n<td>&gt;204</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Kidney</strong></p>\n<p>Creatinine (μmol/L) or urine output</p>\n</td>\n<td>&lt;110</td>\n<td>110–170</td>\n<td>171–299</td>\n<td>300–440 or &lt;500 mL/day</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt;440 or &lt;200 mL/day</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\6\>\n<p><strong>MAP =&nbsp;</strong>mean arterial pressure. <strong>Epi</strong> = epinephrine. <strong>Nonrepi</strong> = norepinephrine.&nbsp;<strong>¤ = </strong>Adrenergic agents administered for at least 1 h (doses in&nbsp;μg/kg per min).</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p class=\p1\>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\p1\><strong><span class=\s1\>Organ dysfunction</span></strong><span class=\s2\>&nbsp;is identified by a&nbsp;</span><strong><span class=\s1\>SOFA score of&nbsp;≥ 2</span></strong></p>\n<p class=\p1\><span class=\s2\>A<strong>&nbsp;simplified</strong> version, recommended by the Sepsis 3 taskforce, is known as the </span><span class=\s1\><strong>quick sepsis-related organ dysfunction assessment \qSOFA\ score</strong>.&nbsp;</span><span class=\s2\>It includes:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\>Systolic BP ≤100 mmHg</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\>Respiratory rate ≥ 22/min</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\>Altered mentation/sensorium</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\p2\><span class=\s3\>Each criterion carries 1 point. A&nbsp;</span><strong><span class=\s4\>qSOFA score of ≥ 2</span></strong><span class=\s3\>&nbsp;is associated with&nbsp;</span><span class=\s4\><strong>increased mortality</strong>&nbsp;due to sepsis</span><span class=\s3\>.</span></p>\n<p class=\p1\><strong><span class=\s1\>SOFA vs qSOFA:</span></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p3\><strong><span class=\s4\>SOFA</span></strong><span class=\s3\>&nbsp;is a more&nbsp;<strong>comprehensive</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>accurate</strong>&nbsp;scoring system that is&nbsp;</span><span class=\s4\>particularly superior to&nbsp;qSOFA in the&nbsp;<strong>ICU setting.</strong></span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><strong><span class=\s4\>qSOFA</span></strong><span class=\s3\>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<strong>simplified</strong>&nbsp;derivative of SOFA for&nbsp;<strong>bedside</strong>&nbsp;assessment that is&nbsp;</span><span class=\s4\>particularly useful&nbsp;<strong>outside the ICU setting</strong></span><span class=\s3\>&nbsp;(i.e. ward/emergency department).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\p2\><span class=\s3\>Thereby, the best description of&nbsp;<strong>sepsis</strong>&nbsp;would be :</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\>Suspected or documented infection with&nbsp;<strong>SOFA score ≥ 2</strong><br>OR</span></li>\n<li class=\p3\><span class=\s3\>Suspected or documented infection with&nbsp;<strong>qSOFA score ≥ 2</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\s3\>However, note that these scores were originally designed as a&nbsp;<strong>predictive tool</strong>&nbsp;that calculates the&nbsp;<strong>risk of death from sepsis</strong>&nbsp;rather than a diagnostic tool.</span></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1889, 'Surgery', 'PM1635. Computed Tomography Severity Index (CTSI)/Balthazar Scoring for Acute Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\><strong>Balthazar Score</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Balthazar Grade</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Appearance on CT</strong></td>\n<td><strong>CT Grade Points</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Grade A</td>\n<td>Normal CT</td>\n<td>0 Points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Grade B</td>\n<td>Focal or diffuse enlargement of the pancreas</td>\n<td>1 Point</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Grade C</td>\n<td>Pancreatic gland abnormalities and peripancreatic inflammation&nbsp;</td>\n<td>2 Points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Grade D&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Fluid collection in a single location</td>\n<td>3 Points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Grade E</td>\n<td>Two or more sites of fluid collection and/ or gas bubbles in, or adjacent to, the pancreas</td>\n<td>4 Points</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\><strong>Necrosis Score</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Necrosis Percentage</td>\n<td>CT grade points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>No necrosis</td>\n<td>0 points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>0 to 30% necrosis</td>\n<td>2 points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>30 to 50% necrosis</td>\n<td>4 points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Over 50% necrosis</td>\n<td>6 points</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<p>The numerical Computed Tomography Severity Index (CTSI) has a <strong>maximum of 10&nbsp;points</strong>, and<strong>&nbsp;</strong>it is the <strong>sum</strong> of the Balthazar grade points and pancreatic necrosis grade points.&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>CTSI score 0-3: Mild pancreatitis</p>\n<p>CTSI score 4-6: Moderate pancreatitis</p>\n<p>CTSI score 7-10: Severe pancreatitis</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1890, 'Surgery', 'PM1632. Assessment of severity of acute pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Bedside Index for Severity of Acute Pancreatitis (BISAP) </strong>includes:\n<ul>\n<li>Blood urea nitrogen, &gt; 25 mg/dL</li>\n<li>Impaired mental status, Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) score &lt;15</li>\n<li>Systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS)</li>\n<li>Age &gt; 60 years</li>\n<li>Pleural effusion<br>One point is given for each.&nbsp;BISAP score&nbsp;≥ 3 indicates severe pancreatitis.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Harmless Acute Pancreatitis Score (HAPS)</strong><br>If all the following are present then it is considered non-severe, i.e., no death, no need for dialysis, and no need for ventilation:\n<ul>\n<li>Absence of rebound tenderness or guarding</li>\n<li>Normal hematocrit</li>\n<li>Normal serum creatinine<br><br></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Acute Physiology and Chronic Health Evaluation (APACHE II</strong><strong>) </strong>\n<ul>\n<li>A score of 8 or more is considered to be severe</li>\n<li>Can be done at admission and repeated any time</li>\n<li>Complex, not specific for AP, and based on the patient’s age</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ranson’s score</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Modified Glasgow criteria -&nbsp;</strong>3 or more positive criteria, the disease is considered to be&nbsp;<strong>severe</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Atlanta classification</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1891, 'Surgery', 'PM1627. Laboratory Findings in Acute Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Elevated serum amylase and serum lipase</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Serum amylase level rises immediately and peaks in few hours and returns to normal in 3–5 days</li>\n<li>Serum amylase level&nbsp;<strong>lacks specificity</strong></li>\n<li>Serum amylase levels do not correlate with the severity of pancreatitis.</li>\n<li><strong>Serum lipase </strong>is<strong> more specific,</strong> and it is more useful when the&nbsp;patient presents <strong>24–48 hours later</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Hyperglycemia</li>\n<li><strong>Hypocalcemia</strong>, hypoalbuminemia</li>\n<li>Leukocytosis</li>\n<li>Elevated serum levels of hepatic enzymes like alanine aminotransferase (ALT)</li>\n<li>Azotemia, due to prerenal acute renal failure in case of severe fluid loss</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1892, 'Surgery', 'PM1626. Clinical Features of Acute Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Symptoms:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Acute onset of <strong>epigastric pain</strong>, which is <strong>severe, constant, and refractory</strong> to usual doses of analgesics.</li>\n<li>Typically <strong>radiates to back</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Relieved in the sitting forward position</strong></li>\n<li>Nausea, repeated vomiting, retching, and hiccups</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Signs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hypotension, tachycardia, and tachypnea</li>\n<li><strong>Grey Turner sign (A):</strong> Bluish discoloration of the&nbsp;<strong>flanks</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Cullen’s sign (B):</strong> Bluish discoloration around the&nbsp;<strong>umbilicus</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Fox sign:</strong> Discolouration <strong>below the inguinal ligament</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Pleural effusion (left &gt; right): Dullness on percussion, decreased breath sounds</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/78928c54b3b64e26b96c46fe256cdb41x720x378.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/1cf4b407b97446da85893885a52395bfx561x364.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1893, 'Surgery', 'PM1625. Causes of Acute Pancreatitis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Common causes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Gallstones - most common</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Alcohol</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Post-ERCP </strong>(Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography)</li>\n<li>Blunt trauma, abdomen</li>\n<li>Post-operative (cardiothoracic, upper gastrointestinal, biliary)</li>\n<li>Hypertriglyceridemia</li>\n<li>Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Uncommon causes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hyperparathyroidism</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Hypercalcemia</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Deficiency of apolipoprotein CII</strong></li>\n<li>Pancreas divisum</li>\n<li>Periampullary diverticulum</li>\n<li>Vasculitis</li>\n<li>Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP)</li>\n<li>Connective tissue disorders</li>\n<li>Ischemic–hypoperfusion states</li>\n<li>Hereditary pancreatitis</li>\n<li>Cystic fibrosis</li>\n<li>Renal failure</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Drugs</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>L-Asparaginase</li>\n<li>Steroids</li>\n<li>Sulfonamides</li>\n<li>Tetracycline</li>\n<li>Valproate</li>\n<li>Azathioprine</li>\n<li>Anti-retroviral drugs</li>\n<li>Estrogens</li>\n<li>Thiazide diuretics</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Rare causes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Autoimmune</strong></li>\n<li>Infections (mumps, coxsackie B, cytomegalovirus, parasite)</li>\n<li>Malnutrition</li>\n<li>Scorpion bite</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1894, 'Surgery', 'PM1606. Serous cystadenoma of the pancreas', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Benign</strong> with no chances of malignancy.</p>\n<p>Commonly in <strong>females</strong>&nbsp;(female to male ratio - 2:1), older age group</p>\n<p>The site of occurrence of&nbsp;Serous cystadenoma is <strong>uniformly distributed</strong> across the pancreas.</p>\n<p>Gross and microscopic appearance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Microcysts giving a <strong>honey-comb appearance</strong></li>\n<li>Glycogen-rich cells</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Computed tomography (CT) findings: <strong>Central calcification</strong>, with radiating septa giving the <strong>sunburst appearance.</strong></p>\n<p>Fluid analysis: mucin negative, low serum levels of carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) and amylase.</p>\n<p>Treatment: Mainly conservative</p>\n<p>Resection: If symptomatic or if malignancy is suspected</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1895, 'Surgery', 'PM1605. Cystic Neoplasm of the Pancreas', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Characteristics</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Serous Cystadenoma</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Mucinous Cystadenoma</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nature</td>\n<td>Benign</td>\n<td>Benign, but high risk of malignancy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Epidemiology</td>\n<td>Common in females (F:M = 2:1) and older age&nbsp;<br>Associated with von Hippel Lindau syndrome&nbsp;</td>\n<td>Most common cystic neoplasm of the pancreas&nbsp;<br>Common in perimenopausal females</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Usual site</td>\n<td>\n<p>Usually tail of the pancreas, can be uniformly distributed</p>\n</td>\n<td>Body and tail of the pancreas</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Microscopy</td>\n<td>Microcysts giving a honey-comb appearance Glycogen-rich cells</td>\n<td>Mucin-producing epithelium<br>Ovarian-like stroma<br>Stains positive for estrogen and progesterone</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CT</td>\n<td>Central calcification, with radiating septa giving sunburst appearance.</td>\n<td>\n<p>Solitary cyst with fine septations, surrounded by a rim of calcification.</p>\n<p>Eggshell calcification, large tumor size, or a mural nodule are suggestive of malignancy</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cyst fluid analysis</td>\n<td>\n<p>Mucin negative</p>\n<p>Low CEA and amylase</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Mucin-rich aspirate</p>\n<p>High CEA and low amylase</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Treatment</td>\n<td>\n<p>Mainly conservative</p>\n<p>Resection: If symptomatic or if malignancy is suspected</p>\n</td>\n<td>Resection (because of risk of malignancy)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Prognosis</td>\n<td>\n<p>Good</p>\n</td>\n<td>Poor</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1896, 'Surgery', 'PM1375. Clinical features of glucaganoma: 4Ds', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Diabetes – </strong>usually mild and not associated with ketoacidosis</li>\n<li><strong>Dermatitis – </strong>Necrolytic erythema migrans</li>\n<li><strong>Deep vein thrombosis</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Depression</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1897, 'Surgery', 'PM1370. Whipples Triad', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Whipple’s triad </strong>describes the clinical symptoms<strong> of insulinoma.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Symptoms of<strong> hypoglycemia after fasting or exercise</strong></li>\n<li>Plasma glucose levels<strong> &lt;2.8 mmol/L or 50 mg/dL.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Relief</strong> of symptoms after&nbsp;<strong>intravenous administration of glucose</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1898, 'Surgery', 'PM1745. Neurological Impairment Examination', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The Medical Research Council (MRC) grading of muscle power</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Grading </strong></td>\n<td><strong>Description </strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>No movement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Flicker of movements</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Active movement with gravity elimination</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Active movement against gravity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Active movement against resistance but power less than full</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Normal power</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The ASIA (American Spinal Injury Association) neurological impairment scale:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Impairment scale </strong></td>\n<td><strong>Description </strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>A</td>\n<td>Complete impairment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>B</td>\n<td>Sensation present, motor absent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>C</td>\n<td>Sensation present, motor present, but not useful (MRC grade less than 3/5)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>D</td>\n<td>Sensation present, motor useful (MRC grade more than equal to 3/5)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>E</td>\n<td>Normal functions</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1899, 'Surgery', 'PM1304. Psammoma Bodies', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Psammoma bodies are visible in the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Meningioma</li>\n<li>Serous cystadenocarcinoma Ovary</li>\n<li>Papillary carcinoma thyroid.</li>\n<li>Papillary type of renal cell carcinoma</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1900, 'Surgery', 'PM0343. Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\ng-scope\>\n<p><strong>GCS Score</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\ng-binding ng-scope\>13-15 represent mild injury</li>\n<li>9-12 represent moderate injury</li>\n<li>Scores ≤8 represent severe injury </li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\ng-scope\>\n<p><strong>Head Injury Severity: Clinical classification</strong>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<table border=\1\ width=\253\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Eyes Opening</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Score</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Spontaneously</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>To verbal command</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>To painful stimulus</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Do not open</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 163\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Non-testable</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>NT</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table border=\1\ width=\250\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Verbal response</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Score</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Normal-oriented conversation</td>\n<td>5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Confused</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Inappropriate words only</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sounds only</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>No sounds</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 163\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Non-testable</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>NT</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table border=\1\ width=\242\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Motor Response</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Score</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Obeys commands</td>\n<td>6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Localizes to pain</td>\n<td>5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Withdrawal/flexion</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Abnormal flexion/Decorticate posturing&nbsp;</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Extension/Decerebrate posturing&nbsp;</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>No motor response</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 163\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Non-testable</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>NT</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Minimum value: </strong>3</p>\n<p><strong>Maximum value:</strong> 15</p>\n<ul>\n<li>GCS, in particular, the <strong>motor score</strong>, is the <strong>best predictor of neurological outcome.</strong></li>\n<li>If an area cannot be assessed, no numerical score is given for that region, and it is considered “non-testable.\ (NT)</li>\n<li>In case of <strong>endotracheal intubation or tracheostomy</strong>, the verbal component of the score is <strong>denoted as NT</strong>.</li>\n<li>A score of&nbsp; ‘1’ is not recorded in missing components, instead, NT is used</li>\n<li>when a component is Not Testable, a total score is not recorded because the score will be low and this could be confusing to medical colleagues. This may also imply that the patient is more unwell than they actually are.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 163\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>NOTE:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>A new parameter, \pupil reactivity score\ has been added to GCS, and now, it is referred to as GCS-P.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>P stands for \Pupils unreactive to light\</p>\n<table border=\1\ width=\160\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pupils unreactive to light</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Score</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Both pupils</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>One pupil</td>\n<td>1&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Neither</td>\n<td>&nbsp;0</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>The pupillary score is subtracted</strong> from the GCS score to give the final value. Therefore, the range of GCS-P is 1–15.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The minimum frequency of observations for patients with GCS equal to 15 should be as follows, starting after the initial assessment in the emergency department:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\p-rich_text_section\>Half-hourly for 2 hours,</li>\n<li class=\p-rich_text_section\>Then 1-hourly for 4 hours,</li>\n<li class=\p-rich_text_section\>2-hourly thereafter.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Should the patient with GCS equal to 15 deteriorate at any time after the initial 2-hour period, observations should revert to half-hourly and follow the original frequency schedule.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1901, 'Surgery', 'PM1809. Thyroid Malignancy - Most Commons', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Most common<strong> primary</strong> thyroid malignancy – Papillary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common thyroid malignancy associated with<strong> radiation</strong> - Papillary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common malignancy of thyroid associated with<strong> lymphatic spread</strong> – Papillary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common thyroid malignancy associated with <strong>blood and bone metastasis</strong> – Follicular carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common thyroid malignancy in <strong>iodine sufficient areas</strong> – Papillary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common thyroid malignancy in <strong>iodine deficient areas</strong> – Follicular carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most common thyroid malignancy associated with <strong>Multi Nodular Goiter</strong>&nbsp;- Follicular carcinoma</li>\n<li>Thyroid malignancy associated with<strong> amyloid</strong> - Medullary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Thyroid malignancy associated with <strong>MEN 2 syndrome</strong> - Medullary carcinoma</li>\n<li>Most aggressive thyroid malignancy with <strong>worst prognosis</strong> - Anaplastic carcinoma</li>\n<li>Thyroid malignancy with <strong>best prognosis</strong> - Papillary carcinoma</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1902, 'Surgery', 'PM1748. AJCC 8th edition Changes in the TNM staging of Thyroid neoplasms:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Differentiated Thyroid Cancer:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>age</strong> <strong>cutoff</strong> used for staging is increased from 45 to <strong>55 years</strong> of age at diagnosis.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Minor extrathyroidal extension</strong> detected only on histological examination is <strong>removed from the definition of T3</strong> disease and therefore has no impact on either T category or overall stage.</li>\n<li>N1 disease no longer upstages a patient to stage III. If<strong> &lt; 55 years</strong> of age at diagnosis, <strong>N1 disease is stage I</strong>. If <strong>≥ 55 years</strong> of age, <strong>N1 disease is stage II.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>T3a</strong> is a new category for tumors <strong>&gt; 4 cm confined to the thyroid gland</strong></li>\n<li><strong>T3b</strong> is a new category for tumors of any size demonstrating<strong> gross extrathyroidal extension into strap muscles</strong> (sternohyoid, sternothyroid, thyrohyoid or omohyoid muscles)</li>\n<li><strong>Level VII</strong> lymph nodes, previously classified as lateral neck lymph nodes (N1b) is re-classified as central neck lymph nodes <strong>(N1a)</strong> to be more anatomically consistent and because level VII presented significant coding difficulties for tumor registrars, clinicians and researchers.</li>\n<li>In differentiated thyroid cancer, the presence of <strong>distant metastases</strong> <strong>(M1)</strong> in older patients is classified as <strong>IVB</strong> disease rather than IVC disease. Distant metastasis in anaplastic thyroid cancer continues to be classified as IVC disease.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>TNM staging</td>\n<td>7th AJCC (2010)</td>\n<td><strong>8th AJCC (2018)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Primary tumor(pT)</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TX</td>\n<td>Cannot be assessed</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T0</td>\n<td>No evidence of cancer</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T1</td>\n<td>Tumor ≤ 2 cm, intrathyroidal\n<ul>\n<li>T1a:&nbsp;≤1 cm, intrathyroidal</li>\n<li>T1b<strong>:</strong>&nbsp;1-2 cm, intrathyroidal</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T2</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>2-4 cm, intrathyroidal</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T3</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>&gt;4 cm limited to the thyroid or any size with minimal extrathyroidal extension (muscle, soft tissue)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td><br>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>T3a:&nbsp;</strong>Tumor <strong>&gt;4 cm limited to the thyroid</strong></li>\n<li><strong>T3b:&nbsp;Gross extrathyroidal extension</strong> invading only <strong>strap muscles</strong> (sternohyoid, sternothyroid, thyrohyoid or omohyoid muscles) from a tumor of any size</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>T4</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>T4a Invades subcutaneous tissue, larynx, trachea, esophagus, or RLN</li>\n<li>T4b Invades prevertebral fascia or encases carotid or mediastinal vessels</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>-do-<br><br></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Regional lymph nodes (pN)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>NX</td>\n<td>Regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N0</td>\n<td>No lymph node metastasis</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N1a</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Positive in level VI; unilateral or bilateral disease</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Metastasis to level VI or VII;&nbsp;</strong>unilateral or bilateral disease</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>N1b</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 927\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Metastasis to unilateral, bilateral or contralateral lateral neck lymph nodes (levels I, II, III, IV or V) or retropharyngeal lymph nodes</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>-do-<br><br></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Distant metastasis (pM)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>M0</td>\n<td>No Distant metastasis</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>M1</td>\n<td>Distant metastasis present</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>TNM classification of thyroid tumors according to AJCC 7<sup>th</sup> edition vs 8<sup>th</sup> edition:</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; TNM CLASSIFICATION of Thyroid tumors</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>PAPILLARY OR FOLLICULAR TUMORS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage</td>\n<td>TNM&nbsp;AJCC 7<sup>th</sup> edition</td>\n<td><strong>TNM AJCC 8<sup>th</sup> edition</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&lt;45 y</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>&lt;55 y</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>I</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Any T, any N, M0</td>\n<td>&nbsp;-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>II</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Any T, any N, M1</td>\n<td>&nbsp;-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;≥45 y</td>\n<td><strong>&nbsp;&gt;55 y</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>I</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T1, N0, M0</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>T1-2</strong>, N0, M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>II</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T2, N0, M0</td>\n<td>\n<p>&nbsp;T1-2, <strong>N1</strong>, M0</p>\n<p><strong>T3</strong>, <strong>any N</strong>, M0</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>III</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1572\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>T3, N0, M0</p>\n<p>T1–3, N1a, M0</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td><strong>T4a, any N</strong>, M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV A</td>\n<td>\n<p>T4a, N0-1a, M0</p>\n<p>T1-4a, N1b, M0</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>T4b, any N</strong>, M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;IV B</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T4b, any N, M0</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>any T, any N, M1&nbsp;</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>IV C</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Any T, any N, M1</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>- deleted-</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>MEDULLARY THYROID CANCER&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage</td>\n<td>TNM&nbsp;AJCC 7<sup>th</sup> edition</td>\n<td><strong>TNM AJCC 8<sup>th</sup> edition</strong>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>I</td>\n<td>T1, N0, M0</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>II</td>\n<td>T2–3, N0, M0</td>\n<td>-do- &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>III</td>\n<td>T1–3, N1a, M0</td>\n<td>-do-&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV A</td>\n<td>\n<p>T4a, any N, M0;</p>\n<p>T1-3, N1b, M0&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV B</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T4b, any N, M0</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV C</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Any T, any N, M1</td>\n<td>-do-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Anaplastic :</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Unlike previous editions where all anaplastic thyroid cancers were classified as T4 disease, anaplastic cancers now use the<strong> same T&nbsp; definitions as differentiated thyroid cancer</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Intrathyroidal disease</strong> (<strong>T1-3a)</strong> is stage <strong>IVA</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Gross extrathyroidal extension</strong>(<strong>T3b,T4)</strong> or <strong>cervical lymph node metastases (N1)</strong> is stage <strong>IVB</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Distant metastases</strong> <strong>(M1)</strong> are stage <strong>IVC</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<p>ANAPLASTIC CANCER</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Stage</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>TNM&nbsp;AJCC 7<sup>th</sup> edition</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>TNM AJCC 8<sup>th</sup>edition</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>IV A</p>\n</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T4a, Any N, M0</td>\n<td>&nbsp;<strong>T1-3a, N0,</strong> M0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;IV B</td>\n<td>&nbsp;T4b, Any N, M0</td>\n<td>\n<p>T1-3a, <strong>N1</strong>, M0;</p>\n<p><strong>T3b</strong>, Any N, M0;</p>\n<p><strong>T4</strong>, Any N, M0</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IV C</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Any T, Any N, M1</td>\n<td>&nbsp;-do-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1903, 'Surgery', 'PM1693. Types of Neck Dissections', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dissection</strong></td>\n<td><strong>LN removed</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Other structures removed/preserved</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>RND</strong></td>\n<td>l-V</td>\n<td>CNXI, IJV, SCM removed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>MRND l</strong></td>\n<td>l-V</td>\n<td>CNXI preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>MRND ll</strong></td>\n<td>l-V</td>\n<td>CNXI, IJV preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>MRND lll</strong></td>\n<td>l-V</td>\n<td>CNXI, IJV, SCM preserved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>END</strong></td>\n<td>l-V</td>\n<td>CNXI, IJV, SCM removed+ one/more LN groups +/- non-lymphatic structures</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SND</strong></td>\n<td><strong>LN removed</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Primary site of cancer</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Supra-omohyoid</strong></td>\n<td>l-lll</td>\n<td>Oral cavity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Extended supra-omohyoid</strong></td>\n<td>l-lV</td>\n<td>Oral cavity and oropharynx</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Postero-lateral</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>ll-V</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Skin over posterior scalp and upper neck</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lateral</strong></td>\n<td>ll-lV</td>\n<td>\n<p>Oropharynx, hypopharynx,&nbsp;larynx</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Anterior(Central)</strong></td>\n<td>Vl</td>\n<td>Thyroid/midline structures</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>RND- Radical Neck Dissection; MRND- Modified Radical Neck Dissection; END- Extended&nbsp;Neck Dissection; SND- Selective&nbsp;Neck Dissection</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1904, 'Surgery', 'PM1692. Lip reconstruction flaps', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Up to <strong>half of the lip</strong> can be removed and closed primarily.</li>\n<li>Defects encompassing between <strong>one half and two-thirds</strong> of the lip require <strong>augmentation</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Karapandzic flap</strong> consists of circumoral incisions with the circular rotation of the skin flaps while <strong>maintaining innervation</strong>.</li>\n<li>When the defect involves the <strong>commissure</strong>, the <strong>Estlander flap </strong>is used, and the&nbsp;<strong>Abbé flap</strong> is used for more <strong>midline defects</strong>.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1905, 'Surgery', 'PM1689. Salivary gland tumors and their frequency', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Most (90%) of the <strong>minor salivary gland</strong> tumors are <strong>malignant</strong>, whereas <strong>parotid gland tumors (90%)</strong> are <strong>benign</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Pleomorphic adenoma</strong> is the <strong>most common</strong> tumor of the <strong>parotid.&nbsp;</strong> It is a benign tumor.</li>\n</ul>\n<table width=\540\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\141\>\n<p><strong>Type</strong><strong> of Salivary gland</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\115\>\n<p><strong>Location</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\124\>\n<p><strong>Frequency of tumor</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\159\>\n<p><strong>Percentage of malignancy</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\141\>\n<p>Major</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\115\>\n<p>Parotid</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\124\>\n<p>Common</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\159\>\n<p>10–20%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\141\>&nbsp;</td>\n<td width=\115\>\n<p>Submandibular</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\124\>\n<p>Uncommon</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\159\>\n<p>50%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\141\>&nbsp;</td>\n<td width=\115\>\n<p>Sublingual</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\124\>\n<p>Very rare</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\159\>\n<p>85%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\141\>\n<p>Minor</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\115\>\n<p>Upper aero-digestive tract</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\124\>\n<p>Rare</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\159\>\n<p>90%</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1906, 'Surgery', 'PM1674. Important points regarding salivary gland tumors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Most common<strong> neoplasm </strong>of the salivary gland:<strong> Pleomorphic adenoma</strong></li>\n<li>Most common <strong>malignant</strong> tumor of the salivary gland:&nbsp;<strong>Mucoepidermoid carcinoma</strong></li>\n<li>Most common <strong>benign</strong> tumor of the&nbsp;salivary gland in<strong> children:</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Hemangioma</strong></li>\n<li>Most common <strong>malignant</strong> tumor of the&nbsp;salivary gland in <strong>children: Mucoepidermoid carcinoma</strong></li>\n<li>Most common malignant tumor of the minor salivary glands:&nbsp;<strong>Adenoid cystic carcinoma </strong></li>\n<li>Most common gland affected by pleomorphic adenomas: Parotid gland</li>\n<li>Tumor of the salivary gland with <strong>perineural invasion</strong>: Adenoid cystic carcinoma</li>\n<li>Tumor that shows a&nbsp;hot spot in <sup>99m</sup>Tc&nbsp;scan: <strong>Warthin’s tumor</strong></li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1907, 'Surgery', 'PM1312. Indications for parathyroidectomy in patients with asymptomatic primary HPT (2013-2014 NIH Consensus Conference Guidelines)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Serum calcium &gt;1 mg/dL above the upper limit of normal</li>\n<li>Renal:&nbsp;<br>\n<ul>\n<li>Reduction in creatinine clearance by 30%</li>\n<li>24-h urine calcium &gt;400 mg/day</li>\n<li>Presence of nephrolithiasis or nephrocalcinosis</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Skeletal:&nbsp;\n<ul>\n<li>Decreased bone mineral density (T score &lt;-2.5)</li>\n<li>Presence of vertebral fracture</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Age &lt;50 years</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1908, 'Surgery', 'PM1309. Secretion of medullary thyroid tumors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Medullary thyroid tumor secrete the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Calcitonin </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA)</strong></li>\n<li>Calcitonin gene–related peptide</li>\n<li>Histaminadases</li>\n<li>Prostaglandins E 2 and F 2 α</li>\n<li>Serotonin</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Calcitonin and serotonins are responsible for diarrhea in MTC.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1909, 'Surgery', 'PM1307. Thyroid Surgeries', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li><strong>Lobectomy</strong> - One entire thyroid lobe is removed.</li>\n<li><strong>Hemithyroidectomy </strong>- Total lobectomy of <strong>one lobe</strong>&nbsp;+isthmusectomy</li>\n<li><strong>Subtotal thyroidectomy</strong> - 2 x subtotal lobectomy (Leaving greater than 1 g of thyroid tissue <strong>on each lobe</strong>)+ isthmusectomy</li>\n<li><strong>Near total thyroidectomy</strong> - Total lobectomy but leaving less than 1 g of tissue adjacent to the RLN at the ligament of Berry <strong>on one lobe&nbsp;</strong>+ isthmusectomy (also known as Hartley-Dunhill procedure)</li>\n<li><strong>Total thyroidectomy</strong> - 2 x total lobectomy + isthmusectomy</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/37d806d8f5f747feb61aeddccca35d7bx1280x1686.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1910, 'Surgery', 'PM1306. Poor Prognostic Factors in Follicular Carcinoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Age &gt;50 years</li>\n<li>Tumour size &gt;4 cm</li>\n<li>High tumour grade</li>\n<li>Marked vascular invasion</li>\n<li>Extrathyroidal invasion</li>\n<li>Distant metastasis</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1911, 'Surgery', 'PM1255. Bethesda Criteria to Select Patients for MSI Testing', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>The Amsterdam criteria <strong>or</strong> one of the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Two cases of HNPCC-associated cancer in one patient, including synchronous or metachronous cancer</li>\n<li>Colon cancer and a first-degree relative with HNPCC-associated cancer and/or colonic adenoma (one case of cancer diagnosed before age 45 years and adenoma diagnosed before age 40 years)</li>\n<li>Colon or endometrial cancer diagnosed before age 45 years</li>\n<li>Right-sided colon cancer that has an undifferentiated pattern (solid, cribriform) or signet cell histopathologic characteristics diagnosed before age 45 years</li>\n<li>Adenomas diagnosed before age 40 years&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Remember: Bethesda criteria is also used for reporting thyroid cytopathology which guides clinical decision.</strong></p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1912, 'Surgery', 'PM0785. Radioiodine uptake of thyroid gland', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) scans are interpreted as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>High</strong> (or normal) radioiodine uptake indicates de-novo synthesis of the hormone. Therefore, there is increased hormone synthesis</li>\n<li><strong>Low</strong> (nearly absent) radioiodine uptake indicates:\n<ul>\n<li>Inflammation and destruction of thyroid tissue with release of the preformed hormone into the circulation</li>\n<li>Extrathyroidal source of thyroid hormone</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Conditions with high and low RAIU are given below:</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>High RAIU</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Low RAIU</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Graves’ disease</li>\n<li>Toxic multinodular goiter</li>\n<li>Toxic adenoma</li>\n<li>Thyroid cancer</li>\n<li>Hydatidiform mole</li>\n<li>TSH-secreting pituitary adenoma</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Acute phase of Hashimoto’s thyroiditis</li>\n<li>Drug-induced— iodine, amiodarone-induced thyroiditis</li>\n<li>Subacute/ Dequervain thyroiditis</li>\n<li>Radiation thyroiditis</li>\n<li>Metastatic follicular thyroid carcinoma</li>\n<li>Factitious (iatrogenic) thyrotoxicosis</li>\n<li>Struma ovarii (extrathyroid source)</li>\n<li>Hamburger thyrotoxicosis (exogenous source)</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/84debe461e9e4ef6a8de25fbe9c71e7fx1280x3027.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1913, 'Surgery', 'PM0782. Werner  classification', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Werner classification reflects the severity of the ophthalmopathy.</li>\n<li>It is well known by the acronym of <strong>NO SPECS.</strong></li>\n<li>Each grade is further subdivided as 0-4 and a-c.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Grades of Werner classification:</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Grade</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Feature</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Acronym</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>No signs or symptoms</td>\n<td><strong>N</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Only signs (lid retraction)</td>\n<td><strong>O</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Soft tissue involvement (chemosis, grit)</td>\n<td><strong>S</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Proptosis (minimum &lt;23mm, moderate, marked &gt;28mm)</td>\n<td><strong>P</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Extraocular muscle involvement</td>\n<td><strong>E</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Corneal involvement</td>\n<td><strong>C</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Loss of sight</td>\n<td><strong>S</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1914, 'Surgery', 'PM0195. NICE Guidelines for CT in Head Injury', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>National Institute for Health and Care Excellence <strong>(NICE) Guidelines</strong> for Computed Tomography <strong>(CT) in Head Injury</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Indications for CT </strong>imaging <strong>within 1 hour </strong>of following risk factors being identified:</p>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 351\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>Glasgow Coma Score (GCS) &lt;13 at any point</li>\n<li>GCS &lt;15 at 2 hours after injury on assessment in an emergency department</li>\n<li>Focal neurological deficit</li>\n<li>Suspected open, depressed, or basal skull fracture</li>\n<li>More than one episode of vomiting</li>\n<li>Post-traumatic seizure</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Indications for CT </strong>imaging <strong>within 8 hours:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Age <span>&gt;</span>65 years</li>\n<li>Coagulopathy (e.g., aspirin, warfarin, or rivaroxaban use)</li>\n<li>Dangerous mechanism of injury (e.g., fall from a height, road traffic accident)</li>\n<li>Retrograde amnesia &gt;30 minutes</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1915, 'Surgery', 'PM2297. Skin Grafting : Phases of Graft Uptake', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1968\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Skin graft uptake</strong> occurs in three phases:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Imbibition </strong>(Plasmatic circulation): During the <strong>first 48 hours,</strong> the graft is nourished with plasma exudate from the host bed capillaries.</li>\n<li><strong>Inosculation:</strong> <strong>C</strong><strong>ut vessels</strong> from the host bed <strong>line up</strong> with the cut ends of the vessels of the graft to form anastomoses.</li>\n<li><strong>Neovascularization:</strong> <strong>B</strong><strong>lood vessels grow</strong> from the recipient bed <strong>into the graft.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1968\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Sensations return to the graft over time, with <strong>reinnervation beginning at approximately 4 to 5 weeks</strong> and being completed by 12 to 24 months. <strong>Pain returns first</strong>, followed by light touch and temperature returning later.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Some books give that the 3 phases are imbibition, revascularisation (inosculation+neovascularisation) and organisation (fibrin layer holds the graft in place and this is replaced with fibroblasts by day 7).</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1916, 'Surgery', 'PM2215. Burns – Formulae for Fluid Calculation(Updated according to ATLS 10th edition 2018 guidelines)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Parkland’s formula</strong> gives the total fluid requirement for 24hours. <strong>Half</strong> of this volume is infused in the <strong>first 8 hours</strong>, and the <strong>remaining half</strong> is infused in the <strong>next 16 hours</strong>.</p>\n<p>This formula is recommended for those who have sustained large <strong>deep partial-thickness or full-thickness burns</strong> that cover more than 20% of the TBSA in adults and more than 10% in children.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Formulas provide a <strong>starting target rate</strong>; Subsequently, the amount of fluid provided should be adjusted based on <strong>urine output</strong>.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Category of burn</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Amount of Ringer’s Lactate given for 24 hours (ml)</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Target urine output (ml/kg/hour)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td rowspan=\3\><strong>2nd/3rd-degree burns</strong></td>\n<td>Adults&nbsp;</td>\n<td>2 x weight in kgs x % TBSA</td>\n<td>0.5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&lt;14 years</td>\n<td>3 x weight in kgs x % TBSA</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&lt; 1 year or &lt;30kgs</td>\n<td>3 x weight in kgs x % TBSA + 5% dextrose on a maintenance rate</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>4th-degree burns / Electrical burns</strong></td>\n<td>All ages</td>\n<td>4 x weight in kgs x % TBSA</td>\n<td>1-1.5 (until urine clears)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Dextrose maintenance:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>100 ml/ kg in 24 hours for 10 kg</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>50 ml/kg for next 10 kg</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>20 ml/kg for every kg after 20 kg</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Evan’s formula</strong> is used for <strong>normal saline</strong>.</p>\n<p>For the first 24 hours:</p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Amount of NS administered = weight in kgs x % TBSA</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Amount of colloid administered = weight in kgs x % TBSA</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>5% Dextrose administered= 2000 ml</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After 24 hours, the amount of NS and colloid administered is half. 2000 ml of dextrose is maintained.</p>\n<p><strong>Muir and Barclay’s formula</strong> for colloids:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>1 portion of colloid = (weight in kgs x % TBSA)/2</li>\n<li>6 portions of colloid are administered over 36 hours</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1917, 'Surgery,', 'PM2207. Acute Compartment and Crush Syndromes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>1. Acute Compartment Syndrome</strong></p>\n<p class=\p1\>Acute compartment syndrome is an elevation of the intracompartmental pressure (ICP) which increases the risk for tissue ischemia and necrosis.</p>\n<p><strong>Causes</strong>: Fractures (70%) and severe soft tissue injuries (30%). Common fractures causing compartment syndrome include&nbsp;tibial diaphyseal (most common), distal radius, and forearm fractures.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Pathology</strong>: Increased pressure in one of&nbsp;the osseofascial compartments due to bleeding, oedema or inflammation. A vicious cycle of ischemia → edema→ ischemia leading to necrosis of the muscles and nerves within the compartment in&nbsp;6 hours or less.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Clinical features</strong>: Five Ps: Pain,&nbsp;Paraesthesia, Pallor, Paralysis and Pulselessness.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Management</strong>: Fasciotomy to decompress the threatened compartment if the differential pressure (ΔP) goes &lt; 30 mmHg.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b3795f2c59974b46aed885144c3fb36ax975x813.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>2. Crush Syndrome&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>Crush syndrome is the systemic manifestation of muscle necrosis. It is commonly caused due to prolonged external compression of an extremity.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Causes</strong>: Crush injuries sustained during motor vehicle accidents, earthquakes, mining and other occupational accidents.</p>\n<p><strong>Pathology</strong>: Underperfusion of muscle causes myonecrosis. When the limb is freed, there is a release of toxic metabolites causing reperfusion injury. Reactive oxygen metabolites create further tissue injury. Free myoglobin can get precipitated in the renal glomeruli.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Clinical features</strong>: The affected limb is pulseless, red, swollen and blistered. Sensation and muscle power may be lost. There can be signs of impaired renal function, metabolic acidosis, hyperkalemia and hypocalcaemia.</p>\n<p><strong>Management</strong>:&nbsp;Encouraging high urine output, alkalization of the urine, hemofiltration, radical excision of dead muscles, fasciotomy if there is compartment syndrome.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1918, 'Surgery', 'PM1952. Timing of primary cleft lip and palate procedures:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Cleft lip alone</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Unilateral (one side) - One operation at 3–6 months</li>\n<li>Bilateral (both sides) - One operation at 4–5 months</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cleft palate alone</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Soft palate - Only one operation at 6 months</li>\n<li>Soft and hard palate - Two operations\n<ul>\n<li>Soft palate at 6 months</li>\n<li>Hard palate at 15–18 months</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Cleft lip and palate</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Unilateral - Two operations\n<ul>\n<li>Cleft lip and soft palate at 5–6 months</li>\n<li>Hard palate and gum pad with or without lip revision at 15–18 months</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Bilateral - Two operations\n<ul>\n<li>Cleft lip and soft palate at 4–5 months</li>\n<li>Hard palate and gum pad with or without lip revision at 15–18 months</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Secondary management</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hearing, Prophylactic myringotomy, Regular audiological testing -&nbsp;6–12 months</li>\n<li>\n<p>Speech, Velopharyngeal surgery, Speech and language therapy -&nbsp;18 months</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Orthodontic management</p>\n<p>- Mixed dentition -&nbsp;8–10 years<br>- Permanent dentition -&nbsp;14-18 years</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Excision of maxillary arch, Rhinoplasty -&nbsp;16+ years</p>\n</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1919, 'Surgery', 'PM2156. Indications for Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (CABG)', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Class I indications for CABG</strong> from the American College of Cardiology(ACC) and American Heart Association(AHA).</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Left main disease</li>\n<li>Three-vessel disease with or without proximal LAD disease</li>\n<li>Two vessel disease with proximal LAD disease</li>\n<li>Survivors of sudden cardiac death with presumed ischemia-mediated VT &nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong> Other indications for CABG include the following:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Disabling angina</li>\n<li>Ongoing ischemia in the setting of a non–ST-segment elevation (MI) that is unresponsive to medical therapy</li>\n<li>Poor LV function but with viable, nonfunctioning myocardium above the anatomic defect that can be revascularized</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1920, 'Orthopaedics,', 'PM2041. Thoracic outlet syndrome and its tests:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Thoracic outlet syndrome (TOS)</strong> is a neurovascular syndrome caused due to the compression of the lower trunk of brachial plexus (C8 and T1) and subclavian vessels in the thoracic outlet between the clavicle, the first rib, and scalene muscles.</p>\n<p>Clinical features due to compression of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\fontstyle0\>Brachial plexus: Pain and paraesthesia along the ulnar aspect of the arm.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\fontstyle0\>Subclavian vessels: Cyanosis, cold fingers, pallor and Raynauds phenomenon.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Provocative tests</strong>: Adsons test, Halsteads maneuver, Wrights test, Roos test.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Adson’s test:&nbsp;</strong>The examiner locates the radial pulse while arm is held in extension, external rotation, and slight abduction. The patient is instructed to take a deep breath and turn head towards the test arm while extending the neck.&nbsp;This manoeuvre will tense the anterior and middle scalenes. If there is outlet obstruction, the radial pulse will get diminished or absent on that side.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/84b5e5eb4d1143958be3dd50c53a3787x1280x1429.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Halstead maneuver (reverse Adsons):&nbsp;</strong>The examiner palpates the radial pulse and applies downward traction on the tested extremity while the patient’s neck is hyperextended and rotated to the <strong>opposite side</strong>. Diminished or absent pulse indicates a positive test.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/5dfd59610ed4480eb08ec567e78533cdx1280x2558.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Wright’s hyperabduction test:&nbsp;</strong>The examiner palpates the radial pulse and hyper-abducts the arm. The patient takes a deep breath and may rotate or extend his neck for additional effect. Absence of pulse indicates a positive test.</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/8dde492c1e9b4216982a97ebdbba9d15x1280x1416.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p class=\p1\><strong>Roos test:&nbsp;</strong>The patient abducts the shoulders to 90 degrees and flexes the elbow to 90 degrees. The patient is made to open and close the hand repeatedly for three minutes. The test is positive if the patient is unable to complete the test or experiences cramping, pain, numbness, on the affected side.&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/d3299a6fd29841c58c0b784671708142x1279x1140.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1921, 'Surgery', 'PM1663. Locations of the Common Mediastinal Masses', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Anterior Mediastinum</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Middle Mediastinum</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Posterior Mediastinum</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Thymoma </strong><strong>(most common in anterior mediastinum)</strong></p>\n<p>Lymphoma</p>\n<p>Germ cell tumors</p>\n<p>Thyroid and parathyroid<br>masses</p>\n<p>Bronchogenic Cyst</p>\n<p>Aneurysm</p>\n<p>Thymic cyst</p>\n<p>Parathyroid adenoma</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Cysts (MC in middle mediastinum):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pericardial (most common)</li>\n<li>Bronchogenic</li>\n<li>Enterogenous</li>\n<li>Neuroenteric</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Vascular masses (an&nbsp;aneurysm)</p>\n<p>LN enlargement and lymphoma</p>\n<p>Mesenchymal tumors</p>\n<p>Pheochromocytoma</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Neurogenic tumors&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Meningoceles</p>\n<p>Mesenchymal tumors</p>\n<p>Pheochromocytoma</p>\n<p>Lymphoma</p>\n<p>Bochdalek hernia</p>\n<p>Bronchogenic Cyst</p>\n<p>Enterogenous Cyst</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->');
INSERT INTO db_pearl_m (pid, subject, pearl_title, pearl_desc) VALUES
(1922, 'Surgery', 'PM1049. The circle of death/Crown of death/Corona mortis:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>It is a vascular continuation formed by the common iliac, internal iliac, obturator, inferior epigastric, and external iliac vessels.</li>\n<li><strong>Accessory obturator artery</strong> which is a <strong>branch of inferior epigastric artery</strong>, arches over Cooper’s ligament and <strong>joins the normal obturator artery</strong> and forms a <strong>complete vascular ring</strong>.</li>\n<li>Injury leads to torrential haemorrhage which is difficult to control.</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/ebb18bac0c394f00907132f945123f8ex1280x1244.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1923, 'Surgery', 'PM0583. Signs related to venous thrombosis', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Sign</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Moses’</p>\n<p>sign&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>Clinical&nbsp;sign found in patients with deep vein thrombosis of the lower leg involving the posterior&nbsp;tibial&nbsp;veins. The sign is positive if pain is elicited when the calf muscle is compressed forwards against the tibia, but not when the calf muscle is compressed from side to side.&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Homan’s</p>\n<p>sign&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>Another clinical sign found in patients with deep vein thrombosis. It is the&nbsp;discomfort behind the knee on forced dorsiflexion of the foot.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Lowenberg’s</p>\n<p>sign&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>Clinical&nbsp;sign found in patients with deep vein thrombosis of the lower leg. The sign is positive when pain is elicited rapidly when a blood pressure cuff is placed around the calf and inflated to 80 mmHg.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1924, 'Surgery', 'PM0554. Indications for Operative Repair of Aneurysm', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Condition</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Criteria for surgical repair</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Symptomatic aneurysm</td>\n<td>&nbsp;Any size</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ascending thoracic aortic aneurysm - asymptomatic</td>\n<td>&gt;5.5 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Descending thoracic aortic aneurysm -&nbsp;asymptomatic</td>\n<td>&gt;6 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Abdominal aortic aneurysm -&nbsp;asymptomatic</td>\n<td>&gt;5.5 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Popliteal artery aneurysm - asymptomatic</td>\n<td>&gt;2-3 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ascending thoracic aortic aneurysm in Marfan’s syndrome or bicuspid aortic valve</td>\n<td>&gt;4-5 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Rapidly&nbsp;growing&nbsp;aneurysms&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>&gt;0.5 cm/year for ascending aortic aneurysms</p>\n<p>&gt; 1cm/year for descending aortic aneurysms</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1925, 'Surgery', 'PM0542. Indications for operative repair of thoracic aortic aneurysm', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Clinical scenario</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Indication for operative repair</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Symptomatic aneurysm</td>\n<td>Any size</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Asymptomatic ascending thoracic aortic diameter</td>\n<td>&gt; 5.5 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>When the diameter of an ascending aortic aneurysm has increased</td>\n<td>&gt; 0.5 cm per year</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Asymptomatic descending thoracic aortic diameter or</td>\n<td>&gt; 6 cm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>When the diameter of descending&nbsp; aortic aneurysm has increased</td>\n<td>&nbsp;&gt; 1 cm per year</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Asymptomatic ascending thoracic aortic diameter in patients with Marfan’s syndrome or bicuspid aortic valve</td>\n<td>4-5cm</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1926, 'Surgery', 'PM0196. Crawford classification of thoracoabdominal aneurysm:', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><ul>\n<li>Extent I - Left subclavian artery to the suprarenal abdominal aorta.</li>\n<li>Extent II - (most extensive type) - Left subclavian artery to the infrarenal abdominal aorta, and they often reach the aortic bifurcation.</li>\n<li>Extent III - Lower descending thoracic aorta (below the sixth rib) to the abdomen.</li>\n<li>Extent IV - Begins at the diaphragmatic hiatus and often involve the entire abdominal aorta.</li>\n<li>Extent V- 6th intercostal space to above the renal artery</li>\n</ul></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/b0759ed161eb4d93804b429546ead698x1280x2559.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1927, 'Surgery', 'PM1115. Clark’s Classification', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Level</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Depth of invasion</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>I</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Epidermis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>II</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Invades papillary dermis but doesn’t fill it</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>III</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Fills papillary dermis, impinging on reticular dermis n=but not invading</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>IV</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Invades reticular dermis</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>V</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Invades subcutaneous tissue</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://cdn1.dailyrounds.org/uploads/99e283b061f24dc299595215e6d7660ax902x595.PNG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1928, 'Surgery', 'PM1114. Breslow’s  Classification of Malignant Melanoma', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p>Breslows classification of malignant melanoma:</p>\n<table class=\wikitable\ border=\1\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Stage</th>\n<th>Depth</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage I</td>\n<td>≤&nbsp;0.75mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage II</td>\n<td>0.76&nbsp;mm - 1.50mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage III</td>\n<td>1.51&nbsp;mm - 4 mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Stage IV</td>\n<td>&gt;4 mm<sup class=\reference\></sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>TNM staging based on the thickness of invasion according to AJCC:</p>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 754\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<ul>\n<li>T1 - ≤1.0 mm</li>\n<li>T2 - 1.01-2.0 mm</li>\n<li>T3 - 2.01-4.0 mm</li>\n<li>T4 - &gt;4.0 mm</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <!---->\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\>\n        <img _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\img-responsive ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ src=\https://dhmbxeygs57ff.cloudfront.net/uploads/42b06a5ff91d479b80343a49d7fe388ax1280x1019.JPEG\><!---->\n      </div><!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1929, 'Surgery', 'PM2507. CEAP Classification of Chronic Lower Extremity Venous Disease', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><div class=\page\ title=\Page 1027\>\n<table><colgroup><col><col><col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 995\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>CEAP (Clinical-Etiology-Anatomy-Pathophysiology)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Clinical&nbsp;classification (C)*</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C0</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No visible or palpable signs of venous disease</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C1</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Telangiectases or reticular veins</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C2</p>\n<p>C2r</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Varicose veins</p>\n<p>Recurrent varicose veins</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C3</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Edema</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C4</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Changes in skin and subcutaneous tissue secondary</p>\n<p>to chronic venous disease</p>\n<p>C4a-Pigmentation or eczema</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C4b-Lipodermatosclerosis or atrophie blanche</p>\n<p>C4c-Corona phlebectatica</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C5</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Healed ulcer</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>C6</p>\n<p>C6r</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Active ulcer</p>\n<p>Recurrent active venous ulcer</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>S</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>With symptoms attributable to venous disease</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>A</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Absence of&nbsp;symptoms attributable to venous disease</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Etiological</strong>&nbsp;<strong>classification (E)</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ec</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Congenital (Klippel-Trenaunay syndrome)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ep</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Primary</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Es</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Secondary (postthrombotic syndrome, trauma)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Esi</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Secondary (intravenous)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ese</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Secondary (extravenous)</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ec</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Congenital</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>En</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No venous cause identified</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Anatomic</strong>&nbsp;<strong>classification</strong> <strong>(A)</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>As</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Superficial</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ad</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Deep</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Ap</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Perforator</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>An</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No venous location identified</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\3\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Patho-physiologic&nbsp;classification (P)</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pr</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Reflux</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Po</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Obstruction, thrombosis</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pr,o</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Reflux and obstruction</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\2\ rowspan=\1\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>Pn</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p>No venous pathophysiology identified</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\page\ title=\Page 1027\>\n<div class=\section\>\n<div class=\layoutArea\>\n<div class=\column\>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The descriptor A (asymptomatic) or S (symptomatic) is placed after the C clinical class.</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Telengiactesia refers to tiny intradermal venules &lt;1 mm in diameter.</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Reticular veins refer to small dilated subdermal blue veins of 1 to 2.9 mm</li>\n<li aria-level=\1\>Varicose veins refer to dilated tortuous veins &gt;3 mm in diameter</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1930, 'Surgery', 'PM2492. Cancers associated with important oncogenes', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><table border=\0\>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Oncogenes</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td><strong>Associated cancers</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><em>c-MYC</em></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Burkitt’s lymphoma</p>\n<p>Adenocarcinomas of the breast, lung, and colon</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><em>N-MYC</em></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Neuroblastoma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p><em>L-MYC</em></p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<p>Small-cell carcinoma of the lung</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><em>K-RAS</em></td>\n<td>Colon, lung, and pancreatic tumors</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><em>N-RAS</em></td>\n<td>\n<p>Melanoma</p>\n<p>AML</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><em>H-RAS</em></td>\n<td>Bladder and kidney tumors</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div><!---->\n      <!---->\n    </div><!---->'),
(1931, 'Surgery', 'PM2491. Growth Factor Receptors and Associated Tumors', '<div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\ style=\\>\n      <div _ngcontent-smq-c132=\\ class=\ng-tns-c132-18 ng-star-inserted\><p><strong>Growth factor receptors and Associated Tumors</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Category</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>Proto-Oncogene</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Mode of activation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Associated tumor</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>EGF-receptor family</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>ERBB1 (EGFR)</em></p>\n<p><em>ERBB2 (HER)</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Mutation</p>\n<p>Amplification</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Adenocarcinoma of lung</p>\n<p>Breast carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>FMS- like tyrosine kinase 3</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>FLT3</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Point mutation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Leukemia</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Receptor for neurotrophic factors</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>RET</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Point mutation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Multiple endocrine neoplasia 2A and B, familial medullary thyroid carcinoma</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>PDGF receptor</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>PDGFRB</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Overexpression, translocation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Gliomas, leukemias</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Receptor for KIT ligand</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>KIT</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Point mutation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Gastrointestinal stromal tumors, seminomas, leukemias</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>ALK receptors</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p><em>ALK</em></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\113\>\n<p>Translocation, fusion gene formation</p>\n<p>Point mutation</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\1